<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AlaskaQuake     04-25 0137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alaska Quake,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moderate Earthquake Shakes Gulf of Alaska</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake occurred Monday in the
Gulf of Alaska, the U.S. Geological Survey reported.
   The tremor was centered about 350 miles southeast of Anchorage
and occurred at 5:48 p.m. local time (9:48 p.m EDT.)
   USGS earthquake monitors in Golden, Colo., said they recorded
the tremor at a preliminary magnitude of 5.6 on the Richter scale.
It was reported felt strongly in Yakataga.
   There was no immediate word of any damage or injuries.
   The Richter scale is an open-ended gauge of energy released by
an earthquake as measured by ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means that the ground
motion is 10 times greater.
   A quake with a magnitude of 5 can cause considerable damage in a
populated area.
</TEXT>
