<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 2357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FicusOutbreak     04-25 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ficus Outbreak,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ficus Trees Growing Wild In South Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ficus tree, long considered sterile, now has a
way to reproduce on its own, and scientists in South Florida are
bracing for an explosion of the lush, iron-rooted titan of the
tropics.
   The ficus benjamina, or weeping fig, may be a finicky house
plant, but it grows very large very fast in hospitable climates.
Its dense crown snuff out plants below, and its notorious roots can
muscle through pavement to strangle other large trees and choke
pipes.
   Ficus had been held in check by their inability to reproduce _
until now.
   Tiny insects from India and tropical regions have found their
way to Florida and are allowing the trees to pollinate the wild
seeds, which are spread by birds and animals that eat the small
berries.
   A single tree can produce millions of seeds a year.
   ``You get the idea it's just a rain of these things coming down
all the time,'' said Doyle McKey, tropical biologist at the
University of Miami, where ficus have been seen sprouting on stone
walls and sidewalk cracks.
   Until such insects as the female fig wasp came to Florida, ficus
could only be reproduced in plant nurseries from other cuttings.
That meant the spread of ficus was limited to where property owners
planted them.
   Most of the wild seedlings spotted so far are small, but the
growth has been widespread. They have been seen dotting lawns and
forests throughout South Florida and north to the Tampa Bay area.
   ``I think we're going to see our landscape change,'' said Robert
Knight Jr., a researcher at the U.S. Department of Agriculture's
subtropical research station in Coral Gables.
   It's too soon to tell whether they'll be mostly a suburban
nuisance or begin to crowd out native vegetation in unspoiled
areas, scientists say.
   ``They might become a pest in our nature preserves and
hammocks,'' McKey said recently. ``Otherwise, the habitat is going
to be in suburbia in our landscapes, where everything else is
unnatural.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
