<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cuba-Church     04-25 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-Church,0718</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba Accepting Church To Certain Extent</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TINA SUSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The visit last week of New York Cardinal John
O'Connor to Cuba marked the latest in a series of moves indicating
greater government acceptance of religion in this communist nation.
   Thousands of worshipers filled cathedrals in Havana and
Santiago, Cuba, for Masses celebrated by the Roman Catholic
cardinal during his four-day visit.
   One woman, Ruby Jane Padron, said her husband, Alberto, had been
imprisoned 22 years simply for being a practicing Catholic.
   But when asked if she was afraid to be at the Mass in Havana,
she said: ``Nervous? No, we are not nervous here. No, that was in
the past. It's different now. The hands of the communists are
easier _ not so harsh.''
   Cuban leader Fidel Castro met with O'Connor on Wednesday night
and, according to the cardinal, agreed to grant more visas for
foreign nuns to come to Cuba.
   Last month, Cuba authorized 19 foreign priests and an expatriate
Cuban clergyman to work in Cuba, along with the 210 priests already
in the communist nation.
   Last year, the government allowed importation of 30,000 Bibles.
And in 1986, the leadership called on citizens to respect the
beliefs of churchgoers.
   Cuba now has an office of religious affairs, and Castro has made
no secret of the fact that he would welcome a visit by the pope.
   There apparently is more than one reason for this relaxation.
   The number of Roman Catholics has decreased to an acceptable
level, by government standards.
   When Castro siezed power in 1959 about 85 percent of Cubans were
Roman Catholics. Now Roman Catholics make up an estimated 41
percent of Cuba's 10.2 million people.
   In addition, the government has realized that it's possible to
be loyal both to the church and to the revolution.
   ``Theoretically it is possible, and in reality it also is,''
Education Minister Jose Ramon Fernandez told reporters while
touring Havana's historical colonial section with O'Connor.
   Even O'Connor told reporters, ``All of us in the United States
would be revolutionaries, I guess. We are the product of a
revolution. I've never thought of myself as a bad Catholic for that
reason.''
   Cuba's treatment of religion began changing around 1985 after
the publication of the book ``Fidel and Religion,'' by the Rev.
Carlos Alberto Christo, a Brazilian priest.
   Castro told Christo he never opposed the Catholic Chuch as an
institution _ only those ``militant Catholics ... from the rich
class that supported the counterrevolution.''
   He described as ``models for Communists'' the Catholic nuns who
work in Cuban hospitals and mental asylums.
   O'Connor said he drummed the idea of the church's
resourcefulness into Castro during their talk, and Castro responded
eagerly.
   Castro welcomed the idea of having an American clergyman as a
liaison between the U.S. government and Cuban political prisoners
in an attempt to get the United States to accept the prisoners, the
cardinal said.
   The two also discussed the possibility of church assistance in
helping Cuba obtain medical supplies unavailable on the island
nation.
   Closer church-state relations and especially a papal visit would
boost Cuba's image abroad.
   ``The church could be very very helpful in explaining to the
world at large what is legitimate in the revolutionary government
here in Cuba,'' O'Connor said.
   Government officials turned out in force to greet O'Connor, and
the cardinal indicated the Vatican would pay close attention to
this in deciding whether Cuba should be added to the pope's future
itinerary.
   The reaction in churches and on the street to O'Connor's
presence gave credence to the cardinal's comment that the faith in
Cuba is still solid, despite years of restrictions.
   One elderly woman clutching rosary beads rushed up to pastor
James McCarthy, O'Connor's secretary, as he walked through the
streets of Old Havana and told him what a wonderful thing the
cardinal's visit was.
   ``No political system, no ideology, is going to be ultimately
successful in driving (the faith) out,'' O'Connor said. ``Success
could be achieved for a period of time, but the seed is there, and
it keeps springing back into flower.''
</TEXT>
