<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nightline     04-25 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nightline,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABC's `Nightline' Begins Week Of Shows From Jerusalem</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC's ``Nightline'' tonight begins a week of
shows live from Israel, including a three-hour panel discussion in
Jerusalem before an audience of 700 Israelis and Palestinians.
   ``Good Lord only knows'' how the live discussion will turn out,
said ``Nightline'' anchor Ted Koppel, who has done shows in
previous years from South Africa, the Philippines and Southeast
Asia.
   ``This just seemed like one of those subjects that is so rich
and meaty it really can't be covered in an hour or two over here,
so we're going to spend a week over there,'' said Koppel before
leaving for Jerusalem from which most of the shows will be
broadcast.
   Monday night's one-hour broadcast will feature an interview with
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzak Rabin, as well as other guests not
yet lined up as of this weekend.
   Likewise, guests for the ``town hall meeting'' on Tuesday had
not been determined. Koppel said participants would include
Israelis and Palestinians, though selection of Palestinian
representatives was difficult because Israeli government officials
will not participate if there's anyone sympathetic to the Palestine
Liberation Organization involved.
   The trip was planned last year, Koppel said, before the recent
violence on the Israeli-occupied West Bank prompted new interest in
the conflict between Palestinians and Israelis.
   ``What we're trying to do is make it clearer to an American
audience what the different positions are and also make it clear
what you're dealing with is not a homogenous Israeli point of view
or for that matter a homogenous Palestinian point of view. There
are shadings,'' said Koppel.
   ``Part of what we're going to try to do out there, and I'd say
probably the most important thing we going to try to do is provide
a context that critics of television, I think quite correctly, have
suggested we have not been providing over the past couple of
years.''
   The rest of the week's schedule was not set, though Koppel said
he hoped to interview King Hussein. That show would originate from
Amman, Jordan.
   As far going to the West Bank itself, Koppel said, ``I'm sure
I'll be taking a few field trips.''
   Koppel said officials in the region had been cooperative so far,
but he added: ``I've spent too much time in the Middle East to take
anything for granted. I'll find out when I get on the air.''
</TEXT>
