<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz 1stLd-Writethru   04-25 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0717,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Leaves Soviet Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>PRECEDE, Moscow</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Shultz in Tblisi, Kiev; picks up 4th
pvs: Shultz and ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TBLISI, USSR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz attended
religious services in the Soviet Union on Sunday, extolling the
``spread and acceptance of faith'' in a subtle jab at this nation's
institutionalized atheism.
   Shultz flew out of Tbilisi, the capital of the southern Soviet
republic of Georgia in the Caucasus Mountains, after a day of
sightseeing.
   He headed for Brussels, Belgium, to brief members of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization on his talks in Moscow Thursday and
Friday with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   Before he left, in Tblisi and in Kiev, he delivered an overt
message on religious freedom, attending the Georgian Orthodox
Cathedral here Sunday and St. Sophia's Cathedral in Kiev on
Saturday.
   Even at a lavish lunch here with dozens of writers, singers and
artists, Shultz went out of his way in a toast to say: ``I could
feel, in a sense, I was in the presence of the Creator.''
   In Kiev, Shultz also visited Babi Yar, the Nazi killing ground
in World War II, where tens of thousands of Jews and other
Ukrainians were slaughtered.
   ``We have to say to ourselves always, never again,'' Shultz
vowed.
   In St. Sophia's, a cathedral that Communist authorities have
converted into a museum, Shultz said the majestic building ``just
shows you the commitment of and power of religion.''
   In an evolving human rights policy, Shultz has kept up U.S.
pressure on the Soviets to expand Jewish emigration while pressing
for more freedom of religious practices for all citizens.
   Tblisi, a relatively relaxed city far from Moscow, has
functioning churches and even two jewish synagogues. Shultz,
addressing the patriarch, Iliya II, and the congregants who jammed
the small cathedral, said he understood their desire for ``progress
in belief, in religion.''
   ```You must be meaning progress in the spread and acceptance of
faith because it has an immense continuity,'' Shultz said, ``It
couldn't be more evident them being here in this church.''
   Shultz and Shevardnadze reported little progress in the talks,
which focused on a treaty that would halve U.S. and Soviet arsenals
of strategic nuclear weapons.
   The goal had been to complete the treaty by May 29 when
President Reagan journeys to Moscow for a summit meeting with
Gorbachev. But officials have expressed doubt the pact will be
ready by then because too many disagreements remain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
