<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     04-25 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KEWANEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver Ratliff doesn't know what the
12,000-pound acorn-shaped piece of iron is, but he likes it.
   Workers from Ratliff Bros. & Co. were clearing a site for a
restaurant in Abingdon when they dug up the massive object buried
about a foot underground.
   His workers hauled it back to Kewanee, thinking the iron might
be worth several hundred dollars. But Ratliff says the mystery
object has brought him so much attention he won't scrap it.
   Now, Kewanee is abuzz as folks in this town of 14,500 try to
figure out what it is.
   ``At first we were worried it was a bomb,'' said Ratliff, 68,
who has unearthed many strange things in his 46 years in the
construction business.
   Army bomb specialists examined the find Tuesday and determined
it wasn't a bomb. But that was all they could say.
   ``Everyone in town is plotting and scheming to explain what this
thing is,'' said Steve Bialowbreski, a truck dispatcher at
Ratliff's. ``There is no way it's a wrecking ball because it's too
heavy and there's no way to hook on to it.''
   Ratliff ran his hand along the rusted exterior of the object as
it sat Friday in the rear of his company's yard.
   ``Whatever it is, it sure was made nice,'' he said.
   Some Ratliff workers think the 3-by-5-foot hunk of iron is an
old bank safe.
   Retiree Jim Cinnamon speculated that the thing was a weight used
to anchor something huge _ a blimp or a crane; farmer John Betts
theorized it's the base for a flagpole.
   Ratliff and some of his friends have tried, with no success, to
drill into the object.
   With the mystery unsolved, Ratliff is considering sandblasting
the knob, painting it and using it to mark the entrance to his
business.
   ``Maybe it would become a tourist attraction,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a clash of wits in the tradition of
British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, the Founding Fathers and
the Ivy League. In the end, the U.S. Senate and Brown University
emerged as winners.
   Teams from Yale University and Brown took sides in the final
round of the National Debate Championships on whether to abolish
the Senate.
   Yale senior Bart Aronson, taking his role of prime minister for
a make-believe Her Majesty's Government quite seriously, denounced
the Senate as ``fundamentally undemocratic.'' He called it a rich
man's club that slows the legislative process and unfairly shifts
power to small states.
   His partner, Victor Miller, pressed the attack, questioning the
purpose of creating a Congress with two houses _ the 200-year-old
compromise between large states like Virginia and small ones like
Rhode Island.
   ``Why should an artificial boundary like a state have a voice,
Mr. Speaker? People should have a voice,'' insisted Miller.
   But Brown's Jason Grumet, speaking for Her Majesty's Loyal
Opposition, countered that ``all political boundaries are
artificial. Except for rivers, there's nothing separating us from
Canada. I don't want to share things with Canada.''
   Swayed by this nationalism, traditionalism, federalism _ or the
Brown team's more humorous heckles _ the audience declared the
Opposition team the winners Saturday by a 2-1 margin.
   About 50 two-student teams competed at the two-day tournament at
Johns Hopkins University sponsored by the American Parliamentary
Debate Association.
</TEXT>
