<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArchMoore Bjt   04-25 0754</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arch Moore, Bjt,0777</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biggest Opponent Of West Virginia's Governor Is His Self-Created
Image</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CN2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Arch Moore is finding that perhaps
his toughest opponent in his re-election bid is the image he helped
create for himself.
   The almost mythical Moore benefited from an influx of federal
funds and a healthy economy as he opened highways, constructed
buildings and created jobs during his first two terms from 1969 to
1977.
   But he has been criticized during his third term as skippering a
rudderless ship awash in financial problems that the captain cannot
or will not control.
   Moore, 65, faces his first serious political challenge in May
10's GOP primary in which he is seeking an unprecedented fourth
term. His opponent, Morgantown businessman John Raese, is an
aggressive campaigner who has capitalized on the state's woes.
   ``Everybody changes as they mature,'' former state GOP Chairman
Kent Strange Hall said of Moore. ``I think the real changes are the
circumstances and conditions in which he's operating.
   ``Number one, he doesn't have the money that was available
either through federal funding or the state's economy. And
secondly, he doesn't have the team of department heads and advisers
he had in the first eight years.''
   Moore's administrative abilities have drawn the most fire. Even
administration officials concede that when Moore was returned to
office in 1984, people expected a miracle turnaround that Moore has
been unable to produce.
   The governor can point to a record of hard work, a gradual
reduction in the unemployment rate and increased industrial
development, but the days of major announcements have ended.
   A spokesman for the state Manufacturers Association, for
instance, says the state has lost 36 major plants between 1979 and
1986, idling 4,450 workers, and said 28,000 manufacturing jobs were
lost in the plants that remain open.
   Moore's first two terms were marked by a burgeoning economy.
Federal money poured into the state, and Moore took the credit. He
seemed to be everywhere at once, opening 225 miles of West
Virginia's 515 miles of interstate highway, overseeing construction
of the state Science and Cultural Center on the Capitol grounds,
and luring new businesses.
   The myth of the all-knowing, all-seeing leader is one that he
helped cultivate in a state where registered Democrats outnumber
Republicans 2-1.
   Even a 1976 federal extortion indictment did not slow him. On
the day he was indicted, Moore called a news conference to announce
he would seek a third consecutive term, although the state
constitution appeared to prohibit it.
   Moore was acquitted, but the state Supreme Court barred his
re-election bid.
   He left what he said was a $234 million budget surplus, a
booming interstate highway building program and reasonably strong
coal, steel and glass industries.
   Moore opened a law practice and ran unsuccessfully for the U.S.
Senate in 1978 and governor in 1980.
   When Moore again entered the governor's office for an
unprecedented third term in 1985, he found the state in much
different shape.
   The unemployment rate hit 18 percent the year before as the
state's economy hit rock-bottom. The state faced a $250 million
debt in the unemployment compensation fund that had been run up by
Democratic Gov. Jay Rockefeller. The Legislature had enacted huge
tax increases. And federal funding for highway construction and
other projects dwindled.
   Moore asked the Legislature for a myriad of economic tools to
attract business, and later claimed success. He says he has
attracted more than $1 billion in development money during each of
the past two years, and that the unemployment rate dropped below 11
percent in 1987.
   Critics, however, scoffed at his economic announcements, saying
thousands have fled seeking jobs elsewhere. A West Virginia
University study found the state lost 52,600 of its 1.9 million
residents since 1980.
   Raese, a newspaper publisher and coal and limestone company
owner, calls himself a conservative, pro-business candidate. He
says Moore has failed to adjust spending to the state's dwindling
tax income.
   ``Arch Moore is just a credit card governor,'' Raese said during
a recent interview. ``He's marching to an old liberal tune of the
late 1950s and early 1960s.''
   According to a poll released today, Raese holds a substantial
lead over Moore among Republicans and independents, 54 percent to
30 percent. Sixty-nine percent of the Republicans surveyed rated
Moore's performance as governor as poor or fair.
   The poll, conducted by The Associated Press, the Charleston
Daily Mail and WSAZ-TV, had a margin of error of 4.4 percentage
points.
</TEXT>
