<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FairHousing     04-25 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fair Housing,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Softening Position on Fair Housing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is softening its
opposition to Democrat-sponsored fair housing legislation but still
opposes provisions it says would deny the right to trial by jury
and be unfair to elderly people, according to a Housing and Urban
Development official.
   Another administration objection _ that a new ban of
discrimination against the handicapped could force landlords to
accept drug addicts or alcoholics _ was addressed in two amendments
passed last week.
   The bill, expected to be voted on Tuesday in the House Judiciary
Committee, would toughen enforcement of the Fair Housing Act of
1968 and expand it to ban discrimination against handicapped people
and families with children in rental or sale of living space. A
similar bill has been introduced in the Senate.
   The administration had introduced its own fair housing
legislation and favors an expansion of the act which now bans
discrimination on the bases of sex, ethnic origin or religion.
   But it is wary of the version now being discussed in the House
Judiciary Committee, believing it may be unconstitutional and
unfair to some landlords, tenants and home buyers, HUD general
counsel J. Michael Dorsey said in an interview Friday.
   The committee last week rejected changes that would have met
some administration objections, but it tentatively approved one
excluding abusers of controlled substances from being classified as
handicapped.
   Another amendment would allow landlords or sellers to reject
people ``whose tenancy would constitute a direct threat to the
health or safety of other individuals.''
   Dorsey said there is broad agreement that discrimination against
the handicapped should be added to the law. But he had said in a
letter to the Judiciary Committee last week that the Democratic
version ``does not clearly allow those who provide housing to
exclude individuals with current impairments, such as current drug
abuse, that pose a threat to property or safety of others.''
   Major objections to the bill have come from the Justice
Department which opposes the setting up of an administrative law
judge system to handle discrimination cases, rather than having
them go to a regular jury.
   Dorsey said that despite strong objections to parts of the
proposed bill, the administration is taking a softer stand than it
has in the past. But he said it has not altered its major
objections to the Democratic proposals.
   ``We are not saying anything about a veto at this point at
all,'' he said.
   President Reagan has submitted four bills to amend fair housing
laws _ in 1983, 1985, 1986 and this year. Dorsey said the current
Democratic bill is ``not the one that we would prefer.''
   But he indicated the administration wants fair housing laws
expanded before Reagan leaves office.
   Dorsey said the administration supports the idea that
discrimination cases can be brought for single incidents rather
than requiring that a pattern of discrimination be proven, which is
required under the 1968 law. But he said the administrative law
judge plan does not pass ``constitutional muster.''
   Dorsey noted that the provision banning discrimination on the
basis of ``familial status'' is designed to protect families with
children.
   But he said in the letter, ``This provision intended to ensure
fairness may well have substantial unfair effects'' on older
Americans and people without children.
   The bill allows retirement communities or buildings where all
the tenants are over 62 to ban children, but singles communities
that also have younger people in them would have to accept families
with children.
   Ralph G. Neas, executive director of the Leadership Conference
on Civil Rights, which endorses the Democratic bill, said that
despite administration opposition, he expects bipartisan support
for the final measure.
   ``This administration, led by the Department of Justice, has
compiled the worst civil rights record of any administration in
half a century,'' Neas said in a telephone interview.
   But he said the Justice Department has failed in all previous
efforts to limit civil rights and ``we believe once again a strong
bipartisan consensus will reject this one.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
