<DOCNO> AP880425-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Carlucci-SDI     04-25 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carlucci-SDI,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Defends SDI, Scores Account of Critical Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci says
predictions that the Star Wars missile defense system won't work
``are like saying 10 years before we had helicopters that
helicopters were doomed to failure.''
   Carlucci on Sunday defended the administration program to create
a hi-tech space shield against Soviet missiles, saying a panel of
non-government experts believes the system is ``fundamentally
sound.''
   He disputed a report in Sunday's edition of The Washington Post
that quoted an unpublished congressional study as saying the system
would ``suffer a catastrophic failure'' if it were used against a
multiple missile attack from the Soviet Union.
   ``That's about ``like saying 10 years before we had helicopters
that helicopters were doomed to failure,'' Carlucci said in an
interview on ABC-TV's ``This Week with David Brinkley.''
   The study was conducted by the Office of Technology Assessment,
a non-partisan scientific arm of Congress.
   Carlucci said he had a panel of non-government technicians and
engineers evaluate Star Wars, and it concluded that ``the program
is fundamentally sound and that we can build a militarily effective
SDI (strategic defense initiative) program, and that is the goal.''
   Carlucci said the Defense Department has been studying the
congressional report, which he described as long and complex, but
he said there has been no official comment on it.
   He said SDI is ``a program that we are currently designing. It
has not even entered the developmental stage, much less the
deployment stage.''
   Meanwhile, the Post reported in Monday's editions that a
high-level Pentagon panel has recommended to Carlucci that he
sharply cut the proposed initial SDI deployment from a system of
space-based weaponry to a less costly and much less effective
system of ground-based rockets.
   Quoting unidentified senior Pentagon officials, the newspaper
said the panel directed by Robert Everett, chairman of the
Pentagon's senior scientific advisory group, has told Carlucci that
such a ground-based defense is worth pursuing as an initial step.
   Last September, then-Defense Secretary Caspar W. Weinberger
approved the acceleration of six SDI programs, the first decision
to push Star Wars technologies from pure research toward
development. The six projects then entered what is known as a
``demonstration and validation'' phase, in which various components
needed for a working system would be tested.
   No decision has been made on which of the six would be the first
deployed.
   The six programs, which had been recommended by the Defense
Acquisition Board, the Pentagon's highest internal review panel,
include:
   _The ground-based surveillance and tracking system, a missile
that could be fired into space to obtain tracking information on
missiles approaching the United States.
   _The space-based surveillance and tracking system, a satellite
system that would be deployed in space to identify and track enemy
missiles.
   _The boost surveillance and tracking system, another type of
orbiting satellite system that would provide an alert if enemy
missiles were launched.
   _The re-entry vehicle interception system, small missiles that
could be fired from the ground to intercept and destroy enemy
missiles during the middle and latter stages of their flight.
   _The space-based interception system, small ``kinetic kill''
rockets on an orbiting platform in space. The rockets could be
fired at enemy missiles shortly after launch and would destroy them
through a direct collision.
   _And the battle management-command, control and communications
system, the ``brains'' of any Star Wars defense. This would consist
of a series of high-powered computers that would be programmed to
select targets and direct weapons against them.
   In the interview Sunday, Carlucci said the Post story on the
report by the Office of Technology Assessment ``took selected
quotes out of that report'' and drew conclusions from them. ``What
you're reading from is some kind of a leaked document,'' he said.
   The Post said it had obtained the report's ``summary chapter.''
   The newspaper said the report shows that detailed computer
instructions needed to destroy thousands of warheads streaking
towards the United States probably cannot ``be produced in the
foreseeable future.''
   The overall conclusion of the report is that, despite five years
and $12 billion worth of scientific research, ``many questions
remain about the feasibility of meeting SDI goals,'' which include
the ability to ward off a Soviet missile attack and eventually
eliminate the threat posed by Soviet missiles.
</TEXT>
