<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0314EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel Bjt   04-25 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, Bjt,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Party: Voters Will Have Final Say On Peace Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The left-of-center Labor Party adopted a
campaign platform saying Israel will never completely withdraw from
the occupied territories and that voters will be asked to approve
any Middle East peace settlement.
   The platform for November's election appeared to be more
hard-line than the U.S. peace initiative initially backed by Shimon
Peres, the head of the Labor Party and the foreign minister in
Israel's coalition government.
   The platform adopted Sunday apparently was aimed winning over
voters on the right who might consider the party too ``dovish.''
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, meanwhile, told the Cabinet on
Sunday that 1,700 Palestinians, more than one-third of the 4,900
arrested since protests began Dec. 8, were being held without trial
for up to six months.
   Israel media said Rabin also criticized the Justice Ministry
during the Cabinet meeting, saying it was hampering army efforts to
deport more Palestinian agitators. Israel has deported 20
Palestinians to Lebanon since Dec. 8 and ordered the expulsion of
at least four others.
   Also Sunday, the army lifted a four-day ban that had prevented
Arabs in the occupied lands from traveling to Israel. The army also
permitted the delivery of gasoline to the occupied areas for the
first time in more than a month.
   No major clashes were reported between Arabs and Israeli
soldiers in the occupied lands on Sunday.
   The Labor Party platform promised voters a final say, either
through elections or a referendum, on any Middle East peace
settlement, said Labor spokeswoman Michal Cohen.
   The platform, written by Peres, also says Israel will never
withdraw completely from the West Bank and Gaza Strip it captured
in the 1967 Middle East war, Ms. Cohen told The Associated Press.
   It calls on Israel to seek direct negotiations with a
Jordanian-Palestinian delegation, to be preceded by an
international peace conference with strictly ceremonial functions.
The Palestine Liberation Organization would not participate in the
talks.
   A negotiated interim agreement on limited self-rule for the 1.5
million Palestinians in the occupied lands would remain in effect
for up to five years.
   The document also specifies that a final settlement should allow
no Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza, preserve all Jewish
settlements there and maintain Jerusalem as the united capital of
Israel.
   It says areas with a high percentage of Arab residents may be
turned over to Palestinian-Jordanian control.
   These specifics in the platform go beyond the U.S. peace
initiative, which do not dictate any such terms. The section on
settlements remaining intact presumably would conflict with the
views of the American government, which has consistently urged
limiting Jewish settlements in the occupied territories.
   Peres' call for giving Israeli voters a final say on any peace
plan has not been stated before. The U.S. peace initiative also has
never directly said that any international peace conference would
be strictly ceremonial in function.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir head of the right-wing Likud bloc
said on Sunday that Israel would ``never part with the West Bank
and Gaza Strip.'' In a speech to the central committee of his Herut
Party, Shamir also suggested that gradual and limited Palestinian
self-rule was as far as he was willing to go.
   Labor and Likud are in the fourth year of a fragile coalition.
Peres and Shamir traded jobs in October 1987.
   Also Sunday, the Defense Ministry asked the Finance Ministry for
an additional $162 million to cover the cost of combating the Arab
uprising, said spokesman Eitan Haber. He would not elaborate, and
it was not immediately clear if that sum represented all the money
the ministry has spent in connection with the uprising since Dec.
8, or only a part of it.
   Last month, the Economics Ministry said the uprising has cost
Israel $312 million in lost production, lost exports and added
security costs.
   Rabin also said 165 Palestinians have been killed in the
uprising, including 147 by the army. According to U.N. figures, the
Palestinian death toll has reached 173. An Israeli soldier and
Jewish settler also have died.
</TEXT>
