<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0407,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar and Stock Prices Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Nikkei closing figure</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tokyo share prices rose across the board today and
the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed at a record high while the dollar
stayed stable throughout the day.
   The Nikkei index of 225 selected issues in the Tokyo Stock
Exchange gained 155.08 points from Saturday's closing to end the
day at 27,213.45, the highest level for the market's main index.
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 125
yen, up 0.35 yen from Friday's close of 124.65 yen. It had opened
the day at 125.05 yen.
   ``Share prices, including large-capital issues such as steels,
are faring well'' as investors were buoyed by the strength of the
Japanese economy, said Masahiro Umemori of Nomura Securities.
   He said some investors were awaiting first-quarter figures on
the U.S. gross national product, scheduled to be announced in
Washington Tuesday.
   A foreign exchange dealer at a Japanese commercial bank said
morning trading on the dollar was very slow because investors were
waiting for the U.S. GNP figures. Speaking on condition of
ananymity, he said slow trading was expected throughout the week as
Japan enters a major holiday season next week.
</TEXT>
