<DOCNO> AP880425-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Extremes     04-25 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Extremes,0846</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Front Soars, Communists Slide In Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-France-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first round of the presidential election was a
historic moment for two political parties. The far-right National
Front achieved unprecedented support, and the Communist Party
tumbled to an all-time low.
   Perhaps most important for the future of France was the 14.5
percent won by Jean-Marie Le Pen, president of the National Front.
The party has emerged as a significant new force in French
politiics with its strident anti-immigrant, ``French first''
campaign.
   ``Nothing ever again will be done in France without the voters
of the National Front,'' exulted Le Pen, 59, after the results
became clear in Sunday's election. He said there has been a
``radical transformation of the national (political) landscape.''
   Premier Jacques Chirac, who will face Socialist President
Francois Mitterrand in the May 8 runoff, won only 19.9 percent of
the vote and desperately needs National Front support if he is to
have any chance of overtaking the president, who scored 33.9
percent.
   Chirac has vowed he will not do a deal with Le Pen for his
backing, but he may have no choice but to do so despite the nearly
universal condemnation it will bring him. Le Pen says his
instructions to his voters will depend on what Chirac says and does
in the coming week.
   While Le Pen's performance was a surprise, well above the 10
percent to 12 percent he had been accorded in pre-election opinion
polls, the 6.8 percent won by Andre Lajoinie, the official
Communist candidate, was predictable and confirmed the steady
decline that began in 1981.
   The stodgy, tightly structured Communist Party has been losing
members for a decade, essentially because it has failed to adapt
its language to a changing French society which is better educated,
more sophisticated and less doctrinaire.
   The Communists were hampered by the candidacy of Pierre Juquin,
leader of a splinter reformist movement who won 2.1 percent.
   The poor showing of the official Communist candidate could lead
to further internal party dissension of the sort that led to the
rebellion by Juquin and others over the past four years.
   The Communist Party, which once was the major force on the
French left accounting for more than a quarter of the vote, began
to fall significantly with the 1981 presidential election when
party Secretary General Georges Marchais won only 15.3 percent of
the vote.
   That fell to 11.3 percent in the 1984 election for the European
Parliament and 9.8 percent in the 1986 National Assembly election.
   Sunday's score was the lowest registered by the French Communist
Party in a national election since the party was founded in 1920.
The previous low was 8.4 percent in the 1932 legislative vote.
   In the 1974 presidential election, Le Pen won a minuscule 0.7
percent. In 1981, he was not even able to gather the 500 signatures
of elected officials necessary to get on the ballot.
   But in 1984, the National Front, thoroughly vilified by all of
the traditional parties, nearly equaled the Communists in the
European vote with 11 percent and matched them in the 1986
legislatives with 9.8.
   Bruno Megret, Le Pen's campaign manager, called 1988 ``a major
turning point in the political history of our country.''
   Francois Bachelot, a National Front deputy in Parliament, said
the score was ``not just the most remarkable event of the first
round of the presidential elections, it is the essential political
event of the post-war period.''
   The combined vote of Chirac, head of the conservative Rally for
the Republic party, and former Premier Raymond Barre, supported by
the center-right Union for French Democracy, totaled less than 37
percent, a serious setback for the traditional rightist parties.
   Though Chirac rejects making overtures to the National Front, he
boldly addressed Le Pen's favorite themes in a short television
appearance after the election was over.
   He appealed to ``all those who want security to be assured, and
delinquence, criminality and terrorism to be fought with all
necessary firmness, our national identifity to be preserved and
clandestine immigration also to be fought...''
   Political analysts generally agreed that Le Pen's newfound
support was based as much on a widespread dissatisfaction with
traditional parties as his anti-immigration and law-and-order
stands.
   ``I am a little ashamed for France that a man like Le Pen ...
has won 4 million votes,'' said Marchais. ``That poses a problem
for me and that poses a problem for my country. He has taken votes
from the working-class electorate.''
   He added that France had ``no reason to be proud'' of a man
whose policy is ``founded on racism.''
   Lajoinie stressed that he ``waged my campaign not to be elected,
but to affirm demands for new policies.'' He added: ``In that
context is is obvious that the real influence of the French
Communist Party goes very far beyond the results that we registered
today.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
