<DOCNO> AP880425-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0518EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Chirac     04-25 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Chirac,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chirac Faces Old Foe In Second Run For Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-France-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Jacques Chirac, an energetic leader and a
tireless campaigner, will need to draw on those traits as he fights
what is expected to be an uphill battle in next month's runoff
presidential election.
   The neo-Gaullist, who has been head of the government for two
years, finished second in the first round of the election on
Sunday, receiving 20 percent of the vote compared to 34 percent for
President Francois Mitterrand.
   When Chirac faces Mitterrand in the May 8 runoff, the
conservative premier will be challenging the president who
appointed him. One poll released Sunday predicted Mitterrand will
win the runoff with 55 percent of the vote.
   By finishing second Sunday, Chirac improved on his first
presidential run seven years ago. He lost out in the first round in
1981, finishing third behind former President Valery Giscard
d'Estaing and Mitterrand.
   Chirac became premier in March 1986 when the conservatives
ousted the Socialists from control of the National Assembly in
legislative elections. He then formed the new Cabinet and was
formally named premier by Mitterrand.
   Chirac's conservative Rally for the Republic is the largest
party in the center-right government coalition. The energetic
premier has at various times been compared to a bulldozer, a
computer and a robot.
   While Chirac's immense energy and ability to make tough
decisions rapidly is considered a key asset, critics consider it a
liability. There are those who feel he is too impulsive to be
president.
   Chirac is simple in his tastes and acknowledges he likes Western
movies, detective novels, gin rummy and a good glass of beer. He is
the champion of a liberalized free-market economy.
   Chirac was born Nov. 29, 1932, in Paris. He was educated in the
capital, except during World War II period, and spent most of his
holidays at the family's country home in the south-central Correze
region.
   After graduating from the Institute for Political Studies in
Paris, he fought as a lieutenant in the Algerian War. He completed
his studies at the National School for Administration, whose
graduates are destined for the top ranks of the civil service.
   A frequent visitor to the United States, Chirac hitchiked around
America as a youth, working for a time as a fountain clerk at a
Howard Johnson restaurant. He was a protege of the late President
Georges Pompidou, who referred to him as ``my bulldozer.''
   Chirac won his first election in 1967 _ a seat in the National
Assembly from the Correze district. He became a secretary of state
in the Finance Ministry, then moved on to be minister for relations
with Parliament, agriculture minister and interior minister.
   In 1974, at the age of 41, he became premier for the first time
under Giscard d'Estaing.
   Chirac resigned after two years, complaining of a lack of
authority and disagreement over economic policy. In 1977 he was
elected mayor of Paris, a post he continues to hold.
   Instead of supporting Giscard d'Estaing in the runoff against
Mitterrand in the 1981 election, Chirac told his supporters to vote
their conscience, a move believed to have contributed to Giscard
d'Estaing's defeat and a source of bitterness between the centrists
and conservatives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0641EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--ChemicalLeak     04-25 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Chemical Leak,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contained, 1,800 Residents Return Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPPERHILL, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,800 people in three East
Tennessee communities and a nearby Georgia town were allowed to
return home after a cloud from a toxic chemical leak dissipated,
officials said.
   Tennessee Chemical Company workers were searching for the cause
of Sunday's leak.
   About 1.1 tons of sulfur trioxide leaked from an indoor tank
into a building at the company, said Carolyn Merritt, plant
environmental manager. She said it wasn't known how much escaped
from the building.
   Residents of Copperhill, Newtown and Coletown, Tenn., and
McCaysville, Ga., were advised late Sunday that it was safe to
return home, said James Francis, operations director for the
Tennessee Emergency Management Agency.
   Francis and Merritt said they knew of no injuries, but
McCaysville Fire Chief William Wright said some evacuees there
reported burning eyes and itchy throats and feelings of nausea.
   The chemical, which forms sulfuric acid when combined with
moisture, is manufactured at the plant for use in making products
such as detergent, Merritt said.
</TEXT>
