<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0616EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ColumbiaProtest     04-25 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Columbia Protest,0743</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>'60's Protesters: Past and Present</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The old issues were blurred with ambivalence for
some of the '60's revolutionaries who grappled with their past
during a reunion at Columbia University.
   The adrenaline surge they remembered from the former struggle
has been tempered by wistfulness, perhaps, because the dream didn't
last.
   ``It didn't just die; it was profoundly defeated,'' said Tom
Hurwitz. a freelance cinematographer who thought a majority's greed
overcame a minority's ideals.
   ``You become an anachronism _ and a very bitter one _ if you're
not careful,'' said Bettina Berch, who was among the hundreds of
former protesters who last weekend marked the 20th anniversary of a
weeklong student uprising that shut down the Ivy League campus.
   ``One of the things that makes me sad is that people who are
younger than us picked up on the drugs and forgot most of the rest
of what we were saying,'' said Ann Hunter, 40. ``Drugs were our
biggest mistake.''
   During panel discussions, a party and an indoor picnic, they
recalled how about 1,000 people, mostly students, barricaded
themselves inside five buildings the week of April 23, 1968. The
protest drew international attention to the issues of racism, the
Vietnam War and the status quo in general.
   ``This has plunged some of us into a lot of memories that one
still feels ambivalent about,'' said Berch.
   After college, Berch clung to her anti-establishment leanings.
She said she was ``kicked out of academia'' in a tenure fight after
seven years of teaching at Barnard College and is now writing a
book.
   ``In their own terms, we were an aberration, a time when they
lost control,'' she said. ``We became very difficult creatures.''
   Some people refused to discuss their feelings, saying the
reunion had brought back painful memories.
   ``I remember seeing people I knew with arms in slings and heads
in bandages,'' said Ann Hunter, now a law editor.
   Acting Columbia College Dean Henry Coleman was held hostage
during the revolt. Professor Orest Ranum lost a decade's research
when a protester torched his files.
   Later, Ted Gold, a member of the radical Weather Underground,
was killed when a homemade bomb exploded in a Greenwich Village
townhouse in 1970; David Gilbert is serving a 75-year prison
sentence for his role in a 1981 armed car robbery.
   At a panel discussion, an audience of 500 applauded more
youthful memories of the two men.
   Others chose to recall the lighter moments:
   _The wedding of Andrea and Richard Egan in occupied Fayerweather
Hall; Episcopal chaplain William Starr crawled in through the
window.
   _A pie tossed in the face of a Marine colonel recruiting on
campus.
   _Mark Naison, now a historian, taking his Ph.D. oral exam in a
building that was under occupation. He passed the exam and his
professors left through a window.
   ``There was a sense of real life, real peace, real happiness,''
said Hunter. ``There was a feeling of opening up _ people engaging
in real dialogue. People who had gone around like little moles
began to speak up.''
   ``(There was) incredible unity, a kind of physical feeling,''
agreed Hurwitz. ``It was a triumph of morality in a way that
morality has rarely triumphed since.''
   ``It's sort of sweet, like people around the campfire,'' said
Dave Crebs, 33, of Boston, about the reunion.
   The returning alums opted for bluejeans or baggy corduroys, a
few teamed with ties and sports jackets, a few with paunches. There
were plenty of smiles and embraces, and buzzwords like ``the
perversion of capitalism'' surfaced now and then.
   ``Up against the wall!'' hollered members of the audience,
invoking the once-familiar phrase to request that a podium be moved
away from the movie screen at a panel discussion.
   They applauded Abbie Hoffman, who wore a tie-died T-shirt and
sat in the front row _ a prominent bald spot and a red bandana
adorning his frizzy, gray hair.
   Hoffman had helped fuel the strikers' conviction, along with Tom
Hayden, H. Rap Brown, Stokely Carmichael, William Kunstler, Allen
Ginsberg and the Grateful Dead.
   ``It was not a prank or a party, although many have described it
as the best time of their lives,'' said Mark Rudd of Albuquerque,
N.M., who was chairman of Students for a Democratic Society in 1968.
</TEXT>
