<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Stable Against Yen; Stocks Climb In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tokyo share prices rose across the board today and
the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed at a record high. The dollar
remained stable.
   The Nikkei Index of 225 selected issues in the Tokyo Stock
Exchange gained 155.08 points from Saturday's closing to end the
day at 27,213.45, a record closing for the market's main index.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at a moderate 850
million shares.
   Market watchers said the firmer dollar and rising bullish
sentiment in the market helped the stock prices rise in a broad
activities.
   ``There is no particular issues that rose more noticeably than
others,'' said a trader at a major Japanese securities firm, who
spoke on condition of anonymity. ``But there is general sentiment
among the investors that share prices still have more room above
them.''
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at
125.00 yen, up 0.35 yen from Friday's close of 124.65 yen. It had
opened the day at 125.05 yen.
   Traders said investors were cautious ahead of Tuesday's pending
release of U.S. Gross National Product figures for the first
quarter of 1988.
   ``The dollar opened at a relatively high level at 125.05 (yen)
and flctuated only a bit around that level,'' said Hiroaki
Shukuzawa of Sumitomo Bank, a Japanese commercial bank. ``And the
dollar continued to show some strength throughout the day.''
</TEXT>
