<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0617EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OilSpill     04-25 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Spill,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Birds Threatened by Oil Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto OAT1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARTINEZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wildlife rescuers fear hundreds of more
birds could be found coated in some of the 21,000 gallons of crude
oil that spilled along 10 miles of Suisun Bay.
   More than 100 oil-covered birds and other wildlife were taken
Sunday to Berkeley and Walnut Creek to be cleaned following
Saturday's spill just outside the northeastern reach of San
Francisco Bay, where it joins the Sacramento-San Joaquin Delta,
rescuers said.
   ``Oil and marshes don't go together,'' said Al McNabnay, vice
president of Mount Diablo Audubon Society. ``It's doomsday for the
little birds and the big ones.''
   Cleanup crews used vacuum trucks, skimming boats and absorbent
barriers at various sites to mop up the oil, which began leaking
into Peyton Slough and then Suisun Bay from drainage pipes leading
to a storage tank at a Shell Co. refinery.
   Workers mainly tried to contain the thick, gooey slick in the
slough and the adjacent Shell Marsh, a bird habitat.
   ``We've classified this as a major oil spill,'' said Capt. David
Zawadzki, of the Coast Guard's Marine Safety Office.
   Officials warned that the biggest threat to wildlife would come
if any of the oil reached marshes on the northern side of the bay
or wetlands along the San Francisco Bay.
   If the oil reached the bay, it would be virtually impossible to
contain, said Capt. Ryan Broddrick of the state Fish and Game
Department.
   ``It would race up and down the bay with the tide and affect
hundreds of miles of marshland,'' he said.
   The International Berkeley Bird Center reported receiving 55
ducks covered with oil. They were expected to survive. About 40
birds received at the Alexander Lindsay Museum in Walnut Creek also
were in good condition, said Ms. Granados.
   The museum also received two muskrats, pond turtles, ducks and a
great blue heron, a protected species.
   Jay Holcomb, spokesman for the Berkeley center, said he and
others fear they will find hundreds more birds coated in oil today.
   Officials did not know how many birds have been found dead at
the scene. Two were reported to have died at the rescue centers.
   The spill occurred at the peak of the nesting season, said state
wildlife biologist Bob Wright.
   The leak was quickly plugged, said Shell spokeswoman Judith
Morad.
   KGO-TV of San Francisco quoted unidentified Coast Guard
officials as saying the cleanup of boats and the marshes would cost
at least $250,000 and take several days.
</TEXT>
