<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0629EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArmenianDemonstrations     04-25 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Armenian Demonstrations,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Rally In Three Cities To Commemorate Armenian Massacre</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Armenian-Americans rallied in three U.S. cities to
commemorate the 73rd anniversary of a massacre in which Armenians
claim more than 1.5 million of their countrymen were killed by the
Ottoman Empire.
   In Los Angeles, at least 13 protesters were arrested Sunday
after they smashed windows and burned a symbolic Turkish flag
during a protest at the Turkish Consulate, police said.
   Most of the demonstrators had been part of a crowd of 10,000 who
gathered earlier Sunday at Los Angeles City College.
   ``We can't change the tragedy that occurred 73 years ago under
the Ottoman Empire, but we can and we must change the way the world
thinks about that genocide,'' California Lt. Gov. Leo McCarthy told
the crowd.
   Vasken Khodanian, spokesman for the Armenian Human Rights
Council, said Armenians want the Turkish government to recognize
the killings and compensate the survivors.
   Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., told the crowd he has asked
President Reagan to discuss the plight of Armenians during the
summit with Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev. Armenia is a republic
of the Soviet Union.
   ``Let us hear no more of glasnost if ... Gorbachev will not
guarantee Armenian rights. Let us not think that 1915 cannot happen
again,'' he said.
   The Los Angeles Armenian community of 200,000, the largest
outside the Soviet Union, annually commemorates the massacre.
   In New York, more than 2,000 people gathered in Times Square.
   ``We are here to try to get Congress to pass a resolution to
declare April 24 as a Day of Remembrance and to get the U.S. State
Department to drop the word `alleged' when referring to the
Armenian genocide,'' said Sam Azadian, a rally organizer.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch told the crowd: ``The truth is that there
was an attempt by the Ottoman Turks to destroy the Armenians and
thank God they were not successful _ but the truth is they tried.
If we do not remember what happened to the Armenians we will not
remember what happened to the Jews.''
   Many survivors of the massacre were among the Times Square
crowd, including 80-year-old M. Manuelian.
   ``When I was a little boy I remember the Turks coming and taking
everything from us,'' Manuelian said. ``They took my father away
and I never saw him again.''
   Rep. Joseph Kennedy, D-Mass., told nearly 1,000 demonstrators in
Watertown, Mass., that people everywhere had a moral responsibility
to call attention to the tragedy.
   ``Oppression and injustice to one people is a moral loss
affecting all mankind,'' Kennedy said.
   Leaders of the march in the Boston suburb said the protesters
also were expressing their solidarity with the people of the Soviet
region of Nargorno-Karabakh, which Armenians want attached to their
republic.
   Foreign powers have ruled Armenia for most of its history. On
April 24, 1915, more than 200 Armenian intellectuals and political
leaders were slain or deported by the crumbling Turkish Ottoman
Empire, signaling the start of more than eight years of killings.
   Turkish officials have said that 300,000 Armenians perished in
the turmoil of deportations and local reprisals. Some historians
estimated 600,000 died.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0640EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-NewCaledonia     04-25 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Caledonia,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Separatists Defiant After Four Days Of Violence In New Caledonia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-France-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police were ordered to return
gunfire with gunfire as they sought to end four days of violent
clashes with Melanesian separatists in which 27 policemen were
kidnapped and four killed.
   The violence disrupted elections in this French Pacific island
territory in which residents voted for regional candidates and for
a slate of nine candidates running in the first round of France's
presidential contest.
   French Minister for Overseas Territories Bernard Pons arrived in
this archipelago late Sunday and instructed gendarmes to ``respond
to arms with arms.'' Leopold Joredie, a leader of the Kanak
Socialist National Liberation Front, today said the separatists
would continue their ``mobilization.'' Pons' instructions were ``a
declaration of colonial war,'' he added.
   The verbal confrontation followed four days of violence between
police and pro-independence Melanesians that began with the
storming of a police station Friday on the island of Ouvea, 90
miles northeast of the capital of Noumea.
   Twenty-seven gendarmes were taken hostage in the attack and
three of their colleagues were hacked to death with machetes. A
fourth gendarme injured in the attack died on Sunday in a Sydney,
Australia. Three Melanesians were injured.
   The kidnappers demanded the regional elections be canceled and
that police reinforcements be removed from the island. They also
demanded that negotiators be sent from Paris to discuss
independence for the island.
   ``We do not negotiate with terrorists and criminals,'' Pons
said. ``These terrorists will be treated as terrorists.''
   At dawn today, 11 of the hostages were freed, French Defense
Minster Andre Giraud announced in Paris. About 300 police continued
combing a forest in northern Ouvea for the remaining 16 hostages.
   A Kanak Socialist National Liberation Front statement issued in
Paris said the traditional tribal chiefs requested the release ``to
avert reprisals against their tribe and the population'' by the
French army.
   ``France's policy in New Caledonia today is worthy of a banana
republic,'' the statement said.
   Later today, a teen-age Melanesian was fatally shot in a clash
between police and militant separatists, the privately-owned radio
station TUW reported. It said the youth died after French gendarmes
and Kanaks opened fire as the police were leaving their post in the
eastern town of Canala.
   On Sunday, an officer was shot in the stomach while guarding a
polling station in Canala, on the island's east coast.
   Barricades were set up by the separatists to disrupt polling,
ballots were burned, telephone lines were cut and police used tear
gas to disperse crowds of protesters on several islands.
   Thirty-eight of 139 polling stations were closed because of
gunfire and explosions which punctuated the elections as voters
cast double ballots in presidential and regional elections.
   Officials said turnout in the voting, boycotted by militants
seeking independence, was 56.3 percent. Conservative Premier
Jacques Chirac, who finished second behind incumbent President
Francois Mitterrand with 19.9 percent of the vote in France, scored
an overwhelming victory among those casting ballots in New
Caledonia, taking nearly 74.6 percent of the vote.
   Chirac will face Mitterrand in a runoff election on May 8.
   In voting for 48 legislative seats, the pro-French Rally for the
Republic in Caledonia, the territorial branch of Chirac's
neo-Gaullist Rally for the Republic Party, won 35 and the
extreme-right National Front won eight.
   Two small, right-wing parties won three seats, while dissident
separatists won two. Those holding the 48 seats also will assist in
four regional councils.
   Joredie said actions to disrupt Sunday's elections were a
``first step.''
   ``The second step is the second round. We must establish a force
sufficient to open discussions with the new government'' toward
independence, he said.
   ``There are people here who are ready to fight to the end,'' he
said by telephone.
   The new territorial assembly was created by Chirac's government
over the objections of militant native Melanesians, known as
Kanaks, who make up 43 percent of the island group's population of
145,000. Thirty-six percent of the residents are Europeans, while
the rest are mainly Asian or Tahitian.
   Many of the Melanesians are demanding independence for New
Caledonia.
   Police in Noumea said six gendarmes were injured Sunday in
Canala by ``thrown explosives.'' They were taken to a hospital in
Noumea, where one was listed in serious condition.
</TEXT>
