<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady In Calm Trading, Gold Slightly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was steady in calm European trading
today. Gold prices rose slightly.
   The dollar is likely to trade quietly in the coming days and may
move a bit higher until midweek, several dealers said. But a
Frankfurt dealer said he expects a downturn for the dollar close to
the end of the week since there are no substantial factors
supporting the currency.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar rose 0.35 yen to a closing 125.00 yen. Later, in London, it
fell back to 124.55 yen.
   Financial markets in Italy were closed for a national holiday.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
rates:
   _1.6745 West German marks, up from 1.6730
   _1.3835 Swiss francs, down from 1.3840
   _5.6865 French francs, unchanged
   _1.87775 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8770
   _1.2320 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2324
   _1,244.50 lire, unchanged
   In London, it cost $1.8815 to buy one pound, cheaper than
$1.8880 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $448.85 a troy ounce,
down from late Friday's $449. But at midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a higher recommended price of
$449.75.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $449.25, up from $449 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell to $451.13 from Saturday's
$451.58.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.41 a troy
ounce, down from Friday's $6.46.
</TEXT>
