<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0748EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NATO-Shultz     04-25 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO-Shultz,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Says Danish Arms Issue Poses Problem For NATO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
today said NATO faces a problem if Denmark attempts to forbid U.S.
warships with nuclear arms from docking at its ports.
   ``It's up to all of us to measure up to our responsibilities,''
Shultz said after briefing the North Atlantic Council on his talks
last week in Moscow.
   He acknowledged prospects were dim that the United States and
the Soviet Union would conclude a treaty to halve their strategic
nuclear arsenals in time for the May 29-June 2 summit meeting in
Moscow.
   ``It's extremely difficult to get there,'' Shultz said at a news
conference before flying home.
   Shultz said if a strategic arms reduction treaty (START) is not
signed at the Moscow summit, the Reagan administration would keep
pushing in its twilight months for an accord. ``We'll keep at it,
we're not going to stop,'' he said.
   But he disputed suggestions that superpower relations had
slumped since December's signing of a treaty last year to ban
intermediate-range nuclear missiles.
   Citing the Soviet decision to withdraw an estimated 115,000
troops from Afghanistan, Shultz said of East-West relations, ``I
think the picture is one in which we see general progress.''
   After the session with the NATO allies, Shultz met privately
with Uffe Ellemann-Jensen, the Danish foreign minister, to register
his concerns over a Danish Parliament resolution that could bar
U.S. warships with nuclear arms from Danish ports.
   On April 14, Danish socialists pushed a measure in Parliament
that required the government to tell visiting ships that nuclear
arms are barred from Danish ports in peacetime.
   For 30 years, Denmark has barred such ships from its ports, but
the government avoided the provision by not asking ships if they
were carrying nuclear arms.
   After the vote, Denmark's center-right government, which opposed
the measure, called for early elections on May 10.
   Ellemann-Jensen said, ``We want to get a clear message from our
voters they want Denmark to remain a full member of the alliance.''
   Denmark is one of the 16 members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization and among the leaders in pushing for nuclear
disarmament negotiations with the Soviet Union.
   Ellemann-Jensen said he wants to end Denmark's maverick position
within the alliance. ``If we get the signal from the voters we are
asking for, it will be possible to reach a fair solution.''
   Such a solution would mean Denmark sticks by its current ban on
nuclear arms on its soil and simply expects visiting warships to
respect that, he said.
   U.S. and British warships, as a matter of policy, never divulge
if their warships carry nuclear arms. The Danish resolution has led
Britain to suspend visits to Denmark by Royal Navy vessels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0814EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-France-Election 2ndLd-Writethru a0516 04-25 0852</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Election, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0516,0875</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitterrand To Face Chirac In Bid For Second Term</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with party endorsing of Chirac,
exit polls; Pickup 5th graf pvs, `However, Barre ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY6,7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative Premier Jacques Chirac today received
the backing of the centrist Union for French Democracy in his
uphill battle to defeat Socialist President Francois Mitterrand in
the presidential runoff May 8.
   Chirac, a 55-year-old neo-Gaullist, finished a distant second in
first-round voting Sunday to Mitterrand, who is seeking a second
seven-year term.
   Chirac picked up the support of the centrist party's leader,
64-year-old Raymond Barre, Sunday night shortly after polls closed.
Barre, a former premier, finished third in the voting.
   The Union for French Democracy formally endorsed Chirac today,
but it was not known how many of its supporters would vote for
Chirac. Exit polls showed many members of the centrist party might
support Mitterrand in the runoff.
   ``I support him in his fight,'' said Barre of Chirac. ``And I
ask all those who voted for me to vote for him in the second
round.''
   However, Barre did not write Chirac a blank check. ``I count on
him to defend the objectives to which we are particularly attached,
an open and tolerant society that rejects xenophobia, racism and
extremism,'' Barre said.
   His comments were aimed at the candidate of the extreme right,
Jean-Marie Le Pen, who finished just behind Barre and whose
endorsement could be key to a Chirac victory.
   Le Pen, president of the National Front, won 14.5 percent of the
vote _ well above predictions. His campaign speeches included calls
for deporting immigrants and quarantining victims of acquired
immune deficiency syndrome.
   A cartoon in the leftist daily Liberation today showed Le Pen,
dressed as a stormtrooper, standing inside Chirac's open mouth and
saying, ``From now on, nothing in this country gets done without
me.''
   In an editorial, Liberation editor Serge July wrote: ``Two years
under Mitterrand have multiplied discontent with Chirac. Le Pen has
systematically welcomed this, once again making France an
`exceptional' democracy, the only one in the Western world where
the economic and political crisis has engendered an extremist
electorate.''
   Le Pen, 59, said he will tell his supporters at a rally on
Sunday how to vote on May 8.
   An editorial in the conservative daily Le Figaro today said the
task of attracting Le Pen followers without alienating Barre's
constituents was difficult but not impossible.
   ``The right has no reason to call this a lost cause as long as
Chirac can rally around him all the men and women in this country
who don't want Mitterrand's re-election,'' Le Figaro said.
   With 98 percent of the vote counted on Sunday, the 71-year-old
Mitterrand had 33.9 percent, ahead of Chirac, who with 19.9 percent
did not do as well as expected. Barre was third with 16.6 percent.
   A telephone poll conducted by state-run Antenne 2 television
after the results were announced showed that Mitterrand would
defeat Chirac in the runoff, winning 55 percent of the vote.
   In a brief statement, Mitterrand said on Sunday: ``Now the
choice is simple. To all of you who serve France, we have great
tasks before us. Let us rally together, neglecting no effort to win
May 8.''
   The Communist Party, once a significant political force, slumped
to its lowest score in party history, with Andre Lajoinie getting
6.8 percent.
   Rounding out the nine-candidate field were Antoine Waechter, an
ecologist with 3.8 percent; Pierre Juquin, leader of a splinter
Communist reformist group, 2.1 percent; Arlette Laguiller, head of
the Trotskyist Worker Strggle Movement 2 percent; and Pierre
Boussel leader of another Trotskyist group 0.4 percent. Turnout by
France's 38 milion voters was more than 82 percent.
   The choice facing French voters May 8 is more over what kind of
president they want rather than the positions of the two candidates.
   This is Mitterrand's fourth presidential race. He was defeated
by Gen. Charles de Gaulle in 1965 and by Valery Giscard d'Estaing
in 1974 before winning in 1981.
   Chirac, a smiling, energetic campaigner, heads the neo-Gaullist
Rally for the Republic Party.
   He has run the government since the right won the legislative
elections in 1986 in what the French call ``cohabitation'' with a
leftist president.
   The president is the chief of state. The premier, elected by the
legislature, is the head of government. Sunday's vote marked the
first time a president and premier have opposed one another in a
presidential election.
   Discussion in the next few days is likely to focus on a date and
format for a televised Mitterrand-Chirac debate. Mitterrand has
suggested Thursday. Chirac wants a date in the final week of the
campaign.
   A debate is vastly more important to Chirac, who hopes it will
help him make up ground against the president.
   On the issues, both candidates support an open economy and want
to improve France's education system, spending more on technical
training and research.
   On foreign and defense policies, both speak of the need for
France to become more involved in Europe's defenses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
