<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0828EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Caterpillar-Jobs     04-25 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Caterpillar-Jobs,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>12,000 Union Members Vote on Caterpillar No-Strike Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ratification of a limited no-strike clause
will mean more jobs for Caterpillar Inc.'s parts subsidiary, union
and company officials say.
   Voting over several days by some 12,000 members of United Auto
Workers Caterpillar locals nationwide was capped Sunday with
ballots in Peoria and Decatur, where union officials reported large
majorities favoring the no-strike agreement.
   A final official vote tally still must be transmitted from the
union to the company, Gil Nolde, a company spokesman, said late
Sunday.
   The agreement extends indefinitely the contract with Caterpillar
Logistic Services, a parts-distribution subsidiary that covers
about 1,000 employees. Most of the workers are based in Morton,
Ill., with some in Delavan, Ill., and Memphis, Tenn.
   Caterpillar officials, based in Peoria, said they needed the
no-strike clause to attract major contracts for CLS. The subsidiary
was formed in January 1987 to provide warehousing and distribution
services for parts and equipment for companies around the world.
   CLS President James Baldwin said recently the company is ready
to bid on or sign three such contracts in 1988, including one with
the Defense Department. He said the contracts could translate into
thousands of new jobs.
   Union officials had feared that without approval of the limited
no-strike clause, the company might move the jobs to non-union
facilities.
   Under the agreement, CLS parts-distribution workers will remain
on the job even if the UAW and Caterpillar don't reach a master
contract agreement by Sept. 30, and even if manufacturing workers
decide to strike.
   The parts-distribution workers would not be allowed to strike
until after a new central bargaining agreement is reached. They
then would have 60 days to negotiate a new local contract and could
strike at the end of that period.
   ``We are pleased with the vote,'' Jerry Flaherty, Caterpillar
vice president of employee and labor relations, said in a statement
late Sunday. ``We can now talk to potential customers about
continuing, reliable CAT Logistics service from facilities with UAW
employees. It means more jobs, and that's good news.''
   In Peoria, the agreement won 62 percent of the votes cast from
United Auto Workers Local 974, with 837 in favor of it and 519
against, said Tony Green, the local's president. The vote covered
plants in East Peoria, Mapleton and Mossville.
   In Decatur, Local 751 members who participated gave the
agreement an 82 percent vote of approval, said Local President
Larry Solomon. He refused to say how many of his 2,000 members
voted, or to give the actual vote totals.
   ``I think the general sentiment is that if it could mean jobs,
we've got to try it,'' Solomon said.
   Union members in Memphis, Tenn., Denver, Colo., Dallas, Texas,
York, Pa., Davenport, Iowa, and Aurora, Ill., already had ratified
the agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
