<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon     04-25 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Against Car Bombing As Death Toll Reaches 70</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tripoli was brought to a standstill
today as citizens went on strike to protest the nation's worst car
bombing in three years. The death toll in the blast rose to 70.
   Police said 100 people remained hospitalized following
Saturday's blast in a crowded vegetable market in this northern
port city.
   A man wounded in the explosion in the low-income Tabbaneh
district died early today, increasing the total number of dead to
70.
   Schools, shops, cafes, restaurants, cinemas, banks and other
businesses were closed today throughout Lebanon's second largest
city, whose 850,000 people are predominantly Sunni Moslem.
   The strike, on the second day of a 48-hour period of public
mourning, was called by city leaders.
   The explosion claimed the most lives of any car bombing in
Lebanon since March 8, 1985, when 80 people were killed and 250
wounded in an explosion in the Shiite Moslem district of Bir
el-Abed in south Beirut.
   No group has claimed resonsibility for Saturday's blast in
Tripoli, 50 miles north of Beirut.
   Earlier car bombings have been blamed on sectarian strife
stemming from Lebanon's 13-year-old civil war between Moslems and
Christians as well as feuds involving Palestinians, Syrians and
Israelis.
</TEXT>
