<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-Strike     04-25 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Strike,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transit Workers Strike In Western Polish City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bus and tram drivers in the western city
of Bydgoszcz went on strike today, forcing thousands of people to
walk to work and testing Poland's determination to limit wage
increases in the face of steep price rises.
   Workers seeking higher pay listed 10 demands in their
unauthorized job action.
   Negotiations were taking place with a deputy mayor and a deputy
provicial governor at a streetcar depot in the city, said a
spokeswoman at the official transport workers union office.
   The drivers want wages to match those earned in other cities, as
well as some management changes, she said.
   Officials said it appeared there would be no early end to the
walkout. Solidarity Chairman Lech Walesa said he was planning to
travel from his home in Gdansk to Bydgoszcz to offer support.
   Prices in Poland have gone up 42 percent since the beginning of
the year, the result of planned increases mandated by a government
economic reform program.
   The increases prompted nationwide pressure for pay raises among
workers. Government figures said wages rose on average 45 percent
by April 1.
   Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, alarmed by the trend,
last month warned enterprise managers they could be fired if they
were too generous with their payrolls, thereby fueling inflation.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said the unauthorized walkout
at the Provincial Transportation Enterprise in Bydgoszcz began
today at 6 a.m.
   ``The first shift refused to work,'' Urban said in a telephone
interview. ``I can't say it is the biggest strike (in recent
years). I can't even call it a strike. They didn't declare a strike
and it has no organized form.''
   Second-shift workers also refused to begin work at 2 p.m., said
a spokeswoman at Bydgoszcz transit headquarters.
   A parked bus blocked the gates of the main depot but there were
few other outward signs of discord, said a Solidarity activist in
the city, Ryszard Helak.
   Urban said the demands included a $15 a month salary raise, plus
a eight cent increase in the 38-cent-an-hour wage.
   The union spokeswoman, who would not give her name, said the
transit system employs about 2,800 workers. Urban said 229 buses
and 60 trams were idled in the city of 375,000 people, located 150
miles northwest of Warsaw.
   ``It looks like it will take a long time to resolve it,'' said
Halina Jarminowska, a spokeswoman for the Bydgoszcz Voivoidship,
the provincial government.
   ``People had to walk to work this morning,'' she said.
``Factories which have buses drove people from the night shift home
and then took those coming for the morning shift. Those working in
offices, youths going to school, had to walk.''
   Helak said Solidarity did not organize the strike.
   Walesa on Sunday said large-scale strikes might be needed to
spur reform in Poland.
   The spokeswoman at the official union office in Bydgoszcz, one
of the unions put together by the government after Solidarity was
banned in the 1981 martial law crackdown, said the strike took her
organization ``by surprise.''
   ``It was an initiative of the drivers,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
