<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Hammer     04-25 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Hammer,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hammer Signs New Joint Venture Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. industrialist Armand Hammer, whose huge
joint venture coal mine in China has been plagued by disputes,
signed a contract today to build a new joint venture coal
preparation plant.
   He also signed an agreement for his Occidental Petroleum Corp.
of Los Angeles to sell two Chinese companies technology to produce
phosphoric acid.
   Hammer, 89, refused to disclose the dollar value of the new
projects and insisted Occidental is not losing money on the $800
million Antaibo coal mine in north China, the largest and most
high-profile U.S.-Chinese joint venture.
   Occidental has a 25 percent share in the mine, 230 miles
southwest of Beijing in Shanxi province.
   It opened with great fanfare in September but has been operating
well below capacity because of mechanical problems and disputes
with the Chinese partners over the price at which the coal should
be sold.
   ``We consider the problems we have had there minor problems,''
Hammer told a news conference after signing the two new contracts
at Beijing's luxious Diaoyutai state guesthouse.
   ``Those are the start-up problems you have with every project,''
he said. ``These will be settled and we will be at full production
we estimate by the end of the year.''
   Asked about the financial cost of the disputes and delays,
Hammer said, ``We don't figure we've lost anything.''
   He insisted the mine can be profitable once it begins producing
at its capacity of 15 million tons of raw coal per year, even if
coal prices don't recover from their current low of about $20 per
ton.
   China's official Xinhua News Agency recently reported design
problems with the mine's washing plant, which it said left too much
moisture in the coal. It blamed the mine's low production level on
the washing plant problem.
   There also have been reports of personal feuding between the
Occidental and Chinese technical staff at the mine.
   Hammer said his current visit to China was not a
trouble-shooting one.
   ``I'm not here because of those problems,'' he said. ``They are
being straightened out without me. I came because the Chinese have
invited me to celebrate my 90th birthday.'' Hammer turns 90 on May
21.
   Chinese President Yang Shangkun gave a banquet in Hammer's honor
tonight and Premier Li Peng invited him to a banquet Tuesday.
   Hammer said he hopes to sell Antaibo coal to South Korea, which
has no diplomatic relations with China but conducts a growing
indirect trade with it.
   He said South Korean officials have invited him to visit and
that he plans to bring up the subject of selling coal.
   Occidental officials said one of the contracts signed today
calls for construction of a coal preparation plant in central
China's Henan province with capacity to process 900,000 metric tons
of raw coal for coking. No date was given for construction to begin.
   Occidental holds a 55 percent share of the venture, while the
China Kang Hua Development Corp., a newly formed company under
Henan provincial control, has 45 percent.
   The other contract calls for use of Occidental technology at
four phosphoric acid plants to be built in China. The China Wuhan
Chemical Engineering Corp. and China National Chemical Construction
Co. were the purchasers.
</TEXT>
