<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GrapeCaper 1stLd-Writethru a0465 04-25 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Grape Caper, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0465,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pennies Worth of Grapes Land Shopper In Jail</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs to include mention of Michigan case earlier this
month.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shopper landed in jail after an off-duty
policeman spotted him popping grapes in his mouth as he walked
through a supermarket produce section.
   ``They're taking me for eating grapes!'' Arthur Culberth yelled
as he was taken in handcuffs from a Winn-Dixie grocery store in the
predominantly black and impoverished Liberty City section of Miami.
   Culberth, 55, was charged Saturday with petty theft and
resisting arrest without violence. After spending the night in
jail, he was released with a promise to appear for a court date.
   Culberth, a plumber, said he broke open a $1.65 package of
grapes and plucked a couple into his mouth as he shopped with his
wife and stepson.
   Off-duty Miami policeman Roger Smith, who moonlights as a
security guard at the store, saw Culberth and told him he would
have to pay at once.
   ``He was given a chance to pay for the grapes and refused,''
Smith said. ``I had no other alternative.''
   But Culberth's wife, Linda, said the couple planned to pay for
the fruit when their $30 order was rung up.
   ``How in the world is it petty theft if we're shopping? It's
wrong, real wrong,'' she said of the arrest. ``We always pay our
bills.''
   Miami policeman Erol Stewart, who also moonlights at the store,
said Winn-Dixie has arrested about eight people in the past two
years for refusing to pay for food they had eaten.
   Earlier this month in Jackson, Mich., 52-year-old Eli Bradley
Jr. was charged with larceny from a building for allegedly eating
two pounds of grapes in a grocery store. Bradley, who could be
sentenced to four years in prison if convicted of the felony, said
he bought $14 worth of fruit in the store, and admitted he may have
sampled only one or two grapes.
   The prosecutor in Jackson said he filed the felony charge,
instead of misdemeanor shoplifting _ which carries a 90-day jail
term _ because several repeat shoplifters he's prosecuted have
received probation.
</TEXT>
