<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1000EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Brezhnev     04-25 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Brezhnev,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Strip Brezhnev's Name From City Square</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet authorities have stripped the name of
former President Leonid I. Brezhnev from a city square in the
capital of the republic of Kazakhstan.
   Brezhnev's name was dropped from the square in Alma Ata, the
biggest city in the Central Asian republic.
   An order from the Communist Party Central Committee, the
Presidium of the Supreme Soviet and the government's Council of
Ministers dated April 1 was included in a booklet of latest
official orders received today by The Associated Press.
   The order did not indicate if a new name was chosen for the
square. It said the workers of Alma Ata had asked that Brezhnev's
name be removed from the square.
   A city, some neighborhoods, numerous factories, a tank division,
a military academy and other areas and institutions were named
after the Soviet president following his death in 1982.
   But, under the leadership of Soviet Communist Party chief
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, Brezhnev has been blamed for a period of
stagnation and corruption in Soviet society.
   As a result, his name has been dropped in several instances.
   In January, a city of 460,000 people and a region of Moscow were
stripped of Brezhnev's name.
   Officials announced in February that Brezhnev's son-in-law, Yuri
Churbanov, would be tried for corruption.
   The weekly newspaper Nedelya renewed the attack on Brezhnev in
its latest weekend edition, charging that Brezhnev and members of
his circle gave each other valuable jewelry, limousines and furs.
   Ethnic rioting broke out in Alma Ata in December 1986 after
Gorbachev protege Dinmukamed Kunaev, an ethnic Kazakh, was replaced
by Gennady Kolbin, a Russian. At least two people died in the
rioting, and shops and cars were burned.
</TEXT>
