<DOCNO> AP880425-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1008EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Minorities     04-25 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Minorities,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zhao Ziyang Says Tibetan Separatists Will Fail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang said
today that China will deal forcefully with separatist movements,
such as the one in Tibet, and that such movements are doomed to
failure.
   ``Nowadays, a very small number of people are attempting to
split our motherland,'' Zhao said at a conference of 4,000 people
representing China's 56 nationalities.
   ``It is not difficult to see that they are not representing the
interests of our people, and they are only the agents of some
anti-Chinese foreign forces. Their vain attempt of splitting China
cannot possibly be realized.''
   Zhao did not mention Tibet by name but it was clear that he was
referring to the faraway province.
   The Tibetan capital of Lhasa erupted in pro-independence riots
last fall and again in March. The bloody protests were led by
Buddhist monks loyal to the exiled spiritual leader the Dalai Lama.
   Tibetan authorities have allowed almost no foreign journalists
into Tibet and released few details of action taken against
rioters. Sources in Lhasa have reported hundreds of arrests
following the March disturbance. Chinese officials say five people
died in the March riots. Unconfirmed reports have put the death
toll as high as 24.
   Zhao said China must carry out a two-pronged policy to promote
the interests of minority nationalities and ``forcefully oppose and
deal with any separatist efforts.'' His comments were carried by
the official Xinhua News Agency.
   Zhao told the gathering that discrimination against minority
ethnic groups is a problem everywhere in the world except China.
   He claimed China has banned discrimination against minorities,
protects them by law and grants them privileges not available to
Han Chinese, who comprise 92 percent of China's 1 billion people.
   Chinese minorities, which include 55 ethnic groups, were often
the victims of persecution during the first three decades of
Communist rule in China, when the government tried to eliminate
religious worship and local languages and customs.
   In the past decade Beijing has tried to redress some of the
wrongs of the past and now encourages minorities, many who live in
sparsely populated, strategic areas of western China, to retain
their traditions.
   Zhao is the author of a plan to give priority to economic
development of coastal China.
   There has been concern that Zhao's plan would further widen the
income gap between the coast, which is mostly Han Chinese, and the
interior where many minorities live in pockets of poverty.
   Zhao urged minorities to use foreign capital, science and
technology to develop their economies and compete in national and
international markets.
</TEXT>
