<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BurningMan     04-25 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burning Man,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Dies After Setting Himself on Fire In Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MACON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police and worshippers who watched in horror
as a man set himself on fire during an evening church service
remain puzzled over why he soaked his clothing in gasoline, then
walked down the aisle in flames.
   Willie J. Boone, 41, of Macon died Sunday morning, about eight
hours after he torched himself at the Friendship Baptist Church. He
suffered burns over all of his body, said Bibb County Deputy
Coroner James Fain. Boone died at Medical Center of Central Georgia.
   The Rev. J.L Mills, pastor of the church, helped extinguish the
fire and told Boone to go back outside and get some air. There was
a lot of smoke in the church from the fire, and Mills said it was
making it difficult to breathe.
   ``He got up nice and easy, went out to the front and
collapsed,'' Mills said.
   The pastor said that Boone never hollered or cried _ he only
muttered, ``It's all right.''
   Police said they found an antifreeze container that apparently
held gasoline which Boone used to douse himself before lighting the
fire.
   Mills said a musical program was almost over when ``I saw the
children looking curious and I looked back'' from the first row.
   ``I saw this young man coming up the middle aisle ablaze of
fire,'' Mills said.
   Many in the church became hysterical, the pastor said. He added
that Boone was a stranger to the 40 to 50 people in the church
sanctuary.
   Police Capt. Robert Hernandez said investigators were continuing
to check into Boone's background Sunday, but had not come up with
any possible explanation for his actions.
</TEXT>
