<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ElevatorExplosion     04-25 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Elevator Explosion,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigation Of Elevator Explosions Begins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOLIET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators say it could be days before
they determine the cause of the explosions that killed five workers
and reduced a grain elevator complex to rubble.
   ``The cause is still undetermined,'' Joliet Fire Chief George
Plese said of the blasts Friday at the ADM Growmark granary on the
banks of the Des Plaines River.
   Rescue workers labored for 29 hours in search of three of the
victims, whose bodies were recovered Saturday, he said.
   The state fire marshal's office and the U.S. Occupational Safety
and Health Administration are investigating the two explosions,
Plese said.
   Dick Burket, a spokesman for Archer-Daniel-Midland Co., said
late Sunday the company's insurance and safety people also have an
investigation under way.
   Plese said OSHA impounded much of the structural steel from the
four silos destroyed by the blast.
   The last three of the five victims were found crumpled in the
basement of the granary, crushed by the wave of corn and soybeans
that swept them there, the chief said.
   They were identified as Donald E. Zack of Joliet, Daniel
McLaughlin, 18, of Manhattan and Michael Dupuis, 23, of
Bourbonnais, said Will County Deputy Coroner William Ferguson.
   ``As far as I can tell from the preliminary examinations at the
scene there was no burning on these bodies,'' Ferguson said
Saturday. ``Indications are that they would have died instantly
from the injuries.''
   The bodies of Mark Stewart, 20, of Princeton, and Dale Brent
Slatton, 28, of Newark, were found Friday.
   Officials ruled out a witness' report that the blasts blew a
worker off a barge and into the river, and a search of the river
was called off, Plese said.
   ``This is just one of those tragic things that should never
happen,'' said Dan Stewart, whose son was killed.
   For the Slatton family, the loss came on the heels of another
son's death in an auto accident less than a year ago.
   ``It's totally devastating to have three sons and to lose two,''
said the victim's mother, Carol.
   Three other people, including the elevator's manager and
assistant manager, were injured in the blasts. Only one, trucker
James Rayburn, remained hospitalized Sunday.
   Rayburn, who was pinned in his truck for 40 minutes when it was
buried with debris, was in fair condition at St. Joseph's Medical
Center in Joliet, said nursing supervisor Ida Dercoli.
   The blasts turned the 100-foot silos into mounds of twisted
steel, reinforced concrete and 70,000 bushels of corn and soybeans,
Plese said.
   ``We had to dig through all of that to get at these people who
were buried,'' he said by phone Sunday from Joliet.
   Local construction trade unions, trucking and wrecking companies
and nearby fire departments volunteered in the rescue effort, Plese
said.
</TEXT>
