<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Agnew     04-25 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Agnew,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spiro Agnew Loses Supreme Court Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Vice President Spiro T. Agnew lost a
Supreme Court appeal today in a lawsuit alleging he was cheated out
of more than $2 million for arranging a deal between a defense
contractor and the Argentine government.
   The justices, without comment, refused to order the setting
aside of more than $340,000 in a special fund Agnew and another
businessman would receive if they win the lawsuit.
   Agnew, an international business consultant, charged in a 1986
suit filed in federal court in New York City that he was cheated
out of a commission he earned for winning a telecommunications
contract for Aydin Corp. of Delaware.
   Agnew said Aydin Corp. and Alicanto S.A., an Argentine company,
retained him to help open doors in 1980 with the Argentine ruling
military junta.
   His suit said Alicanto was to recieve a 15 percent commission
from Aydin and then pay Agnew between one-third and one-half that
amount, more than $2 million.
   But Agnew alleged that Alicanto instead paid a $3.65 million
bribe to a ``bagman'' who passed it on to Argentine Air Force Gen.
Lami Dozo to help win the contract.
   Agnew said Alicanto then lied to him, claiming the deal fell
through when in fact Aydin won a $57 million contract to provide a
microwave communications system to the Argentine Air Force.
   Agnew and William H. Woolverton Jr., a former vice president of
Alicanto, are suing Alicanto and its president, William H. Shaw.
   U.S. District Judge Jack B. Weinstein last year refused to order
Alicanto and Shaw to place more than $340,000 in a fund that would
go to Agnew and Woolverton if they win their suit.
   In their appeal to the Supreme Court, Agnew and Woolverton said
Alicanto's assets now may be ``moved out of the United States and
most likely out of Argentina'' so that they will be out of reach of
any court judgment.
   Agnew, elected vice president in 1968 when Richard M. Nixon
headed the Republican ticket, resigned in 1973 after he was accused
of accepting bribes and kickbacks while a Baltimore County
executive in Maryland.
   He pleaded no contest to tax evasion in that case.
   Agnew said in his suit against Alicanto and Shaw that he was
cheated out of the commission by people who believed his past
reputation would bar him from winning any case in court.
   Agnew said he was told by a lawyer who worked for Aydin that
``nobody would believe him if he sued (because of) prior events
related to his holding public office.''
   The case is Agnew vs. Alicanto, 87-1464.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
