<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WilliamsTakeover 1stLd-Writethru a0547 04-25 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Williams Takeover, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0547,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Williams College Administrators Met With Protesters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with talks resuming, picking up
4th graf pvs, `The students ....'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Williams College administrators
resumed talks today with protesters who are occupying a dean's
office and demanding more attention to the education of racial
minorities.
   Talks began at 7 a.m., barely six hours after negotiators broke
from a previous meeting, college spokesman James Kolesar said.
   The two sides had met for two hours Sunday afternoon, with
Williams President Francis C. Oakley taking part, then reconvened
at 9:15 p.m. and talked into the early morning hours.
   Representatives of both sides called the Sunday talks
``constructive.''
   The students, members of a group called the Coalition Against
Racist Education, took over the Jenness House on Friday morning and
issued 13 demands that included the hiring by the prestigious
liberal arts school of more minority faculty members and the
admitting of more minority students, while incorporating more
minority perspectives into the curriculum.
   ``They're responsive to us,'' said one of the student
negotiators, Monique Waddell, 19, a sophomore from New York City,
referring to the administration representatives that included Dean
Stephen Fix and Provost Neil Grabois.
   ``The meeting is showing some progress,'' she said. ``There's
not a sense of negativity. The energy that is flowing is
constructive, so that's good.''
   She added, ``It's just a matter of getting them to understand us
better.''
   The talks were conducted in the physics building, adjacent to
the Jenness House.
   Minority students comprise 13 percent of the 2,000-member
student body. The protesters include students from Asia, the
Caribbean and the Pacific islands as well as American blacks and
Hispanics.
   About 10 percent of the 278-member faculty belongs to a minority
group.
   Sunday, administration officials and the protesters discussed
three of the demands. These were: establishing full scholarships
for low-income minority students from urban areas; creating a
campus cultural center for minority groups, and hiring a special
assistant to the president to recruit more minority teachers.
   School spokesman Jim Kolesar said the administration would not
comment specifically on the talks but he called the discussions
``constructive.''
   While the negotiations were under way, a young white man was
seen taping a sign saying ``Quality, Not Quotas'' on a window at
Jenness, with the words facing inside the house. It was later
removed.
   Freshman Jillian Charles, who spent Saturday night inside the
house, said she heard rocks being thrown at the building.
   Jenness House, which serves as the dean's office while the main
administration building is being renovated, is tucked in a corner
of the campus, making the protest less conspicuous. While some of
the hundreds of parents visiting over the Parents' Weekend
expressed concern and even support for the protest, they largely
spent the weekend undisturbed by it, said Ellen Berek, news
director for the school.
</TEXT>
