<DOCNO> AP880425-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-AirSpace     04-25 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Air Space,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Ruling on Property Owners' Rights in Wyoming Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling
that property owners' rights are not violated when they are
required to remove structures that could interfere with low-flying
planes.
   The court, citing the lack of a ``substantial federal
question,'' rejected an appeal by a Cheyenne, Wyo., man fined $200
a day for refusing to trim a 48-foot cottowood tree on his property.
   Terry Rogers, the tree owner, said a Cheyenne ordinance imposing
a height limit on structures near the local airport is
unconstitutional because it takes property without just
compensation.
   His tree, at 48 feet, would have to be cut to 25 or 30 feet to
comply with the ordinance. Rogers said that would kill the tree,
costing him $2,064.
   After he lost an earlier challenge to the ordinance's
constitutionality, Rogers was found guilty of violating city law
and fined $200 a day beginning Nov. 20, 1986.
   Court documents did not indicate the total fine assessed against
Rogers.
   The Wyoming Supreme Court last December upheld the fine,
rejecting claims that the air space above Rogers' property belonged
to him.
   The state court also rejected Rogers' argument that because the
tree was in place prior to enactment of the ordinance he was
entitled to keep it.
   The state court said the local law ``allows for the continuance
of a non-conforming use. It does not allow the expansion of a
pre-existing non-conforming use.''
   ``In other words,'' the state court said, ``a violation occurred
if the tree was allowed to grow higher than it stood in October
1974 when the ordinance was adopted.''
   The tree has grown some 18 feet since the fall of 1974, the
state court said.
   The justices in 1986 rejected a related appeal by Rogers.
   The case is Rogers vs. Cheyenne, 87-1462.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
