<2ND_LINE>PM-Syria-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0540,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Arafat, Assad Meet In Damascus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs, Assad, Arafat meet. PICKS up 4th graf
`Arafat was accompanied ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hafez Assad today met PLO Chief
Yasser Arafat at the presidential palace, only the second time the
Arab leaders have come face-to-face since Arafat was expelled from
Syria five years ago.
   Presidential spokesman Jibran Kourieh said Assad and Arafat
began meeting at 5 p.m. (10 a.m. EDT) at Assad's Mohajirine palace.
   The session follows the assassination of Arafat's top deputy _
Khalil Wazir _ and was seen as a step toward a reconciliation
between Assad and Arafat.
   Assad and Arafat last met at the Arab summit last November in
Amman, Jordan. The Palestine Liberation Organization chief was
accompanied to today's meeting by seven senior aides, Kourieh said.
   Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa of Syria also attended the
meeting, the presidential spokesman said.
   Arafat earlier met with other Palestinian leaders to prepare for
the crucial session with Assad.
   George Habash, leader of the Marxist Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, said that three-hour meeting ``touched on
all issues'' Arafat would discuss with Assad.
   Arafat arrived in Damascus from Libya on Sunday.
   Arafat was accompanied by Col. Mustafa Kharroubi, a senior aide
to Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi. Syria's official media
reported Kharroubi met with Assad today, but gave no details.
   Gadhafi and President Hadli Benjedid of Algeria had accelerated
efforts to reconcile Assad and Arafat after Wazir was assassinated
in Tunisia on April 16, apparently by an Israeli commando unit.
   Wazir, 52, was buried in Damascus last Wednesday. Arafat, his
long-time comrade and co-founder of the guerrilla movement, did not
attend because of his feud with Assad.
   A reconciliation between Arafat and Assad, two of the key
figures in the Arab conflict with Israel, would do much to forge
Arab unity.
   Arab leaders have been trying for years to get Assad and Arafat
to make up their differences. While Wazir's assassination was a
severe blow to the PLO, most Arab leaders believe it has
accelerated efforts to reconcile Syria and the PLO.
   In addition to Habash, today's PLO meeting at the Rawda guest
palace included Nayef Hawatmeh, secretary-general of the Democratic
Front for the Liberation of Palestine; Suleiman Najjab, leader of
the Palestinian Communist Party and Salah Khalaf, the No. 2 man in
Fatah, the largest PLO faction.
   Hawatmeh told reporters that ``we all agreed that this a rare
opportunity'' for reconciliation with Syria, which expelled Arafat
in June 1983 amid a mutiny within the PLO inspired by Damascus.
   He said there was a ``unanimous belief'' among the Palestinians
that ``this opportunity would lead to the restoration of warm
relations between Syria and the PLO'' and bolster the 4{-month-old
Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   Wazir was popular with both Arafat loyalists and pro-Syrian
dissidents. Palestinian factions, divided since the PLO-Syrian
rift, all denounced his killing and vowed revenge.
   Wazir, known as Abu Jihad, was the apparent mastermind of the
Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied territories.
</TEXT>
