<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSFoundation     04-25 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Foundation,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Foundation Plans New Organization To Help AIDS Patients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ford Foundation is organizing and helping
finance an umbrella organization to give financial assistance to
AIDS patients and their families, a newspaper reports.
   The foundation, the nation's wealthiest, was expected to
announce today the formation of the National-Community AIDS
Partnership, The New York Times said.
   The partnership is designed to pool the resources of the Ford
Foundation, corporate donors and other philanthropies to help local
organizations across the country provide housing, day care,
counseling, and education for victims of acquired immune deficiency
syndrome and their families.
   The announcement was expected at the annual conference of the
Council on Foundations, which opens today in Los Angeles, the
newspaper said.
   In addition to providing funds, the Ford Foundation hopes that
its own status will attract organizations and corporations that
have been reluctant to become involved in AIDS funding.
   Shepard Forman, a Ford Program director, acknowledged that major
foundations have been slow to respond to the AIDS crisis.
   ``I feel we all should have been there with an appropriate
response five years ago but we were not,'' he said. ``We're there
now and the question is how do we get others to join us.''
   The Ford Foundation will make an initial contribution of $2
million to the partnership. Smaller sums will be contributed by
other philanthropies in the partnership, including the Kaiser
Family Foundation, $200,000; the Rockefeller Foundation and the
Gannett Foundations, $100,000 each; and the Xerox Foundation and
the Aetna Life and Casualty Foundation, $50,000 each annually for
two years.
   The partnership will be administered by the National AIDS
Network, a Washington group which helps 450 community-based AIDS
organizations.
   Community foundations in nine regions have agreed to raise from
$100,000 to $500,000 to match contributions made by the national
partners for a total of about $8 million. More community groups are
expected to join the partnership later this year.
   The nine regions are the New York-New Jersey area; southern and
northern California; the Southwest; Hartford, Conn.; Washington,
D.C.; Atlanta; Minnesota; and Cleveland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
