<HEAD>Six Arrested At Rocky Flats Nuclear Protest Reunion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six activists were arrested for blocking a
railroad track at the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant during a
reunion of protesters who were at a massive demonstration 10 years
ago.
   ``There wasn't any planned civil disobedience. It was all
spontaneous,'' activist Ellen Klaver said of Sunday's protest.
``The attitude of the police had a lot to do with it. They were so
rigid.''
   The demonstrators marched 10 miles from Boulder to Rocky Flats,
where about 150 people who gathered on the tracks for then, pitched tents
and danced the ``Hokey Pokey.'' Many had
participated in protests that began A 10-year
reuniopril 29, 1978, when dozens
were arrested.
   Longtime peace activist Daniel Ellsberg told the small reunion
Sunday the militaristic ``cold war'' mentality that made Ronald
Reagan president eight years ago is receding before a resurgence of
pacifism.
   The plant, 16 miles northwest of Denver, makes plutonium
triggers for nuclear weapons. It is operated by Rockwell
International Corp. for the U.S. Department of Energy.
   The protesters were ordered to leave five times Sunday by a
guard. Most backed away from the tracks, but the six continued to
chant and dance.
   ``Most people do not support nuclear weapons,'' one activist
shouted at the guards. ``You have no right to be here. You're
participating in murder.'. ``I'd never done anything like that before.
We
really got to know each other because of our common cause. We were
very supportive and loving.''
   Dorskind said he is not as impulsive today as he was then. ``I'm
much more careful about the decisions I make. I'm not ready to turn
my head so fast, just because somebody gives a liberal rap.''
