<2ND_LINE>PM-Colors Shooting, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0526,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Fatally Shot While Standing In Line To See Gang Movie</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to CORRECT that shooting is not first
violent incident linked to movie, but is first resulting in death;
picks up 6th graf pvs, `The suspect ....'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man wearing gang colors was shot
to death by a man wearing a rival gang's insignia while waiting in
line to see ``Colors,'' the first fatality linked to the much
criticized movie about out-of-control street gangs.
   Police were seeking the suspect, a man in his 20s, who fatally
shot the 19-year-old victim Sunday afternoon while he stood in line
at a cinema in this community east of San Francisco.
   The movie depicts the rival Los Angeles-based Crips and Bloods
gangs. The suspect was wearing a red handkerchief, as do members of
the Bloods, while the victim had on a blue handkerchief, signifying
the Crips, authorities said.
   The bullet hit a 17-year-old girl after it passed through the
victim's head, but she was not seriously injured, said Stockton
Police Lt. David Swim.
   ``Colors'' opened nationwide April 15 at 425 theaters amid
protests and tight security following predictions of audience
violence.
   In Los Angeles, arrests were made after minor scuffles at two
theaters on the film's opening night. And in Colma, south of San
Francisco, police ordered a downtown theater to stop showing the
movie because crowds nearly got out of hand opening night.
   Sunday's incident began when the victim was standing in line
with his brother-in-law and girlfriend, said Swim, reading a
statement.
   The suspect and at least two male companions drove by the
theater, then returned and parked, said Swim. The suspect got out
and approached the victim and asked, ``Are you a ricket?''
   Swim said ricket is a derogatory term for Crips members.
   Swim said the victim's girlfriend stepped between the two and
told the suspect they did not want any trouble. The suspect then
turned toward the car when his two companions began fighting with
the victim's brother-in-law.
   As the victim went to the aid of his brother-in-law, the suspect
returned and pointed a gun at him, said Swim. The victim began to
run, but the suspect fired one shot that hit the victim in the head.
   ``Colors,'' starring Sean Penn and Robert Duvall, opened to
large crowds at many theaters April 15, but little of the
anticipated violence materialized.
   The Guardian Angels, the self-styled citizen crime-fighters,
were among those claiming the film glorified gangs and would prompt
violence.
   Charles O. Glenn, executive vice president of Orion Pictures,
the film's distributor, recently defended the movie.
   ``If there is anything this picture does not do, it does not
glorify gangs or gang violence.'' Glenn said.
   Authorities have kept a presence at theaters in Los Angeles and
other places with known gangs during screening of the movie.
   In Los Angeles, three people were killed over the weekend in
gang-related attacks not connected to the movie, including an
alleged gang member who was killed Sunday after he shot a sheriff's
deputy in the back.
   The Los Angeles County sheriff's deputy was saved by a
bulletproof vest, said Deputy Roxanna Schuchman. The deputy then
returned fire and killed the alleged gang member, whose name was
not released.
   In other gang violence, a 17-year-old man was stabbed to death
Friday night and another man was fatally wounded in a drive-by
shooting early Saturday, police said.
</TEXT>
