<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChurchBan     04-25 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Church Ban,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman, Child Barred From Entering Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church officials turned away a woman and her
troubled 9-year-old son from services at an Episcopal church,
enforcing a court order barring them because of the boy's
disruptive behavior.
   ``This is God's church, not your church,'' Sheryl Geartz quietly
told the half-dozen men who blocked the door Sunday at Grace
Episcopal Cathedral.
   Ms. Geartz prayed aloud before leaving: ``Dear Lord, we know
this is your house. We ask you to open your doors to let us in. In
Jesus' name, we pray.''
   She then took her son and 7-year-old daughter to another church.
   The cathedral had obtained a restraining order in Shawnee County
District Court last week that barred her and her son Jason on the
grounds that the boy disrupts services and his mother will not
control him.
   The church's petition for a restraining order described Jason's
``disruptive and dangerous activities,'' such as pulling the fire
alarm, making loud noises, throwing objects and destroying property.
   Ms. Geartz admits that Jason has misbehaved, but she says he has
emotional problems and that taking him to church every week has
improved his conduct.
   The dean of Grace Cathedral, the Very Rev. Robert R. Shahan,
said at a news conference later Sunday that the church worked with
Ms. Geartz for seven months to try to restrain Jason.
   ``The level of disturbance moved from being merely annoying to
being utterly intolerable,'' said Shahan.
   Some church members stopped attending services or stopped taking
communion because of the disruptions, Shahan said.
   ``We were faced with a situation in which one person had
determined her needs were paramount to the needs of the entire
congregation,'' he said. ``Our duty, as we see it, must be to the
congregation as a whole.''
   Church officials were unable to find a solution Ms. Geartz would
accept to control the boy, Shahan said. The dean, the head
clergyman of the cathedral, said he expected criticism from people
who would ask, ``Is getting a restraining order what a loving,
caring Christian community does?''
   ``The answer is, this is what a loving, caring Christian
community does, after seven months of trying to help, to no
avail,'' he said.
   Ms. Geartz said she was aware that she was under court order not
to appear at Grace Cathedral, but she said she went to take a stand
for people who are emotionally disturbed.
   ``Where will it stop?'' she said. ``If they ban my son from this
church, are they going to ban other children and even adults who
have emotional problems?''
   Ms. Geartz said she would pray before deciding whether to
attempt to attend services next week.
</TEXT>
