<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Parrot-Fire     04-25 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Parrot-Fire,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parrot Succumbs To Teflon Fumes After Alerting Owner Of Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An African gray parrot alerted her owner
by calling out his name when a Teflon-coated pan caught fire, but
died from the fumes after the fire was extinguished.
   A veterinarian said burning Teflon has been found to cause
respiratory arrest in birds.
   Chris Barnes, a University of Colorado student, said 7-year-old
Coco died exactly one year after his mother, Barbara Barnes Givens
of Aurora, gave him the bird as a birthday present.
   Barnes, 21, who shares a house with five other students in
Boulder, said one roommate arrived home early Saturday and put a
pot of water on the stove to make spaghetti.
   Barnes said the roommate went to his room and made a telephone
call, then fell asleep while the water boiled away.
   Barnes said about 4:30 a.m. he heard Coco screeching in the
living room, next to the kitchen, and then calling his name.
   He got up and found the kitchen was filled with smoke and the
Teflon lining of the red-hot pot was aflame.
   Barnes said he put out the fire and aired out the room, then
checked on Coco and found that the bird appeared to be all right.
But several minutes later, he said, he found the bird on the floor
of her cage.
   Coco was valued at $1,000, could whistle the theme from the
movie ``The Good, the Bad and the Ugly,'' and had a life expectancy
of more than 100 years.
   ``This is really tragic,'' Barnes said. ``I was going to put her
into my will'' to provide for future care.
   Veterinarian William Dernell said Coco's death is typical of
other bird deaths involving Teflon cookware.
   He said an Illinois veterinarian has found that burning Teflon
on cookware can release noxious fumes that cause respiratory arrest
in birds.
   ``It doesn't take much,'' Dernell said. ``In some cases no
burning has to take place. If the Teflon gets hot enough, noxious
fumes can be released and respiratory arrest (in birds) can occur.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
