<DOCNO> AP880425-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Korea     04-25 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Korea,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. To Seek Increased Korean Support for U.S. Troops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is asking the government of
South Korea to give more money for the support of 43,000 American
troops stationed there, an administration source said today.
   A team of Pentagon and State Department officials will
officially raise the request in June at the next round of regularly
scheduled talks with South Korea in Seoul, said the official. He
asked not to be identified.
   ``We will be talking about increased direct support,'' he said.
``One reason we feel they should increase their contribution is
their economic performance. The other is our own budget problems,''
he said.
   South Korea has enjoyed an economic boom in recent years, with a
record $9.78 billion account surplus last year. South Korea's trade
surplus with the United States grew 39 percent in 1987.
   South Korea now contributes more than $100 million annually for
the upkeep of the U.S. force, said the official.
   In 1985, South Korea paid $34 million in direct funds for the
upkeep of the U.S. forces, said the official. It also contributed
about $1 billion indirectly through tax and rent exemptions for the
public lands used by the U.S. military, he said.
   The United States is asking the Seoul government for an increase
of $120 million, but the South Koreans would be willing to give
only $60 million more
   at most, The Washington Post reported today. The official
refused to discuss those figures.
   Many South Koreans have been angered by reports of the U.S.
request, saying that although the trade figures favor their
country, its residents are relatively poor by Western standards.
South Korea's per capita income is $3,000 annually, compared with
about $17,500 in the United States.
   U.S. officials are also concerned that as South Korea builds up
its military strength it will no longer want U.S. help to protect
the country against Communist North Korea.
   ``We must keep our troops there to counter the northern
threat,'' said the American official. ``There's no doubt about
that.''
   Without U.S. troops, the South Korean military is weaker than
its northern neighbor, which enjoys the support of the Soviet Union
and China.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
