<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Denmark-Derailment     04-25 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Denmark-Derailment,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Danish Train Derails, Killing 7, Injuring 67</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passenger train today raced through
a station where it was supposed to stop and then derailed. Danish
television said seven people were killed and 67 injured.
   ``There are several overturned cars, partly on top of each
other,'' Assistant Police Commissioner Palle Hasselgren told Danish
radio.
   The radio reported the train, traveling from Fredricia to
Copenhagen, derailed as it was to return to the main track from a
side rail which was used because of repair work.
   The train was not scheduled to stop for passengers at the small
rural station at Soroe, but was supposed to halt because of the
track change. Instead it went through the station at high speed,
the radio said.
   The engine and the two first cars flew off the track, causing
the following five cars to overturn, the report said.
   The derailment occurred about 50 miles southwest of Copenhagen.
   The express train, with a capacity of 300 people, was nearly
full. However, a group of children on their way to school got off
at the station before Soroe, the radio said. Many passengers were
businessmen from Funen island on their way to the Danish capital.
   Police helicopters and air force planes were called in to help
evacuate casualties.
   The dead were not immediately identified. Their nationalities
were not known.
</TEXT>
