<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InstituteEvacuation     04-25 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Institute Evacuation,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pace Slow As Town Evacuated as Part of Drill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INSTITUTE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only a handful of people left their
homes and jobs today when local officials conducted their first
evacuation drill in this ``Chemical Valley'' community, the site of
the nation's only methyl isocyanate plant.
   Sirens sounded to signal the evacuation at about 9:25 a.m. and
brought little immediate response. About one hour later, only some
30 people had arrived at an emergency shelter set up in nearby
South Charleston.
   Volunteers participating in the drill, which was designed to
simulate a leak in a railroad tanker at the plant, said they
believed the operation was going well. But at least one resident
said ``mayhem'' would result if a real emergency occurred.
   Institute is the site of a Rhone-Poulenc chemical plant that
formerly was owned by Union Carbide Corp. The plant produces methyl
isocyanate, the chemical that leaked from a Union Carbide plant in
Bhopal, India, in 1984, killing more than 2,000 people.
   Less than a year later, a leak of another chemical at the
Institute plant sent 135 people to the hospital, prompting the call
by some community leaders for an organized evacuation plan in case
of a major leak.
   Barbara Oden, assistant vice president of academic affairs at
West Virginia State College, next to the plant, was in Institute
during the 1985 leak and said today's drill was ``useful'' even if
people didn't participate.
   ``We really didn't know what to do (then). At least now we have
some idea,'' she said. ``People normally don't take things
seriously. They don't think it can really happen.''
   Local officials responded to the problem of evacuating the town
of 1,500 by building a one-lane emergency road out of town to help
residents flee, but the gate to that road is kept locked except
when needed. Today was the first time it was used.
   ``I can envision cars all over the track. It's just a little
trail. It would be mayhem. It will be a mess,'' said Barbara Clark,
a health and physical education instructor at the state college.
   Today's evacuation was conducted under special circumstances.
West Virginia State called off classes this morning, so there were
no students to evacuate from academic buildings. The town also was
evacuated in stages so the roads leading out of town wouldn't be
too crowded.
   ``When this was prepared, people didn't take it seriously,''
said Lois Thurston, a custodian at West Virginia State College.
``I'm sure if the students were here, they wouldn't know what was
going on.''
</TEXT>
