<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Iran-Contra     04-25 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Reprimands North, Co-Defendants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the Iran-Contra case barred
defendants today from presenting witnesses at a pre-trial hearing
on whether the prosecution relied on testimony given Congress under
a grant of immunity.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell took the action, and gave
Oliver L. North and two of his co-defendants a tongue-lashing,
because they disobeyed his order establishing procedures for the
hearing.
   Independent Counsel Lawrence E. Walsh was allowed to testify,
and he told the court of an elaborate procedure he established so
that his entire staff would avoid exposure to the immunized
testimony, especially from news reports.
   Walsh is unable to use immunized congressional testimony by the
defendants to prosecute them, unless perjury is committed.
   Testifying with immunity during the Iran-Contra hearings were
North, a former National Security Council staff member;his one-time
boss, former National Security Adviser John M. Poindexter; and
businessman Albert Hakim. The fourth defendant, retired Air Force
Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord, testified without immunity.
   Gesell said the three immunized defendants ``ignored'' his order
that they present a single grand jury witness who might testify
that his grand jury testimony was influenced by the immunized
congressional testimony.
   Instead, lawyers for the three immunized defendants sought to
present three witnesses, and issued subpoenas for Walsh and eight
members of his staff to testify at the hearing. Gesell, who had
ordered that only Walsh need testify, canceled the subpoenas last
week.
   ``Since the defendants did not comply, they won't be allowed to
present witnesses,'' he said today when the hearing began.
   ``It's not unusual that defendants make decisions that they are
not going to cooperate with the court. That's their right. We will
proceed whether we have confrontation and name-calling or not.''
   During the hearing, special independent counsel Herbert J.
Stern, who is handling the immunity question, introduced into
evidence memos written or ordered by Walsh, which instructed his
staff to avoid exposure to the immunized testimony and to other
information on the defendants.
   The memos also included instructions to grand jury witnesses and
grand jurors to avoid such exposure, especially through news
articles or broadcasts.
   The defendants in the case are charged with conspiring to use a
lawful presidential order permitting the sale of arms to Iran as a
springboard to illegal actions, including supplying assistance to
the Nicaraguan Contras when such aid was banned.
</TEXT>
