<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--China-Population,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Planning Cuts Chinese Births by 200 Million, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government-backed family planning has cut
Chinese births by about 200 million in recent years, but baby
boomers are leading another population surge, according to an
official report quoted Monday.
   China's family planning policy, which limits the number of
children per couple and promotes late childbearing, has cut the
births since the 1970s, the domestic China News Service said in a
report appearing in Hong Kong newspapers.
   China, the world's most populous nation, has more than 1 billion
people. Officials have estimated it must keep the birth rate below
1.5 percent to reach its planned population limit of 1.2 billion at
the turn of the century.
   But the birth rate was 2 percent in each of the last two years.
A primary reason for the increase, expected to last until at least
1995, is that people born in the baby boom years of 1962-75 are
reaching maturity and having their own babies, the reports said.
</TEXT>
