<HEAD>Scholz to be New Defense Minister, Sources Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Berlin Justice Minister Rupert
Scholz will be named West Germany's defense minister, replacing
NATO Secretary-General designate Manfred Woerner, government
sources said Monday.
   The sources said Chancellor Helmut Kohl will name Scholz as the
new defense minister during a news conference on Tuesday.
   Chief government spokesman Friedhelm Ost declined to comment on
reports naming Scholz as the new minister on Monday, but confirmed
Kohl would name Woerner's replacement on Tuesday.
   Scholz, 50, is to move into the post May 20, according to the
sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   A lawyer, Scholz is West Berlin's senator for justice and
federal affairs, and a delegate to the federal parliament in Bonn.
   He is considered a staunch backer of NATO and West Germany's
membership in the alliance and strong supporter of close ties with
the United States. He is also a ranking member of Kohl's ruling
Christian Democratic party.
   Woerner, the outgoing defense minister, will take over NATO's
top job July 1, the first West German to hold the post. He has
served as West Germany's foreign minister since October 1982.
