<1ST_LINE>r p BC-UTAHAt-A-Glance     04-25 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-UTAH At-A-Glance,</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the methods for picking
delegates from Utah to attend the 1988 Democratic and Republican
national conventions this summer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Caucus
   Date: Monday, April 25
   Presidential filing deadline: None.
   Pledged delegates: 23 Super delegates: 4 TOTAL: 27
   Delegates allocated: Monday, April 25
   Selection of delegates:Saturday, June 18
   
   Utah Democrats use a three-step system of caucuses and
conventions to pick pledged national convention delegates.
   All of the state's 23 pledged national convention delegates will
be allocated among presidential candidates in proportion to
presidential preferences expressed by write-in ballot at Democratic
mass meetings to be held around the state on April 25.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Caucus
   Date: Monday, April 25
   Presidential filing deadline: None.
   Delegates: 26
   Delegates allocated: Saturday, June 11
   Selection of delegates: Saturday, June 11
   
   Utah Republicans choose their national convention delegates
through a process of meetings and conventions, beginning with
neighborhood ``mass meetings'' on April 25.
   These mass meetings will choose delegates to county conventions,
and in 17 counties will pick delegates to the state convention. In
the remaining 12 counties in Utah, delegates to the state
convention will be chosen by the county conventions.
   Delegates in this process are not bound from one level to the
next and candidates for national convention delegate need not
declare their presidential preference.
   All national convention delegates will be chosen at that state
convention.
</TEXT>
