<1ST_LINE>u a PM-SubmarineFire-Sailors     04-25 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Submarine Fire-Sailors,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sailors Solemn on Return From Crippled Submarine</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Submarine Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sailors who abandoned ship
when the submarine USS Bonefish caught fire arrived here today
aboard a Navy frigate for a flight back to their home port of
Charleston, S.C.
   The 66 uninjured crewmen were solemn faced and refused to answer
reporters' questions about Sunday's fire aboard the submarine. They
were taken to a waiting cargo plane.
   Twenty-three members of the 92-person crew were injured,
according to the Navy, and three were listed as missing.
   The injured men, three in serious condition, were taken aboard
the aircraft carrier USS John F. Kennedy, the Navy said.
Helicopters from the carrier landed this morning at the
Jacksonville Naval Air Station with the injured, who were then
taken to Jacksonville Naval Hospital, said Stuart Johnson, a
hospital spokesman.
   Another hospital spokesman, Nick Young, said that 20 of the
injured were ambulatory, but he had no further information.
   Most of the sailors departing the fast frigate USS Carr in
Mayport were wearing blue coveralls and sneakers, but some were
shoeless. A few carried small plastic bags, apparently holding a
few of their belongings.
   Five families drove overnight from Charleston to greet relatives
at dockside. The families were allowed to go aboard the Carr for
private greetings.
   Lee and Alice Causey of Jacksonville were on hand to greet the
ship and their son, 30-year-old Petty Officer 1st Class Avery L.
Causey.
   ``He didn't say much. He was just glad to be back,'' Lee Causey
said. ``It's good to see him. I was on a submarine for 21 years, so
I know what he's going through.''
   Mrs. Causey said she first heard about the fire early this
morning, when her daughter-in-law called from Charleston.
   ``I was very scared and praying,'' Mrs. Causey said.
   Wesley Causey said all his brother asked for was a pair of shoes.
   Chaplain Bill Perry went aboard the Carr and visited the crewmen.
   He said the general mood was ``overwhelming fatigue,'' adding
that most had been up all night and many had been on watch the
night before.
   ``They've been through a real trauma,'' Perry said.
   He said he told the men that relatives and fellow servicemen in
Jacksonville and Charleston had been praying for their safety.
   Most of the sailors spent the night in the mess hall of the
Carr, talking with each other about the experience.
</TEXT>
