<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Mayors-Drugs     04-25 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mayors-Drugs,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayors, Police Chiefs Hear Federal Drug Message</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Field commanders in the national war on drugs
heard a pair of federal battle plans on Monday, plans that found
different groups to blame for the growing problem, and different
solutions.
   A Democratic member of Congress charged that the Reagan
administration lacked an organized plan to battle drugs, and he
called for a drug summit meeting with the heads of Latin American
nations.
   A top aide to President Reagan, on the other hand, said it was
time to put more pressure on those who use drugs.
   In remarks to a meeting of the National Conference of Mayors,
Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., said it was not enough that the Drug
Enforcement Administration and other Justice Department agencies
were battling drugs. They should be getting help from the State
Department, the Education Department, the Defense Department and
the Department of Health and Human Services,
   ``It's not a question of whether we're losing the battle, it's a
question that we don't even know who's in charge of the war,''
Rangel told a session of mayors and police chiefs.
   But Gary L. Bauer, Reagan's assistant for policy development,
told the meeting that the nation does not appear to have reached
the collective state of mind neded to defeat the drug problem.
   Drugs pour into America because there is a market for them, he
said, and the battle needs to be waged against the users.
   Accomplices in crime are young couples who think it's all right
to use drugs casually on the weekend, abstainers who look away when
others use drugs, sports heroes who set a bad example by using
drugs, college presidents who know drugs are on campus but fail to
act, civil libertarians who tie up the courts with technicalities
and sophistry and television and movie producers who glorify drugs,
Bauer said.
   ``Unless we find the political will to penalize the users as
well as the dealers,'' the drug problem will remain, he said. The
nation cannot buy or blast its way drug free with financial
programs and the military, he said.
   Rangel, pressed by New Orleans Mayor Sidney Barthelemy, said he
plans to introduce a measure to direct federal anti-drug funds
directly to large cities, rather than through federal and state
bureaucracies.
   In addition, Rangel called for increased participation of all
federal agencies in anti-drug battles.
   To begin with, he said, the State Department should call a
summit of nations from Latin America to find ways to cooperate in
the drug war. A plan must be developed to work with people.
   ``You can't take a farmer who is making $10,000 on coca leaves
and tell him to go back to his former crop that made $500,'' Rangel
said.
   In addition to involving the State Department, Rangel questioned
the reluctance of the Defense Department to join in patroling the
borders, asked for Education Department anti-drug programs and
suggested drug rehabilitation organized by the Health and Human
Services department.
   As to the suggestion that more and more drug users be arrested:
``Where do you put them?'' he said.
</TEXT>
