<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ContraTalks     04-25 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Talks,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Sandinista Official in Miami For Contra Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Sandinista official was in Miami today for
talks with representatives of the Contra rebels as the two sides
prepared for a new round of peace negotiations in Nicaragua later
this week.
   Sandinista Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Tinoco was meeting
secretly with the Contra directors' secretary to discuss ``the
agenda and arrangements'' for talks to begin Thursday in Managua,
rebel leader Adolfo Calero said.
   Calero also said the Contras will demand the Sandinistas
immediately allow U.S. food and supplies to rebel troops as a
precondition for any further talks based on the agreement reached
last month in Sapoa, Nicaragua.
   ``If that is not done the whole Sapoa agreement will collapse,''
Calero said.
   An internal Contra memo written by Luis Fley, who goes by the
name Cmdr. Johnson, recently called the situation of the Contras
troops in the field ``critical.''
   Calero said the Sandinistas must immediately agree on what the
rebels call the ``modus operandi'' for getting the humanitarian aid
to the Contra forces inside Nicaragua.
   The plight of the troops has reportedly been a contributing
cause to a rift among the Contra leaders, but today Calero
downplayed the differences among the five directors.
   He denied leading a movement to fire top Contra Cmdr. Enrique
Bermudez, but acknowledged two other rebel field commanders, Walter
Calderon and Diogenes Hernadnez, had objected to the peace talks.
He also said three top civilian employees of the rebel troops had
been replaced by military officials.
   But he inisted there was still unity among the directors of the
Nicaraguan Resistance, as the Contras are formally called.
   All five directors, including Aristides Sanchez, who skipped the
last meeting in Managua for ``personal reasons,'' will fly to
Nicaragua for this week's negotiations, Calero said.
   Calero refused to discuss where Tinoco was conducting the
pre-meeting talks with the directors' secretary in strongly
anti-communist Miami. But he said there were no plans for the
Sandinista foreign ministry official to talk with the directors
themselves here.
   Tinoco previously has accused the Contras of engaging in
political maneuvering to avoid a definitive cease-fire while they
receive U.S. aid.
</TEXT>
