<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AP-Services     04-25 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP-Services,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press To Boost Speed, Add Staff, Expand Art Services</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Associated Press will speed up its
DataStream news delivery system to about 9,000 words a minute
beginning in June, add to its news staff, and introduce new photo
and graphics services, President Louis D. Boccardi announced Monday.
   He said these ventures into ``the new world of news'' will help
the news cooperative meet its responsibilities to its members, now
numbering a record 1,428.
   Boccardi told the AP annual meeting that 10 to 15 people will be
added to the domestic news staff during 1988.
   ``The bulk of these will go to our line bureaus, whose state and
regional news coverage is so important to you,'' he told publishers
and editors of newspapers that use the AP. ``With the membership
increasing as it has, the demands on our state bureaus are
increasing. And we must meet those needs.''
   AP Board Chairman William J. Keating said, ``Never in its
140-year history has the Associated Press faced greater challenges
or more exciting prospects than in 1988, with newspaper membership
at a record-high level.
   ``A strong, dedicated and talented staff and a commitment to
leadership in news technology will meet those challenges,'' Keating
said. ``At the same time we members must remember that our
cooperation and our help is essential to AP performance.''
   Boccardi said the AP is about to move from a speed of about
1,050 words a minute to about 9,000 on its DataStream and
DataFeature wires.
   ``We will begin in June installing at highspeed newspapers a new
generation of AP microprocessors that will enable us, state by
state, to leap to 9,600-baud delivery,'' he said.
   For newspapers with systems that need slower speeds, the
delivery rate can be reduced, but he said ``the news will fly on AP
circuits at 9600.'' That increase in capacity will avoid crowding
that can slow copy delivery just as a crowded highway can slow
traffic.
   ``We are raising the speed limit from 55 mph to 440 mph and ...
we're widening the AP interstate from four lanes to eight,''
Boccardi said.
   He said three successful test installations of the new AP
electronic darkroom for large newspapers are in place in St.
Petersburg, Fla., Chicago and Minneapolis. In June, Boccardi said,
the AP will unveil a PC-based electronic darkroom for smaller
newspapers.
   He also announced that the AP will be offering members a new
picture transmitter for the handling of their own photos _ a small,
portable system enabling a photographer to transmit photos from
color or black and white negatives without making prints.
   The AP already has put that system into use in covering such
events as the Winter Olympic Games and the NCAA basketball
championships in March. The transmitter, called the AP@Leafax 35,
was developed to AP specifications by Leaf Systems Inc. of Natick,
Mass. AP holds exclusive distribution rights.
   By the end of the year, Boccardi said, the AP will begin
operating a new service called DataFeature Graphics that will
deliver news graphics offered by syndicates and supplemental
services.
   He also said the AP has now converted worldwide to all-color
photography, a step taken in the United States more than a year ago.
   By next spring, he said, a new financial markets system will be
ready for AP members. ``You will be able to use our feed to create
stock tables in virtually any form you wish, emphasizing local
companies or industries, for example,'' he said.
</TEXT>
