<DOCNO> AP880425-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan Bjt   04-25 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0718</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Najib Offers To Withdraw Troops From Pakistani Border Areas</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KAB2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib on Monday offered to
withdraw Afghan troops from their posts near the Pakistani border
if anti-communist guerrillas and Pakistan agree to do the same.
   ``We are ready to create a non-military line'' between
Afghanistan and Pakistan, Najib said at the opening of celebrations
marking the 10th anniversary of the Afghan revolution that
installed a Soviet-backed government.
   Najib told an assembly of three small parties loyal to his
government that such a withdrawal would allow the estimated 3
million Afghan refugees in Pakistan to return home.
   However, the proposal appeared to be little more than a
face-saving acknowledgement of the difficulties the Afghan army is
having against onslaughts by anti-communist guerrillas, based in
Pakistan and supplied with U.S. and Chinese weapons.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in 1979 to help quell an
uprising by a guerrilla front.
   The Soviet Union has agreed to start withdrawing its estimated
115,000 troops from Afghanistan on May 15 under a U.N.-mediated
agreement signed April 14 in Geneva by the United States, the
Soviet Union, Afghanistan and Pakistan.
   The United States, China and several other countries have been
aiding the Afghan guerrillas via Pakistan. The Soviet Union arms
the Afghan military forces. Each superpower has reserved the right
to continue its assistance as long as the other one does.
   The guerrillas, who were not direct party to the Geneva accord,
have vowed to continue fighting until Najib's government is
overthrown.
   On Sunday, Najib confirmed a guerrilla claim that the Afghan
army had been pushed out of Barikot, a key post on the Pakistani
frontier.
   Barikot, 150 miles northeast of Kabul, controls a major road
leading into Afghanistan from Pakistan. The guerrillas said the
victory opened a new, direct supply route for weapons into
Afghanistan.
   The guerrillas said Monday they have taken control of three
other strategic towns in recent weeks: Ghorband, 50 miles north of
Kabul, and Maarouf and Darwazgai, both in the south about 30 miles
from the Pakistani bordar.
   Western sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
guerrillas captured Ghorband in late March. There was no immediate
word on the other two claims.
   The guerrillas also said Najib's government is negotating with
Moslem guerillas for the release of a provincial governor captured
by insurgents earlier this month.
   The insurgents are holding the governor of northern Kunduz
province, the chief of police and two senior Afghan army officers.
The governor and the two other officials were not identified.
   Brig. Abdullah Haq Ulomi said the Afghan army would withdraw
from the border at ``the points that are needed _ several dozen if
necessary.''
   Ulomi heads the Afghan army department of the Central Committee
of the ruling People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan.
   A foreign diplomat warned that U.S. officials were incorrect to
assume that guerrilla victories near the Pakistani border were
signs the Soviet-backed government was in trouble.
   ``We are very surprised by the optimism of American officials,''
said the diplomat, who asked not be identified.
   ``They believe the government of Najib will collapse after the
withdrawal of the Soviet troops, but this optimism seems to me and
to other Western observers to be very worrying because it is
absolutely not true,'' he said.
   Najib, in his speech at the Polytechnic Institute in Kabul,
called the Soviet withdrawal ``the significant event of the year.''
   He asserted that the Soviet troops have enabled the Afghan army
to maintain a military balance with the guerrillas.
   Najib said his army must maintain this balance and much has to
be done to prepare for the return of refugees.
   About 5 million Afghans _ one-third of the country's population
_ have fled since the Soviet intervention. About 3 milllion are in
Pakistan, and most of the rest are in Iran.
   Najib spoke in Dari for one hour to the Revolutionary
Organization of Afghanistan, the Peasants Organization of
Afghanistan and the Toilers Organization of Afghanistan. His
remarks were translated by government employees.
   The 10th anniversary of the revolution is Wednesday, but parades
and speeches marking the event will take place Tuesday.
</TEXT>
