<DOCNO> AP880425-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0518 04-25 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0518,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tornadoes Rip Through Texas, Georgia; More Thunderstorms on Tap</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Georgia tornadoes, picking
up 2nd graf pvs, `Two men ....'
^By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms raced across the South and Midwest today after
tornadoes in Texas ripped through a mobile home park, injuring two
people and destroying several structures.
   Two tornadoes touched down north of Valdosta, Ga., today, one
near the tiny community of Bemiss and one to the east in Naylor,
said dispatcher Robert Rudd of the Lowndes County Sheriff's
Department.
   ``We've got severe damage,'' he said. One mobile home was
demolished in Bemiss, and wires and trees had fallen all across the
county, making several roads impassable, he said.
   There was no word of any injuries.
   Two men were injured Sunday night when their mobile home was
hurled onto a highway and destroyed in north-central Texas. The
men, ages 69 and 72, were hospitalized in stable condition.
   ``We received a report of heavy damage to two other mobile
homes, one nearby and another about one-quarter mile away, and a
barn,'' said Juan Fulton of the Parker County Fire Department.
   Thunderstorms with winds gusting up to 70 mph were scattered
Sunday night from western Oklahoma to south-central Texas.
   Rain and snow fell over the Rockies of northwest Wyoming and
western Montana. Snow advisories were in effect for the mountains
of Montana east of the Continental Divide and the northern
mountains of Wyoming, where 3-8 inches of snow was expected.
   Clear skies covered the Great Lakes region and portions of the
Ohio Valley this morning, while temperatures dropped to about the
freezing mark. Freeze or frost advisories were in effect for lower
Michigan, northern Indiana, Ohio and northeast Kentucky.
   The forecast for today called for showers and thunderstorms over
the lower Mississippi Valley, Tennessee, Alabama, South Carolina,
Georgia and northern Florida; scattered showers and thunderstorms
over Utah, Colorado, Nebraska, eastern Kansas, Oklahoma and Texas;
rain or snow over the northern Rockies and the northern High
Plains; and rain or flurries scattered over northern New England.
   Much of the nation will have high temperatures in the 50s or
60s, while highs will be in the upper 30s and 40s over the northern
half of the Rockies, from eastern Montana to upper Michigan and
across northern New England; in the 70s and 80s over the southern
third of the country; and in the lower 90s over Florida and
southern Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 27 at
Gwinn, Mich., to 79 at Del Rio, Texas, and Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 54 partly cloudy; Boston 44 windy; Buffalo 35
fair; Charleston, S.C. 63 fair; Cincinnati 35 fair; Cleveland 44
fair; Detroit 37 fair; Miami 74 fair; New York 48 fair;
Philadelphia 45 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 41 cloudy; Portland,
Maine 38 cloudy; Washington 47 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 31 partly cloudy; Chicago 39 fair;
Dallas-Fort Worth 59 cloudy; Denver 40 fair; Des Moines 49 fair;
Indianapolis 35 partly cloudy; Kansas City 53 cloudy;
Minneapolis-St. Paul 47 fair; Nashville 47 cloudy; New Orleans 75
