<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Gulf 2ndLd-Writethru a0643 04-25 0935</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Gulf, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0643,950</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts 3 grafs on Coast Guard ships before penultimate graf
pvs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is still mulling whether to
increase U.S. military involvement in the Persian Gulf, a White
House spokesman said today, amid indications of fresh
administration concern about the American presence there.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said a number of options are still
being weighed and that ``no decisions have been made'' on the
possible broadening of the U.S. escort role for neutral ships in
the strategic waterway.
   But Fitzwater contradicted remarks that administration officials
had made last Friday, indicating a decision had been made to expand
the U.S. role to allow American warships to protect neutral vessels
under attack.
   Officials, who declined to be named publicly, said last week
that a more aggressive U.S. policy in the gulf had been decided
upon. They said such a policy was aimed at deterring Iranian
attacks against gulf shipping. The change in policy, they said at
the time, was a direct result of the mining of a U.S. frigate and
Monday's extensive fighting between Iranian and U.S. forces.
   But during his daily White House briefing today, Fitzwater
talked of the possibility of returning U.S. forces in the gulf to
the limited rules of engagement that applied before last Monday,
when the United States attacked two Iranian platforms and the two
nations' forces subsequently exchanged fire.
   While the spokesman emphasized that several options remained
under study, Fitzwater indicated a concern within the
administration about an Americanization of the Iran-Iraq war.
   ``Right now the rules of engagement are essentially the same as
they were last week, reflecting the emergency nature of the
situation,'' he said. ``But the question is, where do we move back
to? But I can't discuss specifics.''
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, interviewed from Brussels,
Belgium, on NBC-TV's ``Today'' program, also indicated a U.S.
interest in restraining the role of American military involvement
in the gulf.
   ``We will not get tied up in any serious shooting war with the
Iranians,'' Shultz said. He added that the final decision is up to
Reagan _ and that it hasn't yet been made.
   ``As far as our rules of engagement are concerned, what the
right ones are for this stage of the game in the gulf are being
considered in Washington, and there is a process of consultation
going on and I think it's premature to describe them in any
particular way,'' Shultz said.
   Fitzwater said that ``during the conflict last Monday, the rules
(of engagement) were changed to accommodate the military situation
that was encountered.''
   ``You'll recall at that point that our ships were engaging
hostile forces in any number of areas, and we now want to move back
to our conservative set of rules. And so that decision has to be
made about where to move back to,'' he said. ``You see, the rules
were changed to accommodate the military aggression that was
encountered that day. Once that is no longer the case, we want to
move to something that would be more sustainable in the long term.''
   Among the options being examined is adding Coast Guard ships to
assist the U.S. Navy fleet in the Persian Gulf, where an Iranian
gunboat attack on a neutral vessel drew a muted reaction from U.S.
officials Sunday.
   Adm. William Crowe, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said
the attack on a Saudi-owned tanker reflected a ``level of violence
... much less'' than in the mining incident that touched off last
week's U.S. retaliatory strike against two Iranian offshore
platforms.
   ``We consider our response on Monday a suitable response for the
indiscriminate mining, and we do not contemplate any more violence
unless Iran continues what we would say is an indiscriminate and a
threatening pattern,'' Crowe said on CBS-TV's ``Face the Nation.''
   The captain of the Saudi-owned Sea Trader said there were no
casualties but the ship suffered slight damage in the grenade and
machine gun attack at 7:30 a.m. Sunday (11:30 p.m. EDT Saturday).
   On the option of adding Coast Guard vessels, Defense Secretary
Frank Carlucci said the use of the crafts would provide more
flexibility in the gulf, but no decision has been made.
   ``They have somewhat smaller ships which give a better
patrolling capability. It would free our larger ships for other
missions,'' Carlucci said on ABC-TV's ``This Week With David
Brinkley.''
   Crowe said Coast Guard vessels would be ideal for assisting
warships in the escort of merchant vessels, watching sea lanes to
prevent mine-laying and guarding offshore installations from
attacks by small craft.
   The Coast Guard vessels the Pentagon may send to the gulf are
lightly armed, Island-class patrol craft now used mainly against
drug traffic in the Caribbean, the service said today.
   the 110-foor-long ships travel at a maximum speed of 26 knots
and carry two officers, two chief petty officers and an additional
crew of up to 14.
   The ships are armed with one 20 mm machine gun in the front, and
two 7.62 mm machine guns elsewhere, said spokesman Nicholas
Sandifer. Jane's Fighting Ships says each craft can carry an
additional 20 mm machine gun.
   The United States remains officially neutral in the 7{-year-old
Iran-Iraq war although it used U.S. warships to guard
American-flagged Kuwaiti tankers from attacks since last summer.
   The Iranian attack on the Sea Trader came hours after Reagan, in
his weekly radio address, warned Iran that ``continued military and
terrorist attacks against nonbelligerents and refusal to negotiate
an end to the war will be very costly to Iran and its people.''
</TEXT>
