<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GraveyardDispute     04-25 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Graveyard Dispute,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kraft, Suburban Chicago Officials Scrapping Over Graveyard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTHFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kraft Inc. wants to dig up the remains
of members of several farm families and move them to an established
cemetery, but some local officials are fighting the plans.
   ``These were the settlers of our community. This site should not
be disturbed,'' said Northfield Township Supervisor Gregg Goslin.
   ``We are looking at an irreplaceable part of this community's
history,'' he said recently as he picked his way through underbrush
surrounding the cemetery northwest of Chicago.
   Goslin said he is trying to persuade Kraft officials to change
their plans to uproot the overgrown cemetary in order to construct
a new office building.
   But Kraft doesn't want the ``abandoned and long neglected''
cemetery in its front yard, said spokeswoman Magnes Welsh.
   The cemetary hasn't had a new burial since June 1924. Many of
the headstones are no longer legible and are partly covered with
earth.
   The company wants to dig up the graves and move them to an
established cemetery, she said.
   But Kraft needs permission from the Northfield Township Board of
Trustees before it moves the remains of the estimated 20 people
buried there.
   The board has scheduled a public hearing on the request for next
month.
</TEXT>
