<DOCNO> AP880425-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1358EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Israel     04-25 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Israel,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Council Condemns Killing Of Abu Jihad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council voted 14-0 today to
condemn the assassination of PLO deputy commander Khalil al-Wazir.
   The United States abstained from voting. It could have vetoed
the resolution.
   Tunisian officials and Israeli sources say Israeli commandos
gunned down Wazir, the Palestine Liberation Organization's
52-year-old military commander, at his home in suburban Tunis on
April 16. Israel has neither confirmed nor denied the allegations.
   The Security Council resolution condemns the slaying but does
not explicitly criticize Israel. However, the resolution approved
today does refer to a 1985 resolution passed after Israel bombed
PLO headquarters in Tunis. The 1985 measure condemned Israel and
demanded that it refrain from further ``acts of aggression.''
   U.S. Ambassador Herbert Okun said the United States could not
vote in favor of the resolution today because it lays all the blame
on Israel without taking note of Arab aggression against the Jewish
state.
   He also praised Tunisia as a peaceful nation and a friend of the
United States.
   ``The perpetration of politic assassination on Tunisian soil
stands in stark contrast to Tunisia's longstanding tradition of
non-violence,'' he said.
   Both Tunisia and the PLO expressed satisfaction with the U.S.
abstention. The United States generally uses its veto to shield
Israel in the council.
   Scores of speakers harshly condemned Israel for practicing state
terrorism and warned that Wazir's murder would not end the unrest
in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Wazir, known as Abu Jihad, was the mastermind of the
4{-month-old Palestinian uprising in the territories.
   His slaying has served as a catalyst for possible reconciliation
between Syria and the PLO, something many Arab leaders believe
could help forge Arab unity.
   PLO leader Yasser Arafat and Syrian President Hafez Assad met
today in Damascus, only their second face-to-face meeting since
Arafat was expelled from Syria in 1983.
   Council members who belong to the movement of nations professing
non-alignment with either superpower _ Algeria, Argentina, Nepal,
Senegal, Yugoslavia and Zambia _ sponsored the resolution on
Tunisia's complaint.
   The other current council members are the Soviet Union, Britain,
France, China, Brazil, Italy, Japan and West Germany.
</TEXT>
