<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Surgeon-SlayingAttempt     04-25 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Surgeon-Slaying Attempt,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Surgeon Accused of Attempting to Kill His Hospitalized Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief of oral surgery at
Aurora's Fitzsimons Army Medical Center has been accused of trying
to inject his hospitalized wife with a suspected pesticide, police
said.
   Police Sgt. Joe Kenda said Sunday the alleged incident was the
result of an ``ongoing dispute of a domestic nature.''
   Col. Dennis Earl Parmer, 52, of Colorado Springs, was arrested
late Saturday at Penrose Hospital here after a lab technician said
he saw a syringe stuck into his wife Carol's intravenous support
system, police said.
   Parmer was held in El Paso County Jail in lieu of $500,000 bond
on suspicion of attempted first-degree murder. He was still there
Monday, according to authorities.
   Carol Parmer, 44, was moved to the intensive care unit after the
incident and was listed in good condition. At the time of the
incident, she was being treated for deep-vein phlebitis _ a
clotting and inflammation of veins of the leg, officials said.
   ``We can't be sure if poison was injected'' until toxicology
tests are completed, said hospital spokesman Dr. Michael Guthrie.
``Clinically, she seems fine.''
   Lab technicians with the coroner's office were analyzing the
suspected pesticide to determine what it is and how it would affect
a human body, El Paso County Coroner Dr. David Bowerman said.
   The alleged attempted poisoning occurred during the end of
visiting hours Saturday, Guthrie said.
   ``A hospital employee came into the room to do a blood drawing
on another patient and happened to see what was going on,'' said
Guthrie.
   Police at first thought the incident might have been an
attempted mercy killing.
   Guthrie said although the woman's phlebitis is serious it is
``not life threatening and certainly not terminal.''
   A ``serious incident report'' will eventually be forwarded to
the Pentagon for review, officials said.
</TEXT>
