<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Pele 1stLd-Writethru a0571 04-25 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Pele, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0571,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Hawaiian Religious-Rights Appeal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last 2 grafs to show Supreme Court already has ruled on
similar case.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today turned down an appeal
by native Hawaiians who say plans for developing geothermal energy
in a volcanic area will violate their religious rights.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the proposed
development will not interfere unlawfully with access to sacred
land by worshippers of the goddess Pele.
   The native Hawaiians said the development ``by turning a
pristine, virgin rain forest into a spiderweb of pipelines, roads,
geothermal wells and production plants ... would by accepted
religious doctrine destroy the goddess Pele.''
   Pele was described as ``the magma, the heat, the vapor, the
steam and the cosmic creation which occur in volcanic eruptions.
She is seen by Pele people in the lava, images of her standing
erect, dancing and extending her arms with her hair flowing into
the steam and clouds.''
   At issue are more than 9,000 acres of land in an area called the
Kilauea Middle East Rift Zone on the island of Hawaii.
   The Hawaii Supreme Court ruled in July that state officials did
not infringe on the religious practices of the natives by setting
aside the land for geothermal development.
   The state court noted that the development site was moved about
five to 10 miles from a location ``where tradition suggests Pele
resides.'' The state court said the natives failed to prove
significant harm would be done to their religious practices.
   But the worshippers of Pele said it is impossible to identify
the precise sacred areas where they are commanded by the goddess to
conduct private ceremonial rituals. The precise sites are revealed
by mysterious signs, they said.
   The Supreme Court last week ruled in a similar case from
California that road-building and timber-harvesting in a national
forest does not violate Indians' freedom of religion even if land
they consider sacred is altered.
   The case acted on today is Dedman vs. Hawaii Board of Land and
Natural Resources, 87-605.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
