<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nepal-Run     04-25 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nepal-Run,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Woman Completes Part Of Trans-Himalayan Run With Pet Dog</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BINAYA GURUACHARYA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American trying to become the first
woman to complete the 2,000-mile trans-Himalayan run arrived in
Katmandu on Monday _ behind schedule and with a broken foot, but
determined to carry on.
   ``Although I'm 10 days behind schedule, I will catch up,'' said
Mary Margaret Goodwin after she emerged from the woods with her pet
dog, Velia.
   Goodwin said she had broken her foot two weeks earlier and will
see a doctor on Tuesday.
   ``But there is nothing which will prevent me'' from finishing
the run, Goodwin, 50, declared.
   Goodwin, from Fort Lewis, Wash., started out from Darjeeling,
India, and traveled 400 miles before reaching the Nepalese capital
more than six weeks later with her 2-year-old German shorthair
pointer.
   She said she had been trying to break a 1984 record set by two
British brothers, Adrian and Dick Crane, in which they completed
the trans-Himalayan run in 92 days.
   But ``I can't find the route they mentioned in their report. The
route that I took was definitely longer,'' Goodwin said.
   She said she had been suffering from high fever for the last
four days and has already lost about 31 pounds.
   ``Two nights ago, I almost collapsed,'' she added. ``But, I'm
optimistic of completing the whole trip. I think the worst part of
it is over now.''
   She said she had been completing about 10 miles to 50 miles a
day.
   The Darjeeling-Katmandu route is the ``hardest mileage I have
ever done in my life,'' added Goodwin, a veteran long-distance
runner. ``This is not only running, but climbing too. The weather
turned out very hostile this year. It was snowing in the Everest
region,'' she said.
   Goodwin became the first woman to run the 1,000-mile route
through Scotland, Wales and England, and also completed a
2,000-mile trip through Japan in 1986.
   She is scheduled to leave Katmandu on Thursday and reach Gulmarg
in Kashmir, India, by early June to finish the run.
</TEXT>
