<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Afghanistan     04-25 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Afghanistan,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Says Najib Call for Better Ties is `Absurd'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A call by Afghanistan's President Najib for
better relations with the United States is ``absurd,'' the State
Department said Monday.
   In an interview with a 12-member, private U.S. delgation, parts
of which were published Monday in The Washington Post, Najib said
he was ready ``for any kinds of compromise'' with the U.S.-backed
rebels trying to topple his Soviet-backed government.
   One possible compromise is for the return of exiled King
Mohammed Zahir to act as a rallying point for a broad-based
government that would run the country after the Soviets withdraw
their troops, he said.
   Moscow, which sent elements of the Red Army into Afghanistan in
1979, has undertaken to start pulling out some 115,000 troops on
May 15 under a U.N.-mediated accord.
   ``All the conditions are now present and I think the Americans
could play a great role,'' Najib was quoted as saying. ``We want to
live in friendship with the United States of America without losing
any element of our friendship with the Soviet Union.''
   But a State Department spokeswoman, Phyllis Oakley, said that
since the United States views the Soviet-appointed Najib government
as illegitimate, ``I think the question of our improving relations
with it is absurd.''
   She labeled Najib's comments Soviet propaganda.
   In his talk with the Americans, mostly retired officials and
U.S. business executives, Najib also said he would only accept a
cutoff of Soviet aid to his government if the U.S. stopped aiding
its rebel allies.
   ``That comment we also view as absurd, of equating Soviet aid to
the regime in Kabul with U.S. assistance to the government of
Pakistan,'' Mrs. Oakley said.
   The United States has said it would stop arming and financing
the seven rebel groups if the Soviets end their support for the
Najib government.
   Mrs. Oakley said the delegation went to Kabul ``strictly in a
private capacity and has no sanction whatsoever from the U.S.
government.
   ``In fact, before the group members departed for Kabul, we
recommended that they not make the trip and alerted them to the
likelihood that the Afghan and Soviet propaganda organs would
exploit their activities.''
   This is the first U.S. delegation to visit Afghanistan since the
1979 Soviet incursion. Robert E. White, who heads the group, said
after the Najib interview that the Afghan government would have to
share power with the rebels before any change could be made in ties
with the United States.
   Two members of the group boycotted the 80-minute interview to
show their disapproval for Najib and their support for the rebels,
the Post said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
