<DOCNO> AP880425-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1622EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissingMusician     04-25 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Musician,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parents Look For Clues To Son's Disappearance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple from Dayton, Ohio, have become
frequent visitors to Orlando, handing out fliers, asking questions
and checking people and places their missing musician son may have
known and visited.
   ``We keep hoping that we will find him alive but the longer it
goes, it makes us worry more that we won't,'' says Stanley Chism
about his missing son, Stanley Chism Jr., 23.
   Police found his bloodstained shirt, other clothes and a crowbar
covered with blood in a trash bin. His girlfriend's phone number
and a bank deposit slip were in the shirt pocket. Blood was found
on the back seat of his car.
   The younger Chism disappeared shortly after calling his parents
and girlfriend Feb. 5. His roommate and members of his gospel music
group reported him missing Feb. 8.
   On their first trip to Orlando, Chism and his wife Georgia went
to motels, shopping centers and other places to look for their
son's car. They handed out fliers with information about their son
and tried to contact anybody who had known him.
   The car was found after somebody read a newspaper advertisement
that the Chisms placed. In addition to the blood, Orange County
sheriff's deputies found Chism's glasses and boots in the car, his
father said. A sheriff's spokesman said samples of the blood were
being tested.
   ``Foul play could be involved, but right now we haven't found a
victim,'' said sheriff's spokesman Jim Solomons. ``We are doing
everything we can. We are working this case diligently.''
   Chism's parents disagree.
   ``We feel that from the beginning, the police (sheriff's)
department has not shown a concern for a missing person,'' said the
elder Chism, an evangelist. ``That is the reason we have driven
miles and miles.''
   Solomons disputes the parents' claims. He said the sheriff's
office followed standard procedures in handling a missing person
report.
   Chism, who played piano in a gospel group known as Loretta
Carter and the Sounds of Praise, had planned to leave Orlando in
March and work with his father in a ministry.
   For his mother, the worst part is not knowing.
   ``It's like you can't grieve because you don't know that he is
dead and you can't go on because you can't find him,'' she said.
</TEXT>
