<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContinentalTrial     04-25 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Continental Trial,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Luxury Lifestyle Prompted Bank VP's Participation in Scheme</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be updated with closing arguments for defense.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Continental Illinois National Bank officer
John Lytle's luxurious lifestyle and mounting personal debts led
him to scheme with two Oklahoma men to defraud the bank,
prosecutors said Monday at his trial.
   ``By the summer of 1981, Lytle lived a lifestyle virtually fit
for a king, like the `lifestyle of the rich and famous,'''
Assistant U.S. Attorney Ted Helwig contended during closing
arguments.
   Lytle, Tulsa oil driller Jere Sturgis and William Patterson,
former head of oil and gas lending at the failed Penn Square Bank
of Oklahoma City, are charged with participating in a scheme to
defraud Continental.
   Lytle, a former Continental vice president, is accused of taking
kickbacks in exchange for funding and attempting to fund high-risk
energy loans from Continental Illinois National Bank & Trust Co. to
Penn Square customers.
   The three men have pleaded innocent. Lytle, 52, and Patterson,
37, are charged with wire fraud and misapplication of bank funds.
Sturgis, 40, is charged with wire fraud.
   U.S. District Judge Milton Shadur is presiding over the trial,
which is into its sixth week.
   The indictment cites Lytle's involvement in $44 million in loans
made by Continental to 12 Penn Square customers. It does not say
how much was recovered by the Chicago bank, which came to the brink
of collapse in 1984 in part because of its troubled energy loans.
   Continental was rescued with a $4.5 billion federal bailout.
   Those loans were approved in 1981 and 1982 _ at about the same
time, Helwig charges, that Lytle received nearly $600,000 in
kickbacks from Patterson in the form of unsecured personal loans
from Penn Square.
   He said Lytle, a 20-year Continental veteran who oversaw the
bank's oil and gas lending in Oklahoma, needed the money because he
was living well beyond his means.
   ``He had a home he was doubling in size, vacations, two vacation
homes, and $565,000 (from the Penn Square Bank) that he used to buy
cars, furs, and jewelry.
   ``He had become so completely dependent on Bill Patterson, he no
longer had the interest of Continental first and foremost,'' Helwig
said.
   Lytle, impassive during government arguments, took notes. He sat
facing the jury, wearing a brown suit and scuffed penny loafers _
one with a hole in the sole.
</TEXT>
