<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ChicagoMayor     04-25 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicago Mayor,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Special Mayoral Election Now Could Be Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city board of elections voted Monday to hold
a special mayoral election next year if the city clerk declares a
vacancy in the mayor's office.
   Eugene Sawyer has been serving as acting mayor since last
November when then-Mayor Harold Washington, the city's first black
mayor, died after suffering a massive heart attack in his office.
   Sawyer was elected by the City Council, and his supporters
contend the next mayoral election should be in 1991, when
Washington's term would have expired.
   Under the three-member board's unanimous decision, City Clerk
Walter Kozubowski must decide whether a vacancy exists in the
mayor's office.
   Deputy City Clerk Daniel J. Burke said Kozubowski has not
decided what to do and would await an opinion from the city's
corporation counsel.
   Otis Chism, administrative assistant to the general counsel for
the Board of Elections Commission, said he was not sure what
prompted the decision.
   Supporters of Alderman Tim Evans, expected to be one of Sawyer's
chief mayoral challengers in the next election, have been seeking a
1989 election.
   Chism said the matter could end up being settled in court, where
two lawsuits are pending. One asks for a 1989 special election, and
the other seeks a 1991 vote.
   The board's vote today followed last week's decision by the
State Board of Elections to postpone until May 4 making any
recommendations on the question of when the city's next mayoral
election should be.
   Burke said that if an election is held, the city board agreed to
Feb. 28 as a primary election date in 1989 with April 4 as a
general election date.
</TEXT>
