<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MilwaukeeFire     04-25 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Milwaukee Fire,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spectacular Fire Tears Through Buildings; No One Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MI2,4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A paint store erupted in flames with a pair of
explosions, forcing panicked residents to jump from upstairs
apartment windows into the arms of bystanders as firefighters
fought to control the blaze early Monday.
   A dozen people were injured in the fire that destroyed the store
building and badly damaged three other buildings, but only one was
admitted to a hospital.
   However, the blaze was so intense that rescuers initially were
convinced there would be fatalities and the Fire Department ordered
25 body bags sent to the scene.
   ``People that were in the building, some of them on the third
floor, they said they felt the building drop,'' said Deputy Fire
Chief William Walker. ``The north wall dropped out and they jumped
to their safety. And nobody was seriously injured that I know of.''
   ``It was very fortunate,'' he said. ``They must have had a
friend upstairs.''
   The fire began with an explosion at the paint store at 11:13
p.m. Sunday, fire officials said. Within minutes after the first
firefighters arrived, a second, more powerful explosion ripped
through the paint store, blowing out one wall and creating a
fireball that rapidly spread to nearby structures.
   Cheryl McMurray, 33, and Joe Bell, 44, were sitting at a dining
table in a third-floor apartment above the store.
   ``The floor went right out beneath us,'' Ms. McMurray said.
``Everything in the kitchen was shaking. He (Bell) had me by the
hand and pulled me down the stairs. It took us 20 seconds to get
out the front door, but the smoke was really intense.
   ``By the time we got to the second floor it was really hot. As
soon as we got outside, it went poof. It just went poof.''
   Caroline Boatman, who was at a bar a block and a half away, said
several bar patrons left with her and began shouting outside to
awaken people in the neighborhood. She said several people joined
together to catch residents who jumped from windows when the
building began collapsing.
   ``I opened the window and some people were shouting to me. I
just jumped and they caught me,'' said David Bedwell, 24, who
jumped from the second flood in his underwear.
   ``There was no fire yet, but then David (Bedwell) jumped out
.... and others saw him and began jumping too,'' Ms. Boatman said.
   It took five hours for 165 firefighters using 30 pieces of
equipment to bring the fire under control. Authorities predicted it
would be some time before investigators determined the cause.
   The only person hospitalized was Jae Ahn, 31, listed in fair
condition with a spinal injury she suffered when she jumped from
her second-story apartment.
   ``The floor exploded, and at the same time the ceiling collapsed
down,'' said her husband, Young Ahn, a foreign exchange student at
the University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee.
   Ahn lowered himself out a window using an electrical cord, but
it broke and he fell to the ground. His wife then jumped holding
the couple's 23-month-old daughter in her arms. The child suffered
only scrapes to the face.
   Aside from destroying the paint store and the apartments above
it, the fire also damaged a duplex next door, and two taverns.
   Twenty-eight people were left homeless, and all received
assistance from the Milwaukee chapter of the American Red Cross.
</TEXT>
