<2ND_LINE>AM-Burglar Bond,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Busy Burglar Gets Hit With Big Bond</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $10,000 bond couldn't hold a man who
has since been accused of 194 counts of burglary, so a judge has
multiplied the defendant's bond by 1,000 _ to $10 million.
   Judge Mike McDonald said he did not realize Dwight Christopher
had a record of past burglary convictions and had other charges
pending when he set his bond at $10,000 on March 4 after he was
booked with a count of burglary.
   ``He bonded out within an hour and a defense attorney caught him
coming out the window of a house the next day,'' McDonald said
Sunday.
   Christopher, 35, of Baton Rouge, was arrested again on March 16
and an investigation led to all the charges of committing 194
burglaries since July 1987 to support an alleged $300- to
$500-per-day cocaine habit, said police Officer Jeff Wesley.
   After learning that Christopher had a five-page rap sheet,
McDonald ordered him held without bond Friday, but was told he
couldn't legally do that.
   ``I believe that Mr. Christopher is a threat to society, and I
believe that I can hold him without bond, but just to be safe I
placed a $10 million bond on him,'' McDonald said.
   Christopher was released from the Louisiana State Penitentiary
last year after serving nine years of a 30-year sentence for
burglary.
   In addition to the burglary charges, Christopher is being held
on counts of second-degree battery, auto theft and resisting an
officer, booking records show.
</TEXT>
