<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Child Abduction,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Sends Reagan Legislation for Return of Abducted Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House passed and sent to President Reagan
on Monday a bill providing for the prompt return of children
abducted from a parent and taken to another country, often by the
other parent.
   The measure, approved by voice vote, would implement an
international treaty on child abduction that the United States
signed in 1981 and the Senate approved five years later.
   The House, which had passed an almost identical bill March 28,
approved on Monday a slightly different Senate version giving
jurisdiction over international child abduction cases to both state
and federal courts.
   The measure is intended to remove difficult, time-consuming
legal issues involved in returning children abducted to another
country, or helping foreign parents recover children wrongfully
taken to the United States.
