<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Election     04-25 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Election,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chirac Rallies Forces, Refuses To Negotiate With Far Right</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Jacques Chirac, desperate for votes in the
election runoff against President Francois Mitterrand, rallied
conservative forces Monday but still refused to deal with the
extreme-right National Front.
   Nearly all political analysis focused on Chirac's need to
attract supporters from National Front leader Jean-Marie Le Pen,
who won a stunning 14.4 percent of the vote in Sunday's first-round.
   The premier, head of the neo-Gaullist Rally for the Republic
party, garnered only 19.9 percent of the vote. He was far behind
the president who led all challengers with 34 percent.
   Mitterand, a Socialist, is heavily favored to win a second
seven-year term in the May 8 runoff.
   The Chirac campaign announced a televised debate between the
premier and the 71-year-old Mitterrand had been scheduled for
Thursday, an encounter they believe can only help Chirac.
   By Monday afternoon, 99 percent of the vote had been counted,
lacking only returns from French Polynesia.
   Former center-right Premier Raymond Barre, 64, who finished
third with 16.6 percent, immediately threw his support behind
Chirac, 55, and called on his voters to do the same.
   On Monday, the centrist Union for French Democracy, which had
backed Barre, also gave Chirac its endorsement.
   It was not clear, however, how many of Barre supporters would
actually vote for Chirac. Polls indicate a significant number could
cross over to Mitterrand, who has moved markedly to the center
since becoming president in 1981.
   Le Pen, 59, whose campaign focused on curbing immigration and
crime, said he would wait until a major National Front rally May 1
to announce what counsel he would give his voters.
   If Chirac wants his votes, Le Pen said, he will have to announce
``concrete acts in the area of housing, in the area of subsidies to
immigrants ... and also in the area of family allocations.''
   One of the National Front's main arguments is that immigrants
are taking French jobs, overburdening the French welfare system and
making less money available to help needy French citizens.
   ``It is up to Jacques Chirac ... to define what electoral
majority is possible for him,'' Le Pen said. ``Then we will see if
that jibes with what we feel it should be.''
   Le Pen said the vote of his supporters depended on their
individual choice, but he added: ``It is certain that if I give a
warm counsel, it has a good chance of being widely followed.''
   Chirac called a meeting of his Cabinet on Monday and told them:
``It goes without saying that no negotiation will be held with
anybody.''
   Nonetheless, the subject of immigration is popping up with
increasing frequency in the remarks of both Chirac and his aides.
   ``He (Chirac) already has taken on Le Pen's themes and ideas,''
said Socialist Party spokesman Jean-Jack Queyranne. ``Will he also
take the men and allow them ministerial portfolios?''
   Chirac noted that Sunday's voting carried a message: ``It is up
to the (conservative) candidate to respond to the preoccupations of
the French people, to their expectations, to their hopes such as
they have been expressed (by the vote).''
   Alain Juppe, budget minister and spokesman for the Chirac
campaign, said the National Front performance was a message that
was based on three or four ideas.
   ``The first is that immigration is a problem of French society
today and that we perhaps have not done enough in this area and
that we must tackle the problem with respect to our values and our
convictions,'' he said.
   Juppe said Chirac must ``rally a wide range of the French to
avoid a new period of Socialism, of laxness and undoubted decline
and political troubles for France.''
   Francois Leotard, Chirac's culture minister, said the National
Front has indicated that ``things that are totally unacceptable for
the immense majority of French, and things which can be discussed.''
   ``Let us try to make the distinction between all of that, but
without negotiating anything whatever with anybody. Xenophobia and
racism are not for us.''
   Lionel Jospin, first secretary of the Socialist Party, said the
voters had shown Sunday that ``Chirac does not inspire confidence.
They don't think that he can be president.''
</TEXT>
