<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz     04-25 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Tells Denmark To Meet Responsibilities Under NATO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz on
Monday urged Denmark to ``measure up'' to its NATO responsibilities
and to stop a resolution that would effectively ban allied ships
from Danish ports.
   Shultz met with Danish Foreign Minister Uffe Ellemann-Jensen to
restate U.S. concerns about a Danish Parliament motion which
demands that visiting warships not carry nuclear arms into Danish
harbors.
   ``It constitutes a real problem,'' Shultz said of the April 14
motion.
   Denmark's minority center-right government opposed the measure
and has called for early elections May 10.
   ``If you like the benefits (of NATO membership) ... then you
ought to like the responsibilities that go with making that
possible,'' Shultz said.
   He met with Ellemann-Jensen after briefing NATO foreign
ministers on his talks last week in Moscow with Soviet leaders.
   The talks were held to prepare for the May 29-June 2 summit
meeting between President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev. Shultz said prospects for a treaty by then to halve U.S.
and Soviet strategic nuclear arms were dim.
   ``It's extremely difficult to get there. There are hard issues
to get at. They involve a lot of pick-and-shovel work,'' he said.
   The issues deal with verification of compliance and counting
different arms systems under a Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty,
Shultz told reporters at NATO headquarters.
   He said he would continue negotiating after the summit in the
last months of the Reagan administration.
   ``We'll keep at it, we're not going to stop,'' he said, citing
``broad bipartisan support'' for a START accord in the United
States.
   He denied superpower relations had slumped since last year's
signing of a treaty to remove hundreds of medium-range nuclear
missiles from Europe.
   Citing Moscow's decision to withdraw its troops from
Afghanistan, Shultz said, ``I think the picture is one in which we
see general progress.''
   Ellemann-Jensen said his government was looking to the May 10
elections for an answer to the NATO problem.
   ``We want to get a clear message from our voters that they want
Denmark to remain a full member of the alliance,'' he said. ``If we
get the signal from the voters we are asking for it will be
possible to reach a fair solution.''
   That means Denmark would stick by its current ban on nuclear
arms on its soil but would not demand a declaration from visiting
ships, he said.
   U.S. and British warships, as a matter of policy, never say if
their warships carry nuclear arms. The Danish resolution has led
Britain to suspend visits to Denmark by Royal Navy vessels.
   Ellemann-Jensen said, ``Both the Americans and the British have
made it clear many times it would be necessary to discuss the full
participation of Denmark in military matters if we'' effectively
banned allied warships from these two countries.
   Shultz said the parliamentary resolution, while an internal
Danish matter, has NATO-wide implications. Norway also formally
bans nuclear arms from its territory and there have been calls
there for a motion similar to the one in Denmark.
   Denmark bans the basing of allied troops on its soil in
peacetime, relying on the United States and Britain to reinforce
its territory in times of crisis.
   Shultz said NATO membership yields benefits but ``it also
entails responsibilities. The two things go together and it is up
to all of us to measure up as best as we can to our
responsibilities.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
