<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Explosions     04-25 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Explosions,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Blacks Convicted Of Murder In 1985 Land Mine Blasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two alleged African National
Congress guerrillas were convicted of murder Monday in connection
with land mine explosions that killed seven people in 1985.
   One of the defendants, Mzondileli Nondula, was found guilty of
planting a mine that killed two white woman and four white children
as they drove in a pickup truck near the Zimbabwe border in
December 1985.
   His co-defendant, Mthetheleli Mncube, was convicted of laying a
mine that killed a black farm worker in the same area in November
1985. Mncube also was convicted of murdering two white policemen
while trying to escape following his arrest in 1986.
   Both defendants pleaded innocent. Defense lawyers are scheduled
to present arguments Tuesday in an effort to avoid death sentences
for the pair.
   Evidence presented during a six-month trial in the northern town
of Messina indicated that both men received military training at
ANC facilities in Angola, Tanzania and Zambia.
   The ANC, outlawed in South Africa, has waged a bombing and
sabotage campaign since 1961 aimed at ending white-minority rule.
   Mncube described himself during the trial as ``an ANC soldier,''
but both he and Nondula said they were tortured by police before
signing confessions. In a separate development Monday, the
state-run South African Broadcasting Corp. reported that a black
policeman was shot dead by an unknown assailant near Newcastle in
northern Natal province.
   The broadcasting company said investigators found cartridges at
the scene from a Soviet-made AK-47 automatic rifle _ a weapon which
authorities say is used by ANC guerrillas.
   Black policemen have been frequent targets of militants who
consider them collaborators with the white-led government.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
