<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Laos     04-25 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Laos,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Laos Agrees to Excavate Crash Site for Missing U.S. Pilots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laos is conducting a joint excavation with the
United States at a site where an American plane is believed to have
crashed during the Vietnam war, the State Department announced
Monday.
   U.S. and Lao officials have been surveying the site in recent
days, and the full American excavation team is expected in Laos
later this week, according to the statement. The digging will take
seven to 10 days.
   This is the third joint excavation as part of U.S. attempts to
account for 555 servicemen missing in Laos for over 15 years. The
two previous ones took place in February 1985 and February 1986,
and a number of remains were retrieved.
   Laos' communist government agreed last August to resume efforts
to account for MIAs after apparently suspending them since the 1986
excavation. In return, the United States has pledged to respond to
Laos' calls for humanitarian assistance.
   ``The United States government appreciates this further step by
the Lao government in our cooperative effort to resolve the issue
of Americans sitll missing or otherwise unaccounted for in Laos as
a result of the war,'' the State Department said.
   Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said she did not know
where the current excavation would take place. The previous two
were in Savannakhet and Saravane provinces, Laos' southern
panhandle area between Thailand and Vietnam.
   Many of the MIAs in Laos were airmen shot down on missions
against the Ho Chi Minh Trail, which North Vietnamese communist
forces used to ferry men and supplies to South Vietnam.
   There are 2,411 American servicemen still unaccounted for in all
of Southeast Asia, according to the Defense Department.
</TEXT>
