<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson-California     04-25 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-California,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Plams Big Effort in California, Manager Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson plans to pour as much as $3
million into California and spend the better part of a month
campaigning there in an all-out effort to win in the nation's most
populous state, his campaign chairman said Monday.
   ``California will be a major player in the presidential
sweepstakes,'' said California Assembly Speaker Willie Brown, who
heads up Jackson's national presidential campaign.
   Noting that it is virtually impossible for either Democratic
front-runner Michael Dukakis or Jackson to get the necessary 2,081
delegates to win the nomination before California's June 7 primary,
Brown said, ``No matter what happens between now and then, we are a
player.''
   With his eye on the state's 314 delegates, Jackson will campaign
in Calfornia from May 5 through May 28, making only about two
forays to other states during that time, Brown told reporters
during a visit to the capital.
   For the first time in the campaign, Jackson may be able to
compete financially because his fund raising has picked up
tremendously, Brown said.
   ``In every place Jackson has been a candidate he has been
outspent three or four or five to one. California is a
media-oriented market. The way our money is coming in for us now,
it's clear we are going to be better than competitive in
California,'' he said.
   Dukakis has led the Democratic field in fund raising and
spending since the beginning of the primary season, but during
March he was not far ahead of Jackson, raising $2.4 million to
Jackson's $2 million.
   Jackson is counting on winning votes from groups that have
supported him in other states, including peace activists,
environmentalists and gay voters, as well as his strong black
constituency, Brown said.
   The battle for the state's sizable Hispanic population is
expected to be intense, with Jackson bringing in former New Mexico
Gov. Toney Anaya and former state health director Mario Obledo to
campaign for him. Dukakis speaks fluent Spanish and has done well
among Hispanics in other states.
   Brown said that if Jackson does well among his constituent
groups and can double the white vote that he got in 1984, he ``is
in a position to spring a surprise in California.''
   Jackson's campaign also hopes to get Dukakis to participate in
joint appearances and debates, but so far only one debate is
scheduled in California, Brown said.
   California is an issue-based state with such regional concerns
as offshore drilling, timber harvesting and coastal protection,
Brown said.
   ``Jackson is a lot smarter than you think,'' he said. ``He is
already hip on those issues.''
   Brown sought to undo recent comments he made about Jackson being
a vice presidential prospect if he does not win the presidential
nomination.
   He said Jackson is running for president only. He said that in
answering questions from reporters about the second spot on the
Democratic ticket, ``sometimes we're not as judicious in our
answers as we should be.''
   He said he knew of no conversations between Jackson aides and
the Dukakis camp about the vice presidential issue.
</TEXT>
