<DOCNO> AP880425-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Scotus-Conservatives     04-25 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Conservatives,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court's Conservative Majority Shakes Liberals With Civil Rights
Action</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court is flexing its conservative
muscle, resurrecting fears among liberals that President Reagan may
have succeeded in pushing the court to the right.
   In a move that sparked sharp criticism and dire predictions from
opponents, a 5-4 court majority said Monday it is thinking about
overturning a 1976 decision considered a key civil rights victory.
   The ruling 12 years ago, never undone by Congress, interpreted a
Civil War-era law as permitting lawsuits for monetary damages
against private businesses and individuals over alleged racial
discrimination.
   The decision in Runyon vs. McCrary, adopted in hundreds of lower
court cases since, has become what one civil rights lawyer called
``a major strand of the civil rights enforcement infrastructure.''
   Four justices said Monday's announcement could shake minorities'
faith in the court.
   ``Time alone will tell whether the erosion of faith is
unnecessarily precipitous,'' said Justice John Paul Stevens, a
swing vote who most often sides with the court's liberals. ``But in
the meantime some of the harm that will flow from today's order may
never be completely undone.''
   Ira Glasser, executive director of the American Civil Liberties
Union, agreed. ``The message is there's a new court and previous
rulings are up for grabs,'' he said. ``If this decision possibly
can be overturned, perhaps a lot more are endangered.''
   The court's three Reagan appointees _ Justices Sandra Day
O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy _ joined Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist and Byron R. White in voting to
restudy the 1976 decision.
   Joining Stevens in dissent were Justices William J. Brennan and
Thurgood Marshall, the court's leading liberals; and Justice Harry
A. Blackmun, another swing vote.
   Will there be five votes to overturn the 1976 precedent?
   Rehnquist, long the court's most conservative member, and White,
a conservative with a generally liberal voting record in civil
rights cases, dissented from the 1976 decision. They are two likely
votes to overturn.
   Scalia is considered as conservative as Rehnquist, and a third
vote to overturn.
   The keys may be the votes of O'Connor, who in recent years has
shown greater independence from the court's conservative bloc, and
Kennedy, whose impact to date has been minimal because he only
joined the court in February.
   Kennedy won Senate confirmation after Reagan's nomination of
Robert H. Bork was rejected.
   Bork's critics in the Senate and among civil rights
organizations said they feared his replacing centrist Lewis F.
Powell on the court could threaten 30 years of civil rights
precedents.
   In its first seven years, the Reagan administration has had
little success persuading the court to adopt the president's
conservative agenda: outlawing abortion, restoring prayers in
public schools and curtailing affirmative action.
   Kennedy, whose views on such matters are unknown, is viewed as a
staunch conservative but less ideological than Bork. The concerns
voiced during the Bork nomination fight were echoed Monday, however.
   Calling Kennedy the key to a ``new court,'' the ACLU's Glaser
said, ``Bork had an extensive record of civil rights animus and
Kennedy did not. But this isn't encouraging.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Richard Carelli has covered the Supreme Court for
The Associated Press since 1976.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1937EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NRC-GAO     04-25 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NRC-GAO,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Faults Nuclear Regulatory Commission's Investigative Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission needs to
improve its investigative office to ensure that its work is done
competently and professionally, according to a congressional study
released Monday.
   ``The important mission and critical safety role of the NRC
require that it possess a first-rate investigative capability,''
the General Accounting Office said in the study, which was released
by the NRC.
   GAO, the investigative wing of Congress, said the study was
based on the review of three investigations made within the nuclear
agency. GAO said that in two cases, the work done by the NRC's
office and inspector and auditor was not thorough enough.
   One case involved allegations by an NRC inspector that superiors
had pressured him to change findings in 1986 about safety
conditions at the Comanche Peak Steam Electric Station in Texas.
   The other involved alleged improper discussions in 1986 between
Victor Stello, the NRC's executive director of operations, and
Steve White, head of the Tennessee Valley Authority's NRC-regulated
nuclear program.
   GAO said its review supported the findings of NRC investigators
who said neither matter was improper. But in both cases GAO said
NRC investigators had not interviewed individuals with key roles.
   The third case looked into NRC's investigation of how a copy of
an internal NRC document turned up in 1985 in the files of the
Louisiana Power and Light Co.'s Waterford III plant _ along with a
memo from LPL's holding company saying the document had been
``received from sources inside'' the NRC.
   GAO said notations on the copy indicated it was duplicated from
the file copy in the office of NRC Commissioner Thomas Roberts, who
was in charge of investigating the alleged leak.
   GAO was critical of the ``very limited'' investigation made by
Roberts, but GAO said it was unable to determine how the copy
reached the regulated utility.
   ``A properly conducted investigation might have provided NRC
with the identity'' of the leaker, according to GAO.
   The case, GAO said, ``demonstrated that a regulated utility
secured unauthorized access to NRC documents. The ability to obtain
such materials could impact on the NRC's enforcement program,
licensing functions and regulatory procedures.''
   ``The NRC should assure that its investigators conduct their
work in a competent manner using professional standards,'' said
GAO, adding that there is a lack of coordination between the NRC's
office of investigations and office of inspector and auditor.
   NRC Chairman Lando Zech said in a statement accompanying the GAO
study that he agrees the agency needs a first-rate investigative
capability.
   ``The commission will give careful consideration to (the) entire
report in our continuing efforts to assure that we carry out our
investigative responsibilities fairly and efficiently,'' Zech said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1938EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-OPEC 1stLd-Writethru a0672 04-25 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OPEC, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0672,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Ministers Prepare for Unusual Oil Meeting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: to UPDATE with closing prices, SUBS 7th graf pvs: Futures
prices; uppicks 8th graf: Senior officials...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC and independent oil exporters on
Monday made last-minute preparations for a series of meetings aimed
at tightening oil supplies and driving prices up further.
   Officials of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
and rival oil producers expressed cautious optimism that an
agreement could be reached this week on joint measures to support
prices.
   ``Any meeting between OPEC and non-OPEC (nations) is important,
but this one is particularly so because prices seem to be weak,''
said Indonesian delegate Subroto, a former oil minister.
   He said all 13 countries participating in the meetings Tuesday
were ``eager to do something'' to prop up prices.
   World oil markets appeared to be taking a cautiously optimistic
stance on the upcoming conferences.
   In the European spot, or non-contract, market, the price of
Brent crude from the North Sea was up about 10 cents a barrel, at
$17.25, in late trading, compared with last Friday's close. Traders
said activity was light.
   Futures prices also edged upward on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, where contracts for June delivery of West Texas
Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, closed at $18.40 per
barrel, up 10 cents from Friday.
   Senior officials from Mexico, Colombia, Egypt, Angola, Oman,
Malaysia, Brunei and China were to meet Tuesday and Wednesday with
OPEC's price monitoring committee, comprised of the oil ministers
of Saudi Arabia, Indonesia, Venezuela, Nigeria and Algeria.
   That is to be followed on Thursday by a meeting of all 13 OPEC
members.
   Also in Vienna, though not expected to participate in the joint
meetings, was Kent Hance, a member of the Texas Railroad
Commission, which regulates the state's oil production of 2 million
42-gallon barrels a day. He has indicated he plans to meet
individually with ministers to discuss his concern about
instability in the oil market.
   Mexico's oil minister, Fernando Hiriart Balderrama, told
reporters that Mexico was ready to accept a 5 percent cut in its
oil exports if other producers agreed to do the same. He declined
to be specific about how many, or which, others must go along.
   Mexico exports about 1.4 million barrels a day of its total
daily output of 2.9 million.
   ``We know that it might be difficult to reach unanimity'' at
this week's meetings, Hiriart Balderrama said through an
interpreter. ``But we expect a substantial number of countries to
do something similar'' to Mexico's proposed cut.
   Together, the eight non-OPEC countries represented in Vienna
produce about 8 million barrels a day, compared with OPEC's
estimated output of between 17.5 million and 18 million barrels
daily.
   Industry analysts expressed doubt that this week's meeting could
reach a concrete agreement on OPEC and non-OPEC production cuts.
But some said it could mark a turning point in OPEC's long and
largely unsuccessful campaign to win closer cooperation with rival
producers.
   The world's two biggest oil producers _ the Soviet Union and the
United States _ were not invited to the Vienna meeting.
</TEXT>
