<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Singleton     04-25 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Singleton,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rapist-Mutilator Ends Parole</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Larry Singleton, who raped a young woman
and cut off her forearms with an ax a decade ago, was freed from
parole Monday and headed for an undisclosed location, his case
continuing to arouse public outrage.
   ``He was a free man according to law at 12:01 (a.m.) today, and
he just simply walked off parole from the place he was located,''
said Bob Gore, spokesman for the California Department of
Corrections.
   ``We have no legal right to follow him any further and no
statutory means of requiring him to go somewhere,'' he said.
   Bob Plath, a member of an inmate support group, said he knew
where Singleton planned to go but could not reveal the location for
fear someone might hurt Singleton.
   Singleton, 60, was convicted of abducting a teen-age hitchhiker,
raping her and then hacking off her forearms near Modesto, 45 miles
east of San Francisco, in 1978. He served eight years of a 14-year
sentence.
   He was under no obligation to tell officials where he planned to
go when his year of parole expired, and gave only noncommital
answers when asked, Gore said.
   ``I think he is very dangerous and unstable. I think he's
operating under a delusion (of innocence),'' said Donald Stahl,
Stanislaus County district attorney. ``I don't know what will
happen when the pressure gets to be too much or if he falls off the
wagon.''
   Singleton, who was drinking heavily the day of the attack, has
not had alcohol during his imprisonment or parole, officials said.
   Singleton's victim, Mary Vincent, is living at an undisclosed
location and still fears Singleton. Her lawyer said she wants to
remain undisturbed and in seclusion.
   Singleton has friends and supporters who do not accept his
claims of innocence but believe he will not be dangerous if he is
lef alone and can stay with people who care about him.
   ``While we can't forget, can't we forgive?'' said Plath, a Marin
County lawyer.
   Angry protests followed Singleton from town to town last year
when officials tried to place him in several San Francisco Bay area
communities on parole. Singleton was finally put in a small trailer
on the grounds of San Quentin prison to complete his parole, but a
few days ago he was moved to an undisclosed location.
   The protests now have shifted north to Azalea, Ore., where
Singleton reportedly will join The Bride of Christ Church after
visiting family in Florida. Frightened residents have denounced the
plan, and earlier this month someone fired a shotgun at church
buildings and vehicles.
</TEXT>
