<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FishTalks     04-25 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fish Talks,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Official To Discuss Bering Sea Fish Ban With
Other Nations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top State Department official said Monday he
will meet with representatives of Japan, South Korea, China and
Poland about a possible voluntary agreement to ban fishing in an
area of the Bering Sea that scientists fear is being overfished.
   Edward Wolfe, ambassador of oceans and fisheries, said he will
brief the four nations in the next few days on U.S.-Soviet fishing
talks last week that included discussion of a moratorium on fishing
in the Bering Sea's so-called ``doughnut hole.''
   While no agreement was reached between the United States and the
Soviet Union over the future of fishing in the ``doughnut hole,''
another round of meetings is expected in Moscow later this spring.
   Wolfe earlier had said the U.S.-Soviet negotiations were
``exploratory'' and involved a ``good exchange of views.''
   Both countries are concerned that overfishing in the ``doughnut
hole,'' by foreign trawlers _ including those from Japan, South
Korea, China and Poland _ could cause a decline in the catch in the
U.S. and Soviet fishing zones that surround the area.
   The 4,500-square mile ``doughnut hole'' is considered one of the
richest fishing grounds in the world and the catch in the area has
grown from about 200,000 metric tons to more than 1 million metric
tons over the past four years.
   Both the Soviets and the U.S. would prefer a voluntary ban on
fishing in the ``doughnut hole.'' The moratorium could be temporary
or permanent as scientists study the fish stocks in the Bering Sea.
</TEXT>
