<HEAD>Bush, With Nomination in Hand, Says He'll Keep Campaigning</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with later comments, hecklers, subbing 4 grafs for
grafs 3-4 pvs, The vice ... campaigning; subs 7 grafs for last 5
grafs pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, campaigning on the eve of the
primary that should put him over the top, promised Monday to keep
``showing the flag'' no matter how firm his grip on the Republican
presidential nomination.
   ``I still want to continue to campaign through the primary
season,'' Bush told the Greater Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce.
   Bush spent the day traveling and speaking in the state, where he
is expected to top the 1,139 delegates needed for the GOP
nomination in Tuesday's primary.
   Most of his remarks were routine, but he answered back after
being met at the Scranton-Wilkes Barre airport by a dozen or so
hecklers, some of them bearing signs urging the United States to
end its aid to the Contras in Nicaragua.
   ``I'm glad to see the (Jesse) Jackson supporters here, or maybe
the Mike Dukakis supporters,'' he said. ``I will welcome them in
debate, I will welcome taking on their ticket and we will beat them
in the fall.''
   He has been virtually unopposed for the Republican nomination
since the withdrawal last month of Sen. Bob Dole. His only
remaining opponent, Pat Robertson, has ceased active campaigning.
   Bush, who has said he expects to face Democrat Michael Dukakis
in the fall election, struck at Democrats who he said ``talk about
despair and agony.''
   ``You're going to see a clear choice'' in the general election,
he said.
   He called Pittsburgh ``tough and resilient'' and compared its
revival to his own.
   ``You took it on the chin'' economically in the 1970s and early
1980s, Bush said.
   ``I know what it's like to be knocked to the canvas,'' he said,
noting his defeat in the Iowa caucuses.
   But Bush said he picked himself up and started anew, calling
that ``a parallel to what you demonstrated here.''
   Despite his apparently insurmountable lead, he said, ``I'm still
showing the flag in Pennsylvania.''
   At campaign stops through the day, Bush:
   _Said he intends to take part in general-election debates with
the Democratic nominee, but he would not be pinned down on dates or
format.
   ``There will be debates. I'm looking forward to them, he said.
But he also said, in an interview with local reporters, ``I'm not
going to let some outside group, even within my own party, set the
agenda.''
   _Said he is in full accord with President Reagan's promise to
veto trade legislation nearing final congressional approval but
also said he hoped some other way could be found to notify workers
of impending plant closings.
   The bill contains a provision requiring 60 days notice when
plants are to be shut down. ``I know it's an emotional issue but it
interferes with our ability to compete.''
   _Told a Republican veterans' rally he would try to maintain the
defense buildup begun by Reagan. ``I'll never be afraid to reach
out for peace, but I'll do it with my eyes open,'' he said.
</TEXT>
