<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Emigration     04-25 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Emigration,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Emigration Documents Worry Soviet Jews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jews seeking to emigrate are receiving revised
invitations from Israel that promise to provide them with visas in
Romania, activists said Monday.
   The activists said the change is apparently part of an effort to
boost emigration to the Jewish state. But it could make it
difficult for Jews to settle anywhere else, they said.
   Invitations from family members and the Israeli government are
the official basis on which Jews are allowed to leave. Visas now
come through the Dutch Embassy, which has handled Israel's
interests since the Kremlin broke relations after the 1967 Middle
East war.
   Sergei Mkrtchyan said Monday he knew of about a half a dozen
people who did not emigrate because the Soviet visa office said
they could go only to Israel with the new invitations.
   ``They rejected it because they wanted to go to America,'' he
said in a telephone interview.
   According to the new invitations, Israeli visas will be issued
in Bucharest, capital of Romania, the only Soviet bloc nation that
has formal relations with Israel.
   Michael Stolar, an American citizen who remains in Moscow
because his Soviet wife is refused permission to leave, said Jews
who want to go somewhere other than Israel are worried.
   ``A lot of people are talking about the problem _ whether it
will increase or decrease emigration, whether the Soviets will let
more people out or whether fewer people will apply,'' he said.
   Both he and Mkrtchyan want to go to Israel and are active in a
group called ``Poor Relatives,'' for people who are denied
permission to leave because a family member will not waive
financial obligations imposed by law.
   They said the new invitations began arriving about three weeks
ago and the long-term effect is unclear.
   In the past, many Soviet Jews left the country through Vienna,
and traveled from there to Western Europe, the United States or
Israel.
   Mkrtchyan said it could be difficult for Jews to go anywhere
except Israel from Bucharest because of limited connections and
because a Jew arriving in Israel automatically becomes an Israeli
citizen, limiting his ability to settle elsewhere.
   Jews who emigrate from the Soviet Union lose their Soviet
citizenship.
   Israel wants Soviet Jews to settle there and has promoted a
direct air link via Romania. Among those emigrating through
Bucharest was Josef Begun, a prominent Soviet Jew who emigrated in
January.
   According to the Union of Councils for Soviet Jews, only 221 of
the 986 who emigrated in March went to Israel, and 42 traveled
through Bucharest.
   The 986 represented the highest total in 15 months. More than
8,000 Jews were allowed to emigrate in all of 1987, many more than
in any of the previous several years but still far below the peak
of 51,000 in 1979. More than 2,400 Jews emigrated in the first
three months of 1988.
   Sources said Israel instructed the Dutch Embassy to continue
issuing visas with which Jews can emigrate through Vienna or any
other transit city, but activists said that may not matter if
Soviet authorities insist on emigrants going by way of Romania.
   Requiring Jews to leave through Bucharest may increase the
number going to Israel by 5 to 10 percent, but the rest want to
settle elsewhere, Mkrtchyan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
