<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oregon Newspaper Survey Shows White Resistance to Jackson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A large number of Oregonians say Jesse
Jackson cannot win the presidential election because he is black,
but only a small number say they won't vote for him because of his
race, according to a newspaper poll.
   The Sunday Oregonian reported that only 5 percent of the voters
surveyed indicated they would not support Jackson because he is
black.
   But 30 percent of those surveyed said they doubted that Jackson
could win a presidential election.
   Pam Smith, an Oregonian who works for Jackson in Chicago as a
press aide, said the focus on race hurts Jackson.
   ``Was there a question of how would Americans accept a Greek?''
she asked, referring to Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis,
Jackson's remaining rival for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
   The poll of 600 registered voters was conducted for the
newspaper April 11-16 by Griggs-Anderson Research. It included
Democrats, Republicans and independant voters.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Brigham Young Place-Kicker Stumps for Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Technically, Jason Chaffetz isn't a member
of the Dukakis family, but the Brigham Young University
place-kicker is like one of the clan when it comes to the
Massachusetts governor's bid for the presidency.
   Chaffetz, the son of Kitty Dukakis' first husband and his wife,
says a close relationship with the family spurred him to stump
through Georgia and Iowa, and also led him to take the role of Utah
co-chairman for Dukakis' Utah effort.
   Sandwiching campaigning between football workouts and semester
finals, Chaffetz, 21, devoted the past few weeks to preparations
for Monday night's statewide political caucuses.
   Chaffetz is linked to the presidential hopeful through his
half-brother, John Dukakis, who remained with his mother after she
and John's father, John Chaffetz, were divorced.
   ``I really believe in Michael Dukakis, and the kind of moral
leadership he's had for my brother,'' Chaffetz said. ``If he can be
a stepfather for my brother, he can be a stepfather for the
nation.''
