<HEAD>Ohio Congressmen Urge Candidates to Support Space Funding</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Ohio's congressional delegation on
Monday called on the presidential candidates to focus more
attention on the U.S. space program during their campaigns.
   ``As someone with first-hand experience in both the race for
space and the race for the presidency ... I know it can be easier
to get into orbit than into the White House,'' said Sen. John
Glenn, D-Ohio. ``But once in the White House, the next president
must be committed to a strong American presence in space.''
   Glenn, a former astronaut who was the first American to orbit
the earth, ran for the Democratic nomination for president four
years ago.
   He said other countries besides the United States and the Soviet
Union are developing space programs. Consequently, he said, the
U.S. space program ``will help determine our position of political
leadership among nations for decades to come.''
   Glenn and Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, spoke from Washington
via satellite to a news conference in Cleveland.
   ``A strong civilian space program is our future,'' Metzenbaum
said. ``It will enable us to explore new horizons. It will create
new jobs ... and it will give us the technology to leap ahead in
medicine, communications and electronics here at home.''
</TEXT>
