<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp     04-25 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Calls for More Volunteers, Iraq Says New Missile Tested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran called Monday for the nation's youth
to prepare to go quickly to the battlefront. Iraq announced it has
successfully tested a new missile capable of reaching deep into
Iranian territory.
   President Ali Khamenei of Iran, speaking on Tehran Radio, said
young Iranians ``should get ready to to be sent to the fronts and
to fight against the enemies of the Islamic revolution in a most
extensive way.''
   ``The young people, especially those who have received training
and who are ready, should move forward their allotted time for
dispatch and go earlier. Others too should continue their dispatch
... in an accelerated form,'' he said.
   Tehran Radio said Khamenei spoke after a meeting of the Supreme
War Effort Council. The broadcast was monitored in Cyprus.
   Iran suffered a battlefield setback 10 days ago when Iraqi
forces recaptured the Faw peninsula in southern Iraq. It had been
seized by Iranian troops in February 1986.
   The two countries have been at war since September 1980.
   Iraq's official news agency, also monitored in Cyprus, said a
powerful new surface-to-surface missile has been tested
successfully.
   The announcement could serve as a warning to Iran not to respond
to the loss of Faw by resuming the deadly missile duel known as the
``war of the cities.'' The last such battle lasted from Feb. 29 to
last Thursday, with the capitals of Baghdad and Tehran being
frequent targets.
   Brig. Hussein Kamel Hassan, director of Iraq's military
industries, informed President Saddam Hussein that the new missile
named al-Abass has a range of 550 miles, according to the news
agency.
   Iraq has used al-Hussein missiles since last August in the duel
with Iran.
   It claimed the al-Hussein missiles were domestically produced,
but Western military analysts believe they are Soviet-designed SS-1
Scud-B weapons with special rocket boosters to give them a range of
up to 400 miles.
   The agency report gave no details of the new missile.
   Western analysts said they thought Iraq may have obtained a
larger missile that also could be equipped with boosters.
   There was a lull in action along the 730-mile front. Both sides
reported scattered skirmishes and artillery duels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
