<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-25 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Storms In The South, Heavy Snow in Montana And Wyoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong thunderstorms shook parts of the South on Monday,
generating tornadoes that caused damage in Georgia and the Florida
Keys, and snow fell in the northern Rockies and the northern Plains.
   Thunderstorms, some severe, rolled across southern sections of
Alabama and Georgia during the morning.
   Two tornadoes touched down in rural Lowndes County in southern
Georgia, heavily damaging several homes and taking down trees and
power lines. No one was hurt.
   ``We've had extensive damage. There's been quite a few houses
which are wiped out completely,'' Lowndes County sheriff's deputy
Robert Rudd said. ``We've got lines down all over the area.''
   Later in the day, in western Georgia, a powerful storm system
spawned at least one tornado in Carroll County but it did not touch
down.
   In Naylor, Ga., the Volunteer Fire Department was heavily
damaged, and fire trucks held up what was left of the battered
building.
   By early afternoon, severe thunderstorms developed rapidly
across northern sections of Mississippi and Alabama as well as
west-central Georgia, and raced eastward at speeds up to 65 mph. A
severe thunderstorm over northwestern Alabama dropped hail as big
as golf balls near Goodsprings, about 25 miles northwest of
Birmingham.
   Severe thunderstorms also produced 1\-inch hail at Anniston,
Ala. One-inch hail pelted Carrollton, Ga., Coldwater, Ala., and
Cleburne County, Ala., during the afternoon. Marble-size hail fell
at Pinson, Ala., and covered the ground at Jones Chapel, Ala.
   ``The hail beat my car all to pieces,'' said Ellen Chaney of
Lowndes County, Ga.
   During the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, 1.02 inches of rain fell
at Albany, Ga.
   In Florida, a waterspout sighted near Key West moved ashore as a
tornado and caused some property damage on Stock Island, the
National Weather Service said.
   Elsewhere, light rain and spotty showers extended from
southeastern Kansas into western Kentucky.
   Heavy snow warnings were posted for south-central Montana and
mountains and foothills of central Montana and snow advisories were
posted for the mountains of northwestern Wyoming and the Big Horn
Mountains of northeastern Wyoming.
   By late morning, 5 inches of snow had fallen at both Bear Lodge
and Arrowhead Lodge in the Big Horn Mountains. Up to 8 inches of
snow was expected in the Big Horns.
   A snow advisory was also posted for Utah's northern mountains
above 5,500 feet.
   A winter storm watch was posted overnight for southwestern South
Dakota as the heart of the storm system was expected to move from
Wyoming into Nebraska.
   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 27 degrees at Cody, Wyo.,
to 92 at West Palm Beach, Fla. The morning low was 17 degrees at
Alamosa, Colo.
   For Tuesday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from
eastern Tennessee through the Carolinas; light rain and showers
over the central Plains, the upper and middle Mississippi Valley
and the western Great Lakesl and showers from western Pennsylvania
to Vermont.
   Highs in the 40s and 50s were predicted from the northern and
central Rocky Mountains through the western Great Lakes, and across
northern New England; in the 60s from southeastern Kansas across
the Tennessee and Ohio valleys to the mid Atlantic Coast, and
across the Pacific Northwest through northern California and into
northern Arizona; in the 90s in the desert Southwest; and in the
70s and 80s over most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
