<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OilSpill     04-25 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Spill,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Sacrifice Marsh To Defend Other Wetland Areas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARTINEZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials planned Monday to sacrifice a
section of wildlife-rich marshland to an oil spill, saying the
tactic would save hundreds more acres of wetlands.
   ``We're trying to keep new areas from becoming oiled,'' said
Brian Hunter of the state Department of Fish and Game. ``We're
willing to try and capture as much oil as we can in 20 acres of
marsh.''
   About 21,000 gallons of thick, unrefined crude gushed Saturday
from a storage tank at Shell Oil Co.'s Martinez refinery, 30 miles
northeast of San Francisco.
   By Monday morning, a slick stretched for 10 miles in Suisun Bay
and Carquinez Strait but was beginning to dissipate in tidal
currents. The biggest concentration was confined to an area of
marshland and coated at least 100 birds.
   Coast Guard spotter planes, six vessels with oil skimmers and 16
vacuum tank-trucks raced to capture oil and save wetland animals.
Floating oil booms were laid in the water to keep oil away from
wildlife areas.
   Coast Guard spokesman Ken Massey estimated it could take until
next week to clean up the spill.
   Shell acknowledged responsibility for the spill, and Massey said
the company would have to pay for the costs of the clean-up and
damages, which would include new paint for the bottoms of thousands
of pleasure boats in area marinas.
   There was no immediate estimate of the damage.
   Shell spokesman Bill Sharkey said the spill was the company's
worst in 73 years. The last at the 850-acre refinery occurred in
June 1986 when a tank overflowed 8,000 gallons of oil.
   By Monday about 100 birds _ including egrets, avocets, cinnamon
teals, mallard ducks, grebes, herons and the endangered clapper
rail bird _ had been rescued and taken to centers in Berkeley and
Walnut Creek for cleaning, Hunter said. The spill also threatened
many nests.
   Volunteers also reported a dozen dead muskrats, several
oil-coated turtles and a dead heron.
</TEXT>
