<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Lebanon     04-25 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Lebanon,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Sinks Dinghy Off Lebanese Coast, Two Reported Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli navy patrol boat fired on a
guerrilla craft near the southern Lebanese port city of Tyre early
Monday and sank the boat, the military reported.
   Israel radio said both people aboard the rubber dinghy were
killed in the attack at about 3 a.m.
   An army official said the navy vessel was on a routine patrol
when it spotted the boat and opened fire.
   Israel radio quoted navy commander Gen. Avraham Ben Shoshan as
saying Arab guerrillas have stepped up attempts to infiltrate
Israel by sea.
   The Israeli military had reported two similar incidents since
December.
   It said that on Feb. 28, the navy sank a boat carrying
guerrillas from Tyre for a planned attack on unspecified targets in
Israel. The army said it did not know how many people were aboard
the craft or if any were killed.
   On Dec. 11, guerrillas from Hezbollah, a pro-Iranian Shiite
Moslem group, fired at an Israeli patrol vessel, killing one
soldier, according to the military. It said the Israeli craft
returned the fire, sinking the Hezbollah boat, and four guerrillas
drowned.
