<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 2007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kuwait-Hijack 1stLd-Writethru a0695 04-25 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kuwait-Hijack, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0695,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kuwait Forms Squad to Fight Hijacking</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with prime
minister's remarks, other details. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will hire foreign experts to train
a special, 100-member anti-terrorism force to combat hijackers like
those who commandeered a Kuwait Airways jumbo jetliner this month,
security officials said Monday.
   Kuwait's crown prince and prime minister, Sheik Saad al-Abdullah
al-Sabah, meanwhile called on ``sister and friendly states'' to
arrest, try and punish the hijackers and asked for inter-Arab
cooperation to fight terrorism.
   He said he did not know if the hijackers were still in Algeria,
where the ordeal ended on its 16th day last Wednesday.
   Kuwait's move came amid growing fears in Arab states that the
7{-year-war between Iran and Iraq will increase terrorism by
pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem groups. Saudi Arabia intends to form its
own anti-terrorist squad, it was reported last month.
   The Saudis are to receive help from Gen. Ulrich Wegener,
commander of West Germany's crack anti-terrorist force. He headed
the commandos that stormed a hijacked Lufthansa jetliner in
Mogadishu, Somalia, in 1977, considered a classic anti-hijacking
operation.
   Many West European countries, including Britain, France, Italy
and West Germany, have elite units which have acted against
terrorists over the last 20 years.
   The new Kuwaiti force will be directed by the Interior Ministry
after a six-month training program by foreign experts in Kuwait and
abroad, said the security officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   They gave no details and did not identify the foreign
specialists.
   Pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems hijacked the Kuwaiti Boeing 747 with
112 people aboard April 5 as it was flying from Bangkok, Thailand,
to Kuwait. The hijackers killed two Kuwaiti passengers before the
ordeal ended in Algiers on Wednesday.
   The hijackers demanded that Kuwait release 17 terrorists
convicted for bombing the U.S. and French embassies in Kuwait in
1983. Kuwaiti officials said they would not release them.
   The hijacking ended when the gunmen slipped off the jet,
apparently after receiving a promise of safe passage to an
undisclosed country. The passengers left the plane shortly
afterward.
   Rashed Abdel-Aziz Rashed, minister of state for Cabinet affairs,
told Saudi Arabia's al-Sharq al-Awsat newspaper that Kuwait had not
been told of the hijackers' whereabouts.
   However, the right-wing daily newspaper al-Seyassa and the
radical al-Rai al-Aam daily reported Monday that Kuwaiti security
authorities, aided by unidentified foreign intelligence agencies,
have identified the hijackers. It did not elaborate.
   Rashed told al-Seyassa that ``certain powers and parties hostile
to the Arabs were behind the hijacking.'' It was an apparent
reference to Iran and the pro-Iranian, Lebanon-based Hezbollah, or
Party of God.
   Iran is Persian, not Arab. Although it shares the Moslem
religion with the Arabs, it adheres to the minority Shiite sect
that has been at odds with the predominant Sunni branch of Islam
for 1,300 years.
   The Shiite fundamentalist Hezbollah is believed to be the
umbrella group for Shiite factions holding most of the 21 foreign
hostages in Lebanon.
   The longest held is Terry Anderson, 40, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   The Kuwaiti Cabinet set up a committee to investigate the
hijacking, Rashed announced Sunday, saying ``murdering the two
Kuwaiti passengers is a crime that will not go unpunished.''
   Prime Minister Saad told editors of local and weekly newspapers
in a televised news conference Monday that tiny, oil-rich Kuwait
``alone cannot put an end to or contain the activity of terrorists.
I hereby issue a frank and sincere call to our Arab brethren to
cooperate to fight terrorism and terrorists wherever they exist.''
   ``The apprehension, trial and punishment of the (Kuwait Airways)
hijackers should take place through constructive dialogue between
us and sister and friendly states,'' Saad said.
   He also said that when the jet landed at Mashhad airport in Iran
early in its Odyssey, Iranian officials pressed the Kuwaiti team
which flew to Mashhad ``to accept all or part of the hijackers'
demands, but the Kuwaiti reply was a clear and frank rejection.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
