<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChurchBan     04-25 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Church Ban,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman, Her Children Find Temporary Haven at Another Church</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEW FERGUSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Episcopal church used a court order to
turn a family away from services because of a 9-year-old boy's
disruptive behavior, but the family found at least temporary refuge
at another house of worship.
   Sheryl Geartz, her son, Jason, and 7-year-old daughter, Jessica,
were turned away from a service Sunday at Grace Episcopal
Cathedral, Topeka's largest Episcopal congregation.
   Officials at Grace had obtained a temporary restraining order
from a district judge last week barring Jason, who they claim has
disrupted services since the family began attending the church
seven months ago.
   After being denied entry, the family was taken by a reporter to
St. David's Episcopal Church, where they attended a service without
incident. As they left, they were greeted by Harry Craig, a deacon
at the church.
   ``Literally, anyone is welcome at St. David's,'' Craig said
Monday in an interview. ``My feeling at this point is: I greeted
her, I met her children and she certainly is welcome to return.
There was no disruption.''
   Officals at Grace Cathedral said the boy had talked loudly,
pulled a fire alarm, thrown objects at worshippers and destroyed
church property during past services. The church's court action did
not specify what the boy had thrown or destroyed.
   ``The level of disturbance moved from being merely annoying to
being utterly intolerable,'' said the Rev. Robert P. Shahan, dean
of Grace Cathedral. ``We were faced with a situation in which one
person had determined her needs were paramount to the needs of the
entire congregation.''
   Ms. Geartz, who is divorced and does not work, told reporters
Sunday her son has been disruptive, but she maintained he has
emotional problems that have improved through church attendance.
   She said she went to Grace Cathedral on Sunday because she
wanted to take a stand for emotionally disturbed people. She said
she would pray this week before deciding whether to attempt to
return there.
   There was no answer to repeated calls to the Geartz residence
Monday.
   A church secretary at Grace Cathedral said she fielded 21 calls
Monday about Ms. Geartz, of which 13 endorsed the church's action
and eight were opposed.
</TEXT>
