<HEAD>India Begins Fencing Border With Pakistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India began fencing its border with
Pakistan on Monday in an effort to curb the supply of weapons to
Sikh militants fighting for a separate homeland, news reports said.
   State-run television said barbed-wire fences were being erected
along parts of the border in northern Punjab state, where India
claims Pakistan is providing support to Sikh separatists.
   Pakistan has denied the allegations.
   Predominantly Hindu India and mainly Moslem Pakistan have fought
three wars since gaining independence from Britain in 1947.
   Meanwhile, Sikh militants shot and killed seven more people in
Punjab overnight. The United News of India news agency said the
victims, six of them Sikhs, were killed in three separate attacks.
   The militants view moderate Sikhs as traitors.
   The killings brought to 815 the number of people killed in
attacks blamed on Sikh militants this year.
   Sikhs form 2 percent of India's 800 million peoeple but comprise
a majority in Punjab. The separatists are demanding an independent
homeland, claiming discrimination by the majority Hindus. Sikhism
if an offshoot of the Hindu religion.
