<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     04-25 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report truck hits mine, 17 soldiers killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An army truck hit a mine
southeast of the capital and 17 soldiers were killed, military
sources said Monday. They reported five soldiers were injured.
   The soldiers perished either in the explosion near Santa Maria
Ostuma, 40 miles southeast of the capital, or when the truck
crashed and burned, said the sources speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Col. Oscar Carranza gave a conflicting report to a radio station
of the deaths in La Paz province. He said the driver lost control
of the vehicle and it crashed, causing grenades carried by the
soldiers to explode.
   Officials in Soyopango, four miles east of San Salvador,
reported the finding of the bullet-riddled bodies of two people who
were taken from their homes Sunday night by men wearing army
uniforms.
   Amparo Montes, justice of the peace, said she identified the
bodies of Nicolasa Rivera Palacios, 77, and her son Juan Hector
Rivera, 45, who were killed by 38-caliber bullets. She said Mrs.
Rivera's body showed signs of rape.
   Juan Hector Rivera's wife Maria Leticia told reporters the
victims were taken from their home Sunday night by men in uniforms
who said they wanted the two to identify a captured guerrilla
suspect. She said she heard shots 90 minutes later.
   In a similar case 10 days ago in La Paz province, the bodies of
three slain men showed signs of torture.
   Gregorio Rosa Chavez, auxiliary archbishop of San Salvador, said
in his homily Sunday that the armed forces were responsible for the
three killings in La Paz. He said investigations by the church
Legal Aid office showed that the victims were taken from their
homes by men in army uniforms.
   Venceremos, the rebels' radio station, said Monday that
guerrilla fighters attacked a military post Saturday in Morazan, a
northeastern province, and caused ``many'' government casualties.
   The armed forces press office said three soldiers were killed
and 18 were wounded in Morazan. It did not mention guerrilla
casualties.
