<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Panama     04-25 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Panama,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama's New Foreign Minister Wants Normal Ties With U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's new foreign minister said Monday
his top priorities are normalizing relations with the United States
and persuading it to lift economic sanctions against his country.
   Jorge E. Ritter also said Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega's
departure would not solve Panama's problems unless it was part of a
``national dialogue'' with the opposition.
   Noriega, commander of Panama's 15,000-member Defense Forces, has
rejected U.S. demands that he resign and leave the country.
Washington responded by imposing economic sanctions against Panama.
   Noriega, who controls Panama's civilian government, was indicted
in February by a federal grand jury in Florida that accused him of
being a drug trafficker.
   ``Let's suppose Gen. Noriega would leave today,'' Ritter said in
an interview. ``Would banks open immediately? No. Would all the
private companies go back in business? No. Would all the people who
lost their jobs because the U.S. froze Panamanian assest get their
jobs back? No.''
   Ritter, who described himself as a Noriega loyalist, had served
for the past 14 months as Panama's ambassador to the United
Nations. He was named foreign minister Sunday in a Cabinet shuffle,
replacing Jorge Abadia.
   Ritter is to return to Panama Tuesday.
   ``It is not in the interest of the United States or Panama to
keep this awkward relationship for long,'' he said in the interview.
   ``We have to get together and talk about it, but it's a very
complicated thing. I myself don't know exactly what's going to
happen.''
   He urged the Panamanian opposition to agree to a ``national
dialogue'' that he said could include negotiations for Noriega's
resignation.
   ``I think people are missing the point when they think Gen.
Noriega's departure is the final solution to Panama's crisis,'' he
said. ``We have to speak about the next elections. We have to speak
about the press that has been silenced. We have to talk about the
future of the economy.''
   Opposition leaders in March rejected what they called an
ill-defined offer of negotiations with the government, saying
Noriega must leave first.
   ``If that (Noriega's departure) is conceded from the beginning,
there is hardly anything that will bring Panamanians and the
government together for a dialogue,'' Ritter said. ``There cannot
be any preconditions for the dialogue.''
</TEXT>
