<HEAD>More Fighting Between Police and Separatists; Two Teen-Agers
Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-10 UPDATE with two deaths, increasing from one.
Pick up 10th graf pvs, President Francois ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two teen-agers were killed in
clashes between police and separatists in violence following
weekend elections in this French Southwest Pacific territory,
police reported Tuesday.
   France's minister for overseas territories, Bernard Pons,
arrived in the archipelego late Sunday and told a news conference
that gendarmes had been ordered to ``return gunfire with gunfire.''
   The latest deaths bring to six the number of people killed in
five days.
   An 18-year-old Melanesian woman, Julie Akaro, was shot to death
Monday during a clash between gendarmes and militant separatists in
the eastern town of Canala, police headquarters in Noumea said.
   The privately owned radio station TUW said gendarmes and
separatists fired as the police were leaving their post.
   A 17-year-old boy of mixed race, shot Monday afternoon in a
confrontation in the west coast town of Houaylou, died early
Tuesday, police said.
   Separatists, most of them Melanesian, continued to hold hostage
16 police officers seized Friday on the island of Ouvea when
violence related to regional elections broke out and four gendarmes
were fatally wounded.
   Eleven other captive police officers were freed at dawn Monday
after tribal chiefs pressured the separatists.
   In Paris, Premier Jacques Chirac said on national television
that the 11 were liberated ``through the use of French army
forces.'' He indicted that efforts were under way to free the
others, but provided no details.
   Chirac called the captors ``terrorists'' and said they would be
tried and punished as such.
   President Francois Mitterrand asked that results in Sunday's
first round of the presidential elections in New Caledonia, held
simultaneously with regional elections, be canceled, a move Chirac
called a ``mean (political) maneuver.''
   Should the request be granted by the Constitutional Council, the
nation's highest legal body, it would not effect the overall
outcome of the French presidential election.
   Mitterrand's campaign headquarters said many polling stations in
New Caledonia had been closed because of threats of violence and
Mitterrand representatives ``were unable to control the regularity
of operations in the other stations.''
   The Socialist president won Sunday's balloting, but ranked
fourth in New Caledonia with 4.9 percent of the vote.
   Chirac, a conservative who placed second and will compete with
Mitterrand in second-round voting May 8, took 74.6 percent of the
New Caledonia vote.
   The separatists, known as Kanaks, boycotted the vote polls to
protest the new territorial assembly created by Chirac's government
over their objections.
   Native Melanesians make up 43 percent of the island group's
population of 145,000. Europeans comprise 36 percent of the
residents. The rest are mainly Asian or Tahitian. New Caledonia is
750 miles east of Australia.
   Pons told reporters that he had given orders that ``all those
who ... (attack authorities without provocation) or take part in
violent actions be neutralized.''
   Leopold Joredie, a leader of the Kanak Socialist National
Liberation Front, called Pons' statement ``a declaration of
colonial war.''
   Violence began Friday with the storming of a police station on
Ouvea, 90 miles northeast of the capital of Noumea.
   Twenty-seven gendarmes were taken hostage and three of their
colleagues were hacked to death with machetes. A fourth gendarme
injured in the attack died in a Sydney, Australia, hospital Sunday.
   Three Melanesians were wounded.
   The kidnappers demanded the regional elections be canceled and
that police reinforcements be removed from the island. They also
demanded that negotiators be sent from Paris to discuss
independence for the island.
   ``We do not negotiate with terrorists and criminals,'' Pons
said. ``These terrorists will be treated as terrorists.''
   About 20 people were killed in 1984 violence that pitted Kanaks
against pro-French settlers.
</TEXT>
