<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hirohito 1stLd-Writethru a0727 04-25 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0727,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito Birthday on Friday; Japan Prepares For His Passing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf pvs, ``Medical equipment ... to
UPDATE with sources saying Hirohito not failing; SUBS 7th graf pvs,
``The emperor ... with 1 graf to CORRECT surgery was to relieve
pressure on intestines, not remove tumor.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito held a rare news conference Monday
to talk of his health and his fabled past as the world's
longest-reigning monarch.
   The annual news conference, which will be broadcast Friday on
the emperor's 87th birthday, came as some Japanese already were
preparing for the death of the emperor.
   Medical equipment has been moved from a hospital on palace
grounds into Hirohito's living quarters so he can die at home, said
sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity. Access to the living
area has been limited to close family members, they said.
   However, they said there was no indication his health is failing.
   Some newspaper have already chosen the words they will use to
announce his death.
   At Monday's news conference for 30 Japanese reporters, Hirohito
talked of World War II and its aftermath, said the sources. It has
been 13 years since his last news conference with foreign
reporters, when he denied planning the attack on Pearl Harbor but
left many other questions unanswered.
   On the throne since Dec. 25, 1926, Hirohito is especially known
for his role as Japan's wartime leader who was considered
semi-divine. He has ruled longer than any monarch alive.
   The emperor underwent surgery Sept. 22 after complaining of
weakness and nausea. Surgeons performed an intestinal bypass to
relieve pressure on the intestines caused by an enlargement of the
pancreas.
   Since then, Hirohito has resumed some duties, but 54-year-old
Crown Prince Akihito has taken an increasingly active role. Under
the constitution, Hirohito is a symbol of Japan, not a political
leader.
   Hirohito has been spending most of his time in the imperial
palace, a vast complex in the center of Tokyo. He has said he lives
like a bird in a cage.
   Three days a week, he goes into his office behind the grand
meeting hall for foreign dignitaries.
   Twenty times a year, the emperor holds religious ceremonies to
mark such occasions as equinoxes, the rice harvest, and his
birthday. Although he renounced his divinity at the end of World
War II, Hirohito still holds the position as the nation's
highest-ranking Shinto priest.
   Japanese feelings toward the emperor differ greatly among
generations.
   There is strong reverence among the elderly, who remember him
when he was believed to be a god. Their first duties as
schoolchildren during a fire were to remove the emperor's portrait.
   Younger people born after the start of Japan's rapid economic
growth tend to take less interest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
