<DOCNO> AP880425-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 2102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AirportSurvey     04-25 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airport Survey,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LA Most Dangerous, Dallas-Fort Worth Safest, Newspaper Poll Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pilots responding to a survey on airport safety
rated Los Angeles International the most dangerous in the nation
and Dallas-Fort Worth International the safest, it was reported
Monday.
   However, many of the pilots said the main factor governing
airport safety is people, and that can vary at any facility at any
time, according to the survey, conducted by The Atlantic
Constitution.
   The newspaper in February and March polled 2,200 pilots who hold
air transportation certificates, asking them to list in no
particular order the five safest and least safest airports.
   The newspaper, reporting the survey results in its Monday
editions, said 1,360 pilots responded. The report did not include
how many times a particular airport was named and did not list
additional airports.
   In addition to Los Angeles International, the airports listed as
the five least safe were Washington's National, New York's
LaGuardia, Chicago's O'Hare and, in a tie, San Diego's Lindbergh
Field and Denver's Stapleton International.
   In addition to the Texas airport, listed among the five safest
facilities were O'Hare, Hartsfield-Atlanta International,
Washington's Dulles and Seattle@Tacoma.
   Many pilots, in written comments, said it was difficult to rate
airports for safety.
   ``It depends on the people,'' wrote a Continental pilot. ``These
constantly change. So an airport that could be labeled unsafe today
might not be tomorrow.''
   A Trans World Airlines pilot said, ``It can be compared to the
question, `Where is the safest place to drive a car?' Texas has
great long and wide roads (that are) well lit. But you better watch
out because an animal or human with a gun might ruin your whole
day. The key is pilot complacency.''
   But quite a few pilots had gripes about specific airports. Some
of the harshest criticism was reserved for Washington's National,
where pilots expressed displeasure with that airport's noise
abatement procedures and the ban on flying over national monuments.
   National's noise rules require them to cut power on takeoff
while performing relatively tricky maneuvers at uncomfortably low
altitudes.
   ``This is particularly a consideration when aircraft are
departing for long flights and may be loaded to or near maximum
allowable weight,'' wrote a Pan Am pilot with 22 years' experience.
``Power loss in conjunction with low-altitude maneuvering and even
minimal wind shear or turbulence could be disastrous.''
   The rule about national monuments makes pilots take awkward
routes in and out of the airport, poll returns said.
   National, the airport of choice for Congressmen and lobbyists,
remains open ``only ... for political convenience,'' one pilot said.
   Los Angeles International also drew the ire of many respondents.
Among the problems at that airport, pilots said, was its varied mix
of small planes and jumbo jets.
   ``Any airport that mixes light aircraft and commercial jet
aircraft is less safe in direct proportion to the number of light
aircraft using the facility,'' one pilot wrote. ``Light aircraft
are difficult to see and often do not show up on air traffic
control radar.''
   Chicago's O'Hare stood out for making both the five-safest and
five-most dangerous lists. It received praise from several pilots
for its controllers' ability to deal well with the combined
pressures of heavy traffic and winter storms.
   To get to LaGuardia, pilots must run the gantlet between Newark
and Kennedy airports, both within 15 miles.
   ``That can make approaches kind of dicey,'' one pilot wrote.
LaGuardia also has strict noise-abatement rules similar to those at
National.
   The paper printed no specific comments on either the San Diego
or Denver airports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 2107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BritainWarplane     04-25 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain Warplane,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Announces Approval of Four-Nation Plan To Build Jet
Fighter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain on Monday announced its approval of a
$37.4 billion jet fighter project involving four European nations.
   Britain was the first to declare its support of the European
Fighter Aircraft. No final decisions have been made by the
governments of West Germany, Italy and Spain.
   Defense Secretary George Younger told Parliament the British
decision still depends on agreement by the three other countries.
   The first of the 800 aircraft are to be in service in 1996.
   British officials expect the defense ministers of the four
countries will approve the project at a meeting in Hanover, West
Germany, on May 11.
   Under a preliminary accord signed in September, Britain and West
Germany each will pay one-third of the cost, Italy 21 percent and
Spain 13 percent.
   Britain and West Germany are to each order 250 of the warplanes,
with the first to come into service in 1996.
   The estimated cost of each jet will be $49 million, and some
West German critics say that is too much.
   Younger said the European Fighter Aircraft ``will fulfill a
vital defense need in the best and most cost-effective way. It will
continue the trend of successful European collaboration in
aerospace (and) it will ensure that our industry remains in the
forefront of this technology to the end of the century and beyond.''
   Denzil Davies, the opposition Labor Party's defense spokesman,
expressed relief that ``on this occasion at least the government
has been forced'' to agree to European rather than American
technology.
   In 1986, Britain scrapped its own surveillance-plane system that
had cost millions of dollars and ordered instead Airborne Warning
and Control (AWACs) aircraft produced by the Seattle-based Boeing
Co.
   The European Fighter Aircraft is among the projects on which the
United States and its European allies are supposed to share
information to avoid duplication in developing technology.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
