<DOCNO> AP880425-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 2145EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TortureJudgment     04-25 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Torture Judgment,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Argentine General Ordered To Pay $21 Million In Civil
Rights Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Argentine general facing
extradition has been ordered to pay $21 million to a lawyer who was
held four years without charges and tortured repeatedly in a prison
run by the general's soldiers.
   The judgment against Carlos Suarez Mason, made public Monday, is
the largest known damage award by a U.S. District Court for human
rights abuses, said Joanne Hoeper, a lawyer for plaintiff Horacio
Martinez-Baca.
   Suarez Mason, commander of the First Army Corps in Buenos Aires
from 1976 to 1979, during a period of military rule, ``directed a
pattern and practice of terror against the general population of
Argentina,'' said the ruling by U.S. District Judge Samuel Conti.
   Suarez Mason, a fugitive from Argentina who is being held
without bail during extradition proceedings, never submitted a
response to the civil suit, refused to answer pretrial questions
and was held in default by Conti.
   Suarez Mason has insisted he has no money after spending his
last $100,000 on lawyers for his extradition case. Ray Archuleta, a
lawyer who sought to represent Suarez Mason in the civil suit did
not return a reporter's calls.
   Suarez Mason, 64, fled Argentina after a civilian government
came to power in 1983. He was arrested in January 1987 at his home
in Foster City, south of San Francisco, after Argentina located him
and requested his extradition.
   Another judge is scheduled to rule Wednesday on Argentina's
attempt to extradite him on charges of 43 murders and 24
kidnappings, allegedly committed by soldiers under his command.
   Martinez-Baca's suit is one of three filed in the San Francisco
federal court by former Argentinians who say they were tortured, or
their relatives killed, by soldiers under Suarez Mason's
supervision.
   U.S. courts have allowed civil suits against foreigners in their
jurisdiction for violations of internationally recognized human
rights, such as torture and summary execution.
   Martinez-Baca, a labor union lawyer and former local government
official in Mendoza, Argentina, said he was arrested in March 1976,
six days after a military coup, and tortured several times before
his release in April 1980. He said Suarez Mason once intervened
personally to block his release.
   The damages can be collected against any of Suarez Mason's
assets that Martinez-Baca and his lawyers can find. Ms. Hoeper said
she was skeptical about Suarez Mason's claim of poverty.
   ``This is someone who is alleged to have taken many millions of
dollars when he was in a position of power in Argentina,'' she
said. ``He paid his attorneys $100,000 in wire transfers from
Argentina and we're sure there's more where that came from.''
   Martinez-Baca, who lives in Oakland and works in a law office,
said he doubted he would ever collect all the money. He said he
would donate half of anything he gets to a fund for victims of
human rights abuses in Argentina.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
