<HEAD>Factory Converting Missile Carriers into Building Cranes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A factory in Odessa is planning to convert
platforms used to transport SS-20 missiles into building cranes as
the weapons are dismantled under a U.S.-Soviet arms control treaty,
Tass reported Monday.
   The official news agency said the first missile platform has
arrived at the Odessa Heavy Lifter Factory in the Ukrainian
republic. Soviet engineers have designed an 80-ton crane will be
mounted on the former missile chassis, Tass said.
   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev signed a
teaty last December to eliminate intermediate-range nuclear
missiles.
   The Soviet Union began pulling its SS-20 missiles out of Eastern
Europe earlier this year, although neither the Soviet Union nor the
United States has yet ratified the treaty.
