<HEAD>Bosnia's President Withdraws Candidacy Over Scandal Accusations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARAJEVO, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mato Andric of the
Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Hercegovina on Monday withdrew his
candidacy for a new term in office after being implicated in a
major financial scandal, Tanjug news agency said.
   Andric was the only candidate and would have been formally
elected at a session of the Bosnian Parliament on April 27.
   On Sunday the official Bosnian youth organization criticized
Andric for his part in a scandal in which the Bosnian
food-processing firm Agrokomerc last year issued uncovered
promissory notes worth about $1 billion.
   The scandal is the worst in Yugoslav history and led to the
resignation and replacement of other Bosnian officials.
   The youth organization said it would not support Andric because
of several ``economic and political flaws'' that occurred in the
republic during his term, including the Agrokomerc scandal.
