<1ST_LINE>r a AM-APMeeting-Hotspots     04-25 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Meeting-Hotspots,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AP Correspondents Discuss World Hotspots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON STATON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Signs of thawing in U.S.-Soviet relations are
giving a measure of hope to some people in the strife-torn Middle
East, The Associated Press' chief correspondent there said Monday.
   ``They hope that there is a spinoff there for the Middle East,''
said Nick Tatro, the AP's chief of bureau in Jerusalem. ``We see in
the Middle East a certain loss of hope, a very negative type of
atmosphere,'' he said.
   Tatro and four other AP executives and correspondents discussed
the situation in their areas in a conversation with AP President
Louis D. Boccardi during the AP's annual meeting here Monday.
   Also participating in the discussion, called ``The World's
Hotspots: A Firsthand View,'' were Bryna Brennan, correspondent in
Central America; Terence P. Hunt, chief White House correspondent;
Michael Putzel, chief of bureau, Moscow; and Barry Renfrew, chief
of bureau, Seoul.
   The failure of Secretary of State George P. Shultz and Soviet
Foreign Secretary Eduard Shevardnadze to find a breakthrough on
arms control ``makes it sure that arms control will not be the
centerpiece'' of the upcoming summit between President Reagan and
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev, said Putzel.
   Despite that, Reagan's staff will be looking for a big public
relations gain for the president, Hunt said.
   ``Unless the president stumbles badly, there is always a bounce
that comes out of the summit,'' he said.
   Reagan will address the Soviet people and a group of Soviet
students during the May summit and will stress that if Gorbachev is
sincere about giving the Soviet people more freedoms, he should
grant them passports to travel freely and ease the restrictions on
the literature they can read, Hunt said.
   Renfrew said South Korea was hoping for success is hosting the
summer Olympics.
   ``They hope the Olympics will launch the country on the path cut
out for themselves as a second Japan,'' he said.
   However, North Korea's potential for violeance cannot be
underestimated, he said, and the North could engage in a major
provocation and interrupt the Olympics, he said.
   Brennan said wars in Guatemala, El Salvador and Nicaragua were
``essentially civil wars which started as reaction to poverty and
land distribution, which was completely unfair.''
 
</TEXT>
