<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 2157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     04-25 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Labor Federation Angered By Threatened Wage Freeze</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This nation's main black labor
federation warned Monday of ``anger and confrontation'' if
President P.W. Botha fulfills a threat to impose wage controls in
the private sector.
   ``The government underestimates just how sensitive an issue
wages is,'' said Frank Meintjies, spokesman for the Congress of
South African Trade Unions. ``We completely reject the state
president's plans to impose a general wage freeze.''
   Meintjies said Botha may feel he can curb wages because black
workers have no vote, ``but he will have to deal with other
consequences _ the anger and confrontation of millions of workers
crucially located at the point of production.''
   The government imposed a wage freeze for public employees
earlier this year as part of its campaign to curb the current 13.4
percent annual inflation rate. This drew bitter protests from white
teachers and railway workers, among others.
   Botha complained last week in Parliament that the private sector
was not holding down salaries and said legislation was being
drafted to force wage and price restraints. He said private
employers were envisioning wage increases in the range of 15
percent.
   ``The reaction thus far from the private sector has been
disappointing,'' Botha said. ``It is becoming increasingly clear
that this quid pro quo will not come about by means of persuasion
or voluntary teamwork. Other mechanisms will have to be found.''
   Major business organizations expressed concern about Botha's
statement. The chairman of a nationwide grocery store chain
defended his company's recent decision to grant wage increases of
up to 25 percent to the predominantly black work force.
   ``The bigger increases were confined to the most needy in the
lower income groups,'' said Raymond Ackerman of Pick 'n Pay. ``If
we did not negotiate the recent increases in a responsible fashion
... we would have faced strikes which would have been far more
costly in the long run.''
   Mentjies said that if the government sought wage restraints, it
``should start by cutting salaries fo government ministers,
directors and shareholders.''
   ``The working class does not want to pay for the disasters of
apartheid's political and economic system,'' Meintjies said.
``Employers will have to decide whether they will be browbeaten or
use their clout to oppose the wage freeze.''
   The Congress of South African Trade Unions, which claims 750,000
members, was the target of a government decree on Feb. 25 barring
it from political activities. The federation, which has taken a
militant and active stance against apartheid, is scheduled to hold
a national assembly this weekend to discuss the ban.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 2159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Denmark     04-25 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Denmark,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Says It Could Not Land Troops in Non-Nuclear Denmark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary George Younger said Monday that
if fellow NATO member Denmark adopts a policy of forcing visiting
ships to say if they are carrying nuclear arms, Britain will not be
able to land troops there.
   ``If we cannot send ships into that situation we clearly would
not physically be able to deliver 13,500 British troops of the U.K.
Mobile Force on site without ships to transport them,'' Younger
told a luncheon for foreign correspondents.
   Denmark's conservative Prime Minister Poul Schlueter has called
an election for May 10 in a showdown with left-of-center foes over
the nuclear issue and its effect on the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
   Schlueter heads a minority coalition government. He called the
election rather than implement a parliamentary vote that could have
forced visiting warships to declare if they had nuclear arms.
   The United States and Britain both refuse, as a matter of
policy, to say if their warships carry nuclear arms.
   Denmark is a key NATO country geographically. Britain is
supposed to land reinforcements there as part of the defense
strategy of the Western alliance.
   Privately, British officials have expressed concern that if
Denmark insists on a nuclear arms declaration, Norway, Greece and
Spain, other NATO members with strong anti-nuclear sentiments,
might follow suit.
   Britain and the United States have already stopped visits to New
Zealand, a non-NATO member, because it insists that ships disclose
the presence of nuclear arms on board.
   ``We and our American allies have a very firm policy that we
never confirm or deny that any of our ships has nor has not got
nuclear weapons on board,'' said Younger. ``It would be valuable
information to the outside world to know either that they have or
have not.''
</TEXT>
