<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Korea 2dLd-Writethru a0771 04-25 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea, 2d Ld - Writethru, a0771,0750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Koreans Vote in Legislative Elections</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs early turnout unexpectedly high. Pick up
4th graf pvs: As in ...; DELETES 15th graf pvs, ``About 26.2 ... to
conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PHIL BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters on Tuesday cast ballots for the
National Assembly in an election the governing Democratic Justice
Party was expected to win over a divided opposition.
   A few hours after the polls opened at 7 a.m. (6 p.m. EDT
Monday), election officials said voting was progressing smoothly in
fine spring weather. Police were on full alert.
   The polls close at 6 p.m. (5 a.m. EDT Tuesday) and most results
were expected to be known within hours. About 26.2 million people
were registered to vote.
   At 9 a.m., election officials reported a 9.5 percent voter
turnout, compared to 9.3 percent during the same period in the Dec.
16 presidential election.
   Despite the unexpectedly strong early turnout, election
officials predicted the overall voting rate would not be high.
   Newspapers had predicted a turnout lower than the 89 percent in
December balloting and 84 percent in the last parliamentary
election in February 1985.
   The Democratic Justice Party of President Roh Tae-woo, who won
the December election with 36 percent of the vote, was expected to
win a majority in the 299-seat National Assembly with less than
half of the popular vote.
   As in December, a split in the opposition vote was expected to
help the governing party.
   Each side has accused the other of fomenting violence, and
opposition leaders say more trouble may follow if people feel
Tuesday's elections are rigged.
   Police fired tear gas Monday at about 1,500 students who
protested in two cities. Authorities reported 90 cases of
election-related violence during he 18-day campaign, with more than
150 people detained and 77 formally charged.
   Scores have been injured, but no exact count was available. At
least 20 injuries were reported Monday.
   Press reports said 145,000 national police were on full alert
with 55,000 assigned to the 13,812 polling stations.
   Roh's party says it provides the stability necessary for
continued eonomic progress and the democratic reforms he has
promised.
   The opposition, whose divisiveness cost it the advantage gained
through widespread anti-government protests last summer, says
victory by the Democratic Justice Party means one-party
dictatorship.
   Opposition leaders also have attacked the governing party about
an embezzlement scandal in which former President Chun Doo-hwan's
younger brother has been arrested.
   A few dozen of the 224 single-member election districts are seen
as opposition strongholds, but many others have one government
candidate running against two rivals from the opposition.
   Spokesman for Democratic Justice say they hope to win about 125
districts, along with about 38 of the 75 seats to be awarded on the
basis of a party's share of the vote nationwide.
   It held 160 of the 276 seats in the last National Assembly,
chosen in 1985.
   Under a new constitution that took effect in February, when Roh
began his five-year term, the new assembly will serve for four
years and has the power to investigate government actions. The
president no longer can dissolve it.
   Opposition and government parties have traded charges of
vote-buying and the South Korean press has reported widespread
irregularities.
   Chai Mun-shik, chairman of the Democratic Justice Party, said in
a statement Monday that candidate Kwon Joong-dong was expelled
after prosecutors displayed 1,345 envelopes, each containing 20,000
won ($27) and campaign leaflets for Kwon.
   Chai apologized to the nation for Kwon's ``betrayal of party
principles of fair elections.''
   Supporters of the opposition said they found thousands of the
envelopes Sunday night at a post office in Andong, south of Seoul.
   Prosecutors later ordered the arrests of two ruling party
supporters in Andong on charges of trying to buy votes for Kwon
with about 85 million won ($114,865) found in 4,296 envelopes at a
post office, the Korean news agency Yonhap reported.
   Police said they had detained 173 people in connection with
non-violent violations of election law and formally charged 120.
Actions involved include tearing down or pasting over election
posters and producing allegedly slanderous campaign leaflets.
   Firebombs and rocks have been thrown at campaign rallies and
political party offices. Supporters of rival candidates have fought
in the streets over such things as the content of campaign leaflets
and placement or removal of posters.
</TEXT>
