<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0774 04-25 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0774,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama Gets New Cabinet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-13 UPDATE with banks to resume some suspended
services, new foreign minister's remarks. Picks up 9th graf pvs, In
Washington ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Banking Commission said
Monday that Panama's banks could immediately resume offering a
dozen services that had been suspended following U.S. actions
directed against this nation's economy.
   The services include handling letters of credit, collecting
outstanding loans and transferring funds within the country.
   The commission called resumption of the 12 services ``an
important and decisive step in the gradual and ordered process''
toward normal banking operations.
   The nation's banks closed March 4 because there was not enough
cash to cover withdrawals. Some banks reopened last week, but only
to accept deposits.
   Panama's civilian chief executive, Manuel Solis Palma, met
earlier Monday with new Cabinet members and other advisers in a
renewed effort to find a way out of the deepening financial and
political crisis.
   Solis Palma named seven new ministers to the 12-member Cabinet
on Sunday night, three of them to sensitive posts in foreign and
economic policy.
   He said the chief task would be to achieve full resumption of
banking services.
   Several diplomats and other observers said privately the new
ministers appeared to be technocrats without sharply defined
political leanings. Solis Palma, considered to be a leftist, said
he had no plans to interfere with private business or industry.
   He said he is willing to talk with opponents, but not if they
continue demanding the resignation of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
who commands the military and police and has the real power in
Panama.
   ``What we will not do is surrender before the start of battle,''
the acting president said.
   Noriega is under indictment in the United States on drug
trafficking charges, accusations which he denies. The Reagan
administration has been trying to oust him since since last summer,
applying a series of sanctions that have paralyzed the economy.
   Jorge E. Ritter, Panama's new foreign minister, said Monday in
an interview at the United Nations in New York that his top
priorities are normalizing relations with the United States and
persuading it to lift its economic sanctions against Panama.
   Ritter, scheduled to return to Panama on Tuesday, had served as
U.N. ambassador for the past 14 months.
   In Washington, an opposition leader said a group of Panamanian
dissidents is planning a military operation against Noriega by next
week.
   Ambassador Juan B. Sosa, who has remained loyal to ousted
President Eric Arturo Delvalle, told reporters the group is made up
of very knowledgeable officers who have many friends in the
Panamanian Defense Forces, which Noriega commands.
   Sosa gave no details, but the group apparently includes
high-ranking defectors who went to the United States soon after
Noreiga deposed Delvalle on Feb. 26.
   Solis Palma said the first task of his new education minister
would be to dismantle what he called the National Council of
Rumors. The latest rumors had said his new appointees would be
leftist ideologues.
   ``We are a capitalist group being attacked by other
capitalists,'' Solis Palma told a news conference soon after
introducing his new Cabinet members. He also rejected earlier
reports in state-run newspapers that called his new team a ``war
cabinet.''
   The new ministers replace officials Solis Palma inherited when
he replaced Delvalle. The National Assembly, dominated by Noriega's
supporters, ousted Delvalle a day after he tried to dismiss Noriega
as commander of the Defense Forces.
   Solis Palma's title is minister in charge of the presidency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
