<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 2256EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-APMeeting-Perot     04-25 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Meeting-Perot,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Billionaire Blames America's Decline On Business, Not Politicians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas billionaire H. Ross Perot on Monday said
the United States had declined as a leader in world affairs and
that business leaders, not politicians, are to blame.
   Since the U.S. economy depends on tax-paying workers, business
leaders should work harder to create more jobs, Perot said.
   Perot, a 57-year-old businessman and philanthropist who in 1978
financed the rescue of two employees held hostage in Iran, was
keynote speaker at the Associated Press Annual Luncheon held here
Monday.
   The luncheon was held on the first day of the 102nd Annual
Convention of the American Newspaper Publishers Association. More
than 2,000 people are attending the three-day convention.
   Perot said the country's decline began after World War II.
   ``We were complacent and arrogant'' after the war, he said. ``We
gave it away at a time when we had an incredible edge.
   ``We've become a people who want to feel good now, at any cost,
and let tomorrow take care of itself,'' he said. ``We and not the
elected officials are the dwarfs and the wimps.''
   Perot said other countries, especially in the Asia-Pacific
region, are outpacing the United States in education, trade and
technology.
   He said that before the federal government can cure the huge
budget deficit, individual Americans must learn not to spend more
than they earn.
   ``The greatest nation in the history of civilization has given
up trying to live within its means,'' he said.
</TEXT>
