<DOCNO> AP880425-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 2312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EEC-Turkey     04-25 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EEC-Turkey,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Row Between Greece, Turkey Blocks EEC Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A row over Cyprus on Monday between Greek and
Turkish officials led to cancellation of a European Economic
Community meeting, according to diplomats.
   ``This is a very serious matter,'' said one diplomat after an
announcement that the Turkey-EEC Association meeting was called off.
   An EEC official, who like the diplomats spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the Turkish delegation refused to take part in the
meeting as a protest of the agenda's mentioning the Turkish
occupation of Cyprus.
   He said the Turkish delegation agreed to discuss political
cooperation with the Community over dinner, but would not attend
the talks themselves.
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher of West Germany failed
to resolve the problem after more than three hours of closed-door
negotiations and postponed the meeting indefinitely.
   Genscher spokesman Hans-Jurgen Chroborg said West Germany, which
holds the rotating EEC presidency until the end of June, hopes to
reschedule the meeting before its term expires.
   Foreign Minister Mesut Yilmaz, the Turkish delegation chief, was
angered over Greece's insistence on including the Turkish
occupation of northern Cyprus in the EEC statement adopted by the
Community's foreign ministers earlier Monday.
   The statement said Ankara's occupation of the east Mediterranean
island has a ``bearing'' on the Community's relations with Turkey.
   The Community went into the meeting with a broad declaration
``taking note'' of Turkey's desire to improve relations with the
12-nation Common Market.
   Turkey wanted the talks to help release a long-frozen EEC
development credit of $748 million. It also wanted a discussion of
the free movement of Turkish workers in the Community and the
removal of restrictions on Turkish imports.
   EEC financial aid to Turkey was frozen since the military coup
in Turkey in 1980.
   Despite a recent thaw in its relations with Turkey, Greece said
last week it would block the funding until Turkish troops were
withdrawn from Cyprus. It also said it wants improved treatment of
the Greek minority in Turkey.
   Turkish military forces invaded northern Cyprus in July 1974 and
a Turkish federated state of Cyprus was set up after Ankara said
the Turkish Cypriot minority there was threatened following a
military coup in Greece.
   Greek Cypriots outnumber Turkish Cypriots on the island by more
than four to one.
</TEXT>
