<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BabyMissing     04-25 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby Missing,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Baby Found; Woman Charged With Kidnapping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAN GEHORSAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 4-month-old baby taken from a hospital was
found safe Monday, and a woman authorities said had impersonated a
relative to gain access to the child was charged with kidnapping.
   LaShae Cherry, taken Saturday from Children's Hospital of
Philadelphia, was found at a house in north Philadelphia after
several tipsters called the FBI.
   ``It's just like a miracle to me,'' the baby's mother,
18-year-old Faye Cherry, said at a news conference at the hospital.
``She started smiling and everything.''
   Cherylle Staley, 21, was charged with kidnapping, criminal
trespass, unlawful restraint, interference with custody of a child
and recklessly endangering another person, police Capt. Robert
Deeds said.
   She was expected to be arraigned later Monday night or early
Tuesday, Deeds said.
   A man who was at the home when the baby was found was not
charged, police said.
   Authorities said Ms. Staley carried the baby out the hospital
Saturday after she impersonated an aunt. The baby, dressed in new
clothes, was recovered without incident.
   FBI assistant special agent Dick Ross said his office received
several calls about a woman claiming to have had a baby, ``and this
was found to be rather unbelievable (to callers) and this was
reported to us.''
   Ross, asked about a motive, said ``there was some feeling of
having to produce a child.''
   A doctor at the hospital said the baby was returned wearing
clean clothes and apparently had been bathed recently.
   ``She received good care over the last 50 hours,'' said Dr.
Leonard Friedland, pediatrician on duty in the hospital's emergency
room when LaShae was brought in.
   LaShae sat quietly during the press conference, gurgling and
sucking on her fist.
   ``As soon as she saw me she just laughed,'' Ms. Cherry said.
   She said she had become convinced Sunday night her baby had been
sold by the woman who took her.
   LaShae had been at the hospital since April 18 for treatment of
pneumonia and diarrhea, according to hospital officials. She was
scheduled to be released Saturday.
</TEXT>
