<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0803EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:Aida Adv29   04-25 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Aida, Adv 29,0620</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, April 29 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Super ``Aida'' For 15,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There won't be any elephants but there will be a
cast of 600 performing for an arena seating 15,000 people in this
summer's ``Aida'' extravaganza at Earl's Hall.
   It is the largest opera setting ever in Britain. The cavernous
hall, also used for ice shows and pop concerts, covers 12 acres and
was the largest reinforced concrete building in Europe when it was
built in 1937.
   Its seating capacity is six times greater than the Royal Opera
House in Covent Garden, and ticket prices at $40 and $47.50 are
about half the price of good seats at the opera house.
   Public fascination with Giuseppe Verdi's opera, first performed
in Cairo in 1871, abounds.
   ``The tickets are going so well that we have extended the run
from six nights to seven,'' said Lilian Hochhauser, who with her
husband, Victor, heads one of three groups of impresarios who got
together to stage ``Aida'' at Earl's Court near Kensington in west
London.
   The triumphal procession in ``Aida'' has included elephants in
some productions but animals were turned down for Earl's Court.
   ``Elephants in Egypt are totally, historically inaccurate, and
camels were not originally known there either,'' Mrs. Hochhauser
said. ``Everybody wants animals but I think perhaps it's better not
to start.''
   Asked about a newspaper report that the impresarios expect a $2
million profit, she said, ``Nothing like that, and you can say I
laughed hysterically.''
   She also declined to say how much the production would cost.
   ``We don't know what to expect because production costs have
risen so enormously. This is unknown territory. There's never been
an opera at Earl's Court before and never one in Britain on this
scale,'' she said.
   ``I think there are thousands of people who are intrigued by
opera and would like to hear one. But they are put off by the price
and the lower-cost seats always sell out quickly.
   ``They feel an opera house is not their world, but they would
feel more at home in a place like Earl's Court,'' she said.
   Mrs. Hochhauser said the Royal Opera and its rival, the English
National Opera, toyed over the years with the idea of going to
Earl's Court.
   ``But they never came up with a solution to the set problem _
they didn't have one to fit,'' she said.
   American mezzo-soprano Grace Bumbry will portray Aida on opening
night and give one extra performance, while other international
stars will rotate in the leading roles.
   The production is the idea of Italian director and designer
Vittorio Rossi, who has put on similar shows in indoor stadiums in
Paris and Zurich.
   ``Aida,'' the grandest of grand operas, tells of the love of
Radames, captain of the Pharaoh's guard, for Aida, a slave and
daughter of the king of Ethiopia whom Radames has captured.
Radames, tricked into betraying military secrets, is buried alive
and Aida chooses to die with him.
   The tricky task of projecting the singer's voices to all parts
of the hall is being solved by having the singers wear tiny radio
microphones. The producers say the distances are so great that the
mikes are unlikely to be visible.
   The London Symphony Orchestra will perform with 85 musicians
conducted by Nello Santi. The London City Ballet is also taking
part as well as the Ambrosian Opera Chorus of 200.
   The production opens on Sunday June 26 and runs through Saturday
July 2.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri April 29</NOTE>
