<1ST_LINE>a i PM-LifeAbroad-Thailand Adv29   04-25 0831</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Life Abroad-Thailand, Adv 29,0854</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs April 29 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LIFE ABROAD: Thailand _ Where White Elephants are National
Treasures</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports by
Associated Press correspondents on the way of life in other
countries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white elephant in Thailand is not
anything you blithely unload. White elephants here are revered and
pampered as national treasures.
   Thailand today is the home of the white elephant believed to
have given rise years ago to the term ``white elephant'' of the
other kind.
   But Thais don't demean the beasts by calling them white
elephants. They call them ``Auspiciously Significant Elephants.''
   They are modern Thailand's link to the days when kings rode
elephants into battle and fought over the white ones.
   White elephants today reside in finely appointed stables, are
assigned two caretakers each and daily consume up to 660 pounds of
specially purchased greenery, garnished with papayas, bananas and
other elephant delicacies.
   White elephants are by law offered to the king and the current
monarch, Bhumibol Adulyadej, has 11 of them. They make themselves
very much at home around his palace, strolling on manicured lawns,
bathing in a lake and liberally stripping the royal foliage.
   White elephants, which are said to bestow good fortune on their
owners, don't come without expense. The herd doesn't earn its keep,
which includes of food bill equivalent to several thousand dollars
a month.
   Hence the term ``white elephant'' as used elsewhere to mean a
possession maintained at very high expense with very little in
return.
   While the term in that sense isn't used in the Thai language,
the English one may have originated from the practice of old Thai
monarchs giving white elephants to nobles. Such gifts could hardly
be refused and the creatures proceeded to eat their masters out of
house and home.
   In former times _ the earliest records of their capture date to
the 15th century _ white elephants bathed behind a screen to
protect them from commoners' eyes. Kings of Thailand (Siam in those
days) and Burma went to war over them.
   Beliefs, some still extant, grew up around them. Ailing
children, it is said, can be cured by walking or crawling under
their bellies. The hair from the tails of white elephants,
incorporated into rings, can ward off evil.
   The fortunes of all elephants have since declined in Thailand.
Massive deforestation has dramatically depleted the wild population
to probably fewer than 2,000.
   Modern machines and roads have reduced elephants' usefulness in
the logging industry and as beasts of burden. Domesticated
elephants, which numbered nearly 13,500 in 1950, are down to fewer
than 4,000 today.
   Roundups in the jungles, royal processions of caparisoned
animals, the thundering charges of elephants in battle have been
replaced by spectacles that some traditionalists regard as less
than dignified. Today, elephants play soccer, take part in mock
combat and lift their trunks on command in hotel reception areas
for the amusement of tourists.
   Only a few outsiders are allowed into the stables of the white
elephants at Chitralada Villa, where the animals, ranging in age
from 10 to 59 years, are protected from undue stress, disease and
any would-be human predators. Killing a white elephant is
punishable by five years in prison.
   Phiphatanachatr Diskul, a veterinarian assigned to the white
elephants' medical care, said the elephants get a blood test every
six months and are given medicines and vitamins as needed.
Initially, the keepers tried to sneak pills into bananas, sticky
rice and other food but since the animals gingerly discarded them,
a 4{-inch syringe now is used.
   To warrant such attention, an elephant must have 11 special
characteristics including whitish eyes and a pinkish palette. White
elephants, or albinos, are rarely if ever all white but rather
mottled with off-whites and other skin tones other than the
standard elephant gray.
   Once such an elephant is found, the word makes its way up
through official channels to the Royal Household in Bangkok. An
expert is dispatched and looks for the requisite characteristics.
He also assesses the beast's personality, bearing and even whether
it possesses a pleasant-sounding snore. If those tests are met, he
proclaims the animal an ``Auspiciously Significant Elephant.''
   At a later date the king presides over an elaborate induction
ceremony, the roots of which lie deep in Hindu and Buddhist lore.
   Sawej Thanapradit, an 82-year-old expert who has worked with
royal elephants most of his life, said the traditions and rituals
surrounding white elephants once also existed in Laos, Burma,
Cambodia and Sri Lanka, formerly Ceylon. But political and social
changes in those countries have turned royal white elephants into
mere albinos.
   ``In Thailand, they will be with us a very long time,'' Sawej
said, explaining that ``Auspiciously Significant Elephants'' are
closely linked to the monarchy, which remains a vigorous
institution.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs April 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
