<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0801EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Panama-EkingitOut Adv02   04-25 0914</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Eking it Out, Adv 02,0943</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs May 2 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Panama Low on Supplies and Prospects for More are Dim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``You can describe what is happening
in the country like this,'' said the head of a major company as he
drew a circle on a piece of paper. ``Have you ever seen a snake
eating its tail?''
   Trapped in the standoff between Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega on
one side and the local opposition and Reagan administration on the
other, Panamanians are using up what little Panama has left, with
dim prospects of getting more.
   ``The country is becoming paralyzed and now we are in the phase
of eating up our inventories,'' said the Panamanian, who is the
general manager of a major American company here. Like most
businessmen here, he spoke only condition of anonymity because of
the sensitive situation.
   ``There is going to be a total exhaustion of supplies on hand,''
he added. ``If we can't import raw materials, when the inventories
run out we can't produce.''
   Banks have been closed to the public by government order since
March 4, because of cash shortages following months-long runs on
accounts and a U.S. freeze on Panamanian assets as part of the plan
to force Noriega out as strongman.
   Without banks, the local economy runs on a cash-only basis. Even
the most reliable customers have lost the credit they had with
suppliers.
   Some Panamanian and foreign banks reopened April 18 but only to
accept deposits.
   Except for some foods such as rice, an essential here, and a few
manufactured goods, Panama runs on imports.
   The situation became critical Feb. 26, the day Noriega
engineered the ouster of President Eric Arturo Delvalle for issuing
an order firing the general. Noriega had just been indicted in the
United States on drug trafficking charges.
   Hardly anyone seems to have escaped in the aftermath.
   _Like everyone else, Harinas Panama, one of the country's three
flour mills, can't buy wheat because its supplier wants cash for it.
   General Manager Tirso A. Wolfschoon said the company is
negotiating to get more wheat, but then there might not be any bags
to put the flour in. He said his suppliers are having trouble
getting materials for cloth and plastic bags.
   _An association of insurance companies announced it can't pay
claims and its clients can't pay premiums.
   _Construction is virtually halted. Equipment stands idle at the
concrete skeletons of twin 24-story condominium towers on prime
real estate.
   _Colgate Palmolive, a wholly owned branch of the U.S. company,
is selling from its inventories of toothpaste, detergents and other
personal care and cleaning products. Like many others companies, it
has given its employees vacations, but General Manager Carlos
Rodriguez said that when worker get back from their vacations, the
factory will use up its inventories.
   ``The main problem will be the massive unemployment this can
generate,'' he said.
   _For 10 years Panama has been self-sufficient in rice, but
growers say farmers aren't planting because of the lack of credit
and uncertainty over whether they'll be able to get fertilizers and
other chemicals.
   Rice on hand normally would last through June or July, they say.
But in the crisis, people are buying only essentials _ and rice is
at the top of the list.
   _Supermarkets are still well-stocked. Nicolas Psychoyos of the
Rey chain said sales are running at 40 percent of last year's. Some
imported items, such as breakfast cereals, cooking oils and canned
fruits, are running low, but local brands and all essentials are
available.
   _Activity in the cluster of white towers of the international
banking center that grew up here in the 1970s is near a standstill.
   According to one estimate, 50 to 70 of the 118 foreign banks
have closed or are in the process of closing. Others say none have
closed officially.
   Some Panamanian economists said they hold out hope that the
center can revive, at least on some scale, but others say it is all
but gone and that business is already moving to Britain's Cayman
Islands in the Caribbean south of Cuba.
   To survive, the Panamanian business instinct has come up with
some creative answers.
   Some companies, like Colgate, have been paying employees with as
much cash as they can muster, giving it to the lowest-scale
workers. The rest receive coupons to buy food at supermarkets.
   Supermarkets and some other businesses are accepting the
paychecks of government employees and in turn using them to pay
utility bills.
   Supermarkets also are accepting checks of low denominations from
suppliers' employees, then returning them for supplies.
   Some businesses are resorting to barter.
   Psychoyos of the Rey supermarket chain said he has exchanged
food or cancelled overdue accounts for windows, doors, reinforcing
rods, wood, cinder block, trucks of fruit and ``just about anything
that has value to it.''
   ``We'll find someone who needs them and pay them with that,'' he
said.
   A beer distributor in the provinces accepted food in payment,
then used the food to pay its employees.
   Even if the situation is resolved soon, recovery will take years
and depend on the influx of foreign aid, according to businessmen
and economists.
   Some Panamanians now question the economic pressure the United
States is using to force Noriega out and reduce the role of his
Panama Defense Forces.
   ``Right now, there's no winner in Panama,'' said one. ``We're
all losers.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs May 2</NOTE>
