<NOTE>$adv 05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, May 5</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Thursday, May 5, the 126th day of 1988. There are 240
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On May 5, 1961, astronaut Alan B. Shepard Jr. became America's
first space traveler when he made a 15-minute, suborbital flight in
a capsule launched from Cape Canaveral, Fla.
   On this date:
   In 1494, during his second voyage to the New World, Christopher
Columbus first sighted Jamaica.
   In 1818, the political philosopher Karl Marx was born in Prussia.
   In 1821, Napoleon Bonaparte died in exile on the island of St.
Helena.
   In 1891, Carnegie Hall (originally named Music Hall) had its
opening night in New York, with a concert conducted by Peter Ilyich
Tchaikovsky and Walter Damrosch.
   In 1904, Cy Young pitched the American League's first perfect
game as the Boston Red Sox defeated the Philadelphia Athletics, 3-0.
   In 1912, the first issue of the Soviet Communist Party newspaper
Pravda was published. (In the Soviet Union, where the old-style
calendar was still in effect, the date was April 22.)
   In 1920, Nicola Sacco and Bartolomeo Vanzetti were arrested and
charged with the murders of a shoe factory paymaster and guard in
Braintree, Mass.
   In 1925, John T. Scopes was arrested in Tennessee for teaching
Darwin's theory of evolution.
   In 1926, author Sinclair Lewis rejected the Pulitzer Prize for
his novel ``Arrowsmith,'' telling the selection committee in a
letter that ``all prizes, like all titles, are dangerous.''
   In 1942, sugar rationing began in the United States during World
War II.
   In 1955, West Germany became a sovereign state.
   In 1955, ``Damn Yankees,'' a musical about a man who sells his
soul to the Devil to help the Washington Senators win the American
League championship, opened on Broadway.
   In 1980, a siege at the Iranian embassy in London ended as
British commandos and police stormed the building. Three of the
Iranian Arab gunmen who had murdered two of their 21 hostages were
themselves killed.
   In 1981, Irish Republican Army hunger-striker Bobby Sands died
at the Maze Prison in Northern Ireland during his 66th day without
food.
   Ten years ago: In Italy, messages attributed to the Red Brigades
said the guerrilla group was ``carrying out'' a death sentence
against kidnapped former premier Aldo Moro because the government
had refused to bargain for his life. (Moro's body was found May 9.)
   Five years ago: An Eastern Airlines L-1011 carrying 172 people
lost power in all three engines shortly after takeoff from Miami on
a flight to the Bahamas. The pilot managed to restart the tail
engine and return to Miami safely; it turned out that mechanics had
failed to install oil seals in the engines, causing their failure.
   One year ago: Former Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord led
off the congressional Iran-Contra hearings. The federal government
began a yearlong amnesty program offering citizenship to illegal
aliens who met certain conditions.
   Today's Birthdays: Actress Alice Faye is 73. Actress Ann B.
Davis is 62. Actress Pat Carroll is 61. Singer Tammy Wynette is 46.
Comedian-actor Michael Palin is 45. Actor Jean-Pierre Leaud is 44.
Actress Tina Yothers is 15.
   Thought for Today: ``What you see is news, what you know is
background, what you feel is opinion.'' _ Lester Markel, American
editor (1894-1977).
</TEXT>
