<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, May 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Japanese Citizens' Movements Protest Plans for U.S. Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAORI KITAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ZUSHI, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citizens' groups in a Tokyo suburb and a
small Japanese island 115 miles out in the Pacific are protesting
plans for U.S. military housing and an airfield in their midst.
   The groups maintain the facililities will dvironments and disrupt their
way of life.
   Zushi, a bedroom community 30 miles southwest of Tokyo, has gone
through four years of turmoil in local politics over the plan to
build housing for U.S. Navy personnel on 200 acres of the Ikego
Forest.
  estroy their
en On Miyake Island, 115 miles from Tokyo in the Pacific Ocean, 85
percent of the 4,300 residents have signed petitions against the
construction of an airfield where U.S. Navy carrier pilots would
practice night landings.
   In both cases the citizens' groups deny anti-American bias. They
say they want only to protect their little bit of nature, a
precious commodity in this crowded country, against encroachments
brought about under the treaty that pledges the United States to
defend Japan.
   ``We are only trying to check our central government going to
far,'' said Akiko Motoyasu of the Save Ikego Forest Group in Zushi.
   Professor Kazunari Minotani, a sociological researcher at Rissho
University, agrees.
   ``Iinment.''
</TEXT>
