<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--BlacksinCollege Adv08-2Takes   04-25 1083</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Blacks in College, Adv 08-2 Takes,1106</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 8</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 3 35mm slides.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Are minority students, especially blacks,
getting a fair shake at college? While it's not like the old days
of overt discrimination, recent incidents indicating recurring
racism have prompted soul-searching at the University of Wisconsin
and other institutions. One thing is certain: The enrollment of
blacks has been dropping and expressions of discontent have been
rising.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From random insults on the street to
graffiti in dorms to fistfights on fraternity row, black students
say, part of their education at the University of Wisconsin-Madison
is learning how to deal with racism.
   Geneva Brown, 23, co-president of the Black Student Union, has
received hate mail and heard herself called a ``spook'' and
``jungle bunny.''
   ``This environment is hostile to blacks,'' she says. ``There is
no reason for any black person to come here or stay here.''
   Solomon Ashby, 21, who came to Madison on a football scholarship
from Portsmouth, Va., says, ``It was a severe culture shock. I went
from a community where everyone I saw was black to being a total
minority.'' After five years, the senior says, ``I still find it
very stressful. I'm in a zoology class of 500 where I am the only
black student.''
   There are 722 blacks among Madison's 43,368 students, or 1.66
percent. That is down from 906 seven years ago, when blacks
comprised 2.3 percent of the students. It's among the smallest
percentages of any major U.S. university.
   Racial incidents have erupted into protests on other campuses,
from the 1986 World Series dispute that spilled over into a racial
brawl at the University of Massachusetts-Amherst to protests at the
University of Michigan-Ann Arbor over racist jokes on a campus
radio station to a furor over a fraternity sex show at the
University of Pennsylvania.
   At Pennsylvania State University, 89 activists, most of them
black, were arrested in April for occupying a building in a protest
over that institution's failure to achieve a court-ordered goal of
5 percent black enrollment. Some 2,424, or 3.6 percent, of Penn
State's 67,278 students are black. Penn State's president, Bryce
Jordan, later dropped the charges.
   The upsurge in racial incidents and strife, coupled with lagging
black enrollments on many campuses, is prompting many colleges to
mount new drives to achieve minority hiring and enrollment gains
that have eluded them in the past.
   Robert H. Atwell, president of the American Council on
Education, says, ``We have hit the wall on minority participation
and are loath to face the tough road ahead. Our own inner fatigue
has been accentuated by an administration that has not seen equity
issues as important.''
   The council has enlisted former Presidents Carter and Ford as
co-chairman of a blue-ribbon commission that will issue a report
this spring on problems that may lie ahead for the United States if
more minorities don't graduate from college.
   Kenneth Shaw, president of the 26-campus University of Wisconsin
system, which has only 3,190 blacks among its 161,887 students,
says, ``This isn't a Sunday school lesson we're talking about.
We're approaching a situation by the year 2000 where a third of our
young people going into the work force are going to be minorities.
We can't afford for them to undereducated.''
   The extent of educators' concern was evident at a recent
videoconference on racism on campuses. The conference was organized
by the Johnson Foundation and Governors State University and seen
by 11,000 people on 176 campuses.
   In panel discussions at the Wingspread Conference Center in
Racine, Wis., and interviews on the Madison campus and elsewhere,
experts agreed that today's racial problems are different from the
outright legal discrimination that once kept black students from
college campuses.
   Reginald Wilson, who directs the Office of Minority Concerns for
the American Council on Education, says much of the student protest
arises from ``a wellspring of alienation'' fed by ``day-to-day kind
of indignities'' inside and outside the classroom.
   He says that in student surveys 70 percent of minority students
will say, `We've got real problems,' while 70 percent of white
students will say, `This is a wonderful place.'''
   Raymond Mack, a Northwestern University sociologist, said, ``It
is the casualness (of racism), the fact that it is built into
American society, that makes it such a continuing problem and so
hard to deal with. It's the little flick, flick, flicks that hurt,
not the one blow.''
   While Atwell and others view Hispanic enrollment rates as
``abysmally low,'' it is the rate among blacks that has attracted
the most attention. And it has been blacks who have been subjected
to most widely noted incidents of racism on campuses.
   According to the U.S. Department of Education's Center for
Education Statistics, black college enrollments fell almost 3
percent between 1980 and 1984, but increased slightly by 1986, the
latest year for which the figures are available. The department
says its survey indicated there were 1,081,000 blacks enrolled in
fall 1986, down from the peak of 1,107,000 in 1980.
   But over the past decade the black share of enrollment has
sagged from 9.4 percent to 8.6 percent. At the same time, Census
Bureau figures show, the percentage of black high school graduates
ages 18 to 24 enrolled in college dropped from 33.5 percent in 1976
to 26.1 percent in 1985.
   Only 26.1 percent of the black high school graduates attended
college, down from a peak of 33.5 percent in 1976, according to the
Census Bureau.
   ``The main problem of access is the kid who doesn't have the
stuff to go,'' says Education Secretary William Bennett. Among
students with similar academic achievements, ``black students are
just as likely or more likely than white students to go to
college.''
   ``Most higher education institutions have been diligent about
recruiting black students...'' Bennett says. ``The most serious
underlying barrier to greater black college enrollment is the need
to enlarge the pool of black students who have had the right
preparation.''
   Black men, in particular, are passing up college. They were
outnumbered by black female college students, 645,000 to 436,000,
in 1986, the Department of Education says.
   In 1985, 34,455 black women received bachelor's degrees, 3
percent more than in 1976. But the number of black male graduates,
23,018, was down 10 percent for that same period.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
