<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1448EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--BlacksinCollege Adv08-1stAdd   04-25 1030</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Blacks in College, Adv 08-1st Add,1051</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 8</NOTE>
<HEAD>MADISON, Wis.: same period.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Overall black enrollment in the University of Wisconsin system
has slid 15 percent since 1980. Other states are wrestling with
similar figures. In New Jersey's nine state colleges and
universities, black undergraduate enrollment dropped from 18,366 in
1980 to 14,237 in 1985. In Rhode Island, 1,975 blacks were enrolled
in colleges and universities in 1986, down from 2,213 in 1980.
   Shaw, the president of the Wisconsin system, kicked up a storm
last November by proposing free tuition for all minorities who
maintained a C-plus average in core academic subjects in high
school.
   The idea drew fire from many sides, including minority leaders
at the Madison campus who feared it would arouse new enmity against
blacks and other minority students. Some said C-plus students
didn't deserve scholarships.
   In a revised ``Design for Diversity,'' Shaw has proposed
doubling minority enrollments by 1993 in part with $1,700-a-year
grants available to 500 disadvantaged Wisconsin residents _ not
just minorities.
   Shaw also wants to raise minority faculty and staff hiring by 75
percent, and to groom 15 new minority Ph.D.s each year for teaching
jobs in the system. The total price tag over four years is nearly
$17 million.
   Shaw builds on the so-called Madison Plan that new University of
Wisconsin Chancellor Donna E. Shalala unveiled in February, six
weeks after arriving in Madison and finding on her desk a thick
pile of recommendations from a student-faculty Steering Committee
on Minority Affairs.
   Shalala, a one-time Carter administration housing official, came
to Wisconsin by way of the presidency of New York City's Hunter
College, where 60 percent of the 19,000 students are minorities.
   Her blueprint, fashioned after a frenetic round of meetings with
faculty, student, staff and community leaders, calls for doubling
freshman minority enrollment by 1993, hiring 70 new minority
faculty over the next three years and 125 minority staff members.
   At Duke University in Durham, N.C., the Faculty Advisory Council
reversed itself last month following faculty and student protests
and required each of the institution's more than 50 departments to
hire one more black faculty member by 1993.
   The University of Wisconsin faculty senate is being asked to
approve an ethnic studies course requirement, and Shalala's
administration endorsed construction of a multicultural center for
students _ although not one left solely in the hands of minority
students, as activists had called for.
   Shalala found $1.6 million in existing funds to launch the plan,
and is asking the state legislature for $4.7 million more for its
first three years. Some of the money will go into financial aid for
the disadvantaged.
   Big debts have become a routine part of college life for many
students in the past decade with the federal government shifting
its emphasis from grants to loans. Many educators suspect that is a
prime reason why the black share of college enrollment has dropped.
They say the military is also recruiting a growing share of black
high school graduates with its promise of both training and a
paycheck.
   David Wright, 23, minority affairs director for the Wisconsin
Student Association, says, ``A lot of people just don't feel like
going out and taking out $20,000 in loans. That's what I've had to
do.''
   ``Then there's the Army: `Be all you can be.' It's tempting,''
says Wright, a senior from Milwaukee who is one of 11 children. ``I
know people who have college degrees who can't buy a job, and I
know people who got jobs out of high school and are making money I
dream of.''
   Fellow senior Solomon Ashby says, ``A lot of people see this
high level of education as superfluous. They'd much rather get into
the job force right after high school. A lot of the trade skills
are making much more money than people with a bachelor of arts
degree.''
   Ashby has worked summers in the shipyards back in Portsmouth as
an $8-an-hour painter, and has seen buddies who chose not to return
to college. ``The future may be somewhat limited,'' he says, but
the jobs pay more than beginning teachers make.
   Charles Holley, 23, from Chicago, also a senior political
science major and co-president of the Black Student Union, says,
``I don't think Madison has a good image in terms of black
students. Everybody who has friends who go to Madison knows there
is nothing for you to do if you're black up here. There's no black
music...The social life is essentially null and void.''
   Shalala says, ``What I want to do is make this place more like
the real world, more multi-ethnic, more multicultural. There is a
new generation of leaders, not only in higher education, but in
this society. We have come up through the civil rights movement,
through the peace movement and through the women's
movement...Twenty years ago, I was one of those demonstraters and I
promised myself if I ever got into a position of power, I would be
different in the way in which I led an institution.''
   The 47-year-old Shalala says Madison will build its minority
enrollment numbers ``the hard way,'' including finding transfer
students and older students, and recruiting heavily in Milwaukee _
something it has not been doing.
   Wisconsin's population is 3.8 percent black.
   ``I have to be real careful,'' Shalala says. ``I can't be so
hungry for minorities that we bring in kids that really can't make
it here...We're not in the remedial business.''
   She notes that on the same day the conference on campus racism
was held at Wingspread, Congress was overriding President Reagan's
veto of the Civil Rights Restoration Act, which bars discrimination
in federally subsidized institutitons.
   ``That is very important for universities,'' she says. ``It
holds us accountable for every department and every program.''
   The success or failure of higher education's current drive to
improve the racial climate and minority participation on campuses
will also be affected by ``who's elected president (and) what tone
is set,'' Shalala says.
   ``We're not going to make deep inroads until we change the way
in which we run urban schools in this country.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 8</NOTE>
