<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1413EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Paris:1968 Adv01-2Takes   04-25 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Paris: 1968, Adv 01-2 Takes,0780</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 1, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Look Back on Paris, May 3, 1968</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   May 3, 1968.
   It began as any other Friday in Paris. People headed for work
with no idea that by nightfall blood would be in the streets, that
students would battle police in an insurrection destined to shake
French society to its roots.
   ``Nineteen sixty-eight was a cultural revolution in every sense
of the word. Afterward, nothing was the same,'' said Regis Debray,
then a radical and today an adviser to President Francois
Mitterrand.
   The month-long series of strikes, protests and pitched battles
nearly brought down the Fifth Republic of President Charles De
Gaulle. He resigned the following year.
   Two decades later, historians call May 1968 the greatest popular
uprising ever experienced by a capitalist democracy in time of
peace. The Events of May, as they are called, still reverberate in
French minds.
   Politics, schools, family life and work, art and popular culture
were transformed. May 1968 was a knife blade that severed past from
future, youth from authority, then from now.
   When the tear gas cleared, a new libertarian tolerance was in
the wind and the twin political pillars of Gaullist nationalism and
communism were permanently fractured.
   Debray said, ``It was a revolution in the way we live, a
transition from an old, rural France where everyone had great
respect for central authority toward a modern, urban France of more
liberal individualists.''
   The spasms of unrest in France were part of a common impulse
felt by a global generation, the affluent postwar children who,
from Berkeley to Berlin, focused their anger in protest of U.S.
involvement in Vietnam, the former French colony.
   Today, many of these angry young men are leaders of French
society.
   The flashpoint of the Events of May was the suburban campus of
Nanterre, where protests the preceding March led to the closing of
the school.
   On May 3, about 500 students staged a sit-in at the Sorbonne,
the old and respected university in Paris, to protest disciplinary
action at Nanterre. By late afternoon masses of riot police had
surrounded the Sorbonne and began making arrests.
   Students poured from Latin Quarter cafes with shouts of
``Liberez nos camarades'' (Free our comrades).
   Fighting began.
   A frantic administration shut down the Sorbonne, for only the
second time in 700 years.
   A week of shocking violence followed. Students erected
barricades of buses, felled trees, benches and streets signs. They
tore cobblestones from the streets and to hurl at police.
   Riot police clubbed students and chased them through narrow
streets, sometimes blocking medical help to the injured. Stinging
clouds of tear gas shrouded Left Bank neighborhoods.
   By mid-May the brutality had swung public opinion behind the
students.
   Writer Mavis Gallant, in her recently published diary, described
the morning after a violent clash that injured 367 students.
   ``Ripped streets around the Luxembourg Station. People who live
around here seem dazed. ... Paving torn up. ... Where I used to
live looks bombed. Burned cars, ugly, gray-black. ... Armed men and
unarmed children. ... We all feel sick.''
   Marc Kravetz, a leading student figure on the barricades and now
foreign editor of the newspaper Liberation, said the burning car is
the single image of the street fighting that endures in French
minds.
   ``The car was the symbol of middle-class achievement,'' he said.
``And bourgeois values were going up in smoke.''
   More than a million people formed a river of flags and banners
pouring down Left Bank boulevards May 13 and reports of
demonstrations came from college towns across France.
   Then, something even more astonishing happened.
   In a spontaneous wave that swept the nation, more than 9 million
people went on strike.
   Normal life in Paris came to a halt. It was impossible to buy a
newspaper, go to school, send a letter, cash a check, ride the bus
or subway, watch television or take a train. Frightened people, who
remembered World War II, began hoarding cigarettes, sugar and
canned goods.
   The difference between the strikes at Columbia University in
Manhattan and the Sorbonne in Paris was that the rest of New York
City barely noticed what was happening uptown at Columbia. Paris
was paralyzed.
   Garbage piled up in the streets. Teachers stopped teaching,
actors stopped acting. The Odeon Theatre was occupied by students
and workers holding marathon debates on creating a new society.
Even rugby players went on strike.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1414EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Paris:1968 Adv01-1stAdd   04-25 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Paris: 1968, Adv 01-1st Add,0614</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 1, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>PARIS: on strike.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The strikes marked the beginning of the end for the Communist
Party, which sabotaged the student movement, believing it an
uncontrollable revolt of spoiled, middle-class kids. But that
attitude permanently alienated intellectuals and youth and
contributed to the eventual election of Socialist president,
Mitterrand.
   More significantly, French politics had to deal with a new force
_ the media. Young people came to view television, radio and
newspapers as not just reporters of events, but tools for the
creation of events.
   Debray said one such creation was Daniel Cohn-Bendit, the best
known of the radical student leaders called Danny the Red because
of his rusty hair and provocative style.
   ``It was not Cohn-Bendit who organized the rallies or did the
concrete work,'' Debray said. ``But he was the one the television
cameras loved, so, whether he wanted to or not, he became a major
leader of the movement.
   ``Nineteen sixty-eight was the beginning of the media's conquest
of French politics and life.''
   Young people realized that all they needed was not a place in
the French Cabinet to be effective but two minutes on the evening
news.
   ``We stopped thinking in terms of traditional politics,'' said
historian Herve Hamon, once a student on the barricades and now
author of a history of the 1968 generation.
   Hamon said as his peers grew older, they indeed rejected
politics to pursue careers in medicine, teaching, the arts _ and,
above all, journalism.
   Cohn-Bendit, born in France of German parents, now publishes a
current affairs magazine in Frankfurt, West Germany. At 43, he
still lives the life of a free-lance radical, writing books and
working with West Germany's anti-establishment Greens party.
   ``I believe I can still legitimize everything I do from my
standpoint in 1968,'' Cohn-Bendit said in an interview with The
Associated Press, adding that events 20 years ago irrevocably
changed morality, sexuality and French education.
   Alain Peyrefitte, who as De Gaulle's Education Minister in 1968
considered Cohn-Bendit a troublemaker, now agrees with his
assessment of the events.
   ``I was against the movement and felt it was my duty to limit it
at the time. But I recognize that in the long-term the effects were
good,'' said Peyrefitte, now head of the editorial board for the
conservative newspaper Le Figaro. ``People became more responsible
for their lives, gained more dignity and felt more free.''
   On May 30, De Gaulle made a long-awaited radio speech,
reassuring French citizens, who were fed up with upheaval, that the
government was in control. Hours later, millions of Frenchmen
jammed the Place de la Concorde, waving the French flag. The nation
cooled down as abruptly as it caught fire.
   Under De Gaulle, a series of reforms came in late 1968 to
decrease the number of students in a classroom, increase personal
contact between students and professors and decentralize the
control of schools.
   Nineteen sixty-eight opened the door for the French feminist
movement in the 1970s and the introduction of legal reforms
governing abortion and contraception. Relationships between men and
women changed.
   The students of the barricades now are graying parents and
relationships between these fathers and sons are less formal, more
tolerant.
   ``In the marches of '68 you never saw any parents,'' said
Kravetz. ``In 1986, in the demonstrations against the education
reforms, parents marched beside their kids. There is greater
communication between the generations now.
   ``To understand what 1968 meant to us, you would have to have
seen what we were like before.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 2044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Germany-Foreigners Adv01-2Takes   04-25 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Germany-Foreigners, Adv 01-2 Takes,0745</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 1, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Foreigners, Especially Turks, Bring Changes to West Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Germany isn't a land of
immigration,'' government officials like to say.
   But a massive influx of Turks and other foreigners has changed
the face of this once insular nation.
   From dozens of kebab stands in big cities to young Turkish
children playing in rural towns, the foreigners are making their
presence felt.
   Nearly 1.5 million Turks live in West Germany, the largest group
among the 4.5 million foreigners in a country with a total
population of 61.3 million. Frankfurt has a Turkish bazaar.
   Yugoslavs number about 590,000 and Italians are the
third-largest with about 535,000.
   One of the Turks is Nedzhati Baris, who has acquired a small but
successful business and an expensive home in the affluent town of
Koenigstein, outside Frankfurt.
   ``My position here now is quite good,'' he said in German at his
store. ``We are well known, since we've been here a long time.
   ``The only worry is bringing my mother for a visit from Turkey.
We've been waiting eight months for a visa.''
   The immigrant workers began arriving in the 1960s and 1970s and
were called Gastarbeiter, German for guest workers, to signify what
was to have been a temporary stay.
   Now, most of the Turks are still work on assembly lines or at
menial jobs shunned by West Germans.
   Journalist Guenther Wallraff's 1985 book on the exploitation of
Turkish workers, ``Ganz Unten'' (Rock Bottom), became a best-seller
and stirred controversy and soul-searching among West Germans.
   Federal and state authorities are trying to reduce the number of
foreigners in the country and make it more difficult for them to
bring in family members.
   But opposition groups say West Germany's economy, one of the
world's strongest, will need even more foreign workers in the
future as the German birth rate continues to drop.
   Although most Turks hold low-paid jobs, some of them are
successful businessmen. Turkish-owned travel agencies specializing
in trips to their homeland are mushrooming across the country,
cashing in on the West Germans' growing interest in Turkey.
   Turks, nevertheless, have been physically attacked by West
German extremist groups, and they face other problems.
   ``According to all our studies, the Turks by far have the most
difficult time integrating into the German society,'' said Hartmut
Reichow, an expert in the federal office for foreigners in Bonn.
   ``This has to do with their background: They have a different
religion (Islam) and come from a totally different culture,''
Reichow said in an interview.
   ``But the situation is much better now than it was in the late
1960s. Then, very few Turkish children went to school. Now, more
and more and are getting even higher education and their prospects
look much brighter.''
   Two high schools in Gelsenkirchen, a Ruhr Valley industrial
city, recently became the first in West Germany to offer the
Turkish language as one of the subjects for the ``abitur,'' the
examination that gives successful candidates a diploma roughly
equal to a junior college degree in the United States.
   The schools, whose student bodies are about a quarter Turkish or
Turkish-born, were the first to apply a long-existing law allowing
a foreign language to be one of the subjects in the final exam.
   Turks are also making their mark on cultural life.
   The Turkish-born director Tevfik Baser scored a hit two years
ago with his movie ``40 Square Meters Germany,'' a moving story
about a the wife of a Turkish worker forced by her husband never to
leave their tiny apartment in Hamburg.
   The leading role was played by Ozay Fecht, who came to West
Germany from Istanbul when she was 18 and became a critically
acclaimed actress and jazz singer.
   Another Turk, Saliha Scheinhardt, who married a West German,
advanced from a textile factory worker, waitress and air hostess to
prize-winning author, writing mostly in German.
   But it is the service sector where Turks and other foreigners
are beginning to play dominant roles.
   They run neighborhood ethnic restaurants and groceries, as well
as tailor and shoe-repair shops.
   ``Istanbul Kebab,'' ``Balkan Grill,'' and ``Italian Pizza'' are
found not only in large cities but also in many villages across
West Germany.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
