<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Germany-Foreigners Adv01-1stAdd   04-25 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Germany-Foreigners, Adv 01-1st Add,0542</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 1, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>FRANKFURT: across West Germany.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In Koenigstein, a half-hour's drive northwest of Frankfurt,
grocer Baris explained that 15 years ago he traded his ice cream
parlor at Adana in the southern Turkey for an uncertain future in
West Germany,
   The 38-year-old immigrant started out as a waiter, then became a
factory worker and now owns the grocery store that doubles as a
tailoring and alterations service in Koenigstein.
   Like most Turks, Baris has no immediate plans to return home.
   ``If the economic situation in Turkey improves, then maybe some
day,'' he said.
   Baris' grocery store sells ornamented samovars and Turkish
coffee pots, water pipes, dried eggplant, Bulgarian goat cheese,
Greek olives, Yugoslav coffee, dozens of Turkish spices and mineral
water, and even casette tapes of Turkish music.
   Baris said 90 percent of his customers in Koenigstein are West
Germans. He opened his business five years ago and took a
250,000-mark ($148,000) loan to buy a house. Baris, his wife and
two Turks work in the store.
   All of Baris' four daughters were born in West Germany. Two of
them, aged 12 and 10, go to a German school. The two younger ones,
6 and 4 years old, go to a Roman Catholic-run kindergarten.
   In Frankfurt, Melek Kapicioglu followed a similar pattern. She
came to West Germany 22 years ago, as a 19-year-old girl. After
working on assembly lines for the electronics giant Siemens, she
opened a tailor shop in downtown Frankfurt five years ago.
   ``I have been here long and I don't really see how I can go back
to Istanbul and work in my profession,'' she said. ``In Turkey,
every woman knows how to sew.'' Both her grown-up children are back
in Turkey.
   Ms. Kapicioglu, also speaking in German, said she would like
West Germany to revise its law and extend business hours for stores.
   ``I work from 8 a.m. to 10 p.m. I cannot serve customers legally
after 6.30 p.m., but I have to work long. My store rent is 2,000
marks ($1,200).''
   West Germany abounds with examples of Turkish and other foreign
influences:
   _In Frankfurt, kebab shops outnumber traditional sausage stands
around the main train station.
   _Newsstands sell Turkish, Yugoslav, Italian, and Spanish papers.
Hurriyet, a Turkish daily, is printed in a Frankfurt suburb in
120,000 copies daily and distributed across the country.
   _When floods hit many parts of West Germany recently, police
vans cruised the streets, broadcasting warnings in both German and
Turkish.
   _West Berlin's Kreuzberg district, with a large Turkish
population, has signs in German and Turkish to warn residents when
they approach the Berlin Wall that they are leaving the American
sector.
   _A cable television service in West Berlin offers Turkish
programs. West Germany's national television network has regular
weekly news and cultural programs in Turkish, Italian, Serbo-Croat
for the Yugoslavs, Spanish and Portuguese.
   _The Turkish bazaar in downtown Frankfurt features coffee shops
where patrons smoke water pipes, several restaurants, small stores
and a mosque on the second floor.
   Frankfurt's Turks hope to build a large mosque with donations
from believers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 1</NOTE>
