<2ND_LINE>BC-Mexican Beer-Corona, Adv 01,1076</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 1, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Mexican Beer's U.S. Success Reflects Sound Planning At Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, a companion story is BC-Mexican Beer-Carta, b0559</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some beer fanciers have brushed off as a
passing fancy the popularity of Corona Extra, the biggest-selling
Mexican beer in the United States.
   Market experts questioned whether the light lager could compete
in an import market traditionally dominated by darker and heavier
European brews.
   Not so Valentin Diez of Cervecerias Modelo, the makers of
Corona. Under his guidance as Modelo's general sales director,
Corona has vaulted into second place among imported beers in the
United States, and the company is aiming to be No. 1.
   In the process, Grupo Modelo, the brewery's parent company, is
exemplifying President Miguel de la Madrid's controversial effort
to wean Mexican industry off years of subsidies and trade
protection to create an export-driven economy that can successfully
compete abroad.
   ``We want to be a model for all Mexican businesses by giving
prestige and credibility to Mexican products abroad,'' Diez said at
his Mexico City headquarters.
   A growing number of American beer drinkers are convinced.
   Americans consumed 25 million cases of Corona Extra last year,
more than double the 1986 figure and 10 times above that just six
years ago.
   Corona captured 18 percent of the U.S. import market in 1987,
second only to Heineken of the Netherlands with 25 percent,
according to Impact International, a New York-based publication
that monitors the beer industry.
   And with Corona now available in only 36 states, Grupo Modelo
directors have reason to believe they'll achieve their goal.
   Diez cited strict quality control, strong advertising and sound
marketing as reasons for Corona's export success. But it has been
sound financial planning at home that has steered Modelo through
Mexico's economic crisis.
   Tight credit, rising costs, slack consumer demand and crushing
private debts have hurt many Mexican businesses, including Modelo's
chief competitor, Cuauhtemoc of Monterrey.
   Modelo avoided these pitfalls by refusing to borrow to finance
investment, when borrowing from foreign lenders was the rage in the
late 1970s and early 1980s. The company continuously plowed its
earnings back into the firm.
   ``Grupo Modelo's policy always has been to grow using its own
resources. That means no debts,'' Diez said. ``We did it by
reinvesting all of our dividends over the years to construct our
own breweries, malt and glass producing firms, our own warehouses
and distributors.
   ``Many at the time thought we were wrong. But this policy has
allowed us to consolidate our leadership position in the Mexican
beer industry.''
   Modelo brands now account for nearly half the Mexican market and
60 percent of all Mexican beer exports, Diez said.
   Corona has been available in western U.S. states since 1966. But
sales growth was limited because a Puerto Rican brewery owned the
U.S. rights to the familiar Corona blue-and-white crown trademark.
   Cervecerias Modelo was able to arrange a concurrent use
agreement in 1983 and bought the trademark two years later.
   ``With the trademark question out of the way, this allowed us to
launch ourselves into the market,'' Diez said.
   Not quite.
   Modelo's governing board insisted on introducing the lager into
the U.S. market on a gradual basis rather than trying to flood it
all at once.
   Corona showed up first in restaurants and bars before it
appeared in liquor stores and supermarkets. The beer became
identified with trendy establishments and ethnic cuisine.
   ``They don't want to just open a market,'' said Roberto Viejo, a
sales director at Modelo. ``They work it, service it. It isn't
just, `Hey, here's a new brand.' No way.''
   Corona's popularity has benefited from a slick advertising
campaign, with its ``Cross the Border'' message linking the lager
to Mexican tourist attractions in magazines and on billboards.
   In Mexico, Modelo has pushed its premium beer at sporting
events. The beer's logo is found everywhere inside Mexico City's
Social Security Park, home to the city's Red Devils and Tigers
professional baseball teams, and at boxing arenas.
   The sports angle is being developed in the United States as
well. A promotional stint during the week of the NCAA college
basketball championships featured six Corona bottles, two of them
empty, and the slogan: ``On to the Final Four.''
   A U.S. Commerce Department decision to revoke trade preferences
for Mexican beer in 1987 didn't hurt Corona's sales growth.
Instead, the company judged it a sign that the brew could
successfully compete on equal terms with other American imports.
   So has President de la Madrid's administration, which cited
Cervecerias Modelo for export achievements. And Diez's colleagues
in the Mexican Association of Sales and Marketing Executives
designated him their distinguished executive of the year in 1987.
   Increased competitiveness means facing the prospect of more
imported beers in Mexico as well. A trade agreement signed with the
United States last year will allow many American beers in Mexico
for the first time.
   Diez is confident Modelo will rise to the challenge.
   ``We welcome them, having plain confidence that the quality of
our beers will allow us to freely compete with the best beers in
the world,'' he said.
   With new markets opening up in New York, New Jersey, Alabama and
the Carolinas this year, Diez predicts Corona sales will jump an
additional 15 percent.
   The company hopes its other leading export brands, Negra Modelo,
Modelo Especial and Pacifico, also will catch on with American beer
drinkers.
   Corona is making inroads in other countries. The lager was
recently introduced in Japan, and after just one year it is the
third-leading import by volume in Canada.
   Distributors in France, Spain, Belgium, Australia and South
Korea have expressed interest in Corona, Diez said.
   Viejo, the sales director, dismissed some experts' opinion that
Corona may already be falling out of the trendy import category in
the American market.
   ``I wouldn't worry about it as long as they keep talking about
it,'' he said. ``Corona is not in or out. It's a mainstream brand.''
   Corona did fall into the list of ``outs'' for beers in
BusinessWeek Magazine's trends list for 1988.
   The brew that took its place in the ``in'' column: Negra Modelo.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
