<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   04-25 1154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,1206</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Say it isn't so. But it is.
   Home videos for babies. We're talking infants here, not children.
   Well, why not. After all, there are books for babies _ those
soft, washable squishy things with big, bright drawings of animals
and toys and virtually no words _ so why not videos?
   V.I.E.W. Video, an acronym for Video International Entertainment
World, is releasing ``Infantasia _ A Musical Mobile for You and
Baby'' just in time for Mother's Day.
   The 25-minute videocassette in VHS sells for $19.95 and features
shapes, colors, animation and nursery rhymes a 5 or 6-month-old
baby or older could enjoy.
   There's a happy blue bird chirping away with moving musical
notes, and cute bunny rabbits cavorting on a sunny, verdant
landscrape. There are 11 songs including ``Pop Goes the Weasel,''
``Brahms' Lullaby'' and ``Three Blind Mice.''
   ``I've tried to create a world of color, shape and song which
would be both fun and learning for baby,'' said Dick Feldman,
president of Network Enterprises, who designed ``Infantasia.''
   Hi-Tops Video has a $14.95, 30-minute cassette for youngsters 5
and under called ``Babysongs,'' featuring such tunes as ``Don't
Wash My Blanket Today.'' From Pacific Arts Video for $19.95 is a
90-minute ``The Little Prince'' for kids 5-12. The Claymation
animation is based on the St. Exupery book.
   Elsewhere in the home video world, Paramount will release
``1900'' in June. The epic about the rise of fascism in Italy stars
Robert De Niro and is directed by Bernardo Bertolucci, whose ``The
Last Emperor'' recently won nine Academy Awards.
   Warner Home Video will release ``Nuts'' next month, starring
Barbra Streisand and Richard Dreyfuss in a courtroom drama.
   Videos reviewed this week: ``The Untouchables,'' ``Adventures in
Babysitting'' and ``Hiding Out.''
   
   ``The Untouchables'' (Paramount Home Video; VHS, $89.95@Beta,
29.95; Rated R)
   
   ``The Untouchables'' is much more than a stylish remake of the
old television series, even though good guy G-men still bust
Chicago ganglords during Prohibition.
   The Eliot Ness played by Kevin Costner is a teetotaler and
loving father who compromises his killing principles as he conquers
thugs who murder a 10-year-old girl with a bomb. He saves babies in
runaway carriages with one hand and tosses gangsters from buildings
with the other.
   The squeaky clean U.S. Treasury agent frets when he shoots
hoodlums, but he openly challenges mobsters and dutifully avenges
the murder of his friends. He fights the mob with accountants and
bullets, overcoming crooked cops and judges.
   The Al Capone played by Robert DeNiro appears too little in the
119-minute film, directed by Brian De Palma and written by David
Mamet. But the savage butchery of his criminal empire comes across.
   DeNiro's Capone is a a boss who keeps his troops in line with
bat-wielding brutality. He jokes with reporters, bribes the legal
system and cries at the opera at the same time he's being told of a
successful killing.
   Sean Connery won an Academy Award as best supporting actor for
his role as an honest cop who joins Ness. He offers this harsh
advice on how to beat Capone: ``He pulls a knife, you pull a gun.
He sends one of yours to the hospital, you send one of his to the
morgue. That's the Chicago way.''
   Fashions by Giorgio Armani enhance the film's stylishness.
   It has an R-rating for language and graphic violence, including
a dinner scene with Capone that is not for the squeamish. But the
good guys win.
   _ By Robert Dvorchak, AP National Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Adventures in Babysitting'' (Touchstone Home Video; VHS@Beta,
$89.95; Rated PG-13
   ``Adventures in Babysitting'' is another adventure-comedy for
the teen set from the Disney Touchstone factory.
   Elisabeth Shue ( ``Karate Kid'') stars as Chris Parker, a high
school senior in a Chicago suburb who reluctantly agrees to babysit
for a neighbor's kids after her boyfriend stands her up. Then her
best friend calls in panic from the downtown bus station _ she has
run away from home, run out of money and begs Chris to come get her.
   So Chris and her three charges head down the expressway, where
they promptly get a flat tire, discover Chris has forgotten her
purse, fall in with a good-natured but impulsive tow truck driver
and get led into a series of ever-more unlikely predicaments,
mostly involving a sinister gang of auto thieves.
   The movie starts off promisingly, with a nice feel for the
middle-class suburban milieu and a disarming spontaneity that makes
you eager to see what weird thing will happen next. But as the
complications grow, screenwriter David Simkins begins relying too
much on stock situations, such as car chases and people hanging
from 40th-story windows.
   Before it all ends, with everyone safely tucked into bed, Chris
discovers that her boyfriend is a two-timing louse and has already
started a new romance with a kind-hearted college kid.
   Miss Shue, a lovely and spirited young actress, comes through it
all remarkably well, and the kids aren't bad either. A fair amount
of raunchy language explains the PG-13 rating.
   _ By Mike Silverman, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Hiding Out'' (HBO Video; VHS@Beta, $89.99; Rated PG-13)
   
   Some movies are a frothy treat on television, but a waste of
money and time in a movie theater. ``Hiding Out'' is one such flick.
   On the small screen, this comedy thriller starring Jon Cryer
(``Pretty in Pink'') is a fun diversion for teens hanging out
together on a rainy Saturday with a killer pizza and lots of
wonderful junk food.
   Cryer plays a stockbroker who is to testify about a mob bonds
scandal. Other witnesses have been rubbed out and Cryer is put
under federal investigation. His agents are as effective as Bozo
the Clown in protecting him and after one FBI agent is killed, he
escapes to an aunt's house, poses as a high school student named
Maxwell Hauser (he takes the name from a coffee can) and becomes
the most popular kid on campus.
   The fun _ and the adventure _ emerge as Cryer's split
personality as BMOC and fugitive stockbroker collide.
   There are a few laughs, some predictable gangster thrills and a
little romance. But don't expect major league acting. There are,
however, some pretty important values in growing up.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
