<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 2052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   04-25 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0664</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   George Gershwin: Rhapsody in Blue, Concerto in F _ William
Tritt, piano; The Cincinnati Pops Orchestra, Erich Kunzel
conducting.
   
   The popularity of George Gershwin's ``Rhapsody in Blue'' owes a
lot to the orchestration prepared by Ferde Grofe in 1942. But there
was an earlier version, also Grofe's work, for Paul Whiteman's
``Experiment in Modern Music'' at the Aeolian Hall in New York in
1924.
   This was the version, and this was the concert, that established
``Rhapsody in Blue'' as an American standard.
   Whiteman commissioned Gershwin on the strength of the composer's
Broadway successes, notably ``Swanee'' for Al Jolson in 1920.
   Setting to work just a month before the concert, Gershwin wrote
a solo piano part and a second piano part which represented the
orchestra. Grofe then helped in orchestrating the piece for eight
violins, double bass, three woodwinds, two horns, two trombones,
tuba, tympani, banjo, celeste, percussion and piano.
   It is this orchestration which the Cincinnati Pops Orchestra has
recreated, using 24 players in the guise of the Cincinnati Jazz
Orchestra.
   It's a beguiling performance. Despite the digital clarity, the
small forces evoke the sound of old 78 rpm recordings and those
make-believe ballrooms of the early days of radio.
   Delightful though it is, the recording also affirms the
rightness of the more familiar 1942 version. In its final bars,
``Rhapsody'' begs for more oomph than two dozen players can muster.
   The Concerto in F, variations on ``I Got Rhythm'' and the
``Rialto Ripples'' rag, performed by the full pops orchestra, round
out a very satisfying hour-plus compact disc.
   _ By Robert Barr, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Pinker and Prouder Than Previous'' (Columbia) _ Nick Lowe
   
   Forgive Nick Lowe for feeling a little baffled about what the
general public wants in its music stars.
   This veteran British rocker has done everything but jump through
hoops in an attempt to break through during the past few years. He
released two solid albums, including the exceptional ``Rose of
England,'' after a string of inferior early 1980s records. He
rerecorded one of his best songs, ``I Knew the Bride'' with Huey
Lewis and the News.
   Still, no luck. The back cover of his new album, ``Pinker and
Prouder Than Previous,'' shows Lowe standing against a brick wall,
gazing wistfully at a street sign called ``Market Place.''
   The relaxed tone of ``Pinker'' suggests Lowe has thrown up his
hands and just decided to do what's comfortable. While the results
are a few notches below his last two records, ``Pinker'' has its
moments.
   Lowe's a rock 'n' roller, as he constantly tried to reassure
fans who saw him on a solo acoustic tour last year, but he takes a
few intriguing left turns at the outset of this record. ``You're My
Wildest Dream'' is a roadhouse blues number backed by the Fabulous
Thunderbirds, and ``Crying in My Sleep'' is a rare ballad.
   He cajoles two fine contributions from friends who happen to be
sterling songwriters. ``Love Gets Strange'' is a John Hiatt
throwaway for which many songwriters would kill, and ``Black
Lincoln Continental,'' by Graham Parker, is a rollicking good time.
   Yet what's designed as this album's showcase is oddly
disappointing. Lowe briefly reunites with former Rockpile partner
Dave Edmunds, with whom he spent much of the 1980s feuding. But the
reunion is only for one song, and instead of complementing the
album, ``Lovers Jamboree'' stands uncomfortably apart.
   One hopes the slightly disjointed feel of this record doesn't
herald a return to Lowe's early '80s sloppiness. He's too much fun,
even when not at his best, to lose heart over a lack of commercial
success.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 2053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Moore Adv06-08   04-25 0780</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Moore, Adv 06-08,0797</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06-08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release May 6-8 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Demi Moore Graduates From Brat Pack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Once a reluctant member of the much-maligned
Brat Pack, Demi Moore has graduated to become a star in her own
right, a budding producer, wife of Bruce Willis of TV's
``Moonlighting'' fame and a future mother.
   These dizzying changes have somehow left the actress more serene
than ever. During a recent interview at Tri-Star Pictures, where
she occupies offices for development of screen projects, she seemed
calm and controlled, a 25-year-old confident of the future.
   Moore currently stars in ``The Seventh Sign'' as a pregnant wife
who is the central figure in a present-day threat of a biblical
apocalypse. The film has received a cool response from reviewers
and the public.
   ``A lot of people have commented that it might be in that genre
of films such as `Rosemary's Baby' and `The Omen,''' she said. ``I
don't think we set out for it to be that type of film. When I read
the script, the story always had an uplifting message, whereas
those other films always dealt with the devil and the concept of an
outside, evil force coming in and taking over.
   ``For me the only evil force in the movie is the human race and
what we're doing to ourselves.
   ``It's the first time I've had to carry a movie, and on that
level it was more challenging,'' she said. ``Also, it's a different
character, and the subject matter was much weightier. I've always
been associated with light, romantic comedies.''
   Moore said some of her roles, in such movies as ``About Last
Night'' and ``St. Elmo's Fire'' had ``moments of emotional depth
that had to be reached. Particularly, `About Last Night' exposed
that I was capable of more than just a frivolous, looking-good
(character).''
   Tri-Star thought so, and she is now developing a film project
based on a book she discovered. ``You just can't be at the studios'
mercy to bring you that ideal role,'' she said.
   Moore, whose parents spotted the name Demi in a fashion
magazine, had an unsettled childhood. She attended 30 different
schools as her advertising manager father moved to various
newspapers of a large chain. Her childhood curiously parallels
those of other young stars such as Tom Cruise and Rebecca De Mornay.
   ``That experience definitely has something to do with how I
ended up here,'' Moore said. ``When you move around a lot, you're
always having to adjust and fit in, meet people and situations.
   ``I've talked to a number of people who have had similar
experiences, Rebecca being one. I don't quite know what it is.
Maybe it's just being able to adjust, fit in, cope, create whatever
you need to survive, make it work.
   ``There are two choices: You can become introverted, isolated
and alone; or you can become extroverted and put yourself out there
and try to fit into the group so you're not alone. I don't think
that always leaves you with a great sense of yourself or of
security.''
   Moore chose to be extroverted, and at 16 she dropped out of
school to become a model. She had the flawless beauty, but at 5
feet-5{ inches, not the height. So she took acting classes and at
18 landed the role of Jackie Templeton on the TV soap ``General
Hospital.'' Her first major film role was in ``Blame It on Rio,''
in which she appeared topless as Michael Caine's headstrong
daughter.
   More films followed: ``No Small Affair,'' ``St. Elmo's Fire,''
``One Crazy Summer,'' ``Wisdom.'' In the latter, she co-starred
with Emilio Estevez, who was then her fiance. Last Nov. 21 she
married Bruce Willis in Las Vegas, Nev. She said their baby is due
in late summer.
   Moore was well prepared for her pregnancy. To research ``The
Seventh Sign,'' she talked to pregnant women and obstetricians and
visited delivery rooms.
   ``It was a lot of fun for me,'' she said. ``I had a leotard suit
with a belly that weighed 10 to 15 pounds. I wore it for two weeks
before the film started, to get the feeling, the walk. People
responded to me differently.
   ``I also had a prosthetic device which was sculpted of rubber
and took six hours to apply, gluing it to my skin. Thank God I only
had to wear it four or five times.
   ``For me it is much more exciting that I got to play pregnant
and make it so realistic, and now to have the real thing happen.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 6-8 and Thereafter</NOTE>
