<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Upshaw Adv06-08   04-25 0978</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Upshaw, Adv 06-08,1002</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06-08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, May 6-8 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Soprano Worked Overtime As Met Season Wound Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She's a bird! She's a maid! She's a flirtatious
landowner! She's a kid sister!
   She's Dawn Upshaw, supersoprano, and during the final weeks of
the Metropolitan Opera season, her sweet, lyric voice seemed to be
piping up all over the place.
   ``If anybody had told me I was going to be doing what I did this
season, I'd have been flabbergasted,'' Miss Upshaw said in a recent
interview. ``It was very draining.''
   What she did, within the space of two months, was sing the
off-stage role of the Forest Bird in Wagner's ``Siegfried''; the
comic housemaid Despina in Mozart's ``Cosi Fan Tutte''; Adina, the
heroine of Donizetti's ``The Elixir of Love''; and Sophie, the
younger sister of Charlotte in Massenet's ``Werther.''
   ``It's not something I would want to do very often _ so many
different things all at once,'' she said. ``The preparation was not
the problem; it was more concentration.''
   The centerpiece of all this activity was four performances as
Adina, by far the biggest role the 27-year-old soprano has sung at
the Met, and one she almost didn't sing at all.
   ``I was the cover (understudy) for Kathy Battle, and supposed to
be singing the smaller role of Giannetta,'' she said. ``The night
of the first performance I was on my way out the door at 10 to 7
when I got the call saying Kathy was sick and could I please go on
as Adina.''
   The same question had been put to her last fall when illness
forced Judith Blegen to cancel a run of Adinas.
   ``They gave me a choice of going on, but it was a new role, a
new style for me,'' she said. ``I thought, `No, I'd better wait.'
They were very nice, they didn't pressure me to rush in.''
   In February, Miss Upshaw decided she was ready _ and the critics
agreed.
   ``The result was a highly successful, charming performance, as
might have been expected from one of the most critically admired
singers of her generation,'' wrote John Rockell of The New York
Times.
   She drew equal praise for the other roles she sang in her
late-season burst. As Sophie, declared the AP's Mary Campbell, she
displayed ``a voice as fresh as spring.'' As Despina, said Times
critic Will Crutchfield, she was ``a joy to the ear.''
   Despina put her in the midst of a backstage drama that Miss
Upshaw would just as soon forget. The Korean soprano Hei-Kjung Hong
_ another budding Met star at age 29 _ had been scheduled to sing
the opening performance. However, according to some accounts, the
evening's star, soprano Kiri Te Kanawa, expressed displeasure and
demanded that she not join the cast until the second performance.
   ``All I know is, someone I know there called and asked me,
`could you come in, we don't think Hei-Kjung's quite ready for the
first performance,''' Miss Upshaw said. ``It's not something I'd
care to discuss with Hei-Kjung. Our friendship is just as it was
before. This didn't have anything to do with the two of us.''
   Though this was Miss Upshaw's fourth season at the Met, most of
her previous appearances were in tiny roles, starting with a debut
as the Countess Ceprano in Verdi's ``Rigoletto.''
   ``I think I had two lines,'' she recalled.
   Verdi is not a composer of whose works she expects to sing a
lot. Miss Upshaw describes herself as ``a lyric soprano, but the
quality is not strictly soubrette,'' meaning she is well-suited for
parts more substantial than the traditional comic maid.
   ``But my voice is not heavy enough for Puccini, not even Mimi
(in `La Boheme'),'' she said.
   There was a time when Miss Upshaw, who grew up in the Chicago
suburb of Park Forest, had her sights set no higher than singing
jingles in TV commercials.
   ``While I was in high school I worked as a secretary for a
jingle producer,'' she said. ``I thought: `this looks good. People
come in, sing for five minutes, go home, and that's how they make
their living.''
   Her plan was to study singing in college and become an expert
sight-reader, a requirement for professional jingling. But when she
went to Illinois Wesleyan University, she discovered the world of
classical music and began to think of a somewhat loftier career.
   David Nott, her voice teacher at Wesleyan and the school's
choral director, encouraged her to attend the Manhattan School of
Music in New York after she graduated. There she studied with Ellen
Faull, a former opera singer and highly respected teacher.
   During the summers, she made the rounds of American music
festivals, such as Aspen and Tanglewood, studying with established
singers and developing a reputation of her own as an up-and-comer.
She also attracted the attention of the Met, which put her into its
informal internship program for young artists.
   ``Like many singers of my age, I didn't have to work for years
in Europe before being accepted here,'' Miss Upshaw said. ``I think
maybe Americans are becoming very proud of our own singers.''
   Next year's Met schedule calls for her to be just as busy as
this season, ``but it'll be more spread out.'' She'll repeat the
Forest Bird, Sophie and Giannetta and also sing Ilia in Mozart's
``Idomeneo.'' Down the road, she will be Zerlina when the Met
stages its long-awaited new production of Mozart's ``Don Giovanni.''
   When not singing at the Met, Miss Upshaw _ who makes her home in
New York with her musicologist husband _ keeps busy performing solo
recitals and singing at major European summer festivals, including
Salzburg and Aix-en-Provence.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 6-8 and Thereafter</NOTE>
