<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Poindexter Adv06-08   04-25 1065</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Poindexter, Adv 06-08,1113</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06-08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, May 6-8 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: A Former Doll Is Hot, Hot, Hot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some rockers turn gray, still rocking. Not David
Johansen.
   The former New York Doll got tired of rock and the road. So he
put some brilliantine on his still-dark hair, worked it into a
Little Richard pompadour, donned a tuxedo and became a jaded lounge
lizard named Buster Poindexter.
   He became the toast of Manhattan with a slick deco act that best
resembled a collaboration between P.G. Wodehouse and Noel Coward.
And the songs he did were novelties and saloon tunes with witty
anecdotes.
   He played at a club called Tramps with his five-piece Banshees
of Blue, and moved to the Bottom Line with his 11-piece Banshees of
Blue. Then he went national. ``Saturday Night Live'' snapped him
up. He was interviewed on ``The Tonight Show Starring Johnny
Carson,'' signed for ``Miami Vice'' and appeared in ads for
Amaretto liqueur.
   His new album for RCA, ``Buster Poindexter,'' has been on
best-selling charts for months. ``Hot Hot Hot,'' a tune he once
heard on a Caribbean vacation sung by a calypso king named Arrow,
was the first single. His newest single, also borrowed, is ``Oh Me
Oh My,'' which was recorded in 1925 by the New Orleans Owls.
   And Buster Poindexter is playing dates in much nicer rooms than
David Johansen ever did.
   ``I like places where your feet don't stick to the floor,'' he
said. ``Until I had the album, there was no going out as Buster
Poindexter. People wouldn't come. You can have the greatest show on
Earth but if they haven't heard of you they're not going to come
out and see you.''
   The 38-year-old Johansen explained the reasons for his new
persona: ``I'd been doing a straight rock 'n' roll show for many
years and I got tired of it. I think I outgrew it. I wanted to do
something a little more sophisticated and something I could
entertain people of all ages with, instead of just kids.
   ``As solo performer David Johansen (after the 1973-75 New York
Dolls heyday), a lot of things I would say were going over the
audience's heads. Now I'm in a situation where I can be funny. It
is very satisfying.
   ``Every year you're singing rock you get older but the kids stay
the same age. Buster is suitable entertainment for all ages. People
who like rock like Buster.''
   He chose the ``obscurities from days gone by'' for the album.
``The reason I started doing Buster Poindexter was, I wanted to
sing all these songs I've cataloged in my head. ... It wasn't like
I seriously expected to do this.
   ``I didn't stop doing the other thing and start doing this. I
started Monday nights at Tramps. I said I was Buster Poindexter so
they wouldn't come expecting to see David Johansen's schtick. For
six months maybe I was singing as both. It was a natural
progression. Now guys on the street go, `Yo, Buster.'''
   Johansen is married to portrait photographer Kate Simon.
   He started in show business in the campy, gay theater troupe,
Charles Ludlum's Ridiculous Theater, and moved on to become lead
singer in a campy, male rock group, the New York Dolls, who wore
high heels and makeup.
   ``I guess I was a precocious kid,'' he said in an interview.
``Most of the people in my family sing, dance, are always in plays.
I was the least inclined in that direction. I'm the one who took it
up as a profession. Now my mother comes to my shows all the time
with her friends.''
   His Norwegian father, who died three years ago, was a light
opera singer who became an insurance salesman when he and his Irish
wife had the first of their six children. ``We always went to see
Broadway shows when we were kids,'' Johansen said. ``I liked them
all.''
   At home on Staten Island, David Johansen's street name was
Buster.
   ``I was the one in the gang who read books,'' he says. ``They
called me Poindexter. Some people have that wanderlust both
physically and intellectually. I had a band in high school, the
Blue Banshees. I wanted to revive that name, for whatever reason
I'm not sure.''
   After high school, he worked for people who owned a store. One
of them was in the late Charles Ludlum's theater company. ``I just
kind of fell into it. Charles Ludlum was a brilliant man, very
generous with his information. I learned a lot. It was like an
apprenticeship. I was a lion in one play, a saint in one. I was an
extra, really.
   ``Then I started up the New York Dolls. At that time rock was
very blue jeans and flannel shirts. We wanted to bring a sense of
flamboyance, fantasy and fun to it. The way we dressed scared the
homophobes (people afraid of homosexuals).
   ``We got involved with each other because we looked like that.
... I don't think we thought what we were doing was particularly
outrageous. I think it translated that way. We made two albums for
Mercury, released many times _ the best of, very best of, complete
works of.
   ``It has been said the New York Dolls were the beginning of
punk. I don't agree. I think it was classic rock 'n' roll we
played. I wrote lyrics that were teen angst with a sense of humor.''
   Johansen said the New York Dolls broke up because they got tired
of each other. ``We were very volatile. We'd have an argument; that
would be it. Most people would say, `We still have this viable
gig.' Not us. We were amateur, I guess.
   ``In retrospect, it was a project that was completed. I don't
want to go around looking like that forever. I see grown men still
wearing their mother's clothes. I say, `There but for the grace, go
I.'''
   After the breakup, Johansen and another band member made money
touring Japan _ Johansen now calls them the Dollettes. Then he
wrote songs and made six solo albums for Epic, continually touring
the United States for eight years.
   ``I love to sing,'' he says. ``It's the schlep that kills me.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, May 6-8 and Thereafter</NOTE>
