<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0643EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Highway1     04-25 0966</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Highway 1,0987</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Highway 1</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY700, NY710, NY711, NY712</HEAD>
<BYLINE>(EDITORS: For suggested side-by-side use with b1119, I-95)
^By THOMAS MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIG SUR, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just before sunset, a golden glow warms
the Big Sur coast where Highway 1 crosses Bixby Creek on a bridge
so graceful it improves its idyllic natural backdrop.
   California native Richard Sears visits the area a half-dozen
times a year just to stare at the stunning scene.
   ``I feel attached to this place,'' he says in a reverent tone.
``I lived in Europe for 20 years. All the time I was gone, I kept
dreaming about this particular highway, this particular spot.
   ``That's why I came home eventually.''
   Sears is not alone in his enthusiasm for the wonders of
California's 644-mile coastal highway. If you picture California in
your mind, chances are you are viewing it from Highway 1.
   Maybe it's the sight of surfers silhouetted against a Santa
Monica sunset, or the brightly colored fishing boats chugging out
of Morro Bay. Perhaps it's the grandeur of Big Sur, or the quaint
Main Street of Mendocino. If these are the jewels of the California
coast, Highway 1 is the necklace.
   It became the nation's first scenic highway in 1964, when the
separate segments of the route were linked under the common name of
Highway 1.
   The journey north begins at Dana Point in Orange County when the
Pacific Coast Highway peels off from Interstate 5. A chain of beach
towns makes up this land of surfboards and string bikinis: Laguna,
Newport, Hermosa, Redondo, Manhattan, Sunset, Santa Monica.
   Yachts take harbor at Newport Beach. Laguna Beach attracts
artists. Huntington Beach is perforated with oil wells. Everywhere
there are whitewashed walls of Spanish-style villas, red-tile roofs
and dangling boughs of purple bougainvillea.
   The highway rolls past Venice and the famous Santa Monica pier
en route to Malibu, where celebrities mingle with common folk. It's
expensive. The traffic is often jammed. The land is not stable.
Grass fires threaten hillside mansions in the summer. Monster waves
damage beachfront homes in the winter. Yet most people who live
here wouldn't trade it for nirvana.
   Highway 1 passes through the lima bean fields and lemon orchards
of Ventura County as it heads up towards Santa Barbara. At Gaviota,
it heads west on a journey through time that takes it from cow
pastures into the space age. Giant radar domes and distant launch
pads mark Vandenberg Air Force Base, the future home of the space
shuttle.
   San Luis Obispo was the site of a California mission, later
became a quiet college town and today is an oasis for motorists.
With the Spanish-influenced architecture of its relaxed downtown,
it proves an excellent tonic for those too long behind the wheel.
   Ten miles west is Morro Bay, and a little farther up the coast
lies San Simeon, where William Randolph Hearst built Hearst Castle.
The dozens of bedrooms in the main house once welcomed the likes of
Gable and Lombard, presidents and kings. The mountaintop mansion is
now a state park.
   The highway now enters Big Sur, 70 miles of coast where the
dramatic Santa Lucia mountains drop suddenly to the sea.
   The highway dances with the mountains here, rising around a
point high over the ocean, then falling gracefully into a sweeping
curve before spinning again toward the sea.
   The deepest canyons are crowned with arching concrete spans
built, like other parts of the highway, with the help of convict
labor from San Quentin prison.
   The beauty of the 714-foot Bixby Creek Bridge belies the
difficulty of its construction from 300 tons of steel, 6,600 cubic
yards of concrete and 300,000 board feet of Douglas fir used as a
falsework.
   Even though 1.5 million people drive through Big Sur each year,
the scale of the landscape generates a feeling of isolation for
some. The greatness of the area has inspired many writers and
artists, including author Henry Miller and photographer Ansel Adams.
   A half-hour north of Bixby Creek sits reclusive
Carmel-By-The-Sea, and a few miles farther rests Monterey with its
once-bustling waterfront that now features one of the world's great
aquariums.
   This is no longer the Cannery Row that John Steinbeck
immortalized a half-century ago. But millions still come here
searching among the crumbling piers for the ghosts of Doc and Wide
Ida.
   The highway races past Fort Ord on its way to the amusement park
at the Santa Cruz boardwalk, where a warm summer night conjures the
smell of cotton candy and the cheap thrill of a rickety wooden
roller coaster.
   Another 70 miles of coastline leads the highway to San Francisco
where the route's beauty is lost is a maze of traffic until
resurfacing across the Golden Gate in Marin County. The highway
clings to the shoulders of Mount Tamalpais before reaching the
funky communities of Stinson Beach and Bolinas.
   For many, a trip along Highway 1 on the north coast will seem
redundant after the scenery further south. But the observant will
find extraordinary beauty in the lagoons and grasslands that have
become refuge to myriad species, including red tail hawks and
peregrine falcons.
   Passing through the towns along the north coast _ Bodega Bay,
Mendocino, Fort Bragg, Gualala (pronounce it wuh-lah-lah) _ it is
hard to imagine one is still in the same state as the sun-'n'-surf
cities of Southern California. Soon, even the Northern California
coast is a memory as the highway turns inland through virgin
redwood groves and Indian reservations.
   At Leggett, the highway comes to an anti-climactic end when it
meets Highway 101, and the traveler has the option of continuing on
the more heavily traveled road _ or turning around and seeing what
Highway 1 looks like from north to south.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0644EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:WithHighway1-Nepenthe     04-25 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: With Highway 1-Nepenthe,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: With Highway 1-Nepenthe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIG SUR, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On a bluff with a sweeping view of the
Big Sur coast, 808 feet above the Pacific Ocean, sits a restaurant
that serves something more with its burgers than a side of fries.
   Nepenthe has been a popular eatery on Highway 1 since the late
1940s, not just with the 1.5 million motorists who pass by
annually, but with many of the writers, artists and thinkers who
have given Big Sur its unique reputation as the birthplace of the
human potential movement.
   The restaurant, designed by Rowan Maiden, a Frank Lloyd Wright
disciple, makes the most of its view with a dining room surrounded
by picture windows and a wrap-around, bi-level patio. Inside and
out, there are giant fireplaces to ward off the chill of the
notorious coastal fog.
   The food, ranging from quiche and burgers to steaks and red
snapper, is good and not unreasonably priced by Big Sur standards.
But it's the history and people of Nepenthe that really makes the
place special.
   The restaurant, named for a mythical Egyptian drug that induced
forgetfulness and eased sorrow, sits beside a log cabin built by
the equestrian Trails Club in 1925.
   The cabin was purchased by Orson Welles in the 1940s, reportedly
as a gift for Rita Hayworth. But she never lived there and the
property was sold again to Bill and Lolly Fassett in 1947.
   Today, Nepenthe is managed by their grandson, Kirk Fassett.
Granddaughter Erin Fassett supervises the dining room and lives in
the rustic cabin.
   Born and raised in Big Sur during the 1960s, they had a good
view of social changes here, and of the changes in people who gave
up the straight life somewhere else to seek an alternative
lifestyle on the California coast.
   ``In Big Sur, there is really only one industry, the
entertainment industry _ restaurants and inns,'' notes Erin. ``So
people who wanted to live here, unless they were independently
wealthy or self-employed, ended up working in restaurants.
   ``I know people who have Ph.D.s or were doctors and didn't want
to be doctors anymore _ people who dropped out of a different life
and were working here. And that's still true ... These people have
gone through a real rebirth in a way, a rejuvenation. They get
excited about life again,'' she said.
   ``Every night, somebody comes through and says `I came here 10
years ago and I was never able to forget it.' It's really kind of a
haunting community. You don't forget it very easily.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0649EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:I-95     04-25 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: I-95,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: I-95</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY700, NY713</HEAD>
<HEAD>(EDITORS: For suggested side-by-side use with b1117, Highway 1)</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Gov. Bob Martinez drove a 1929 Ford Model AA
truck to open the final 33-mile stretch of Interstate 95 last Dec.
19, it marked the end of a superhighway project that began snaking
its way from Miami to Maine 32 years ago.
   The idea for the road was born in the 1940s as a way to speed up
troop movement, when needed, while aiding the burgeoning East Coast
population. It was included in a national interstate network
outlined in 1956 in the Federal Aid Highway Act signed into law by
President Dwight D. Eisenhower.
   Ambitious plans called for the entire network, 90 percent funded
by the federal government, to be carrying traffic by 1972.
   It was designed as an unbroken freeway, but its 1,866 miles are
interrupted in central New Jersey, where there is a short gap near
Trenton. The interstate picks up a few miles later, where it shares
the New Jersey Turnpike. Plans for completing I-95 in New Jersey
were scuttled in 1983.
   I-95 now runs through all or parts of 15 Eastern states and the
District of Columbia, from Miami to Houlton, Maine.
   In parts of the heavily-traveled Northeast, I-95 often becomes a
traffic nightmare.
   Howard T. Owens, a state senator from Bridgeport, Conn., and
chairman of the General Assembly's Transportation Committee,
describes the situation on Interstate 95 in Connecticut as
``absolutely horrendous.''
   ``It's gridlock from 6:30 a.m. to after 8:30. A ride from
Bridgeport to Stamford that should take 25 minutes takes more than
one hour, and if every aspect of mass transportation was used by
the year 2000, we'd still have hopeless gridlock,'' Owens said.
   Work on the $222 million final leg in Florida began in
Jacksonville in February 1985 with money appropriated by Congress
three years before. The last link runs from northeastern Palm Beach
County into Martin County, loops west across the Florida Turnpike
and then meanders back toward the coast to connect with what used
to be a dead-end stretch of the highway in St. Lucie County.
   During several years of construction, the then-incomplete
portion of I-95 became a favorite runway for drug smugglers.
   ``It became the longest runway in the United States for drug
smuggling planes,'' James D. Holt, the sheriff of Martin County,
said when the link was opened in December.
   In Florida, Interstate 95 offers easy access to all of the
Atlantic beaches and is little more than an hour away from Disney
World, Sea World and many other Central Florida attractions.
   ``I didn't know whether I'd live long enough to see it complete
or not,'' said Bill Fowler, of the state Department of
Transportation, who helped oversee work on the ``missing link.''
   Some officials say completion of the section between Palm Beach
and St. Lucie counties in southeastern Florida will open the
Treasure Coast to commuter traffic from as far away as Miami.
   ``You figure a two-hour commute to Miami really isn't any worse
than what some people do to get from one end of Miami to the other,
or Fort Lauderdale,'' said Martin County Commissioner Maggy
Hurchalla.
   But Lance deHaven-Smith, associate director of the Florida
Atlantic University-Florida International University Joint Center
for the Study of Environmental and Urban Problems, sees it as one
more step in ``the Los Angelization of South Florida.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0649EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:WithI-95-Houlton     04-25 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: With I-95-Houlton,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: With I-95-Houlton</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA PARZIALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOULTON, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interstate 95, the 1,866-mile corridor
that takes truckers, snowbirds and salesmen from Maine to Florida,
begins at the Canadian border in this far north potato town.
   Before reaching Bangor, the nearest big city, I-95 winds through
miles of potato farms, brushes the Haynesville Woods _ made famous
by Dick Curless' country and western hit, ``Tombstone Every Mile''
_ then passes through a strand of white birches before cutting
through the brooding Argyle peat bog.
   Remote and isolated, the only access to points south before the
opening of the two-lane highway in 1966 were state Routes 2 and 2A
_ hilly, winding, treacherous roads, particularly in winter. Then
the trip to Bangor could take up to four hours, and had to be a
well-planned event.
   ``We would go only a couple times a year,'' recalls Lois Ward,
62, who has lived her entire life in this Aroostook County
shiretown of 6,750. ``We'd leave early in the morning, do our
shopping, have dinner and it was probably 10 o'clock at night
before we were home. It was an all day thing, but it was grand
fun.''
   Today, the interstate is a four-lane highway and the speed limit
65 mph, which has cut the driving time to Bangor in half.
   ``It was a godsend as far as getting to the southern part of the
state,'' lifelong area resident, Robert Anderson, 50, said of the
highway. ``The interstate can't be equalled in my opinion,
anywhere.''
   The opening of the interstate has increased traffic into the
United States from Canada.
   When I-95 first opened _ two miles from the Maine-New Brunswick
border _ 4,900 people a month entered the United States. By 1987,
273,000 people and 5,000 trucks a month were streaming into the
country, according to Marc Russell, U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service supervisor at the border checkpoint.
   The interstate, which cost $140 million to build from Bangor to
Houlton, also created a new business district, forcing motels,
restaurants and stores from downtown Houlton or Route 2A to close
or move near the highway to accommodate the re-routed traffic.
   Some believe business has increased in Houlton, where the
economy is based on the potato industry and the lumber trade.
   ``There seems to be more activity in Houlton than there has been
in prior years,'' said Anderson, an insurance and real estate
agent. ``Maybe that's just a gut feeling, but there seems to be
more construction. I think development around an interstate seems
to snowball.''
   While the road has made access to southern Maine easier, life in
Houlton, as one resident says, hasn't changed much.
   ``It's just a long way from the rest of the world,'' Mrs. Ward
said. ``Even though you can get to Bangor in just under two hours,
you still have a long way to go if you want to go to Boston.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0650EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:OlympicCity     04-25 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Olympic City,0774</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Olympic City</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY708, NY709</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Once called the Hermit Kingdom, South
Korea is preparing to entertain the world at the 1988 Olympic Games
and show just how much things have changed.
   The country, which for centuries tried to seal itself off from
the world, has been transformed in recent years into one of Asia's
most modern and fastest-growing nations. Staging the Olympics is
the crowning glory of South Korea's economic rise.
   Seoul, a sprawling city of 10 million people, has been preparing
for years to host the Games and ensure that everything is right
when the Olympic spotlight turns on South Korea beginning Sept. 17.
   The city of high-rise buildings, broad avenues and meticulous
neatness is dotted with Olympic flags and banners for the Games.
The five interlocked circles, symbol of the Olympic movement, is
stamped on everything from milk cartons and television logos to
carriages in the Seoul subway system.
   ``The No. 1 games. The No. 1 people,'' proclaim the subway signs
on every carriage door.
   Counters ticking off the days to the start of the games stand
outside all government offices and police stations, in every subway
station and in many shops and businesses. Some buildings even have
little counters in the elevators.
   Newspapers are filled with articles on the Olympics, Seoul taxi
drivers are taking courses in English and other foreign languages,
homeowners are being urged to provide accommodation for tourists,
and hotels and new shops are under construction all over Seoul.
   The sprawling Olympic Park in the south of Seoul, with its giant
stadiums, tracks and pools, is ready for the Games. Workers scurry
around the immaculate complex every day, polishing the stadiums and
trimming lawns and trees.
   But visitors hoping to attend the Olympic Games had better
already have firm hotel and airline reservations. Accommodation is
likely to be scarce with more than 200,000 visitors expected.
   Visitors who want to get the real flavor of Korea should get off
the main streeets and take a walk through the sidestreets and
alleys that are usually just one block over. Street life in Seoul
is colorful and entertaining.
   Little shops offer brightly colored quilts and basketwork,
antique dealers sell old pottery and elaborate Korean chests. Stall
holders are everywhere selling fruit, vegetables and flowers.
   Sidewalk vendors or little makeshift restraurants offer onion
pancakes, rice noodles in red pepper sauce and jam and almond paste
cakes, roast chestnuts and dried squid.
   Koreans like to socialize over food and drink and Seoul is
covered with thousands of restaurants, beer halls, tea rooms, snack
counters and sidewalk vendors serving a vast range of dishes.
   Korean food offers distinctive spicy dishes such as pulgogi, a
barbecued beef that is cooked at your table, and kalbi or barbecued
beef ribs. Kimchi, fiery pickled cabbage that is the most famous
dish in Korean cuisine, accompanies just about every meal.
   Another pleasure are the many small and inexpensive noodle and
rice restaurants where a steaming bowl of fish or beef soup can be
had with noodles or rice for $2 or $3.
   Many visitors enjoy sampling both local brews and Korean society
by visiting Korean beerhalls, where local beers and a potent
sorghum liquor called soju are served. Koreans love to sing and
strangers and friends join in everything from country and western
hits to haunting Korean love melodies.
   Seoul has much to offer shoppers, with bargains in clothes,
luggage, shoes and leather goods, porcelain, Oriental prints,
fabric, and inexpensive jewelery. Several fur companies offer
bargain fur coats that shoppers pick up at the airport on their way
out.
   The city is covered with shops, department stores, arcades and
markets. Many visitors head for the Itaewon District, where English
is widely spoken.
   More colorful are the vast open air markets at Tongdaemun and
Namdaemun where vendors sell everything from sneakers and bolts of
brilliantly colored silk to live carp and turtles for dinner.
   Foreign visitors invariably say language is the biggest problem
they encounter. English and other foreign languages are not widely
spoken. But Koreans will happily assist guests and smiles, nods and
hand gestures are often sufficient.
   One problem confronting Olympic visitors will be very strict
security that could make getting around difficult at times during
the Games.
   The government, concerned about possible terrorist threats from
rival communist North Korea, will deploy tens of thousands of
troops and police to ensure the safety of the Games and the
visitors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
