<DOCNO> AP880425-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0650EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:WithOlympics-Cooking     04-25 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: With Olympics-Cooking,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: With Olympics-Cooking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Seoul metropolitan government has established a Home-Stay
Program involving 668 Korean families to cater to foreign tourists
expected for the Olympic Games in September.
   Part of the preparation for the host homes involves learning
Western-style cooking.
   ``The basic price of the Home-Stay Program ($25 a person per
night) includes breakfast and, obviously, most Western visitors
will not be used to the Korean-style morning meal of soup, fish,
rice and kimchi (a spicy cabbage dish),'' said a city government
official.
   ``We want to be able to offer them the kind of breakfast dishes
they are used to at home. That's no problem in our city's hotels _
but perhaps a new cooking experience for some Korean housewives.''
   The homes in the program, which is operated by the Korea Travel
Bureau, include traditional Korean-style houses and modern
apartments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0651EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Galapagos     04-25 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Galapagos,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Galapagos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PUERTO AYORA, Galapagos Islands, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dolphins, their
bodies luminous in the black sea, swam alongside the bow in the
dark, moonless night, playfully racing our sailboat as it cut
through the water on the second night of our trip to the Galapagos
Islands.
   A few hours later, they frolicked just outside the porthole of
our cabin, waking us up with their high-pitched whistles, seemingly
to watch their midnight antics.
   By then, we were hooked on the wonders of these fascinating
islands, located some 600 miles off the coast of Ecuador in the
Pacific Ocean and populated with strange and unusual birds,
reptiles and animals.
   ``These islands are a unique entity, related to no other part of
this planet,'' writes Tui De Roy Moore in her book, ``Galapagos:
Islands Lost in Time.''
   ``They contain mountains, forests, beaches and bays unlike any
others on the earth,'' she said. ``Here animals and plants have
evolved into unique forms; some have survived scarcely changed,
from prehistoric times.''
   Indeed, a visit to the islands _ there are 13 large ones and
dozens of small ones and reefs spread over about 18,000 square
miles _ is to go back in time.
   Charles Darwin, the English naturalist, visited the islands in
1835 aboard the ship Beagle. His observations were key in
formulating the theory of evolution.
   In his book ``Darwin and the Beagle,'' Alan Moorehead quotes
Darwin as saying about the islands:
   ``Here, both in space and time, we seem to be brought somewhere
near to that great fact _ that mystery of mysteries _ the first
appearance of new beings on this earth.''
   That sense of mystery remains.
   Gray-black swirls and coils left by flowing lava at the turn of
this century, still virtually intact, stretch eerily as far as the
eye can see at Sullivan Bay on Santiago Island.
   Marine iguanas, their heads like armored helmets shaped at the
dawn of time, sun their grayish bodies on rocks at James Bay, also
on Santiago Island.
   The giant tortoises _ the name Galapagos comes from the Spanish
word for tortoise _ lumber across the landscape, much as their
prehistoric ancestors did. They are the world's largest, a ranking
shared only with a species on the Seychelles, the islands in the
Indian Ocean.
   Sailing in a 48-foot yacht, we were able to visit six of the
islands in five days and see a wide variety of animals, birds and
reptiles in their natural habitat as well as hike over volcanic
terrain.
   The trips are regulated by the Galapagos National Park Service,
which limits visitors to 26,000 a year. Tourists are restricted
where they can walk so they don't disturb the islands' ecology.
   We slept and ate aboard the yacht. Food was prepared by a cook
who used local products to make such Ecuadorean specialties as a
mashed potatoes and cheese dish called llapingachos, ceviche topped
with popcorn, and desserts of sweet tomatoes.
   A guide approved by the park service traveled with us, pointing
out blue-footed boobies, lava herons and swallow-tailed gulls by
day and constellations by night.
   Never having been threatened by humans, the islands' creatures
are extraordinarily tame. Nearly all were unfazed by our presence.
   Enormous colonies of sea lions, some swimming, others sparring
and one even nursing a pup on South Plaza Island, let us walk
gingerly among them without scurrying away.
   Some even turned the tables and inspected us.
   A young sea lion pulled himself out of a shallow pool at James
Bay to get a closer look. With his tiny ears alert, he sniffed a
friend's white jogging shoe before slithering away to dry off on a
warm cliff.
   A tiny penguin darted around us, swimming as we snorkeled in
beautifully clear water near Pinnacle Rock on Bartolome Island. A
pelican, maybe hoping for some leftovers from our cook, perched
atop the motor on the dinghy behind our yacht.
   A few creatures were decidedly unfriendly, and we weren't
certain about the intentions of two sharks spotted circling one
night when our becalmed yacht stalled for more than an hour during
a long sail in the deserted waters between two islands.
   The captain of our boat reassured us that Galapagos sharks were
special, like the islands' other creatures. ``Vegetarians,'' he
said with a big smile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0651EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Nepal     04-25 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Nepal,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Nepal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POKHARA, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men and women with heavy loads on their
backs trudge the roads of Pokhara. Some are trekkers _ Americans,
Europeans, Australians _going up into the mountains. Others are
Gurung tribesmen coming down with loads of cloth or grain.
   Pokhara, 124 miles west of Katmandu, owes its existence to the
majestic sweep of half a dozen Himalayan peaks to the north. It
calls itself ``Gateway to Annapurna,'' after the tallest at 26,504
feet.
   It is crowded with young tourists chattering about treks and
older ones waiting hopefully for frequent clouds and mist to part
for a glimpse of the snowy peaks.
   It was not always so. In fact, says retired British Col. J.O.M.
Roberts, Pokhara was once one of the world's most isolated places.
   ``Anything you can see here, cut it down. It didn't exist,''
Roberts said, recalling his initial visit as one of the first
Westerners into the Pokhara valley in 1950.
   Nepal was closed to tourists until 1951, and the ony way to
Pokhara was to walk. French climber Maurice Herzog, the first
European to conquer a major Himalayan peak, bypassed the place en
route to his conquest of Annapurna I on June 3, 1950.
   Roberts said that on his second visit in 1957, he saw only an
airstrip and a tree. Even the oxcart, ubiquitous in south Asia, did
not arrive in Pokhara until 1961, brought in by aircraft.
   Today, where only rocky paths existed, a string of villages
makes up the town of Pokhara. Corrugated tin shops, thatch shacks
and concrete-block houses have sprung up willy-nilly.
   About 70,000 people live in the area. Many are Gurungs or Mayars
who came down from the hills to settle after seeing the outside
world in the famed Gurkha regiments in which Roberts also served.
   D.B. Thapa of the government tourist office said 70,000 visitors
also come to Pokhara each year.
   But natives and foreigners rarely collide, since tribesmen do
their business in the Mahendra Pul area north of the airport, and
Westerners hang out near Lake Phewa to the west.
   At the native bazaar, most signs are in Nepali script, though
the Shakva Tailors advertises ``Satisfaction Is Our Garent.'' A
search for books in English turns up only ``Basic Chemistry'' and
similar texts.
   The lakeside, by contrast, is a bibliophile's dream: 16
bookstores can be found in a 15-minute walk, with titles in a
half-dozen languages traded or sold by wandering readers.
   At one shop, the Bible in German shares a shelf with ``I'll Take
Manhattan'' by Judith Krantz, Tolstoy's ``War and Peace,'' and
``Annapurna, Premier 8,000,'' Herzog's tale of his conquest. Nearby
are books on mountains and mysticism, along with Batik versions of
the Tantric erotic art carved on Nepal's Hindu temples.
   The rest of the lakeside is a similar international jumble: the
Amica German Hair Composer, Axis Steaks and Pizza, the Monsoon
Restaurant _ Japanese food, and Tranquility Lodge offering
``harmony, peace and good energy.''
   ``You can get a room in Pokhara from 15 rupees to 1,500
rupees,'' _ 70 cents to $70 dollars _ said Ranga Nath Timilshina,
19, who was hawking the Amrit Hotel, four rooms each with bath
added to his family's lakeside home.
   A friend, 22-year-old Madabah Prasad Neupane, leaned on his
bicycle and mused about changes since Pokhara's hotel boom began in
the late 1960s. ``People here used to be farmers. Now they find the
hotel business is an easy way to get money,'' he said.
   Roberts grumbles about the ``concrete mess'' of today's Pokhara,
but his trekking service here makes him part of the place. He even
has a role in one supposed legend of the ersatz town.
   One guidebook relates how an expedition that Roberts led in 1957
to climb 22,958-foot Macha Pucchare _ Fishtail Peak, the nearest to
the town _ turned back because Sherpa guides feared the wrath of
the ``mountain goddess.''
   Not so, said Roberts. The Sherpas had no superstitions, and it
was two British climbers who were forced to quit about 150 feet
from the top.
   ``We were beaten by the mountain,'' he said.
   ``It's still not been climbed,'' he added. ``It's nice to have
something untouched.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
