<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:ConnerPrairie     04-25 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Conner Prairie,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Conner Prairie</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY703</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOBLESVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conner Prairie, one of the nation's
most authentic 19th-century villages, is adding something new: a
state-of-the-art, $10.5 million museum center.
   The museum center will open May 7 with a two-day celebration.
   Conner Prairie, six miles north of Indianapolis, depicts the
lives, times, attitudes and values of Indiana's first settlers. It
stretches over 250 acres and attracts 200,000 visitors annually.
   ``You're in your own historical novel or personal John Wayne
movie,'' said Frank Werner, who supervises the museum's
documentation. ``People who know nothing of the 1830s come out here
and suddenly find themselves wrapped up in the history. We awaken
people to the realities _ good and bad.''
   The museum center will house a permanent gallery, temporary
exhibition hall, audio-visual program, restaurant, 100-seat
theater, library, classrooms and administrative offices.
   ``The center has been designed as a complement to the village,''
museum smokeswoman Brenda Myers says. ``It's a modern visitor's
center meant to augment what's outside. The village is real, so why
imitate?''
   Open since 1974, Conner Prairie features ``citizens''
interpreting everyday events from a 19th-century perspective.
Visitors are encouraged to participate in hands-on activities as
they circulate among the town's 30 authentic buildings.
   ``Kids can poke around and play here and that doesn't happen at
most historic sites,'' Myers said. ``There are so many generic
living history museums and `no touch' places out there. That's what
we want to avoid.
   ``We encourage active participation because we want visitors to
get not only a sense of how people lived, but how they felt. How
better to learn history?''
   Werner said family members of all ages enjoy chatting with the
more than 100 history interpreters at Conner Prairie and joining
them in weaving, making soap, cooking, working with wood and
playing pioneer games.
   ``You can't describe what the interpreters do as acting,'' said
Werner, who also participates in the role-playing. ``It goes beyond
acting. You're recreating social, political, cultural and emotional
circumstances.''
   He also underlined the museum's success in educating visitors _
in some cases _ despite themselves.
   ``People expect the typical history museum where everything is
`over there' and roped off,'' Werner said. ``But here, no one's
lecturing you. People's hesitancy breaks down and they become a
part of the village. We impart factual knowledge without their
knowing it.''
   Evening concerts on the prairie, candlelight walks and
hearthside suppers are among the special programs scheduled
year-round at the museum. Families can also relive the pioneer
experience by reserving a rustic cabin on the prairie or by
attending horse races, weddings, funerals and political debates in
the village.
   ``We generally have funerals in the fall, because that was the
cholera season. We aim to make visitors feel and understand that
these are real people, not just historic figures,'' Myers said.
``Everything here has to be tried and true and confirmed by at
least three sources.''
   International pharmaceutical heir Eli Lilly originally purchased
the property in 1934. With his wife, he restored the original
William Conner home, decorating it with period antiques before
donating it and the surrounding farmland to Earlham College in 1964.
   Conner, a frontiersman, trader and statesman, was instrumental
in developing central Indiana during the early 19th century.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
