<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:WithConnerPrairie-Historic     04-25 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: With Conner Prairie-Historic,0232</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>SPECIAL EDITION</BYLINE>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: With Conner Prairie-Historic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   For travelers with a special interest in American history, in
rediscovering American roots, there are numerous book guides to the
past.
   Among them is the lavish Reader's Digest ``America's Historic
Places,'' published this spring ($26.95). It is an oversized travel
guide and reference book to 500 locations throughout the country,
including historic battlefields from Gettysburg, Pa., to the Alamo;
mansions like the Wentworth-Coolidge mansion in Portsmouth, N.H.,
and Beauvoir, the spacious cottage in Biloxi, Miss., where
Jefferson Davis lived the last 12 years of his life; and monuments
from the national capital's Washington Monument to Iowa's Effigy
Mounds, the Hopewell Indian burial sculptures.
   The well-illustrated book has travel-planning details, such as
when places are open and how much they charge, as well as
background text on the sites, listed according to regions.
   Another travel book focusing on America's history is
``Experiencing America's Past,'' a paperback guide to restored,
re-created and reconstructed museum villages (Wiley Press, 1986,
$12.95).
   Authors Gerald and Patricia Gurek list some 40 places from Old
Sturbridge Village in Sturbridge, Mass., a re-created New England
town of the 1830s, to the Greenfield Village and Henry Ford Museum
in Dearborn, Mich., an indoor-outdoor museum dedicated to the
automobile. However, the book deals only with places beteween the
East Coast and the Midwest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
