<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0653EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Asheville     04-25 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Asheville,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Asheville</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Dixieland was a big cheaply constructed frame house of 18 or
20 drafty high-ceilinged rooms: it had a rambling, unplanned
gabular appearance.''
   In Thomas Wolfe's autobiographical first novel, `Look Homeward,
Angel,'' ``Dixieland'' was the fictional name for the place called
Old Kentucky Home, a boarding house run by his mother in his
birthplace of Asheville, N.C. Wolfe moved into the boarding house
when he was about 6 years old.
   ``The construction was after her own plans,'' Wolfe wrote of the
house, ``and of the cheapest material: it never lost the smell of
raw wood, cheap varnish and flimsy rough plastering.''
   Wolfe's mother, Julia (the Eliza of ``Look Homeward, Angel'')
bought the house in 1906 for $6,500. She renovated it, added rooms
and a sun porch and rented to traveling salesmen, vaudeville
performers, school teachers, and others. Her business cards
advertised, ``Large Lawns, No Sick People, Rates Reasonable.''
   Wolfe's father, W.O., refused to become a part of the enterprise
and stayed at the old family home on Woodfin Street, now a YMCA.
   The boarders provided Wolfe with much material for his novels.
   ``Look Homeward, Angel'' shocked Asheville residents of the
time, who objected to the unvarnished, thinly-disguised portraits
of those in Wolfe's fictional town of ``Altamont.'' The book was
banned from the local Asheville library.
   But today, there's renewed interest in Thomas Wolfe _ the 1988
Pulitzer Prize for biography went to David Herbert Donald for
``Look Homeward: A Life of Thomas Wolfe'' _ and Asheville, N.C., is
saying you can go home again.
   The 28-room boarding house at 48 Spruce St. (Spring St. in
Wolfe's novel) is now a literary shrine, open to the public, with
formal tours ($1 admission).
   A ``Living History'' attraction is featured this May 14-15, with
role players at the house wearing period costumes of 1916, the year
Wolfe left Asheville to attend the University of North Carolina in
Chapel Hill.
   ``We try very hard to present the house and its inhabitants
exactly as they were back then,'' says Steve Hill, site manager of
the Wolfe Memorial. ``The costumes of the people playing the role
of boarders are specially made to assure their authenticity.
   ``Once visitors enter the home, they will think they have taken
a trip back in time to 1916. Even the music we play is from that
time period.''
   The house reflects the early 1900s with furnishings and many
personal effects intact. An upstairs bedroom contains Wolfe's
belongings from his New York apartment, including clothing, a
writing table and typewriter (which he never used, preferring to
write in longhand).
   Wolfe, also the author of ``Of Time and the River'' and ``You
Can't Go Home Again,'' among others, died in 1938. The 50th
anniversary of his death will be marked with a special program at
the home in September. In October, there will be an open house to
commemorate his birthday.
   Another tourist site in the area is the Biltmore House, the
George W. Vanderbilt mansion built in Asheville in 1885 by
architect Richard Morris Hunt and landscape designer Frederick Law
Olmsted.
   Touted as ``the largest, grandest residential estate ever built
in America,'' the Renaissance-style chateau has 250 rooms and 17
acres of gardens. Built as Vanderbilt's dream house in the
mountains outside of Asheville, it originally encompassed 125,000
acres.
   After Vanderbilt's death in 1914, part of the estate was deeded
to the federal government to form the nucleus of the Pisgah
National Forest, part sold for a section of the Blue Ridge Parkway
and part incorporated into the residential town of Biltmore Forest.
   The house museum is open for tours and now includes the Biltmore
Winery.
   Asheville is the largest city in western North Carolina, bounded
by the Blue Ridge Mountains to the east, and the Great Smoky
Mountains National Park about 50 miles to the west along the border
with Tennessee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0654EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Airlines     04-25 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Airlines,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The consumer uprising by air travelers appears
to be easing a bit as the 1988 summer travel season approaches.
   Complaints about airline service, though still coming into the
Transportation Department at the rate of several thousand a month,
have eased as airlines try to eliminate what irritates travelers
the most.
   Under government pressure, the major air carriers have scheduled
flights more realistically, eased the bunching of flights around
busy travel times and funneled additional manpower and money into
dealing with their customers.
   ``Much of the confusion and inconvenience is behind us now,''
said Stephen Hayes, vice president for public information at the
Air Transport Association, the airline trade group.
   Hayes acknowledged past problems, but suggested in a recent
speech that the airlines are determined to provide better service.
   Cornish Hitchcock, legal affairs director for the Aviation
Consumer Action Project, a public interest group that keeps tabs on
aviation issues and has been critical of the industry in the past,
also suggests that perhaps the worst consumer problems in aviation
may be over.
   At least, he says, there may not be ``the indifference to the
plight of passengers'' that marked 1987 as far as many of the major
air carriers were concerned.
   ``I'm not sure you can declare victory yet,'' said Hitchcock in
an interview, adding that the test is likely to come as the busy
summer travel season begins.
   For millions of people who travel by air, 1987 often became a
nightmare. In June of last year, the Transportation Department
received as many complaints about air travel as it had received in
all of the previous five months. Members of Congress began talking
of re-regulating the industry and on more than one occasion unruly
passengers stormed a ticket counter because a flight had been
canceled or they faced long delays.
   The turmoil and pressure from Congress caused the Transportation
Department to get tough with the airlines.
   They were told to stop scheduling flights unrealistically,
knowing that delays would result. And in a major change the
airlines were told beginning last September to make detailed
reports to the government about their on-time performance as well
as complaints about mishandled bags and problems with overbooking.
   After six months of such reports, it became clear that even in a
good month about one-fifth of the flights by 14 major airlines are
likely to be late. The airlines worst performance came last October
when one-third of the flights were late.
   Today the on-time record of each flight can be provided by a
travel agent or airline reservation clerk through the reservation
computer. A code shows how often a flight has been on time in the
previous month, although a customer normally must ask for the
information.
   But travelers so far have not availed themselves to such
information on a wide-scale basis, according to travel agents.
Furthermore, some critics have argued that the information is of
minimal value because often a traveler has little choice as to
which flight to take to a particular city.
   Many members of Congress want more detailed consumer reporting
by the airlines, but consumer legislation aimed at the airlines has
been bogged down in a dispute over testing airline employes for
drugs.
   Airline opposition is strongest to provisions in pending
legislation that would require the Transportation Department as
well as airlines to provide toll-free telephone lines for consumer
complaints; provide free tickets for lost baggage; require that
tickets be refundable; and require airlines to establish a minimum
time for flights.
   These provisions if approved would force the cutback of service
and harm consumers, the airlines have argued.
   Meanwhile, the airlines are not yet certain what _ if any _
problems will develop this summer from two new requirements from
the Federal Aviation Administration.
   A new regulation that bans smoking on flights of two hours or
less could unleash not only confrontations aboard aircraft but
prompt a range of complaints about enforcement.
   Furthermore, neither the airlines nor travelers have gotten
accustomed to carry-on baggage restrictions that went into effect
at the beginning of the year.
   As the busy travel season begins both the smoking and baggage
rules are likely to result in at least some friction, says
Hitchcock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0654EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Disabled     04-25 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Disabled,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Disabled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Groups that represent the handicapped are
eagerly awaiting a Transportation Department regulation _ expected
within a few months _ that they hope will clarify their rights
aboard commercial airliners.
   People who must use wheelchairs or are blind have complained for
years that they are being discriminated against and often
embarrassed when they travel by air.
   The battle lines between the handicapped and the airline
industry have at times been tense. According to the National
Federation of the Blind, there have been more than 20 blind people
arrested and taken from aircraft because of disputes over seating
or other issues.
   ``What the blind want most is simple, straightforward,
uncomplicated and reasonable. We want to be left alone to buy our
tickets and fly in peace,'' Marc Mauer, president of the
federation, told a government panel last September.
   The new regulations are expected to provide broad guidelines to
the airlines on how they should accommodate the handicapped and
also provide specific requirements.
   ``Once we get these regulations in draft form a lot of people
will finally know what their rights are and the airlines will know
what their obligations are. Things will be a lot clearer,'' says
David Capozzi, an official of the Paralyzed Veterans of America.
   The regulations stem from the Air Carrier Access Act, enacted by
Congress in 1986 to specifically guarantee the rights of the
handicapped to have access to air travel without discrimination.
   Capozzi, who uses a wheelchair, said issues still to be resolved
include:
   _ The question of where handicapped passengers should be allowed
to sit. Federal regulations include no seating restrictions,
although many airlines have policies that direct handicapped to be
seated in certain sections of a plane.
   _ Should airlines be allowed to set a limit on the number of
handicapped people to allow on a single flight? Airlines want to
restrict such passengers to no more than the number of emergency
exits on an aircraft.
   _ Should a handicapped traveler be required to be accompanied by
an attendant? Advocacy groups for the handicapped argue that should
be up to the traveler involved.
   The seating issue is among the most controversial.
   The airlines want the government to specifically exclude
handicapped passengers from certain seats, such as the row next to
an emergency exit. But groups representing the handicapped scoff at
suggestions that a blind person might be a liability in such a
location. They also say that if there is a restriction it should be
limited to the door adjacent to the exit and not an entire row.
   Some airlines require the handicapped to be seated in specific
seats in an aircraft. Recently, a blind passenger aboard a Midway
Airlines jet was arrested when she refused to move from the smoking
section at the rear of the plane to the first row close to an exit
door.
   Capozzi said that the incident was an example of another problem
facing the handicapped.
   ``They (the airlines) treat the disabled persn as a homogenized
group. You need to look at the individual differences,'' he says.
Travelers who are confined to wheelchairs, for example, like the
first row of an airplane because of the easy access, but to a blind
person that same requirement may not be irrelevant, he suggests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:TexasSeaWorld     04-25 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Texas Sea World,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Texas Sea World</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY707</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shamu, Namu and Kandu are readying a
killer of a sea show that organizers hope will fishtail with the
Alamo and the city's River Walk.
   While the killer whales swim around in a 7 million gallon tank,
gardeners are putting the final landscaping touches on Sea World of
Texas, a $140 million, 250-acre facility billed as the nation's
largest marine theme park.
   The park's ``Big Splash'' opening is set for May 28, but
workers, animals and trainers are already performing in rehearsals
for visitors.
   Sea World, 13 miles northwest of downtown San Antonio, will be
open year-round. It is expected to employ 2,000 people during its
peak summer season, generate a $25 million annual payroll and
attract 3 million visitors bearing another $300 million yearly for
the park's and South Texas' economies.
   City and tourist industry officials have looked at Sea World as
a magnet for tourists to help the state diversify from its
dependency on petroleum, but Sea World chairman George Becker warns
against expecting too much too soon.
   ``I've cautioned a few people that we'll do the very best that
we can, but not to rest on their laurels and expect us to be the
end-all and the answer to all of their business problems,'' he said.
   Visitors can expect to see the park's star, Shamu, a two-ton
killer whale that was among the fish and animals brought in from
three other Sea World parks around the country.
   Shamu will perform in a 4,500-seat stadium. At other, smaller
stadiums, dolphins, seals, sea lions, walruses and other animals
will show their stuff, too.
   Skiers will perform acrobatics in a 12-acre lake, and visitors
can walk across the United States via a one-acre ``map'' of the
country.
   There are restaurants, lounges, a disco for teen-agers and a
playground for children. There also is Cypress Gardens West, a
botanical center where a variety of flowers will bloom year-round.
   San Antonio tourism already generates more than $1 billion
annually, with lures like the Alamo and the River Walk.
   Texas is home to Six Flags of Texas in Arlington and to
AstroWorld in Houston, both of which attract about 1.7 million
visitors a year each.
   Tourist industry officials believe Sea World will help, not
hurt, those amusement parks.
   ``It's actually going to help them because it completes the
triangle of from San Antonio, Houston and the Dallas-Fort Worth
area,'' said Larry Todd, director of the Texas Tourist Agency.
   He said Sea World is following the lead of other tourist
attractions by promoting Texas first and its location second.
   ``I don't think tourism is a panacea, but it's all fresh, new
money and it's an immediate boost to the economy and it's rapidly
becoming one of our top industries,'' Todd said.
   ``We Texans had better face the fact that tourism is an industry
whose time has come. We have sat back and been dependent on oil and
agriculture and haven't needed tourism, and now all of a sudden we
need it and we need to market Texas intelligently,'' he said.
   (Sea World's one-day admission is $18.95 for adults and $15.95
for senior citizens (55 and older) and children 3-11. A 12-month
pass is $49 for adults and $39 for children. Founders Club pass,
available until May 28, is $125 and offers special discounts and is
good for admission through Dec. 31, 1991. Sea World sales office
number is 512-523-3400.)
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Europe     04-25 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Europe,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   As the well-known old European capital cities _ London, Paris,
Rome _ slowly regain travel favor with Americans, ``Andrew Harper's
Hideaway Report'' provides a list of ``enchanting'' small hotels he
describes as ``well-managed, personalized properties nestled in
uniquely private settings.''
   Harper is a pseudonym for the editor and publisher who travels
the world incognito for a monthly newsletter directed primarily at
top business executives with a median annual income of more than
$200,000.
   His choices as ``1987 Hideaways of the Year'' in Europe include
these country house hotels:
   _ Park Hotel Kenmare (Kenmare, Ireland)
   _ Chewton Glen (New Milton, England)
   _ Bodysgallen Hall (Llandudno, Wales)
   _ Arisaig House (Arisaig, Scotland)
   _ La Reserve de Beaulieu (Beaulieu-sur-Mer, France)
   _ Zurserhof (Zurs am Arlberg, Austria)
   _ Falsled Kro (Falsled, Denmark)
   _ Il Pellicano (Porto Ercole, Italy)
   _ Wald and Schlosshotel Friedrichsruhe (near Ohringen, West
Germany)
   _ Pousada da Rainha Santa Isabel (Estremaz, Portugal)
   Two ``urban sanctuaries'' listed by Harper as best small hotels
are The Plaza in Copenhagen, Denmark, and the Hotel de Orangerie in
Bruges, Belgium.
   His selections, he says, are based on service, charm, comfort,
decor, food and ``the intangible Q factor that separates the good
from the truly enchanting.''
   Harper, who promotes his newsletter as ``a connoisseur's guide
to peaceful and unspoiled places,'' limits his circulation to about
15,000 and carries no advertising. He says his subscribers are
willing to pay a premium ``to get away from other people in a very
crowded world.''
   In 1987, more than 6 million Americans visited Europe, about 18
percent more than the previous year, according to the European
Travel Commission. ETC said it was the second best year ever for
U.S. travel to Europe, topped only by the 6.4 million total of 1985.
   The 23 member countries of the commission forecast 1988 traffic
slightly ahead of last year, despite the decline of the dollar
overseas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0656EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Soho     04-25 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Soho,0676</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Soho</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soho, the Bohemian neighborhood famed for its
smorgasbord of restaurants and expensive, tourist-oriented topless
bars, is cleaning up its naughty image.
   Families are moving back to the once seedy half-mile square area
of central London that was originally settled by immigrants and
refugees.
   Trendy restaurants, wine bars and media companies are moving
next door to generations-old firms of tailors, silversmiths and
clockmakers, reclaiming the classic Georgian buildings from what
was collectively known as ``the vice.''
   Part of Soho has become the capital's Chinatown, with Gerard
Street converted into a busy mall lined with Chinese restaurants,
supermarkets, bookstores and pay phones with pagoda-style roofs.
   The impetus for change came from Soho's residents who were tired
of gazing out their windows at pulsating pink neon signs boasting
``Girls, Girls, Girls,'' and of having to slink past peep shows,
pornographic cinemas, lingerie shops and topless bars every time
they took their children to school or shopped for groceries.
   ``The local community realized that it was them or us,''
explained Bryan Burrough, chairman of the Soho Society. ``And we
wanted to make sure it was us.''
   Soho became synonymous with sleaze during World War II when
American soldiers swarmed to its clubs and pubs. But Burrough said
Soho didn't hit rock bottom until the mid-1970s.
   ``Prior to the mid-1960s, `the vice' was represented in the main
by prostitutes who were fairly unnoticeable,'' he said.
   ``In the 1970s it became sex cinemas, topless encounter bars,
all sorts of things totally outside the provisions of the law. So
ordinary, legitimate businesses were being pushed out.''
   The 1,000-member Soho Society was founded in 1972 as a community
group, and one of first accomplishments was to have Soho declared a
conservation area, meaning nothing can be demolished without
permission from the Westminster borough council.
   Westminster then passed tougher laws to regulate the flesh
trade. The borough set aside just 10 licenses for sex shops, and a
spokeswoman says only five were actually issued, all to book and
video stores.
   Burrough said about 20 more sex shops still operate illegally,
compared with a decade ago when 185 Soho buildings were devoted to
the sex industry. He said 18 such buildings were on Greek Street
alone, but now its four short blocks are home to 18 restaurants,
three pubs, two sandwich bars, a patisserie, and only one sex shop.
   Soho, in the heart of London's West End theater district, is
bounded by Oxford Street, Regent Street, Charing Cross Road and
Leicester Square.
   The name is thought to come from the ancient hare-hunting cry,
``So-Ho.'' The area's cosmopolitan flavor dates back to its first
immigrants, French Protestants known as Huguenots who arrived in
the late 1600s. Germans and Italians, many of them cooks and
waiters, arrived in the 1860s and 1870s, followed by Polish and
Russian Jews, many of them tailors, in the 1890s.
   Joining the melting pot were families from almost every other
European country as well as British colonies past and present,
Indians and Hong Kong Chinese.
   In the 1960s a favorite Soho haunt was Carnaby Street, with its
swinging fashion shops stocked with bellbottoms, go-go boots,
miniskirts and fishnet stockings.
   Today, Soho's nooks and crannies are still packed with old
established family businesses. Here the Savile Row tailors have
their workshops, and gold lace is handmade for Buckingham Palace's
livery.
   Sprinkled among them are dozens of new film production and
distribution offices, film laboratories, advertising agencies and
other support services for London's TV and cinema industry.
   Street for street, Soho is said to have more restaurants than
any other part of London, ranging from Japanese sushi bars to a
1950s-style chrome and formica diner.
   Gourmets and gourmands can wallow in a cheese shop offering 200
varieties including car-tire-sized wheels of Swiss emmenthal. A
coffee shop sells 25 types of fresh, aromatic beans, and barbecued
ducks hang in Chinese markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
