<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0659EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:RailPasses     04-25 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Rail Passes,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Rail Passes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PRUDENCE HELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Take the train: That's the message of railroads
all over Europe, North America and Japan.
   Their lures include rail passes and reduced rates, tours
sponsored by the railroads or by companies using rail
transportation, and ride-a-bit, drive-a-bit arrangements covering
trains and cars.
   Railroads have taken into account that a person may not want to
ride the rails continuously, day after day, and yet wants full
money's worth from his pass. So some offer passes that are good for
perhaps nine days of train travel within a 21-day period or 16 days
within a month, or other combinations. Eurail's Flexipass and the
French Railpass fall into this category.
   The Flexipass is one of Eurail's four types of passes, all first
class and covering 16 countries from Austria and Greece to Portugal
and Ireland, but not Britain. For that, one would want the first
class or economy class BritRail pass.
   Eurail, BritRail and the France Railpass all must be purchased
outside the countries concerned.
   Travelers seeking to concentrate on a given region might look
into the Scandinavian Rail Pass, covering Denmark, Finland, Norway
and Sweden and sold in the Scandinavian countries, or the Benelux
Tourrail Pass, covering Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg and
sold only in those countries.
   The European Travel Commission also lists more than a dozen
countries that have their own passes. They include Italy (B.T.L.C.
Pass), Ireland (Rambler), Austria (Austrian Network Pass), and
Switzerland (Swiss Holiday Card).
   A number of countries also offer discounts of up to 50 percent
for senior citizens or sell half-fare cards entitling a traveler to
half-fare on all train travel for a given period.
   On this side of the Atlantic, Amtrak has its All Aboard America
fares, enabling people to take the train to any destination within
one region of the country for a set roundtrip price, within two
regions for a bit more and across the entire country for still
another set price. One intermediate stop is allowed each way.
Amtrak also offers a $7 Return Fare under which the purchaser of a
one-way ticket in many cases can get the return trip for only $7.
On regular Amtrak fares, seniors get a discount.
   Canada's railroad system, Via, has a Canrailpass and a
Youthrailpass, which can be purchased in Canada, and senior
citizens get one-third off regular fares.
   In Japan, there are first-class and ordinary rail passes _ and a
new undersea tunnel, more than 33 miles, linking the main island of
Honshu with Hokkaido to the north.
   In many countries, passes also carry such perks as cut-rate
entry to places of interest or free travel on city buses or subways.
   This is just a glimpse along the tracks. Railroads urge
travelers to consider all the options before they make a choice.
Sometimes a senior discount, for instance, or a one-time payment
for half-fare privileges might be a bigger bargain than a pass.
   Many Americans, unused to trains, may feel lost without a car.
The railroads have the answer: a car waiting at the station.
Explore the countryside, return the car, and board the train again
for the next destination _ and the next car. Eurail users can even
leave the car involved in another country in some cases.
   For travelers who don't want to lift a finger, there are tours
by rail: Mexico's famed Copper Canyon with its 37 bridges and 86
tunnels; Canada coast-to-coast; a nostalgic trip on the Orient
Express from Istanbul to Zurich, Switzerland. You name it. The less
ambitious can take one-day excursions _ from Paris to the chateau
country, or London to Bath, Stonehenge and Salisbury, for instance.
   Tours take care of luggage, hotels, many meals, sightseeing and
escorts to tell one what it's all about and leap the language
barrier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0700EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Spas     04-25 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Spas,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Spas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PRUDENCE HELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What's in a name? Plenty, if it happens to be
Spa, Belgium. For that town in the eastern Ardennes with its
healing waters has given its name worldwide to the spots where
people go to feel better, shape up physically, unknot their
tensions, shed excess pounds and be pampered with manicures,
pedicures, facials, hair-styling and the like.
   Spa, Belgium, was mentioned by the Roman Pliny the Elder in the
first century A.D., it is believed. In the Middle Ages, its healing
waters began to be exploited. Beginning in about the 16th century,
royalty including Margaret of Navarre, Queen Christina of Sweden,
Peter the Great of Russia and Austrian Emperor Joseph II frequented
the resort.
   It is still there, catering not only to those who seek a
``cure,'' but to those who just want a pleasant vacation, with
golf, riding, fishing, tennis, a casino, concerts, a nearby
racetrack and parachute jumping exhibits at a nearby airfield.
   From Alaska to Brazil and Australia and Japan to Greece and
Hungary, people are going to spas _ all kinds of spas.
   Spa-Finders, which puts out a spa catalogue and also uses a
computer to help match people with the right spa for them, lists
eight major categories. They include classic fitness spas that
combine exercise, diet and relaxation in fairly equal proportions;
spas that specialize in behavior modification; those that feature
mineral springs, and holistic spas. The holistic spas are often
vegetarian and offer such Eastern practices as yoga and Siatsu
massage.
   Spas have a vocabulary of their own _ including Siatsu, which is
a Japanese method of massage that follows the patterns used in
acupuncture. A person can become involved with a Scotch hose, Swiss
shower, salt glo, polarity, reflexology, thalassotherapy _ or sit
it out in a Roman bath, a heated sea-water jacuzzi with benches.
   The average person pedaling an exercise bike and swimming laps
at the ``Y'' may think spas are not for her or him. Too expensive.
Not so, say the spa people, who say you can find some costing only
a few hundred dollars a week per person.
   Ryan Vollmer, in ``Affordable Spas & Fitness Resorts,'' says
nearly 90 percent of spas now operating in the United States cost
less than $1,000 a week, and some are priced in the $400 to $500
range.
   Some are advertised for even less: Spend a week at a New
Hampshire retreat that emphasizes stress-reduction by massage,
yoga, meditation, long walks in the woods, sunbathing and swimming,
for instance. Or you can get spruced up at a resort hotel and spa
in the Arkansas Hot Springs National Park-Ouachita Mountain area.
In California, one is invited to bathe in hot springs at
temperatures of 98 to 120 degrees at a kerosene-lit hotel on ground
that was considered sacred for healing by the Indians. Bring your
own food and cook it on a country stove. All these places are under
$400.
   At the other end of the price list are such establishments as
California's Golden Door, whose fans insist it's worth every bit of
the more than $3,000 one will spend for a week's hospitality.
   Jeffrey Joseph of Spa-Finders has found that the spa market is a
United States one. If Americans go abroad, he says, it's usually to
well-known resorts such as Montecatini in Italy, Baden-Baden, West
Germany, or Baden, Switzerland.
   But there are bargains waiting all over Europe and other
countries - including Australia, Margaret Island in the Danube at
Budapest, the Greek island of Kos, Yugoslavia and Austria _ and
Spa, Belgium.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0701EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Cruises     04-25 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Cruises,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Cruises</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY705</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE SCHROEDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   For some vacationers, cruising down the river means viewing
castles on the Rhine, Egyptian monuments along the Nile or jungle
foliage on the banks of the Amazon.
   But Americans with a sense of history who prefer traveling
closer to home will find several offbeat programs offered this
season by tour operators emphasizing the nation's heritage.
   They include a package tour for vacationers lured by the call of
the wild to Jack London country, a sail down the St. Lawrence River
where American patriots skirmished with British redcoats, and the
exploration of rivers once crowded with Union and Confederate
gunboats.
   ``To the pioneers, the rivers were the interstate highways of
America,'' says Jack Biesterfeld, president of Great American River
Cruises, an Illinois-based company that specializes in travel
programs focusing on North American history and heritage.
   According to Biesterfeld, the cruises will be using a variety of
boats and ships ranging from historic paddlewheel steamboats to
sleek river cruisers, and will be combined with land tours ``that
enable the traveler to delve even deeper into the history of
America.''
   Offerings this year include a two-week excursion through Jack
London territory that follows the footsteps of the early gold
miners and sourdoughs of Alaska and the Yukon, with stops at
Dawson, Whitehorse and Skagway.
   Another program is a 10-day ``Cruise to the Mountains''
combining a trip on the Mississippi Queen steamboat from St. Louis
along the Ohio, Tennessee and Mississippi rivers with a tour of the
Great Smoky Mountains.
   There also is an eight-day program tracing the trail of the
California gold rush ``49ers'' on the Sacramento and San Joaquin
rivers, with a motorcoach tour of the rugged California coast from
San Francisco through the Big Sur to Los Angeles, ending with a
two-day stay aboard the Queen Mary.
   ``Hudson Heritage'' is a nine-day tour highlighting the maritime
history of the East Coast, including cruises on Long Island Sound,
and on the Hudson and Connecticut rivers, plus visits to Sleepy
Hollow and West Point.
   Farther afield, another tour operator, New York-based Special
Expeditions, Inc., has scheduled an offbeat 27-day August voyage
called ``Impressions of an Arctic Summer.''
   The voyage aboard the 80-passenger ship ``M.S. Polaris'' begins
in Iceland and ends in Halifax, Nova Scotia. Points in between
include Greenland, Baffin Island, Hudson Bay, Labrador and
Newfoundland.
   Plans call for visits to Eric the Red's Viking settlement at
Narsarsuaq, which dates back to 982 A.D., and several Eskimo
villages. Polar bears inhabit the pack ice, and seabird colonies
abound.
   Other unusual programs beckoning travelers to faraway places
this summer include one-week cruises aboard a 16-passenger wooden
schooner modeled after a Greek pirate ship.
   The schooner ``Andromeda'' departs from Piraeus, the port for
Athens, every Saturday with a crew of five to visit 15 Greek
islands.
   The itinerary includes a call at the port of Gerakas, once a
departure point for infamous pirate ships; the island of Hydra,
where cars are prohibited and donkeys provide the primary means of
transportation, and a picturesque cove on Spetsopoula, an island
privately owned by Greek shipping tycoon Stavros Niarchos.
   ``Sailing around the Greek isles on a pirate ship may sound like
an unaffordable luxury, but in truth it doesn't have to be,''says
Fred Schwartz, executive director of Vacation Network, a
Chicago-based tour operator.
   ``In addition to being one of the world's most beautiful
destinations, Greece happens to be among today's best vacation
values.''
   But the biggest news _ literally _ in the maritime travel
business this year is the launching of what is billed as the
largest cruise ship ever built, ``Sovereign of the Seas,'' a
74,000-ton, $185 million vessel which can accommodate more than
2,200 passengers.
   The ship has 12 passenger decks and is measures 874 feet from
stem to stern, nearly the length of three football fields placed
end-to-end.
   For those who simply love the idea of a cruise _ without
necessarily going anywhere _ there's the Chakiris Fantasy Cruise, a
weekend trip to virtually nowhere. It leaves New York on a Friday
night and goes down the Hudson River outside the harbor into the
Atlantic Ocean until it returns Sunday afternoon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
