<DOCNO> AP880425-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0701EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Brazil     04-25 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Brazil,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Brazil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ripoffs and muggings of foreign
tourists are giving Rio an image problem, and the government _
discreetly _ is trying to persuaded ``gringos'' to skip this famous
city and visit other parts of vast Brazil.
   ``There's only one trouble spot for tourists in Brazil, and
that's Rio de Janeiro,'' Joao Doria Jr., president of Embratur, the
federal government tourist board, told The AP.
   Police figures are imprecise, but almost every day Rio
newspapers carry stories of Americans, Europeans and even Latins
from the Spanish-speaking part of South America complaining of
1,000 percent jackups of taxi fares, thefts of cameras and wallets
from beaches and hotel rooms, and even outright stickups, sometimes
by armed robbers.
   A federal government poster at Rio's international airport shows
a doll-like figure wearing shorts and a flowery shirt, with a
camera around its neck. Written below in big letters is: ``Respeite
o Turista,'' or ``Respect the Tourist'' in Portuguese, Brazil's
language.
   Embratur's official line is that Rio is still a great place. But
meanwhile, the agency is trying to make it easier for foreigners to
visit other parts of the country.
   Many foreigners don't realize that Brazil is bigger in area than
the 48 contiguous United States, and tropical beach cities such as
Recife and Natal at the country's northeastern tip and the Amazon
jungle gateway of Manaus are thousands of miles closer to the
Northern Hemisphere than Rio is.
   Brazil's Varig Airlines has a daily nonstop run from Miami to
Rio. But one extra flight on that route stops weekly in Manaus,
where Embratur has begun a program of ``ecological tourism'' aimed
at the appreciation for and preservation of the remarkable flora
and fauna along the tributaries of the Amazon River.
   Varig, Air France and Air Portugal now include Recife, with its
miles of palm-fringed, balmy beaches and precious Portuguese
colonial architecture, on some of their European flights.
   ``We want to increase airline competition to Brazilian entry
points that are not now generally well known,'' Doria said. ``The
goal is to reduce air fares and attract more visitors.''
   Despite its climate, scenery, music and cheap currency, Brazil
attracts just 1 percent of world tourism. And of the 2 million
annual visitors, most come from neighboring Argentina and Uruguay,
with the United States in third place, followed by Italy and West
Germany.
   ``Because Brazil is a poor country, surrounded by poor
countries, in the far-off Southern Hemisphere, it will never
compete with places such as Mexico, Spain and Italy for
international tourism,'' Doria said. ``But we do think
realistically we can get our share up to 3 percent.''
   But Brazil's own typical Latin bureaucracy often gets in the way
of tourism objectives.
   The Air Force Ministry, which determines international airline
routes, has been reluctant to promote unrestricted air competition.
``The ministry has been, let us say, conservative in this area, but
still we are making progress,'' Doria said. ``Five years ago, no
charter flights were permitted in Brazil. Today we have them every
week from North America and Europe.''
   Brazil's Foreign Relations Ministry often makes foreign tourists
obtain a visa before they can come to brazil. The standard is
reciprocity: If a foreign country requires a visa for Brazilians,
then citizens of that country must get a visa for Brazil.
   ``Sometimes what sounds right diplomatically doesn't make sense
economically,'' Doria said of the visa policy. ``Take the case of
Canada, which recently instituted visas for Brazil, because some
Brazilian tourists were caught working there illegally. So now
Canadians need visas to visit Brazil. But I can't imagine many
Canadians seeking to work illegally in Brazil.''
   ``Our own government's countermeasures was not in our country's
best interests, financially speaking,'' Doria said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
