<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Curacao     04-25 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Travel: Curacao,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Curacao</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY702</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Third Annual Curacao Open International Pro-Am Windsurf
Championship is set to take place in Caribbean waters off the
Holiday Beach Hotel and Casino June 14-19. More than 100
windsurfers are expected to compete for the $35,000 pro prize.
   Curacao, the largest of five islands of the Netherlands
Antilles, is about 40 miles north of Venezuela.
   The 38-mile-long island is generally warm (average 80 degrees),
dry and windy, with June the windiest month (average 18 mph). Most
of the population cluster around the capital of Willemstad near the
east end of the island, while the western half remains relatively
untouched by civilization.
   Visitors return with reports of numerous bays, white-sand
beaches, and calm, crystal clear waters. Highest point on the
island is St. Christoffelsberg, at 1,220 feet.
   A popular site is the Queen Emma pontoon bridge, one of the
oldest pontoon bridges in the Western Hemisphere, which celebrates
its 100th anniversary this year. Spanning St. Anna Bay, the Queen
Emma swings open every time a cruise ship calls to dock at the
terminal in Willemstad or a tanker or cargo vessel sails into the
inner harbor's deepwater port.
   U.S. citizens don't need a passport, but proof of citizenship
and a return ticket.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
