<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Inter-Continental plans to open its new, $50 million hotel in
Atlanta this September. The 375-room hotel is connected to the
Lenox Square shopping center and the Lenox station of the rapid
transit rail line.
   Inter-Continental Hotels Corp., now owned by Grand Metropolitan
PLC, a British conglomerate, now operates 11 hotels in the United
States.
   The Inter-Continental Cancun, on the northeastern Yucatan
peninsula of Mexico, opened in February.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Sunfest jazz and art festival in West Palm Beach, Fla., in
its sixth year, takes place April 28 through May 1. The festival,
which features strolling street entertainers, an art show, a series
of water events as well as the ``Jazz on the Lake'' series, is held
along a three-quarter mile stretch of the Intracoastal Waterway.
   ``Jazz on the Lake'' performances will include entertainers
George Benson, Kenny G, Diane Schuur and Bonnie Raitt, among others.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Orangina Street Performers Festival is set for Memorial Day
weekend in May at Boston's Faneuil Hall Marketplace.
   The four days of entertainment includes a show of puppeteering,
still-walking, balloon sculpting, and juggling.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 Summer Lights arts festival in Nashville, Tenn., is
scheduled for June 2-5, followed by Fan Fair, country music's
annual salute to its fans, June 6-12.
   Summer Lights will expand this year to include the riverfront
along the Cumberland River as well as the downtown historic section.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   New York State celebrates its home-grown wine industry with a
spring festival from May 1 to June 20 in the wine-producing
regions: the Finger Lakes, along Lake Erie, the north fork of Long
Island, and the Hudson Valley.
   In addition to regular tastings and lectures on wine
appreciation, there will be ``release celebrations,'' barrel
tastings of pre-release wines, picnics, hay wagon tours, and art
and antique exhibits.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   A shop in Chicago, called The Savvy Traveler, features travel
gadgets and games from a down-sized coffee maker for your hotel
room to a fold-up bicycle.
   ``It used to be that being comfortable while on vacation meant
taking along a steamer trunk,'' says Sandye Wexler, president of
the store. That doesn't have to be, he says in noting that his shop
has things for all the travelers in the family, including the dog.
The Travel Dog contains disposable dishes and napkins designed for
the traveling pet.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Guests at the Lucayan Beach Resort and Casino in Grand Bahama
can swim with dolphins in the open sea in an unusual ocean
adventure.
   Guests can spend a day with head dolphin trainers, learning
about feeding dolphins, assisting them in their daily activities,
and swimming with the dolphins.
   The Dolphin Experience is a joint program of the Underwater
Explorers Society, Open Ocean Adventures and the Grand Bahama
Development Co.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of people visiting Hawaii grew in
1987 for the sixth straight year, thanks partly to a boost by 1.16
million Japanese visitors, the Hawaii Visitors Bureau says.
   The agency reported that a record 5.79 million people visited
the islands last year, a 3.3 percent increase over the then-record
5.6 million in 1986.
   The number of visitors from the U.S. mainland, Canada and other
points west dropped by 1.4 percent, to 4.19 million.
   The decline was offset by an 18 percent increase in visitors
from Asia and the Pacific, who numbered 1.59 million, including
1.16 million Japanese.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A language expert says it's all right to
call San Francisco ``Frisco,'' even though the city's Convention
and Visitors Bureau guidebook is titled ``Don't Call it Frisco.''
   San Francisco's nickname has been all but eradicated in its home
town, mainly because of language snobbery in the early years of
this century, Columbia University lexicographer Allen Walker Read
told a joint session of the Modern Language Association and
American Dialect Society.
   Read said sailors and miners called the port Frisco at least as
early as 1849. Not until 1882 was there any mention in print of
what he termed ``this feverish campaign against `Frisco.'''
   ```Frisco' has its place on the colloquial, informal level,'' he
sayd, ``and the problem would take care of itself if left alone.''
</TEXT>
