<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CableDeal     04-25 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cable Deal,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Comcast, Tele-Communications Acquiring Storer Cable Properties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL MENEZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal by two of the nation's biggest cable
television concerns to pay about $1.55 billion for the cable
systems of the former Storer Communications follows a bigger
consortium's abortive proposal to buy the properties at a higher
price.
   Comcast Corp. and Tele-Communications Inc. announced Sunday they
had a definitive agreement to acquire SCI Holdings, the company
formed when Storer was taken private by the investment firm
Kohlberg, Kravis & Roberts in a $2.5 billion leveraged buyout in
1985.
   SCI last year sold its six television stations for about $1.4
billion, leaving it with cable television systems serving about
1.48 million subscribers in 12 states in the East and South.
   The acquisition is subject to regulatory approval and other
conditions.
   Comcast and Tele-Communications both members of the consortium
that proposed and later dropped a plan to acquire SCI for about
$2.9 billion earlier this year.
   SCI said in December it had gotten a letter of intent for the
acquisition by the consortium, which included Comcast, American
Television and Communications Corp., which is owned by Time Inc.,
and Taft Cable Partners, a partnership of Tele-Communications and
Texas investor Robert M. Bass.
   That proposal was for an acquisition of SCI's 212 million common
shares at between $9.25 and $9.75 apiece, plus the acquisition of
preferred stock and $2.4 billion in debt.
   But the deal fell through in February when the consortium
attempted to cut the purchase price. John Malone, president of
Tele-Communications, contended that SCI had made inaccurate
representations that were disclosed during the course of the deal,
prompting the group to seek a price reduction.
   Comcast and Tele-Communications did not provide details of the
proposed acquisition in a news release, and telephone calls Sunday
to spokespeople at Comcast headquarters in Bala Cynwyd, Pa. and
Tele-Communications headquarters in Denver were unanswered. SCI
offices in Miami were closed Sunday.
   SCI did state that it estimated the purchase price would mean a
payment of between $4 and $4.50 for each outstanding warrant of SCI.
   Comcast operates cable systems serving about 1.35 million
subscribers plus Muzak franchises. The company also owns American
Cellular Network Corp., which operates cellular telephone systems
in New Jersey, Delaware and Maryland.
   Comcast posted a net loss of $9.4 million in its 1987 fiscal
year, compared with a 1986 profit of $1 million, or 3 cents a
share, due to the costs of financing several acquisitions and to
accounting factors. Revenue rose to $309.2 million from $130.8
million.
   Tele-Communications owns or controls cable systems serving about
six million subscribers, according to industry estimates. It also
owns a 52 percent stake in the operations of the newly merged
United Artists Entertainment Co., which has interests in cable
television and movie theaters.
   Tele-Communications posted a profit of $5.6 million, or 4 cents
a share, in its 1987 fiscal year, down from $72.3 million, or 48
cents a share, the previous year. Its revenue rose to $1.7 billion
from $645.7 million.
   The company blamed the earnings decline on the costs of
financing its acquisition of Heritage Communications Inc. and costs
related to its investment in United Artists Entertainment. The
profit figures included one-time gains of $42.4 million in 1987 and
$165 million in 1986 from asset sales, and a charge of $22.5
million in 1986 from settlement of litigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0294 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0835EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-APMeeting     04-25 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Meeting,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AP Members Meet, Hear Perot, Elect Directors</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Perot speaks about 7 p.m. EDT. No PMs lead is expected; Also
moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   H. Ross Perot, the Texas
entrepreneur-turned-philanthropist, addresses the annual luncheon
of The Associated Press today, as newspaper executives gather to
choose directors for the news cooperative.
   The AP annual meeting and luncheon are opening-day events at the
102nd annual convention of the American Newspaper Publishers
Association.
   Perot developed his Electronic Data Systems Inc. from a $1,000
individual investment three decades ago into a computer-services
giant that he sold to General Motors in 1985 for $2.5 billion. He
has donated millions of dollars to schools, hospitals and other
institutions, and has been outspoken in promoting educational and
other social reforms.
   At their annual meeting, AP members also will hear a report on
world trouble spots from AP correspondents based in Nicaragua, the
Soviet Union, South Korea, Israel, and at the White House. Louis D.
Boccardi, president of the AP, will moderate the panel.
   In a letter to the membership, William J. Keating, chairman of
the board of the AP and president of the Detroit Newspaper Agency,
recalled the founding of the news cooperative.
   ``On a day in May 140 years ago, The Associated Press was
created by a group of newspaper publishers to deliver the best news
report possible for their collective needs, at an affordable
cost,'' Keating said. ``Today in this new world of news, the AP
continues to do just that.''
   In his annual report to the record-high 1,428 newspaper members
of the AP, Boccardi said the growth of the news cooperative carries
a clear message:
   ``We are summoned to an ever-growing responsibility to the news
industry, to service, speed, responsiveness, aggressiveness,
accuracy _ and above all else, to truth and fairness. ...
   ``We do not take this increased responsibility lightly, but we
face it confidently,'' Boccardi said. ``Our record has earned your
trust _ but we know that in the world of news, trust must be earned
anew, day by day, story by story.''
   AP members also will elect five members of the cooperative's
board of directors. Directors Robert G. Marbut of the Corpus
Christi (Texas) Caller-Times and John F. McGee of the Charleston
(W. Va.) Daily Mail are retiring after serving the maximum of three
consecutive three-year terms on the AP board.
   Board nominees are William M. Boyd of the Central New Jersey
Home News of New Brunswick; James E. Burgess of Madison's Wisconsin
State Journal; Katherine W. Fanning of the Christian Science
Monitor; Robert C. Maynard of The (Oakland, Calif.) Tribune; Ted M.
Natt of the Longview (Wash.) Daily News; Donald E. Newhouse of the
Newark (N.J.) Star-Ledger; Paul J. O'Brien of The Salt Lake Tribune
of Utah; James H. Ottaway Jr. of the Middletown (N.Y.) Times
Herald-Record; Stanley H. Stauffer of the Topeka (Kan.)
Capital-Journal, and F. Al Totter of the West Covina (Calif.) San
Gabriel Valley Times.
   Burgess, Maynard and Ottaway are incumbents seeking new terms.
   In addition, Edwin L. Heminger of the Findlay (Ohio) Courier and
John Grey Montgomery of the Junction City (Kan.) Daily Union, were
nominated to a board seat to represent a city of less than 50,000
population.
   Heminger is an incumbent board member. AP bylaws require that at
least three directors must be representatives of newspapers
published in small cities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
