<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Stevens 1stLd-Writethru   04-25 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stevens, 1st Ld-Writethru,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Textile Maker Accepts $1.2 Billion Takeover Proposal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning stock price, details;
no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textile giant J.P. Stevens & Co., target of a
protracted takeover battle, has accepted a $1.2 billion cash offer
from two buyers after initially rejecting the deal, the companies
involved said today.
   The $68.50-a-share deal will split up the 175-year-old fabric
maker, one of the nation's largest textile producers and an
important employer in the southeastern United States.
   The major buyer is rival textile producer West Point Pepperell
Inc., which will keep most of Stevens' sheet and towel operations
but sell some to another textile producer, Bibb Co. of Macon, Ga.,
to satisfy previously announced federal antitrust concerns.
   Odyssey Partners, a Wall Street investment firm that had been
vying with Pepperell to buy Stevens, will get the company's other
operations, including its carpet and industrial fabrics plants, for
about $530 million.
   Pepperell and Odyssey arranged the purchase with Stevens after
an initial $1.2 billion offer was rejected, partly because of the
target company's concerns about the tentative nature of Odyssey's
financing.
   The terms were revised over the weekend to Stevens'
satisfaction, and the deal was accepted.
   In early trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Stevens rose 25
cents to $67.75 a share.
   Pepperell has made its bids in conjunction with the NTC Group,
parent of Bibb. Under terms of the agreement with Stevens, the
Pepperell group will acquire the entire company for $68.50 a share
under a tender offer that will expire at midnight EDT May 6, unless
extended.
   Odyssey will then purchase its portion of the the Stevens assets
from Pepperell. But if Pepperell cannot complete its end of the
deal, Odyssey has agreed to purchase Stevens, subject to financing.
Odyssey's outstanding $68.50-a-share tender offer has been extended
to May 20.
   Pepperell's interest in Stevens has centered exclusively on the
company's sheet and towel operations, which include manufacturing
facilities as well as designer brand names. Those operations
account for 60 percent of Stevens' annual sales, which amounted to
$1.61 billion last year.
   Among the top brand names in Stevens' towel and sheet arsenal
are Ralph Lauren, Laura Ashley, Gloria Vanderbilt, Perry Ellis,
Pierre Cardin and Givenchy, among others. Pepperell's brands
include Arrow, Martex, Lady Pepperell and Burberry.
   Headquartered in New York, Stevens employs more than 23,000
people.
   The takeover maneuvering for the company began earlier this year
when management offered to buy it for $765 million.
   Pepperell and Odyssey went three rounds in a heated bidding
contest before announcing last week that they would work together
to draft a joint buyout proposal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
