<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mostly
higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   A Census Bureau report showing lower-than-expected levels of
soybean meal stocks in March supported the soy complex and the
grain markets, analysts said.
   The agency said this morning that U.S. meal stocks totaled
243,000 tons at the end of March, well short of pre-report trade
estimates of between 290,000 and 320,000 tons.
   ``This indicates that March was a very good month for domestic
use and exports,'' said Richard Loewy, senior grain and oilseed
analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Corn was narrowly mixed in early trading. Wheat was slightly
higher amid concerns about dry weather in spring wheat growing
areas, analysts said.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 1{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.16 a bushel; corn was { cent
lower to } cent higher with May at $2.00} a bushel; oats were 1
cent to 2 cents higher with May at $1.65{ a bushel; soybeans were 1
cent to 2\ cents higher with May at $6.65} a bushel.
   Cattle futures posted sharp losses in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange in reaction to Friday's Agriculture
Department report showing greater-than-expected numbers of cattle
being fattened for slaughter. Pork futures also retreated.
   Live cattle were .07 cent to .97 cent lower with June at 69.85
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .18 cent to .67 cent lower with
April at 79.65 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .45 cent lower
with June at 48.30 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .05 cent
to .70 cent lower with May at 51.95 cents a pound.
   Most livestock and meat futures settled higher on Friday,
although pork bellies were lower.
</TEXT>
