<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BoeingOrder     04-25 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Boeing Order,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing Gets $1.4 Billion Order From Air Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. said Monday it received a $1.4 billion
order for 30 jetliners from International Leisure Group, parent
company of Britain's Air Europe.
   The order includes 22 757-200s and eight 737-400s, subject to
the completion of financing. It was one of the largest orders ever
by a foreign carrier for Boeing 757s, and the second-largest on
record for that jetliner.
   The 757s, powered by Rolls-Royce RB211-535E4 engines, will be
delivered beginning 1989. Each plane can seat up to 185 passengers.
   The first of the eight 737s will be delivered in April 1990.
Each 737-400 can seat up to 159 passengers.
   Air Europe and its Spanish associate, Air Europa, already had an
additional four 757s and five 737s on order.
   Boeing now has 270 firm orders for various models of the 757,
and 2,036 orders for 737s, the best-selling jetliner of all time.
</TEXT>
