<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Firestone 1stLd-Writethru   04-25 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Firestone, 1st Ld-Writethru,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firestone Loses Tire Supply Deal with GM</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with shareholders voting to
accept buyout offer by Bridgestone; picks up 8th graf pvs bg'ng,
Firestone's statement ...; Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders of Firestone Tire and Rubber Co.
have voted overwhelmingly in favor of the $2.6 billion buyout by
Bridgestone Corp. of Japan, Firestone Chairman John J. Nevin said
today.
   The Japanese tiremaker's $80-a-share offer was supported by 99.3
percent of the 58 percent of shareholders who voted on the
question, said Nevin, who announced the outcome at a special
shareholders' meeting this morning.
   Bridgestone's tender offer expires Tuesday, and the acquisition
could become effective Wednesday, Nevin said.
   Approval of the Bridgestone offer comes on the heels of General
Motors Corp.'s announcement that it would drop Firestone as a tire
supplier for its vehicles.
   Nevin would not speculate on why GM made the decision.
   ``To a Japanese company, the long term is considerably more
important. We'll look at this as anything one has to deal with in
the business world and decide what path the company has to take in
the future,'' said Bridgestone spokesman Dennis Allen.
   GM spokesman James Crellin said the automaker's action was part
of ``our rationalization study,'' which is a periodic review of
capacity and future needs of suppliers.
   Crellin declined to discuss how long the phaseout of Firestone
tires would take or discuss the amount of business GM does with its
suppliers.
   ``We've got four other tire suppliers: General Tire, Goodyear,
Michelin and Uniroyal-Goodrich,'' Crellin said. ``There are no
plans to look for another supplier at this time. We will be
informing the other four tire suppliers of the availability of
increased business.''
   Nevin said in a statement issued Saturday that he was
``surprised and disappointed'' by GM's move but said Firestone is
confident it will find other markets for its tires without hurting
profits.
   Firestone's statement offered no reason for GM's action, but the
company said it was ``advised by Bridgestone that the action will
have no effect'' on the $80-a-share buyout offer.
   Firestone said the phase-out would occur over two years.
   Estimates in the trade publication Modern Tire Dealer show that
GM buys about 34 percent of its tires from Uniroyal-Goodrich,
making it GM's largest tire supplier. Goodyear is second at 22.5
percent, Firestone third with 20 percent, General Tire fourth at
17.5 percent and Michelin fifth at 4.5 percent.
   Firestone moved its corporate headquarters in November from
Akron, Ohio, to Chicago. It operates four U.S. plants with 1,400
employees at its main plant in Akron.
   Firestone agreed to be acquired in March by Bridgestone, after
an unsolicited takeover bid by Italy's Pirelli SpA.
   Kimball Firestone, a Firestone board member and grandson of
Firestone founder Harvey S. Firestone, said he did not know what
Bridgestone planned to do after the takeover, but he did not
foresee shakeups in the company's top management.
   ``I think it is tight,'' he said of Firestone's corporate
leadership structure. ``I have an impression Bridgestone plans to
leave top management. But it's their call.''
   He said it also seemed logical to leave the headquarters for
Firestone's North American tire-making operation in Akron.
   Firestone is the nation's second-largest tiremaker after
Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co., with tires accounting for nearly 70
percent of its $4.2 billion in annual sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
