<HEAD>Stocks Close Higher In London</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout to UPDATE with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange closed
higher Monday, boosted by a stronger start on Wall Street and a
spate of late buying.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed up 6
points, or 0.3 percent, at 1,777.6.
   Volume was a scant 307.1 million shares, compared with Friday's
514.9 million shares.
   Traders said the stronger Wall Street opening helped to raise
most share prices from their midday doldrums.
   But traders said interest in opening new positions in the market
remained slim in the absence of new market-affecting news and ahead
of Thursday's release of first-quarter profit figures for Imperial
Chemical Industries PLC, one of Britain's largest companies, and
Friday's U.K. trade data for March.
   ``The main feature of this market is that volume remains
strikingly slim,'' one equity salesman said.
   Even issues that were the center of takeover talk last week
``have seemed to fade from the public's consciousness,'' he added.
