<2ND_LINE>BC-Farmers-Batus,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Board Affirms Desire to Remain Independent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers Group Inc., facing a hostile takeover
attempt by a British-owned conglomerate, said Monday its board of
directors has ended talks on a possible leveraged buyout and would
prefer that the company stay independent.
   The insurer's board members, in a meeting Saturday, also
repeated their opposition to the $4.5 billion offer from Batus
Inc., which is owned by BAT Industries PLC of Britain, Farmers said.
   There was no immediate response from Batus, which has
headquarters in Louisville, Ky.
   The possibility of a leveraged buyout has been alluded to in
sparring over the Batus offer, but the name of the entity with
which the talks were held hasn't been revealed. The board voted
unanimously to end discussions of a leveraged buyout, Farmers said.
   ``While the company is continuing to explore possible
alternatives, the board reaffirmed its view that the interests of
Farmers and its shareholders would be best served by the company
remaining an independent entity,'' Farmers said.
   Farmers, which ranks third in the nation in home and auto
insurance and is the seventh-largest property and casualty insurer,
has said it is willing to talk with Batus, but the two companies
have failed to agree on ground rules for negotiations.
   Batus is a retailing, tobacco and paper companies whose better
known operations include Saks Fifth Avenue department stores and
Kool cigarettes.
</TEXT>
