<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Drugs     04-25 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Drugs,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SmithKline Reports Increase in Sales, Profits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   SmithKline Beckman Corp. on Monday reported a 14 percent
increase in its first quarter profit, boosted by strong sales in
its eye-care division and a weak American dollar.
   The Philadelphia-based company said net income for the first
three months of this year totaled $116.5 million, or $1.34 a share,
compared with earnings of $146.4 million, or $1.15 per share, a
year ago.
   Sales rose 16 percent, to $1.16 billion from $1 billion in 1987.
   ``The sales gain was marked by strong performance from the
diagnostic-analytical and eye care groups together with favorable
currency exchange rates,'' said Chairman Henry Wendt.
   ``The weaker U.S. dollar had the effect of adding $55 million to
corporate sales. Ethical pharmaceutical sales, marked by strong
international results, were 10 percent above last year's first
quarter,'' he said.
   The company reported an increase of 14 percent in worldwide
sales of Tagamet, an ulcer drug, but a 35 percent decrease in the
sales of Dyazide, a hypertension medicine. Wendt blamed the drop on
generic competition and wholesaler buying patters.
   SmithKline reported that Allegan, Inc., the company's eye-care
business, recorded a 30 percent sales increase. With the inclusion
of Allergan Hydron, a contact lens company acquired late last year,
the increase totaled 50 percent.
</TEXT>
