<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Slightly Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose slightly against most major
currencies in quiet European trading Monday. Gold prices also edged
higher.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the market got a small boost from
a statement by West German Bundesbank President Karl Otto Pohl that
the dollar would drop further and such a fall would ``be contrary
to the interests of the United States.''
   But they said most market attention focused on the British
currency following a statement Sunday by Britain's Chancellor of
the Exchequer Nigel Lawson that he didn't want sterling to rise
further.
   The pound ended lower late Monday at $1.8730, cheaper for buyers
than the $1.8880-level it reached Friday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.35 yen to a closing 125.00 yen. Later, in
London, it fell back to 124.60 yen.
   Financial markets in Italy were closed for a national holiday.
In Europe, the dollar was selling for 1,245.50 lire late Monday, up
slightly from 1,244.50 Friday.
   Other late dollar rates, compared with late Friday's rates:
1.6765 West German marks, up from 1.6730; 1.3860 Swiss francs, up
from 1.3840; 5.6915 French francs, up from 5.6865; 1.8790 Dutch
guilders, up from 1.8770; and 1.2309 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2324.
   Gold closed in London at $449.50 a troy ounce, up from Friday's
$449 In Zurich, the late bid price was $450 an ounce, up from $449
late Friday, but dealers said trading was dull and trendless.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell to $451.13 an ounce from
Saturday's $451.58.
   Silver was quoted in London late Monday at a bid price of $6.42
a troy ounce, down from Friday's $6.46.
</TEXT>
