<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
lower Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade despite indications
early in the session that demand for soybean products was stronger
than anticipated.
   The soybean complex had led the grain markets higher in early
trading after the Census Bureau reported lower-than-expected stocks
of U.S. soybean meal at the end of March.
   The numbers indicated greater domestic usage and exports of
soybean meal, but ``with the expectation downstream for poor
domestic use and export, the market couldn't hold,'' said Richard
Loewy, senior grain and oilseed analyst for Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York.
   The soybean market also sold off on expectations that the weekly
U.S. Department of Agrigulture export inspections report would show
8 million to 11 million bushels of soybeans were approved for
shipment last week. But the report, issued after the close, showed
soybean inspections totaled more than 13.1 million bushels.
   Corn futures also weakened on poor export sales. The wheat
market succumbed to continuing fears about dryness in the spring
wheat growing region of the northern Plains, Loewy said.
   At the close, wheat was 3 cents to 4 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.11\ a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
1} cents lower with May at $1.99{ a bushel; oats were { cent to 2\
cents higher with May at $1.65 a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents to
4{ cents lower with May at $6.59 a bushel.
</TEXT>
