<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BoardroomEyes Bjt   04-25 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boardroom Eyes, Bjt,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey Shows Glasses Can be a Power Accessory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN FAHLGREN-TORRES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers with their sights set on moving up in the
business world may do better in eyeglasses, says a new study that
found corporate recruiters look favorably on the bespectacled.
   The survey, conducted by the Dallas-based Pearle Vision Center,
found 79 percent of the corporate recruiters and fashion-image
consultants queried said that glasses connote intelligence.
Sixty-nine percent said they viewed glasses as enhancing a
professional image.
   Joseph Dono, Pearle's senior vice president of marketing, said
Monday that the survey doesn't necessarily mean the 20-20 set
should rush to buy glasses, but it could be a consideration for
those who need corrective lenses.
   ``Eyeglasses are not only functional for vision correction, but
they also make a statement about the individual wearing them,''
Dono said. ``Today's consumer may purchase glasses as a fashion
accessory, or to project a more business-like image for that `board
room' look.''
   Pearle researchers interviewed 100 corporate recruiters and
image consultants in New York, Chicago, Los Angeles and San
Francisco. About 60 percent of those polled recruit either for
executive-level positions or for the financial or communications
field.
   The survey reported 80 percent of the respondents think
eyeglasses help the wearer focus on making a power statement during
a business presentation.
   Removing glasses at strategic points is considered an effective
way to emphasize a particular word or phrase. A third of those
surveyed admitted using glasses for such a purpose.
   ``It's an eye-opener to people who are buying eyeglasses
today,'' Dono said. ``Many people who are buying glasses today
haven't bought eyewear in about two years. Everything has changed
since then. The materials are running the gamut from plastic to
metal to carbon, a very light metal, titanium. And then there are
cosmetic tints available on the lenses and lightweight plastic
lenses.''
   The poll showed the best choice for the work environment for
both men and women is the the classic tortoise-shell frame style,
which for years has suggested a studious, ``bookworm'' image for
the wearer.
   The second-most popular styles with recruiters on men were wire
frames, while ultra-modern designer frames ranked second for women
applicants.
   It may seem ironic that the survey favors wearing glasses at a
time when contact lenses have advanced to include not only hard and
soft lenses, but also gas-permeable, extended-wear and
eye-color-changing lenses.
   ``Not everyone can wear contacts, and many people do not like to
wear contacts,'' Dono said.
   ``The fact that there are designer labels and quality brands
isn't enough of an attraction for everyone,'' Dono said. ``But
amongst people who have to wear glasses, the choices are more
appealing today than they were five years ago.
   Dono said there may be some upwardly mobile business-types who
will begin wearing eyeglasses even if they don't need them because
of poor vision.
   ``There are some people who will and already do wear them for
that reason, but that's a small minority,'' Dono said. ``I mean,
many people wear sunglasses not for the effects on they have on
cutting out sunlight, but because the people think they look good.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880425-0317 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1726EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-USG-DesertPartners     04-25 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USG-Desert Partners,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Desert Partners Completes Financing for USG Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Desert Partners L.P., a partnership headed by
two Texas oilmen, announced Monday that it has finished arranging
the necessary financing for its $1.6 billion cash tender offer for
manufacturer USG Corp.'s stock.
   Desert Partners said it has lined up financing commitments
totaling $1.9 billion, including a $1.4 billion bank facility and
$500 million in subordinated debt.
   The partnership, led by oilmen Cyril Wagner Jr. and Jack E.
Brown, has offered $42 a share in cash for up to 39 million shares
of USG's 45.7 million common shares it doesn't already own. In
addition, Desert Partners would offer around $600 million in debt
securities and warrants, or rights to purchase stock, also valued
at $42 each, for the balance of the deal.
   The cash and securities portions of the takeover bid have a
total value of around $2.2 billion.
   Chicago-based USG, a manufacturer of paper, plaster and wood
products, including gypsum wallboard, has rejected Desert Partners'
offer as inadequate.
   Desert Partners, based in Midland, Texas, holds about 9.9
percent of USG's common shares, acquired last fall for an average
of $45 a share.
   The partnership's $1.4 billion bank facility, arranged by Wells
Fargo Bank and Chase Manhattan Bank, includes $170 million
available only for the payment of interest and expenses.
   The commitments for subordinated debt consist of $300 million
from the investment and finance subsidiaries of Elders IXL Ltd., an
Australian conglomerate, and $200 million from U.S. investment firm
Merrill Lynch & Co. Inc.
   USG's profit for the first quarter, reported Monday, dropped to
$39.7 million, or 77 cents a share, from $85 million, or $1.65 a
share, in the first three months of 1987. First-quarter sales rose,
on the other hand, to $715.2 million from $693.2 million a year
earlier.
   The company said shipments of its products, including gypsum
board, were at high levels but selling prices for domestic gypsum
board were 17 percent below the 1987 first-quarter level.
   USG is the holding company for United States Gypsum Co., USG
Interiors Inc., Masonite Corp. and several other operating
subsidiaries.
   Desert Partners tried last October to acquire USG, but the
partnership said in January that market conditions had forced it to
abandon its plan to offer more than $2.5 billion, or over $50 a
share, for the company.
   In a recent filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
Desert Partners said it intends to explore alternatives to the
acquisition of USG, including an attempt to elect nominees to USG's
board of directors at the annual meeting next month.
   USG sued Desert Partners late last year, claiming that the
partnership violated federal securities law in its negotiations
with USG.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
