<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WeeklySteel     04-25 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Steel,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Output Fell 0.9 Percent in Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel production fell to 1.970 million tons in
the week ended April 23, a decrease of 0.9 percent from the
previous week's 1.987 million tons, the American Iron and Steel
Institute reported Monday.
   The industry's production amounted to 91.9 percent of capacity
during the week, compared with 92.7 percent in the previous week.
   Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at
31.607 million net tons, an increase of 28.5 percent from the
24.595 million net tons in the previous year. The steel operations
of USX Corp., the nation's largest steel producer, were shut down
by a strike during the first month of 1987.
   Production so far this year used 90.4 percent of capacity,
compared with 70.8 percent a year earlier.
   Net tonnage by district for the week ended April 23: Northeast
Coast, 294,000; Pittsburgh, 198,000; Youngstown, 131,000; Lake
Erie, 151,000; Detroit, 169,000; Chicago, 497,000; Midwest,
203,000; Southern, 225,000; and Western, 102,000.
</TEXT>
