<DOCNO> AP880425-0320 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1614EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Oil Bjt   04-25 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Oil, Bjt,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exxon, Mobil, Other Companies Report Strong Quarterly Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major U.S. oil companies, led by top-ranking
Exxon Corp. and second-largest Mobil Corp., reported strong
improvements in their first-quarter earnings Monday, many citing
sharp gains in refining and marketing, as well as chemicals.
   Amoco Corp., Occidental Petroleum Corp. and Unocal Corp. also
reported hefty increases.
   Exxon said its earnings were up 36 percent to $1.46 billion, or
$1.06 per share, compared with $1.07 billion, or 75 cents per
share, in the 1987 first quarter. Sales totaled $22.0 billion vs.
$19.4 billion a year earlier, it said.
   Mobil said its quarterly profit doubled to $505 million, or
$1.23 per share, compared with $252 million, or 62 cents per share
in the 1987 period. Revenue from continuing operations totaled
$13.8 billion vs. $11.7 billion in the first three months of last
year.
   Both companies are based in New York.
   Among the others:
   _Amoco, of Chicago, said its earnings leaped 80.4 percent, to
$469 million, or $1.82 per share, vs. 1987 first-quarter earnings
of $260 million, or $1.02 per share. Sales totaled $5.8 billion in
the first three months, compared with $5.2 billion in the 1987
period, the nation's fifth-largest petroleum company said.
   _Occidental, ranked seventh, said its earnings increased by 16.5
percent to $113 million, or 52 cents per share, compared with $97
million, or 50 cents per share, a year earlier. Both periods
included extraordinary gains, however.
   The Los Angeles-based company said its sales totaled $4.48
billion in the three months, compared with $4.16 billion in the
1987 first quarter.
   _Unocal said its earnings nearly tripled, but were also affected
by special items. The company, ranked 13th-largest, is also
headquartered in Los Angeles.
   Unocal's quarterly earnings totaled $178.4 million, or $1.53 per
share, on $2.3 billion of revenue, vs. $60.7 billion, or 52 cents
per share, on sales of $2.06 billion in the same period of 1987.
   Included in those results were a $456 million one-time gain due
to an accounting change related to income taxes. This was partially
offset by an post-tax charge of $322 million for a writedown of
certain company assets, the company said.
   ``Excess supplies and weak winter demand associated with
warmer-than-normal weather caused crude prices to move sharply
lower during the quarter. Crude prices in last year's first quarter
were higher and relatively stable,'' observed Exxon Chairman L.G.
Rawl.
   The sharply lower crude prices, together with much stronger
margins for petroleum products and record chemical earnings were
``fundamentally responsible'' for Exxon's overall earnings
improvement, he added.
   ``The quarterly comparison was helped by sale of property abroad
and lower incentive compensation costs in 1988, but the effect of
these benefits was largely offset by the absence of 1987 foreign
exchange gains and tax credits associated with foreign
operations,'' Rawl said.
   Mobil Chairman Allen E. Murray said the company's quarterly
performance was the best since 1981, with the most important
improvements occurring in its domestic refining and marketing
segment and chemicals, which posted its ``best quarter ever.''
   The latest report did not reflect the impact of Mobil's
Montgomery Ward unit, which was sold on March 7. Mobil said the
retailer made $19 million in profits, compared with $8 million in
the first quarter of 1987. Those profits and proceeds from the sale
will be posted in the second quarter, the company said.
   Amoco Chairman Richard M. Morrow attributed the company's
performance to substantial strengthening of refined product
margins, compared with the same period last year, along with
continued record earnings by its chemicals division.
   In Los Angeles, Occidental Chairman Armand Hammer said chemical
operations more than tripled during the quarter.
   The company said its 1988 results included an after-tax gain of
$53 million, primarily from the sale of a 25 percent interest in
its Colombia oil holdings, as well as extraordinary gains of $2
million, primarily from capital loss carryforwards.
   Its 1987 first-quarter results included a post-tax gain of $103
million from the sale of certain chemical operations plus $24
million in capital loss carryforwards.
   Fred L. Hartley, Unocal's chairman, said the main negative
factors affecting quarterly performance were higher dry hole costs
and exploratory expense and lower geothermal earnings and domestic
crude prices.
   These were offset somewhat by higher natural gas production in
Thailand and higher refining and marketing profits, he added.
   The writedowns included Unocal's remaining investment in a shale
oil project, about half its investment in mining and processing
facilities in New Mexico and Pennsylvania and 40 percent of its
investment in certain coking facilities at its Chicago refinery.
</TEXT>
