<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-CapCities-ABC     04-25 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-CapCities-ABC,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts Big Jump in 1st-Qtr Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capital Cities-ABC Inc. said Monday its first
quarter profit nearly tripled despite a wider loss at its ABC
Television Network.
   The communications giant warned that its business outlook for
the rest of the year ``is not as encouraging,'' however, because of
anticipated weak advertising demand for the television network and
specialized publications.
   Capital Cities said it earned $70.3 million, or $4.16 a share,
in the three months ended April 4 compared with $23.9 million, or
$1.43 a share, a year earlier.
   First quarter revenue rose 34 percent to $1.29 billion from $959
million a year earlier.
   On an operating basis, income rose 72.2 percent to $167 million
in the quarter from $97.3 million in 1987.
   Broadcasting revenue, which includes revenue for the company's
eight television stations, 21 radio stations and its 80 percent
interest in the ESPN cable network as well as for the ABC
Television network, rose 44 percent to $1.04 billion mainly due to
the 1988 telecasts of the Super Bowl football game and the Winter
Olympics games.
   Operating income in broadcasting rose 86 percent to $164.4
million from $88 million a year earlier.
   Nonetheless, the ABC Television Network reported a
``significantly increased loss'' in the quarter. The company did
not provide a specific loss figure for either period. The network
earned $50 million in all of 1987.
   The company said continuing cost control efforts and income from
the telecast of the Super Bowl by the network failed to offset a
loss in excess of $65 million from the broadcast of the Winter
Olympics.
   The network spent about $350 million for the rights to the games
and production of the telecast but generated only about $285
million in revenue, according to spokesman Joseph Fitzgerald.
   The company said operating earnings for the company's television
stations and ESPN were well ahead of last year.
   Publishing revenue rose 4 percent to $246 million, but
publishing earnings declined 17.5 percent to $28.7 million.
   The company said there were modest revenue gains in the
newspaper and shopping guide operations, partly offset by weakness
in specialized publications.
</TEXT>
