<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1732EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-25 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Slightly Lower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended mixed in light trading Monday,
reflecting dealer reluctance to speculate prior to potentially
market-moving developments later this week.
   Gold prices fell marginally after rising in Europe and falling
in Asia. Republic National Bank quoted bullion at $447.50 a troy
ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, compared with $449.50 late Friday.
   Money dealers attributed the dollar's mixed behavior partly to
uncertainty about the impact of a government report on
first-quarter U.S. economic growth due out Tuesday.
   They also said the Senate's impending vote on a major trade
bill, along with questions about the outcome of a planned OPEC
meeting with non-cartel oil exporters, injected uncertainty into
foreign exchange trading.
   ``There's not much to say today,'' said Christianne Mandell, a
trading analyst at the New York branch of Britain's Barclay's Bank
PLC. ``It was quiet because there's anticipation about events that
are happening later. Until those things come out, there won't be
information to trade on.''
   Traders said the Commerce Department's report on the gross
national product would be a tricky number to interpret. Estimates
range between 1.5 percent and 3 percent, but it will be the
underlying components of that figure that influence the dollar's
value.
   For example, if first-quarter GNP is high, that could boost the
dollar provided that the growth was caused by strength in exports,
thereby helping reduce the trade deficit. But if the growth was
caused by strong consumer demand for foreign goods, that suggests
higher imports, a widening trade deficit and a further decline in
the dollar.
   On the other hand, a substantially lower GNP could boost the
dollar because it implies a slowdown in imports. But it also could
hurt the dollar by relieving pressure for higher domestic interest
rates, traders said.
   ``It's really a Catch-22 situation,'' said Alberto Soria,
foreign exchange manager at the New York branch of Swiss Bank Corp.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.35 yen to a closing 125.00 yen. In London
it retreated to 124.60 yen, and in New York it traded at 124.73
yen, down from 124.91 yen late Friday.
   The British pound fell in London to $1.8730, cheaper than the
$1.8880 reached Friday, largely because of weekend remarks by
Britain's Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson that sterling
shouldn't rise further. In New York the pound fetched $1.8736,
cheaper than $1.8840 quoted Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared with levels late
Friday: 1.6753 West German marks, down from 1.6758; 1.3873 Swiss
francs, up from 1.3849; 1.2317 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2324;
5.6862 French francs, up from 5.6845; and 1,244.75 Italian lire, up
from 1,244.50.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Friday: 1.6765
West German marks, up from 1.6730; 1.3860 Swiss francs, up from
1.3840; 5.6915 French francs, up from 5.6865; 1.8790 Dutch
guilders, up from 1.8770; and 1.2309 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2324; 1,245.50 lire, up from 1,244.50.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
fetched $448.90 an ounce, down $2.
   Gold closed in London at $449.50 a troy ounce, up from $449
Friday. In Zurich the late bid price was $450 vs. $449, and in Hong
Kong it was $451.13 vs. $451.58.
   On the Comex, silver for current delivery fetched $6.355, off 5
cents. Silver was quoted in London late Monday at a bid price of
$6.42 a troy ounce, down from $6.46 Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
