<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0246,0730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Continue To Slide On Weakening Demand</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 14th graf pvs, Corn futures ..., to restore dropped
first reference to analyst Loewy.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices sank Monday on the Commodity Exchange in
New York amid perceptions that demand for the metal is declining
and supplies are on the rise. Precious metals futures also
retreated on the Comex.
   On other exchanges, energy futures were mixed; grain and soybean
futures were mostly lower; livestock and meat were mixed; and
stock-index futures advanced.
   The most active copper contract, for delivery in May, fell 2.65
cents to settle at 90.95 cents a pound.
   Indications of slackening demand and rising supplies have pushed
copper futures down nearly 10 cents a pound in the last two weeks
and the market continues to display technical and fundamental
weakness, analysts said.
   ``Even though you have fairly tight supplies in the near term,
demand is not enough to justify these high prices,'' said Jack
Barbanel, director of futures trading at New York-based Gruntal &
CO.
   Stephen Platt, metals analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Chicago, said he expected demand for copper to weaken further as
summer approaches.
   Precious metal futures retreated in reaction to the dollar's
recent strength, lower commodity prices in general and beliefs that
higher interest rates are just around the bend, the analysts said.
   Trading activity was light ahead of Tuesday's release of monthly
government figures on economic growth and the opening Tuesday
afternoon of a meeting between the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries and non-OPEC oil-producing countries, which
could lead to an inflationary agreement to limit oil production.
   Gold settled $2 to $2.30 lower with June at $450.10 a troy
ounce; silver was 5 cents lower across the board with May at $6.365
a troy ounce.
   Nervousness about Tuesday's oil meeting also overshadowed the
energy futures market at the New York Mercantile Exchange, where
prices finished mixed.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 10 cents to 12 cents
higher with June at $18.40 a barrel; heating oil was .04 cent to
.61 cent higher with May at 51.21 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .24 cent lower to .65 cent higher with May at 52.05 cents a
gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures settled mostly lower on the Chicago
Board of Trade despite indications early in the session that demand
for soybean products was stronger than anticipated.
   The soybean complex had led the grain markets higher in early
trading after the Census Bureau reported lower-than-expected stocks
of U.S. soybean meal at the end of March.
   Corn futures weakened on poor export sales. The wheat market
succumbed to continuing fears about dryness in the spring wheat
growing region of the northern Plains, said Richard Loewy, senior
grain and oilseed analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in
New York.
   Wheat settled 2} cents to 3} cents lower with May at $3.11\ a
bushel; corn was 1 cent to 1} cents lower with May at $1.99} a
bushel; oats were { cent to 2\ cents higher with May at $1.65 a
bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents to 4 cents lower with May at $6.59 a
bushel.
   A Friday U.S. Department of Agriculture report showing
greater-than-expected numbers of cattle being fattened for
slaughter sparked a sharply lower opening in cattle futures on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, but prices recovered to finish mixed.
   Despite the report's indications of rising supplies, packing
houses were aggressive buyers of cattle on Monday, said Charlie
Richardson, an analyst in Denver with Lind-Waldock & Co.
   The early weakness in the cattle market spilled over into pork
pits, however, and persisted despite the cattle market's later
recovery, Richardson said.
   Live cattle settled .65 cent lower to .70 cent higher with June
at 70.17 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .12 cent lower to .20
cent higher with April at 79.95 cents a pound; hogs were .03 cent
to .68 cent lower with June at 48.42 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .40 cent lower to .08 cent higher with May at 52.10
cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures moved higher on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for June delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index settled 2 points higher at 263.85.
</TEXT>
