<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 1840EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Soviet-Economy 1stLd-Writethru f0180 04-25 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0180,0763</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Economy Ailing, New Figures Show</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to CORRECT percent to percentage points in
second graf, CORRECTS 3rd graf to show income increased 4 percent
over first quarter, sted in first quarter; picks up 4th graf pvs,
The first ... A version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From shoes to machines, the Soviet economy had
trouble meeting the country's needs in the first three months of
this year, the government said Monday in a sobering report on
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms.
   Perhaps the most telling admission in the lengthy report was
that national income, the overall barometer of the country's
economic health, fell 2.6 percentage points short of the planned
level.
   National income went up 4 percent over the first quarter of
1987, whereas the plan called for an increase of 6.6 percent. The
same shortfall was reported in labor productivity.
   The first quarter of 1987, to which the new figures are being
compared, was marred by overall poor performance.
   ``Now it's important for everything designated not to remain
only on paper,'' the Council of Ministers, the government's
Cabinet, said Monday in reviewing the economic report.
   The council stressed that many of the economy's bottlenecks were
hurting the country's 285.2 million people.
   ``The shortcomings noted in the work of a series of industries
and complexes became serious brakes in the buildup of production
and increase in people's well-being,'' the council said, according
to the news agency Tass.
   The report covered a period in which a new system was introduced
in the Soviet economy. As of Jan. 1, more than 76,000 state-run
factories and farms responsible for 60 percent of the Soviet
Union's production were required to depend on themselves for the
revenue they need to operate.
   That is one of the key elements of Gorbachev's economic reforms,
aimed at giving local managers more responsibility and flexibility.
The Communist Party chief wants to limit central authorities to
overall planning of the economy and allow local managers to
exercise direct control over production plans and quotas.
   The media said the reforms were not to blame for the
shortcomings noted in the report. Industries and farms operating
under the new requirements ``are performing better than those
working in the old way,'' Radio Moscow said.
   Industrial production increased 5 percent over the first quarter
of 1987, exceeding the 4.5 percent target set in state plans, Radio
Moscow quoted Nikolai Belov, deputy head of the State Committee on
Statistics, as saying.
   Energy production, transportation equipment, computers and
medical equipment all grew strongly, the statistics said.
   But one-third of the machine-building industry, a key sector in
Gorbachev's drive for greater efficiency, did not complete its
orders, the Council of Ministers noted.
   Among the specific problems cited in the report, splashed over
two pages of the government newspaper Izvestia, were shortcomings
in consumer products. It sais 87,000 radio receivers, 44,000
washing machines and 44,000 vacuum cleaners called for in state
plans were not produced. Clothing and shoes were either in short
supply or were left unpurchased because they were old-fashioned or
of poor quality.
   In agriculture, meat, vegetable and dairy production failed to
satisfy people's needs, and in some areas bread quality and
assortment was poor, the report said.
   Of the 15 Soviet republics, Armenia had the worst record from
January to March for fulfillment of industrial contract
obligations. Armenian factories completed just 98.5 percent of
their orders, compared to a high of 99.9 percent for Byelorussia
and Latvia.
   The report also criticized Armenia for not raising workers
salaries, improving household services or building schools,
hospitals and cultural centers.
   During much of February, many of Armenia's factories, schools
and businesses were closed in a strike prompted by an ethnic
dispute.
   The report was released as U.S. intelligence agencies released
in Washington an assessment saying that Gorbachev's reforms ran
into serious obstacles in 1987.
   A joint report by the Central Intelligence Agency and the
Defense Intelligence Agency said the Soviet gross national product
increased only 0.5 percent in 1987, compared with a 3.9 percent
increase the previous year.
   It said the poor performance in 1987 was due to poor weather
that hurt farm production and resistance to change in the Soviet
bureaucracy.
   National income, the barometer the Soviets use, is a measurement
of economic activity that differs from gross national product
because it does not consider the value of some services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
