<DOCNO> AP880425-0331 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 2008EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Trade 1stLd-Writethru   04-25 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate in Last-Ditch Scramble for Trade Bill Votes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``The bill ...'' to UDPATE with vote
now scheduled for Tuesday or Wednesday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators traded last-minute sales pitches
Monday as they fought for votes on a sweeping trade bill advancing
in defiance of presidential veto threats.
   ``You let this bill go down the tubes and I'll tell you where
the champagne corks will be popping _ they'll be popping in Japan
and they'll be popping in Germany,'' said Senate Finance Committee
Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas.
   The bill, scheduled for a Senate vote on Tuesday or Wednesday,
was expected to pass with votes to spare and the major question
remaining was whether it would get enough support to override a
veto.
   ``It's close,'' Bentsen told reporters.
   Democrats were expected to back the measure overwhelmingly while
Republicans were divided.
   The administration and its supporters said a veto would not
finish off the issue for the year and that there still would be
time to pass a stripped-down version that deleted the most
controversial provisions.
   ``I know this is an election year and the majority party may be
looking for a campaign issue rather than a trade bill, but I am
confident the Congress could pass a better bill if this one is
rejected,'' said Sen. Robert T. Stafford, D-Vt.
   The House passed the 1,000-page measure on Thursday 312-107,
more than enough support to override President Reagan's threatened
veto.
   Over the last month, the administration has focused most of its
criticism on a provision that would require all but the smallest
employers to provide 60-day notice of plant closings and
large-scale layoffs.
   A number of business groups have campaigned against the measure,
saying it would dry up capital for investment, frighten off
customers and cause other problems for management.
   Basic provisions of the bill would overhaul the system under
which the United States imposes import curbs in retaliation for
international trade violations and other unfair practices.
   Among other things, it would make retaliation mandatory for
violations except in certain cases, such as national security.
   It also would transfer from the president to the U.S. trade
representative the authority to determine whether retaliation was
in order and, if so, what kind of sanctions to impose.
   Other central features would streamline the machinery under
which the United States imposes import quotas and tariffs to aid
American industries that are threatened by surges in foreign
competition.
   The measure contains scores of other features ranging from
billions of dollars in agricultural subsidies to repeal of the
windfall profits tax on earnings of oil companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
