<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HomeState-Andersen     04-25 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Home State-Andersen,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Tentatively Approves Settlement With Home State Accountant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state judge tentatively approved on Monday a
proposed $5.5 million settlement of Ohio's lawsuit against Arthur
Andersen & Co., accounting firm for the collapsed Home State
Savings Bank.
   Judge Richard A. Niehaus of Hamilton County Common Pleas Court
said he would accept objections to the proposed settlement and make
a final ruling on May 6.
   The state blamed the firm for negligence in auditing Home
State's books, which Ohio officials said contributed to the March
1985 collapse of the Cincinnati-based thrift. Arthur Andersen
denied the state's allegations and admitted no wrongdoing in
reaching the settlement.
   The settlement was reached April 15, after the case already had
gone to trial in the Ohio Court of Claims in Columbus. The case is
before Niehaus because he has jurisdiction over the state's
liquidation of Home State.
   The case is one of numerous civil suits the state filed in its
efforts to recover costs of guaranteeing all the deposits of Home
State after its collapsed. Home State was closed for three months
until another company bought and reopened it in June 1985, allowing
depositors to get their money back.
   Home State collapsed three days after the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission had ESM Government Securities Inc., a
securities trader in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., closed for bankruptcy
with more than $300 million in debts. Home State was ESM's biggest
investor through securities transactions, and lost $144 million
because of ESM's closing.
   Home State's failure caused a statewide crisis for 69 other Ohio
savings and loans insured by the private Ohio Deposit Guarantee
Fund of Cincinnati, which was weakened when Home State drained
backup money to cope with losses and withdrawals by panicked
depositors.
   A number of Home State and ESM have since been convicted of
crimes in connection with the failure of the two institutions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
