<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Goodyear     04-25 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Goodyear,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goodyear Reports Stronger Core Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co. reported Monday
that its first quarter profit from continuing operations rose by
14.2 percent from the previous year, due largely to the company's
focus on its core tire business.
   Goodyear posted net income of $95.3 million, or $1.67 per share,
all from continuing operations, during the quarter ended March 31.
That compared with a profit of $284.2 million, or $3.99 per share,
a year earlier, which included $200.8 million from discontinued
operations.
   Sales during the quarter rose to $2.6 billion from $2.3 billion
in first quarter 1987.
   Goodyear last year sold its Goodyear Aerospace, Motor Wheel and
Celeron Oil and Gas operations, plus other assets. The company sold
those assets under a major restructuring following an unsuccessful
hostile takeover attempt by the international businessman Sir James
Goldsmith.
   Goodyear Chairman Robert E. Mercer said the latest quarterly
results reflected increased global demand for the company's tire
products.
   Goodyear also reported sales growth in its other businesses,
including chemicals, film, industrial hoses, conveyor belts and
power transmission products.
</TEXT>
