<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SandsPurchased     04-25 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Sands Purchased,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Show Promoter Buys Vegas Resort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Massachusetts-based trade show company
is acquiring the Sands Hotel and Casino, a 36-year fixture on the
Las Vegas strip, for $110 million, the company announced Monday.
   Interface Group is acquiring the Sands, a 36-year fixture on the
Las Vegas Strip, from MGM Grand Inc., which is owned by financier
Kirk Kerkorian. The purchase includes the resort-casino and 60
acres of land on the Strip.
   Sheldon Adelson, Interface's chairman, called the Sands purchase
a natural extension of the Interface operations, which already
include trade shows, a New England-based travel operation and a
small airline.
   Kerkorian will continue operating the hotel until the five
Interface partners obtain a Nevada gaming license, which could take
six months to a year, Adelson said.
   Once licensing is completed, Interface plans to build a
1,000-room tower that could cost $60 million to $70 million,
Adelson said.
   The company, based in Needham, Mass., also may build major
convention facilities on acreage purchased at the rear of the
750-room hotel and casino, which is located in the heart of the
rapidly-growing Strip.
   Adelson said Henri Lewin, former president of the Las Vegas
Hilton, would take over management of the hotel. Lewin is chairman
of Aristocrat Hotels of San Francisco, a hotel management and
consulting firm.
   Kerkorian purchased the Sands and the Desert Inn in February
from the Summa Corporation for $167 million. Kerkorian will retain
ownership of the Desert Inn.
   Interface produces the COMDEX computer industry show, the city's
second-largest, attracting nearly 100,000 delegates annually.
Interface also promotes a housewares show and a film festival in
the city, as well as computer industry shows throughout the world.
   ``We plan to integrate our travel and trade show division
vertically, so that the Sands and other Las Vegas hotels are
included in our tour packages,'' Adelson said. ``We are considering
basing one of our aircraft in Las Vegas to service this market.''
   The Interface travel division is the largest tour operator in
New England and operates four L-1011 jet aircraft under its Five
Star Airline division.
</TEXT>
