<2ND_LINE>AM-ANPA-Trade, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0268,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Bill's Fate Debated Before Publishers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf ``The other...'' to CORRECT name to Makoto,
sted Macota.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An omnibus trade bill that President Reagan has
promised to veto could be revised easily to his liking with its
major provisions intact, the chairman of the U.S. International
Trade Commission said Monday.
   ``I think you're a bit premature in calling in the undertaker,''
Susan Liebeler told fellow panalists discussing the bill. The issue
was raised at the 102nd annual convention of the American Newspaper
Publishers Association here.
   The trade bill passed the House by 312-107 last week and is to
be voted on by the Senate this week.
   Reagan objects to a provision requiring most manufacturers to
give 60 days notice of plant closings and major layoffs.
   Liebeler said she thought that Reagan would veto the bill and
that, in a revised version, the notification provision would be
dropped and the bill approved.
   ``You may in fact see a trade bill the administration will
sign,'' she said.
   The other panalists were Makoto Kuroda, vice minister for
international affairs in Japan's Ministry of International Trade
and Industry; Pat Choate, vice president for policy at TRW Inc.;
and William H. Davidson, an associate professor at the University
of Southern California's School of Business Administration.
   The Japanese government has urged Reagan to veto the bill, which
would punish Toshiba Corp. for a subsidiary's sale of sensitive
equipment to the Soviet Union and give the U.S. trade
representative more power to deal with complaints of unfair trade
practices by foreign countries.
   The panalists were divided on the bill, with Kuroda voicing
opposition and Choate and Davidson supporting it.
   The flip side of the trade issue, Choate said, was foreign
investment in the United States, an issue he said the federal
government was ill-equipped to handle because it did not keep an
accurate count of money invested by foreigners.
   ``How can we have a good policy without good information?''
Choate asked.
   Kuroda said Japan's investment in the United States would help
revitalize the economy's of both countries and provide for
technological transfer.
   The discussion, called ``International Trade: Is Protectionism
Dead?'', was moderated by Karen Elliot House, foreign editor of the
Wall Street Journal.
   The panel was the first group discussion in the three-day
convention, which began Monday.
   More than 2,000 people, including about 1,500 publishers who
represent 90 percent of the daily newspaper circulation in the
United States, are attending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
